dozen to the customer, to prevent scalping _ a week to three days
before the film opens.
</P>
<P>
   Many new characters to learn
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, at Mann's Chinese Theater on Hollywood
Boulevard, about 30 people have been queued up for weeks, waiting
to buy tickets on this sacred spot, where the first ``Star Wars''
premiered 22 years ago. Because ``The Phantom Menace'' will open
two months later in Europe, hundreds _ perhaps thousands _ of fans
from the Old World are expected to wing to America to see it
sooner.
</P>
<P>
   It is the first ``Star Wars'' movie personally directed by Lucas
since the original in 1977, and the special effects are reportedly
mind-boggling: Only about one-ninth of the film involves scenes
with just plain human beings doing just plain acting in front of a
camera. Electricity and computer graphics seethe through the rest
of it in an ion-storm, unrelenting.
</P>
<P>
   Kids will have even more strange, pixilated names to memorize:
chiefly Darth Maul, a multihorned demon with a double-bladed light
saber; Jar-Jar, Mace Windu, Rune Haako, Nute Gunray, Darth Sidious,
Boss Nass.
</P>
<P>
   By now, the first bits of the plot of the movie are common
knowledge, thanks to a large article by Time magazine's movie
critic, Richard Corliss. (Time promoted the original ``Star Wars''
as ``The Movie of the Year'' on its cover in 1977, although Corliss
himself found the original film's story ``bad pulp, and so are the
characters of hero Luke and heroine Leia.'')
</P>
<P>
   At the outset of ``The Phantom Menace,'' which takes place about
40 years before the first ``Star Wars,'' a greedy Trade Federation
has imposed a trade embargo on the planet Naboo. Jedi master
Qui-Gon (pronounced Kwai-Gone), played by Liam Neeson, and his
youthful apprentice, Obi-Wan, are sent to settle the matter.
</P>
<P>
   On Naboo, they are joined by a comic figure, Jar-Jar, whose head
vaguely resembles a duck-billed hadrosaurus and who owes something
to J.R.R. Tolkien's glottally challenged character, Gollum, in
``The Lord of the Rings.'' Jar-Jar takes the two Jedi to Amidala,
queen of Naboo, and they prepare to escort her to the bejeweled,
Art Nouveau dream-city of Coruscant, capital of the
weak-but-still-righteous Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Engine trouble diverts the mission to Tatooine, where Qui-Gon
bargains for spare parts with Watto, a globular creature with
hummingbird wings. Watto's 9-year-old slave boy, Anakin, interests
Qui-Gon, who senses the boy's spiritual precocity _ a sure sign of
the Force.
</P>
<P>
   Immaculately conceived
</P>
<P>
   Catholics may raise eyebrows at Anakin's origin: His mother,
Shmi Skywalker, apparently conceived him immaculately, by a pure
union with the Force. He has no fleshly father.
</P>
<P>
   Intrigued, Qui-Gon makes a bet with Watto: If Anakin should win
a pod race against the tarantulalike braggart Sebulba, Watto will
hand him over to Qui-Gon and the lad will be free to pursue his
destiny as a Jedi knight.
</P>
<P>
   The ensuing 10-minute-long pod race sequence is said to be one
of the most eye-smacking highlights of the movie and goes clear
back to Lucas' boyhood dream of becoming a race-car driver.
</P>
<P>
   Anakin is destined to become the iron-lunged Darth Vader, the
evil Jedi seduced by the dark side of the Force, and the father of
Luke Skywalker, the hero of the 1977 ``Star Wars.''
</P>
<P>
   That's all Lucasfilm is saying for now. For the rest of the
movie, you'll have to pay your $8.
</P>
<P>
   But Jude Watson, a Flamingo Park fiction writer, has already
seen the whole script. She had to. She was commissioned to write
``Queen Amidala's Journal,'' a sort of prequel to the prequel.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, Watson has been sworn to secrecy. Anyway, ``Queen
Amidala's Journal'' is just one tiny building-block in the enormous
``Star Wars'' mythos, that by now has expanded like the Big Bang,
thousands of years in every direction from the original movie
trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The copy I had was specially coded, so that if I photocopied
it, they'd know. If I revealed any details, they'd kill my
grandmother. I'm joking!'' Watson said. ``But they are very
security-conscious.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Queen Amidala's Journal'' took her two months' hard work to
write, and she never even met Lucas. ``It was all done by phone and
fax. They check every detail out in California, to make sure you
don't get anything wrong. It is a very meticulously worked-out
universe,'' Watson remembered.
</P>
<P>
   What is it like, living ``A long time ago, in a galaxy far, far
away?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very liberating,'' Watson said. ``I had written books for
girls before. This time I had to put on my tomboy hat and put in a
lot of light saber fights. It was fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Will she go to the movie?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure. Not the first day, but I'll be there. No free tickets,
though. I'll have to stand in line like everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   Camping out a penitent act
</P>
<P>
   University of Florida English Professor Andrew Gordon is so
fascinated by the ``Star Wars'' mythology that he has written a
paper on it, available at his Web site
(web.clas.ufl.edu/users/agordon). Gordon says the special effects
in the movies are brilliant, but the real appeal of the films is
their adroit use of myth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to call `Star Wars' a steam-powered starship. The
appeal is not really the high-tech gloss or the special effects.
Plenty of science fiction movies have been made with great special
effects, but nobody goes back to see them after 20 years,'' Gordon
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead, what we have is an old-fashioned and reassuringly
conservative universe, a universe that makes sense, where there is
clear good and evil _ and good triumphs. You've got very old types,
like the Wise Old Man, the Beautiful Princess, the Elves and Animal
Helpers, the Black Knight, and the Hero who stands in for the whole
culture and redeems us.''
</P>
<P>
   Myth and science fiction blur into a kind of religion, Gordon
believes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Science fiction is very close to religion. The religion of
Scientology was founded by a science fiction writer, L. Ron
Hubbard. Science fiction is an attempt to answer the basic
questions of the universe: Why are we here?
</P>
<P>
   ``Similarly, there's a very strong religious component to `Star
Wars.' George Lucas himself has said that he came up with the idea
of the Force, to get young people thinking about God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to say these people who are standing in line for weeks
and weeks to see the movie are performing a religious rite, a
penitential process of self-purification, to show their worthiness.
It's like climbing the mountain on your knees to gain wisdom. You
voluntarily put yourself through discomfort to demonstrate your
faith.''
</P>
<P>
   And will Gordon see the movie?
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, sure. Got to. But I'm going to wait until the furor
dies down. I'm not going to stand in line.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
