u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT &LR;      05-01 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ROYALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TORRE NOT YET READY TO MANAGE YANKS; ZIMMER TO STAY ON 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ His doctor warned Joe Torre that his rate of
recovery from prostate cancer would be unpredictable, that he could
feel strong and vigorous one day and weary the next. Whereas Torre
once thought he might assume his role of manager on the Yankees'
current road trip, he said Friday that he was not ready and used
two weeks as a time frame for his return.
</P>
<P>
   It could be sooner, it could be later: Torre, still finding
himself tired at day's end in the seventh week since his surgery,
said he might manage next week, hopes he'll be back by the All-Star
Game break, and is sure he'll manage again this year. The exact
date? ``I don't know when I'm going to manage,'' said Torre, who
watched the Kansas City Royals beat the Yankees, 13-6, on Friday
for the first time since Aug. 12, 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Don Zimmer continues to manage the Yankees in Torre's absence in
spite of the pain in his knees, and in spite of the fact that he
called a team meeting earlier this week to inform players he would
retire after Thursday's game. ``I'll be here until he decides to
come back,'' said Zimmer, who answered questions alongside Torre
Friday. ``Whether it be a day, a month, five weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Torre: ``Why don't you ask me again in two weeks _ that's
what I'm thinking about, and if it's ahead of that, then it would
be a nice pleasant surprise for me. I've never been through this,
so I don't know what the timetable would be.''
</P>
<P>
   Torre will watch the Yankees here through the weekend, but is
uncertain whether he will accompany the team to Minnesota on
Tuesday. It's safe to say his mere presence at the ball park does
not inspire the Yankees, for they performed miserably Friday night.
Andy Pettitte was pounded (seven runs in three and one-third
innings), and his failure to cover first base was crucial to the
Royals' four-run rally in the fourth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City bashed five home runs and capitalized on a handful
of mental mistakes made by the Yankees, momentarily undercutting a
protest staged by about 2,000 fans; they were demonstrating against
the financial and competitive disparity between large- and
small-market franchises, and treated the Yankees as symbols of the
system.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the fans greeted the Yankees outside of Kauffman Stadium
as the players arrived for the game, chanting their slogan, ``Share
the wealth.'' Bernie Williams, whose 1999 salary of about $9.5
million is about double what the Kansas City starting lineup will
earn this year, was targeted by fans who held up a sign noting
Williams' pay. Williams acknowledged that he tried moving swiftly
past the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's sort of uncomfortable,'' Williams said. ``You can handle
the yelling when you're on the field and when it's about what you
do on the field, but this goes beyond the game itself. I thought I
was marching into the '60s somewhere.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans waved copies of dollar bills at the Yankees, and once
the game started, they turned their backs from the field while the
Yankees batted and then they departed, en masse, in the top of the
fourth inning. David Cone, a Kansas City native, debated with some
of the protesters during batting practice, but the wittiest retort
came in the form of a banner hauled by a plane: Share? O.K., You
Can Have Irabu.
</P>
<P>
   What Torre said about his plans is not really different than
what he said last weekend in New York _ that he feels great and is
working out regularly, but wants to regain his full energy and
acclimate himself to the demands of traveling before he comes back.
Torre never said he would manage this weekend in Kansas City, only
mentioning to Zimmer that he hoped to return on this trip.
</P>
<P>
   But the fact that Torre said he would join the team here after a
checkup in St. Louis on Thursday led to speculation _ from Zimmer
and others _ that Torre would manage against the Royals. Torre says
he's not ready for that. On many evenings, he said, he suddenly
feels very tired, as his doctor, William Catalona, said he might;
the Yankees usually play at night.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer and Torre had breakfast Friday morning, and Torre seemed
to convince Zimmer that whenever Torre returns, Zimmer should
merely take some time off, rather than retire.
</P>
<P>
   Watching Zimmer manage in pain, Torre said, ``hurts me.'' But he
knows he cannot let Zimmer's condition have an impact on his own
return. ``I can't have it put pressure on me,'' Torre said. ``I
think it'll affect both of us if I come back before that time when
I think it is right. Hopefully, they'll fit him with something that
takes pressure off his knee.''
</P>
<P>
   After some rest, Zimmer presumably would be in a better frame of
mind to decide whether he is going to retire and end his pro
baseball career after 51 years. ``Hopefully,'' Torre said, ``he'll
get to feeling good enough to want to sit next to me.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
