<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 00:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0436 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-DERBY-ADVANCE-HNS     05-01 0721
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-ADVANCE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALAN TRUEX  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ In what may be the most wide-open Kentucky Derby
in years, the designation of a favorite is less significant than
usual.
<TEXT>
<P>
   And usually it means virtually nothing. The Derby favorite has
not won the race in 20 years. The last to succeed was Spectacular
Bid in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert, trying to become the first trainer to win the Derby
in three consecutive years, is likely to find himself in the
favorite's role for today's 4:27 p.m. classic.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his Indian Charlie was the betting choice and
finished third. Fortunately for Baffert, his stable included Real
Quiet, the 8-1 shot who won.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, whose entry of General Challenge and the filly
Excellent Meeting is likely to be the chalk for the 125th Kentucky
Derby, said, ``I'd rather not be the favorite. If you have a good
one, you really don't want to brag on him too much. You feel you're
going to jinx yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are other more valid reasons for wanting to avoid
being the favorite.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Nafzger, who won the 1990 Derby with Unbridled and has
Vicar here this year, pointed out that the trainer of the favorite
is sometimes pressured by the horse's owner to alter his methods.
The favorite is under such media scrutiny that the trainer is
constantly second-guessed.
</P>
<P>
   The horse may sense the media pressure as well. In 1992, the
French-born Arazi, the Derby's last odds-on favorite, appeared
nervous as throngs of reporters followed his every move.
</P>
<P>
   ``The attention factor could have something to do with the
favorites losing,'' said Nick Zito, trainer of one of today's top
contenders, Stephen Got Even.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Nafzger said, ``I don't care about being the
Kentucky Derby favorite. I want to be the favorite for the
Preakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Many racing analysts expect him to get his wish _ win today's
Derby and become the automatic favorite to win the next jewel of
the Triple Crown, the Preakness Stakes.
</P>
<P>
   Vicar is the only colt in the field with more than one Grade I
stakes victory, as he took the Fountain of Youth and Florida Derby
back to back. Nafzger wasn't interested in winning the next Grade
I, the Blue Grass, because he feared wearing down the horse for the
start of the Triple Crown campaign.
</P>
<P>
   In the Blue Grass, Vicar took the lead at the top of the
stretch. But with jockey Shane Sellers following orders not to
extend him, he finished third, which enabled him to avoid being the
Derby favorite.
</P>
<P>
   The media and public are inevitably drawn to the winners of the
Blue Grass and Santa Anita Derby, even though it has been eight
years since any of those champions went on to win the Kentucky
Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Indian Charlie became the media darling after his
victory in the Santa Anita.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Santa Anita Derby took too much out of him,''
Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Santa Anita runner-up Real Quiet who proceeded to win the
Kentucky Derby and Preakness.
</P>
<P>
   Several factors make the Derby especially difficult to predict.
</P>
<P>
   For one, the track surface is unusually deep. Some horses run
well on the hard-packed sands of Southern California but bog down
here. The Derby is for 3-year-olds, most of whom have raced only
five to 10 times in their lives, at tracks other than Churchill.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert said Indian Charlie ``couldn't get over the track at
all.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, Derby fields tend to be overly large. Today's race has 19
horses, after Friday's removal of Arabian import Aljabr because of
lameness.
</P>
<P>
   The more horses, the more likelihood someone besides the
favorite runs well, and the more likelihood of the favorite being
bumped off stride or jammed in traffic.
</P>
<P>
   There is also another ``X'' factor unique to the Derby: the
crowd of 150,000 or more.
</P>
<P>
   With all the people and noise, the paddock can terrify a
3-year-old horse, favored or not. Many have become so unnerved,
they were beaten before the race began.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd also can be a factor during the race.
</P>
<P>
   Said Jack Preston, co-owner of last year's Derby runner-up,
Victory Gallop: ``I've seen horses come out of the far turn and hit
that wall of sound from the grandstand and they just stop. You
never know if that will happen until you run the race.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 0014EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0010 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 00:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0437 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT &LR;      05-01 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATSON GETS A WARMER HOMECOMING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The high school Allen Watson starred at 11 years ago is just a
few miles from Shea Stadium, and his family home in Middle Village
is close enough that dozens of his friends and family members sat
behind home plate Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   In his first outing as a Met starting pitcher 12 days ago,
Watson said he had been distracted for a few innings by the
excitement of pitching in a park so near to so much that mattered.
After he gave up consecutive home runs and trailed by 3-0 to
Montreal after just eight pitches that afternoon, Watson didn't
even look to his father in the stands, figuring that the rough
outing had sent his father home early.
</P>
<P>
   None of the 40 friends and relatives left on Friday night. They
blew into their hands to stave off the cold and were rewarded with
a controlled and mature performance by Watson in the Mets' 7-2
victory over the San Francisco Giants, one of the teams he pitched
for before returning home to Queens.
</P>
<P>
   Watson tied a career high with eight strikeouts and gave up just
three hits and three walks in five innings.
</P>
<P>
   Watson's second victory of the season came over the team that
began the game with the National League's best record (it is now
16-8) and figures to be the Mets' primary competition for a
wild-card spot at the end of the season. He didn't look to his
father Friday night, either, but this time because he figured his
father was so anxious, he was outside smoking.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets really nervous,'' Watson said. ``My mom doesn't even
come, so that tells you something. I want to do well for them, my
friends and family.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson did so well that he is making himself a candidate to
remain in the rotation, even when Rick Reed returns from a calf
injury, probably next week. Watson had command of all of his
pitches on Friday, but particularly relied on a two-seam change-up
he had worked on with reliever John Franco. Given a 4-0 lead in the
first inning, Watson struggled just once, in the fifth inning as he
was running out of gas. But he allowed just one run, and then
struck out Ellis Burks and Jeff Kent, the third and fourth batters
in the order, to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We gave him a lead and he knew what to do with it,'' said
Manager Bobby Valentine, whose team improved to 14-9. ``For them to
get just one run with the middle of the order coming up was the key
to the game. ''
</P>
<P>
   Giants pitcher Shawn Estes was not nearly as composed as Watson.
He walked Rickey Henderson to open the first inning, then yielded a
single to Edgardo Alfonzo (whose four hits tied a career high) that
sent Henderson to third.
</P>
<P>
   After striking out Jon Olerud and with a 3-1 count on Mike
Piazza, Estes was called for a balk by Bob Davidson, the home plate
umpire, for what appeared to be a slight bobbing of his head.
Henderson came home at the same time as Estes. He stalked toward
home plate seeking an explanation but was pushed away first by
catcher Scott Servais and then by Manager Dusty Baker.
</P>
<P>
   But Estes remained rattled. He walked Piazza, then gave up a
double to Robin Ventura that scored Alfonzo. On four straight
pitches he walked Mike Kinkade to load the bases. On a 1-0 count to
Brian McRae, Estes threw a wild pitch and Piazza scored the third
run of the inning. Estes walked McRae to load the bases again. Rey
Ordonez's grounder to third base was fielded by Charlie Hayes, who
tagged Kinkade on the run but allowed Ventura to score to give the
Mets a 4-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Estes settled down briefly after that, until Ventura smashed an
0-1 fastball into the right-field bullpen in the fifth inning for a
5-1 lead. But Watson had been threatened in the top half of the
fifth, too, and his artful escape from potential disaster with just
that one run scored served as the coda to his evening.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Cook yielded a home run to Servais in the sixth, but
after Cook walked two straight batters in the seventh, Turk Wendell
came in to strike out Kent, which, Valentine said, was virtually
the save. Wendell got an official save, too, his first of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE PITCH
</P>
<P>
   It now seems less likely that RICK REED, who has been on the
disabled list since April 12 with a slight tear in his right calf,
will pitch Sunday _ either in New York or in a rehabilitation
assignment. Reed will throw on the side Saturday, Manager BOBBY
VALENTINE said, and General Manager STEVE PHILLIPS said the team
would probably determine the rotation sometime this weekend. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
