<HEADER>
A0439 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-TEAMS-DERBY01-COX     05-01 0691
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TEAMS-DERBY01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Winning Derby requires big stable, good game plan
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Wayne Lukas showed them how.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, when Lukas won the Kentucky Derby with Thunder Gulch,
the trainer started three horses. The next year, when he won with
Grindstone, five Lukas entries were Kentucky Derby starters.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for other trainers to catch on. Quality you
need. Quantity helps, too. ``It's good to have a good horse,'' said
Lukas. ``It's better to have two.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the year of the tag team.
</P>
<P>
   The man of the hour today at Churchill Downs is Bob Baffert, in
a wonderful position to become the first trainer since the race
started in 1875 to win three straight Derbys. Baffert has three
among the top selections, General Challenge, Excellent Meeting and
Prime Timber.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert announced Friday morning that Excellent Meeting would
run in the Derby, not the Oaks on Friday, although she had been
nominated for the event for fillies. The Oaks went to heavily
favored Silverbulletday, Baffert's other top filly.
</P>
<P>
   But the theme of Derby No. 125 is the double entry, the 1-2
punch, or in Baffert's case, the 1-2-3 punch.
</P>
<P>
   Never have so many trainers reached game day for the biggest
event of the racing year with more than one horse in the starting
gate.
</P>
<P>
   There are 19 Derby starters.
</P>
<P>
   Aljabr, the less-regarded of two entries from Sheikh Mohammed al
Maktoum, was withdrawn Friday afternoon with the announcement that
the horse had become lame.
</P>
<P>
   Still, 10 of today's starters are loners, horses without a
stablemate on the firing line. Nine starters are controlled by four
men, trainers Lukas, Baffert, Nick Zito and Elliott Walden.
</P>
<P>
   This opens up all kinds of possibilities.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert could send his filly, Excellent Meeting, out to make a
fast pace, weaken the other horses trying to catch him and set the
race up for one of Baffert's other two headliners.
</P>
<P>
   That's not considered unethical. It happens in racing all the
time when two or more horses in a race are controlled by one
trainer or owner.
</P>
<P>
   But unethical developments do occur.
</P>
<P>
   In tag-team situations, who knows what horse might shut off
another, leaving the way open for his partner?
</P>
<P>
   Money goes to success, which is why so many of the best Derby
horses are with a handful of trainers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baffert is in a word-of-mouth phase,'' said Mike Pegram, owner
of Baffert's 1998 Derby champion, whose wealth came from a lineup
of fast-food franchises. ``The ultra-rich can't wait to get to him
with their horses. I'm talking about a group far above people on my
income level.''
</P>
<P>
   Trainers that have established themselves as long-time Derby
reliables, like Lukas, who has started the race 33 times in 18
years, draw big-money clients. Lukas starts Cat Thief today as well
as Charismatic. They come from the portfolios of two of his richest
clients.
</P>
<P>
   Newcomers like Elliott Walden, never a Derby winner but at the
top or near there in all three Triple Crown races last year with
Victory Gallop, attract horse-buyers quickly when they win top
races like the Belmont Stakes. Walden's entries are Menifee and
Ecton Park.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Zito is an example of just how quickly clients come to a
man with a reputation as a Derby trainer.
</P>
<P>
   Zito, first in the Derby in 1991 and 1994, was abandoned last
year by his leading owner, a newcomer quickly discouraged when his
horses were injured. Practically out of the chase in 1998, Zito is
back this year with Adonis and favorite Stephen Got Even, both
owned by new investors to his stables.
</P>
<P>
   ``The No. 1 thing we do,'' said Ed Plesa Jr., the Calder-based
trainer who trains Derby entry Three Ring, ``is recruit, recruit,
recruit. We've got to find the horses. Then we've got to find the
owners to buy the horses. To win the Derby, you need national
exposure.'' Of the six Derby favorites at 10-1 or less in the
program odds, Vicar is the only one not part of a two-horse
project. The 1990s ends at the Derby as a team operation.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
