<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS HOLD OFF PENGUINS: 2ND ROUND IS IN SIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ The Devils and the Pittsburgh Penguins
finally put together a spirited match that was fast, tense and
entertaining. In the best game thus far in their mostly tepid
series, the Devils won, 4-3, Friday night at Continental Arena to
take a 3-2 lead in the four-of-seven-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Randy McKay scored twice for the Devils, with both goals
assisted by Bobby Holik. The Devils, who were eliminated in the
first round last season by Ottawa, can clinch the series on Sunday
in Pittsburgh. The status of Jaromir Jagr, the Penguins' captain
and superstar who missed his fourth consecutive game with a groin
injury, is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``We skated and we kept taking the body,'' McKay said. ``We set
the tempo last game, and we continued. We forced them to force
pucks over, and we played hard. We're playing with a lot of
aggressiveness. We're not dipsy-doodlers.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils had taken a 2-0 lead on a power-play goal by Scott
Stevens in the first period and an even-strength goal by McKay in
the second. But Pittsburgh tied the game before the second
intermission when Kevin Hatcher and Aleksei Kovalev both scored at
even strength, 13 seconds apart.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils took a 3-2 lead at 1 minute 42 seconds of the third
period on an even-strength goal by Petr Sykora, who carried the
puck up ice, broke through the Pittsburgh defense, left it for
Patrik Elias and worked free near the crease in time to put Elias'
rebound past goalie Tom Barrasso. It was Sykora's third goal of the
series. McKay made it 4-2 at 14:04 by turning in Holik's pass from
close range.
</P>
<P>
   With 1:41 remaining, the Penguins went on the power play and got
a second extra skater when they pulled Barrasso. They cut the lead
to 4-3 at 19:13 on a goal by Kip Miller, set up by Kovalev, who
starred in Jagr's absence. Although they kept the extra skater on
ice for the remaining 47 seconds, the Penguins could not get one
more goal, even after Sykora took a double minor for high-sticking
with 5.7 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens gave the Devils a 1-0 lead at 16:12 of the first period
on the power play. He snapped a shot past Barrasso from the slot
after he took Lyle Odelein's pass in the neutral zone, cut from the
left to the middle and darted into empty space among Penguins
checkers.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end, the Penguins tried to distract Devils goalie
Martin Brodeur. Aleksei Morozov kicked him, skate to skate, and
later, Matthew Barnaby slashed Brodeur's glove after a save, and
Brodeur slashed back. Each got minors. The pace of this one was
much brisker than previous games.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils seemed in control of the game when they took a 2-0
lead at 11:47 of the second period on a goal by McKay, who knocked
in Holik's rebound after Barrasso lost track of the puck. But
Kovalev, the former Ranger, sparked his team to two goals in 13
seconds to tie it. The first, at 16:08, was by Kevin Hatcher, who
turned in Kovalev's feed from the left-wing circle to the slot.
Then Kovalev beat Brodeur from the slot on his second of two whacks
at 16:21.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was scary to sit in the bench and see those two goals,''
Sykora said ``But it shows how strong a team we have because we
came back in the third. We had time to go to the locker room and
regroup. We all stayed positive. It was positive meeting.'' Jagr
did not skate with his teammates at morning practice and stayed for
treatment in the medical room. As he left the building later, he
said he did not know when he would be able to return.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like, if I did play, there is a chance _ 60 or 70
percent _ that I'll get injured again and make it worse,'' Jagr
said. ``Even if I would help the team by playing tonight, I
wouldn't be able to play in the second round. It wouldn't make
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Would he be able to play in Game 6 on Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I feel now, I'm going to say no,'' Jagr said, ``but
everything can change. I thought I would be able to play today.
Obviously, it's changed. I'm not going to tell you definitely no.
But if I feel the way I feel now, I'm not going to play.''
</P>
<P>
   SLAP SHOTS
</P>
<P>
   MATTHEW BARNABY of Pittsburgh, who almost started a pre-game
brawl on Tuesday, antagonized the Devils fans by shooting a puck
into the home net at the end of warm-ups.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
