<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 01:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0450 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BLEWSTER-GAF-AZR &LR;      05-01 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BLEWSTER-GAF-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER'S COMMENTS ON RACE, ETHNICITY, CALLED EMBARRASSING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS MOESER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Slavery wasn't that bad; Native Americans aren't very smart.
Just another day at the office for Rep. Barbara Blewster.
</P>
<P>
   The Dewey Republican's latest gaffe came in a recent
conversation in the House with fellow Rep. Leah Landrum, D-Phoenix,
one of two elected African-Americans in the Arizona Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Landrum says she was offended by Blewster's remarks but not
surprised. This, after all, is the woman who earlier this year
compared homosexuality to ``bestiality, human sacrifice and
cannibalism'' and told another colleague she didn't look Jewish
because she doesn't have a hooked nose.
</P>
<P>
   Those comments have drawn notice around the nation, including
jokes on Howard Stern's radio show.
</P>
<P>
   And the hits just keep coming.
</P>
<P>
   Landrum objected to what she called Blewster's ``rude,
unnecessary'' comments on Native Americans and the history of
slavery in America.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, Landrum said, Blewster criticized Native
Americans, saying ``they were not smart enough to do what they need
to do to get ahead, and that even African-Americans are more
advanced than Native Americans, smarter (than Native Americans).''
</P>
<P>
   Blewster did not return calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   Blewster, who represents the towns of Prescott, Prescott Valley,
Bullhead City and Lake Havasu City, didn't stop there, Landrum
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Her comments had to do with Native Americans today and how
they're not as smart as what they should be,'' Landrum said. ``And
that slavery wasn't that bad, and not that many people lost their
lives. And after the Emancipation Proclamation, everything was
flowery and great.''
</P>
<P>
   Blewster, who is a member of the John Birch Society, is
beginning to attract attention back home, and some of her comments
are drawing fire.
</P>
<P>
   David Spence, a former Yavapai County GOP chairman who was one
of three Republicans who ran against Blewster in 1998, called
Blewster's comments ``embarrassing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's put it this way: She was elected by a populace who was
not aware of what she really stood for,'' Spence said. ``The types
of things Barbara is saying down there she was saying at town
halls, but not many voters were there, so no one heard it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spence said he was particularly offended by Blewster's comment
to Rep. Barbara Leff, R-Paradise Valley, that she didn't look
Jewish because she didn't have a hooked nose. He's vowed to stop
sending money to the Yavapai County GOP until Blewster is gone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, she's not just saying it. She believes it,''
Spence said.
</P>
<P>
   Former Rep. Sue Lynch, a Prescott Republican whom Blewster
replaced, called Blewster's statements ``outrageous.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people are starting to say she's like Ev Mecham,'' Lynch
said.
</P>
<P>
   Landrum said Blewster made the comments during a conversation on
a program that provides breakfasts at public schools. Blewster was
arguing that the program should be eliminated because parents
should spend more time with their children.
</P>
<P>
   Landrum said she told Blewster that some parents can't afford
food to feed their children and that the program provided meals to
kids who otherwise would have nothing to eat in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Blewster said there was always a way to put food on the table
and used American pioneers as an example. Landrum said she pointed
out that the pioneers often had help from Native Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Blewster then apparently implied that it was the pioneers who
made America great. Landrum responded that many people contributed
to the the growth of the United States, including slaves.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people who built this country. It wasn't
just one person that did all the work,'' Landrum recalls telling
Blewster.
</P>
<P>
   That led to a discussion of the economic situation of some
Native Americans and former slaves. Blewster argued that Native
Americans should pull themselves out of poverty today, just as some
Blacks did after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   Blewster said, ``Even during the slavery days, that Booker T.
Washington pulled himself by his bootstraps. And if he could do it,
everybody could do it. Even after the Emancipation Proclamation,
people made it. No one was starving, no one was dying.''
</P>
<P>
   Landrum said she told Blewster that 6 million Africans died in
passage on slave ships, a point Blewster denied. Blewster argued
there weren't 6 million people in Africa at the time, Landrum said.
</P>
<P>
   Some researchers, including Basil Davidson in his book, ``The
African Slave Trade,'' estimate that 6 million to 16 million
Africans died on slave ships before they ever landed in the
Americas over nearly 300 years of slave-trading.
</P>
<P>
   Landrum, who was the victim of a racially motivated attack in
1991 in Tempe, said the nature of Blewster's remarks hit her Friday
as she watched the highlights of a funeral for Isaiah Shoels, an
African-American student who was killed in the Columbine High
School shootings in Littleton, Colo..
</P>
<P>
   Witnesses said Shoels was killed because he was Black and
because he was an athlete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things haven't changed the way they need to be,'' she said.
``It's still an issue. It needs to be addressed. It affects our
children all the time. It affects us all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Landrum said her conversation with Blewster was friendly. But
she cut it off when she realized she wasn't convincing her
colleague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried my best to let her know, but I realized I wasn't
getting anywhere with this, and I told her, `This is one we really
can't discuss. You have your feelings on this, and I have my
facts,' '' Landrum said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't always surprise me when people have certain
mind-sets. It bothers me, it disturbs me, but it's no surprise. And
that's really sad.'' &QL; 
Chris Moeser can be reached at (602) 444-8069 or at
chris.moeser &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
