<HEADER>
A0451 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      05-01 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELIGION COLUMN: A SURVEY'S SURPRISING RESULTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Pie in the sky bye-and-bye'' was the mocking refrain of
political revolutionaries who accused religion of pacifying the
poor with heavenly hopes instead of helping them with earthly
goods. Yet compassion toward the poor, with here-and-now almsgiving
as part of it, has been part of every major religious tradition. So
it is not surprising that three sociologists recently set out to
answer these questions:
</P>
<P>
   Does religion really matter when it comes to giving money to
help the poor? Are the Christian groups that are generally
associated with concern for the poor, namely, serious Roman
Catholics and liberal Protestants, the most generous in aiding the
poor? Do the giving habits of political and theologically
conservative Christians, especially those influenced by the
religious right, show an anti-poor sentiment?
</P>
<P>
   Mark D. Regnerus, Christian Smith and David Sikkink, all
associated with the sociology department of the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill, re-examined data gathered in the 1996
Religious Identity and Influence Survey that had been financed by
the Pew Charitable Trusts. Among questions on ideas about morality,
gender, education and civic activities, this national telephone
survey asked respondents how much of their time or money they had
spent in various social and political activities: ``a lot,''
``some'' or ``none.'' One such activity was giving money to
organizations that helped ``the poor and needy.''
</P>
<P>
   Writing in last September's issue of the Journal for the
Scientific Study of Religion, the sociologists make the data jump
through all the usual hoops: race, gender, education, age, income,
recent financial change, size of family, size of community,
political affiliation. To the latter they add whether respondents
had relied on the Christian Coalition or similar organizations in
deciding how to vote.
</P>
<P>
   The sociologists also analyzed the data according to church
attendance and how important respondents said religion was in their
lives. Respondents were divided into different religious
categories: fundamentalist, evangelical, mainline Protestant,
liberal Protestant, low-attendance Protestant, high- and
low-attendance Catholic, other religious (Jews, Hindus, Mormons,
Jehovah's Witnesses and similar groups whose respondents in the
sample were too few to analyze separately), and, finally,
nonreligious.
</P>
<P>
   And what did they find?
</P>
<P>
   First, religion apparently matters. The nonreligious were far
less likely to report giving ``a lot'' to organizations aiding the
poor than all the religious groups except low-attendance Catholics.
Control for demographic factors, and the nonreligious are
definitely at the bottom of the giving hierarchy.
</P>
<P>
   The degree of religiosity apparently matters, too. The more
actively or intensely religious the respondents, the more generous
they were apt to be, regardless of their religious affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   Second, ``other religious,'' the residual category containing
Jews, Hindus and similar groups, were considerably more likely to
give than even the highest of the major Christian categories. Also,
nonwhites and women reported giving ``a lot'' more often than
whites and men, and college graduates a little more often than
those without degrees. Democrats and Republicans finished nearly in
a dead heat, with Republicans winning by a nose.
</P>
<P>
   Third, liberal Protestants and practicing Catholics do not
especially stand out in their generosity to the poor. By
comparison, evangelical Protestants appear mildly more generous.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, there is no evidence of an anti-poor mentality, at least
as measured by reported giving, among political and theological
conservatives. ``The conventional wisdom regarding the hostility of
politically and theologically conservative Christians toward the
poor appears incorrect, at least on this count,'' the authors
write.
</P>
<P>
   What surprised them even more, however, was that those who
looked to religious-right organizations like the Christian
Coalition for guidance in voting were more likely to report
``significant `pro-poor' giving habits.'' They were strikingly
likely to report giving ``a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The limits of this analysis do not escape the authors. From the
standpoint of the poor, attitudes toward government assistance, tax
relief and health care, or attitudes toward unemployment, economic
growth and unionization, may have far greater consequences for
well-being than personal charity.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the inevitable shortcomings of survey data. What
definitions exist in the respondents' mind of organizations that
help ``the poor and needy''? What do they have in mind by giving
``a lot''? The random differences can be assumed to cancel one
another out. But what if liberal Protestants or, for that matter,
college-educated evangelicals consistently had a more stringent
notion of what constitutes ``a lot''? Systematic differences among
religious, political or demographic categories in understanding
those questions would skew the results.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, public debate about justice for the poor often
slides from what means will best accomplish what goals to ad
hominem judgments about the motives and attitudes of the debaters.
Whether politically and theologically conservative Christians are
right in their prescriptions for relieving poverty is a question
distinct from whether they are anti-poor, a la Ebenezer Scrooge, in
their personal outlook _ and, as with the transformed Scrooge,
giving habits are a reasonable test of the latter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fundamentally,'' the three sociologists say in their
discipline's understated style, ``making the jump from economic
conservatism to declaring persons to be hostile toward the poor
seems unwarranted, according to our research results.''
</P>
</TEXT>
