<HEADER>
A0453 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-THREA-AZR &LR;      05-01 1405
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-THREA-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOMB SCARES ACROSS METRO PHOENIX, BUT NONE FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFFRY NELSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bomb scares, school evacuations and increased police presence
swept across Valley schools on Friday, fueled by hoaxes, rumors,
anxiety and hype in the wake of the Colorado school shootings.
</P>
<P>
   At Peoria High School, 85 percent of the students stayed away.
In Chandler, at least four schools were evacuated. In New River,
bomb sniffing dogs patroled the halls.
</P>
<P>
   And, by the end of the school day, nothing had happened, to the
relief of parents, students, police and school officials. However,
police did arrest one Chandler middle school student for bomb
threats.
</P>
<P>
   Some blamed the hysteria on irresponsible students, some blamed
irresponsible parents. Many blamed irresponsible media.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been blown out of proportion by you guys,'' said Richard
Rivas, a Peoria parent who was dropping off his son at school
Friday. ``I don't mean any disrespect but the media has kept this
thing going.''
</P>
<P>
   At least 10 major school districts reported threats of violence
in the form of bomb scares, Internet messages, drawings and
conversations that sent officials into a state of alert Friday.
Similar incidents were reported across the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Peoria Police spokesman Sgt. Shawn Gormley said his department
has received a year's worth of bomb threats in less than a week.
Other law enforcement agencies in the Valley reported similar
increases.
</P>
<P>
   The threatened violence came just a week after the shooting
rampage in Littleton, Colo., that left 15 dead. Friday also was the
anniversary of Hitler's death. The combination kept many students
away from schools.
</P>
<P>
   Despite assurances by police that Peoria High School wouldn't
come under fire Friday, about 1,700 students _ 85 percent of the
students _ skipped school.
</P>
<P>
   One of them was Fernando Fiferoa, who shook his head as he
watched a squad of Peoria Police bike officers and a team of
security guards patrol the entrances to his school Friday as if
guarding a top-secret military installation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems kind of silly. I mean, nothing's going to happen,''
Fiferoa, a junior at Peoria High School, said. ``Everyone's staying
home.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many Valley teens, the 18-year-old took advantage of rumors
of pending doom hanging over schools on Friday. He skipped classes
to hang out with friends.
</P>
<P>
   Peoria High's concern began last weekend when a message sent out
over the Internet warned students not to attend that school on
Friday because there would be gunfire.
</P>
<P>
   Police traced the message to a 17-year-old Peoria boy, who,
police say, had no intention nor ability to carry out the threats.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a hoax, law enforcement and school officials all
across the Valley are taking each warning seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are all sitting up a little straighter, our vision sharper
and our hearing's a little better,'' said Jim Cummings, a spokesman
for Phoenix Union High School District.
</P>
<P>
   Cummings said the district has investigated rumors of students
bringing guns to campus, students sporting black trench coats, a
riot and bomb threats, but all were false reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``They (students) are playing the media like a fiddle because
they know it will work up the interest and maybe they'll send a
live truck and maybe they'll let school out,'' Cummings said.
</P>
<P>
   But to ensure safety, the district will continue to investigate
each report, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In New River, sheriff's deputies showed up in force at Desert
Mountain Middle School looking for weapons and using dogs to check
for bombs as students arrived for classes Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing was found, but deputies spent the day patroling the
hallways, said Sgt. Dave Trombi, a spokesman for the Maricopa
County Sheriff's Office.
</P>
<P>
   The action was sparked by an incident in which a 15-year-old
Desert Mountain student was taken into custody Thursday for
allegedly bringing an explosive device to school.
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Allen, a sheriff's spokeswoman, said deputies received
secondary information that a group of students planned to bomb the
school.
</P>
<P>
   The father of the Desert Mountain student said deputies and
school officials horribly overreacted in handling the matter. He
said there was no intent by his son to cause harm.
</P>
<P>
   In Apache Junction, bomb threats have become a daily occurrence.
There have been four in four days, most of them called in less than
half an hour before schools let out, said Carol Shepherd, district
spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   A letter was sent home to parents on Thursday, asking them to
talk to their children about the consequences of such threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's criminal that someone would use such a severe
tragedy as Littleton to tag on to,'' Shepherd said.
</P>
<P>
   But police responded to two bomb threats in the Scottsdale
Unified District on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Police said a male caller used a pay phone about 7:30 a.m. to
call in a bomb threat at Supai Middle School, 6720 E. Continental
Drive. Police and Rural/Metro responded but did not find a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The second bomb threat was targeted at Desert Canyon Middle
School, 10203 E. McDowell Mountain Ranch Road. The school received
information Friday morning through a student who read about a bomb
threat on the Internet. It later was determined that the
information was three days old and school was not evacuated.
</P>
<P>
   At Kyrene Aprende Middle School in Chandler, however, hundreds
of students were evacuated to a nearby park Friday morning after
school officials found a note threatening a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took this one seriously and took the kids outside,'' said
Superintendent Brad Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Three children were being questioned about the note Friday
afternoon, and police were searching for a fourth student. It was
unclear whether an arrest would be made.
</P>
<P>
   Kyrene de las Brisas Elementary School, next door to Aprende,
also kept kids outside as police searched the school.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Ken Phillips of Chandler Police Department said Hamilton
and Chandler high schools also were evacuated because of threats.
</P>
<P>
   Heightened security was present at Poston Junior High School in
Mesa after a note appeared on a bathroom mirror announcing a bomb
would detonate at 2 p.m. Friday. A bomb search was conducted but
none was found.
</P>
<P>
   Tension also ran high at Rhodes Junior High. A message on the
Internet stated someone at the school ``would die today,'' said
Judi Willis, Mesa Public Schools spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   At the five Mesa high schools, some students didn't attend
classes as the rumors continued to fly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going in circles and swirling,'' Willis said. ``We need
to find the perpetrator (of the threats) whether it's real or fake
and treat them severely. I'm afraid we have a lot of copycat
hysteria.''
</P>
<P>
   Many students stayed home Friday based on rumor alone.
</P>
<P>
   At Horizon High School in the Paradise Valley district, 70
percent of the 2,600 students didn't show up for classes, although
a district administrator refused to blame the high absenteeism
entirely on rumors of bomb threats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horizon had an early dismissal today (Friday) that was planned
weeks ago,'' said Toby Spessard, an assistant superintendent in the
district. ``It could have been senior `ditch day,' too, obviously a
non-sanctioned event.''
</P>
<P>
   At Horizon, a Phoenix police officer was placed on campus this
week after someone made fliers threatening a massacre similar to
the one in Colorado, and three teachers were designated as hall and
parking lot monitors.
</P>
<P>
   Across town at Desert Vista High School in Ahwatukee Foothills,
more than 50 percent of the student body of more than 2,000 was
absent Friday, despite the school not documenting any threats.
</P>
<P>
   Parents also were pulling their students out of Tempe elementary
schools, said Tempe District spokeswoman Kathy Bareiss.
</P>
<P>
   School officials said media coverage contributed to the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of it is the media is making it out of control,'' said
Barrett, who asked that his schools' threats not be reported to cut
down on copy cat threats. ``There's an element of kids that loves
the attention, loves the excitement that's going to come with
it.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Reporters Christina Leonard, Betty Reid, Melissa Jones, Kelly
Pearce, Diana Balazs and Brent Whiting contributed to this story.
Jeffry Nelson can be reached at (602)444-7117 or at
jeffry.nelson(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
