<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN FORCES KOSOVO DEBATE IN SENATE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ U.S. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has succeeded in
forcing a Senate debate on Monday over his politically explosive
``win at all costs'' Kosovo position.
</P>
<P>
   It was this very debate that leaders of both parties had hoped
to avoid.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said Friday that McCain used a parliamentary procedure
under the War Powers Act of 1973 to compel the Senate to take up
his resolution, which authorizes ``the use of all necessary
force,'' including ground troops, in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   While he has bucked the GOP leadership before, McCain has
rarely, if ever, been so alone on a measure of such importance to
the nation and to his own political aspirations.
</P>
<P>
   Lacking the support of either party's leadership, McCain, a
former naval aviator running for president in 2000, is flying the
equivalent of a political solo mission.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's perfect for him. It's the old profile in courage,''
said Chris Madison, spokesman for Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del., who
co-sponsored the resolution with McCain but expects it to be
tabled, or killed, after Monday's debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``He (McCain) is going against his party, he's going against
what's popular. That's how you distinguish yourself in the middle
of a (presidential) campaign,'' Madison said.
</P>
<P>
   Many of McCain's fellow Republicans oppose the resolution
because they are reluctant to hand President Clinton such
open-ended authority.
</P>
<P>
   Even Senate Democrats who might have been expected to back a
commander in chief of their party are publicly wondering whether
the measure's timing is premature.
</P>
<P>
   The air campaign needs more ``time to function, time to work,''
Minority Leader Tom Daschle, D-S.D., told reporters Friday. ``I
believe that it is working.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain received no guarantee from Senate leaders that the debate
would last long or that his measure would receive an up-or-down
vote on its merits.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a bipartisan group of 17 House members led by Rep.
Tom Campbell, R-Calif., filed a lawsuit against Clinton in U.S.
District Court. They assert that the air campaign violates the War
Powers Act and want a ruling to force Clinton to withdraw U.S.
forces from the region or seek a declaration of war from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said the War Powers Act, which mandates a
congressional role when U.S. forces are sent to war, has been
``routinely violated'' by Democratic and Republican administrations
and congresses alike, and that the law needs to be clarified. But
McCain also says that it is up to the president to lead and that
you can't have ``535 commanders in chief,'' a reference to the
members of Congress.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and Biden came up with the resolution during a
conversation after appearing on TV together several weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We agreed . . . that the president of the United States, if he
were to decide to use ground troops, would need congressional
authorization,'' Biden said in a recent speech. He and McCain also
decided that the president ``should never take anything off the
table once we are in a war,'' Biden said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As almost anyone with any war experience knows, you're never
supposed to show the enemy what you won't do to win,'' McCain said
in an April 13 speech in which he counseled against ``silence and
equivocation'' from Congress.
</P>
<P>
   However, even Biden is having some doubts about the strategy of
bringing the resolution to the Senate floor Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Biden's view all along was, `Let's not bring it up right away,
because it probably doesn't have the votes,' '' Madison said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Senate aides, McCain won a ruling this week from
the Senate parliamentarian to compel Senate action under the War
Powers Act.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, in what I view as a serious abrogation of the
Congress' constitutional responsibility and moral obligations, both
the Democratic and Republican leadership intend to limit debate to
little more than four hours,'' McCain said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``A debate on such a momentous decision should not be given such
short shrift by the leadership. I continue to ask that the time for
debate be extended until at least Tuesday afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House had no comment on McCain's measure. Queries were
referred to two national security press officers, who did not
return telephone calls Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has said that he won't allow presidential politics to
influence his Kosovo positions and that he is basing his decisions
on conscience and his own experience.
</P>
<P>
   Madison, Biden's spokesman, predicted that the Senate will table
the measure, effectively evading responsibility. Tabling a bill
cuts off consideration but is technically not the same as defeating
it.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's edict to ``use whatever force necessary'' runs contrary
to the sentiment of a deadlocked House, which voted Wednesday to
deny support for the air campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called for Americans to unite behind the war
effort. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
