<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-WHITESOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS PULL OUT VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ An eighth-inning rally helped the Anaheim
Angels pull out a 3-1 win Friday night over the Chicago White Sox
before 38,053 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Tied at one entering the bottom half of the inning, the Angels
seemed to come together after Mo Vaughn was hit by a pitch with two
runners on and no one out on the first pitch by reliever Bill
Simas.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Tim Salmon, hit a sacrifice fly to bring home
Orlando Palmeiro for the go-ahead run. With Troy Glaus at the
plate, Randy Velarde stole third. White Sox catcher Brook Fordyce
overthrew on the play and Velarde came home.
</P>
<P>
   The other Angels run was on a Garret Anderson solo home run in
the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleballer Steve Sparks went 72/3 innings, the longest outing
by an Angel starter yet this season. Mark Petkovsek (2-1) appeared
in relief and got the win, striking out Jeff Abbott to escape a
two-on threat in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Percival got three outs for his fourth save.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks gave up just five hits, while striking out four and
walking five. He threw 133 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox starter Jaime Navarro (1-2) took the loss. Navarro
walked Palmeiro and Velarde, the first two batters he faced in the
eighth. He was pulled and replaced by Simas, who hit Vaughn in the
chest with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago scored first when former Dodger Paul Konerko, hitting
just .197 coming into the game, singled off Sparks with no outs in
the fourth to drive in Magglio Ordonez. As the White Sox leadoff
hitter in the fourth, Ordonez reached on a single, then stole
second before scoring. Sparks worked himself out of the inning by
getting the next three batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Sparks seemed sharp. The first two batters he faced
went down easily. Things got rockier though after he walked Frank
Thomas and gave up a single to Ordonez. Luckily, Greg Norton flied
out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Angel half of the inning was hardly more productive. With
one out Randy Velarde went the opposite way and doubled down the
right field line.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn advanced him to third with a groundout. Salmon followed
that with a powerful shot to left, but it was caught at the warning
track by Abbot.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' half of the second inning mirrored the first. Darin
Erstad reached on a double off the scoreboard in right center, but
his teammates were unable to advance him.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim threatened again in the fourth. Vaughn led off with a
sharp single to left. Then Salmon reached on a fielder's choice
that saw Vaughn cut down at second. Erstad and Glaus ended the
inning for the Angels two outs.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to brighten in the fifth. Anderson's 387-foot lead
off homer on a 2-0 pitch evened the game at one. Later in the
inning, Orlando Palmeiro got to first on a walk, but he was
stranded there when Velarde flied out.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, the Angels were back to stranding runners. With
one out, Salmon got aboard on a double to left. Erstad hit into a
fielder's choice sending Salmon to third. Glaus, the next batter,
flied out to center ending the inning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 0127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
