<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0460 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-MARLINS-HN     05-01 0878
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-MARLINS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOSEPH DUARTE  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
MIAMI _ Jeff Bagwell's first home run at Pro Player Stadium was a
memorable one. It even had injured teammate Moises Alou grinning
after the game.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bagwell followed Derek Bell's lead as the two hit consecutive
upper-deck home runs in the seventh inning Friday night, and Sean
Bergman pitched the Astros' first complete game of the season in an
8-1 rout of the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Larry Dierker has pretty much seen it all in 3{ decades
in the baseball business. Or so he thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why you come to the ballpark. It doesn't matter what
two teams are playing; you never know when you're going to see
something amazing,'' Dierker said. ``Unbelievable. Nobody could
even remember even seeing two balls into the upper deck in the same
game _ let alone back-to-back.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell's home run traveled an estimated 417 feet and brought the
entire Astros bench to the steps of the dugout for a better view.
</P>
<P>
   After Bagwell's shot traveled 450 feet, most of his teammates
and the 19,116 in attendance were in disbelief. Both home runs were
to left field and came off Brian Edmondson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty good hitting ballpark,'' said Bagwell, who had
failed to homer in 27 previous games and 96 at-bats at the stadium.
``I can hit a ball that far every once in a while. It had been
awhile since I've done it.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time in three games Bell and Bagwell have
homered back-to-back. And it was the first time consecutive
upper-deck homers have been hit in the seven years the Marlins have
played at Pro Player.
</P>
<P>
   It all came in the unlikeliest venue for the Astros, who made
themselves comfortable with a home-cooked fish fry.
</P>
<P>
   Bergman provided the main course with his best outing of the
season, shutting down the Marlins after the first inning, and the
Astros' offense provided the trimmings with seven runs during a
three-inning stretch in the middle of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We haven't played well here at all (11-20 all-time),'' Dierker
said. ``I don't consider winning one game easily an end to the
problems we've had here. If we win two out of three this series,
that will be a pretty good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hidalgo also homered, and Paul Bako, filling in for
Mitch Meluskey, had three hits and two RBIs.
</P>
<P>
   That was far more support than Bergman needed.
</P>
<P>
   After giving up four straight one-out singles in the first
inning _ an out at the plate helped limit the damage _ Bergman
turned stingy with a mixture of sinkers and sliders. He closed with
eight shutout innings for his first complete game since last June
3.
</P>
<P>
   ``He went right after them with his best stuff,'' Bako said.
``He challenged them with his sinker. If it's not staying straight,
it's a tough pitch to hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Dierker: ``More than anything, he survived the early
innings when they were getting the hits, then he started to get
stronger as the game went on.''
</P>
<P>
   Bergman (1-1) allowed nine singles, struck out five and walked
none. He faced 26 batters after the first inning, two more than the
minimum.
</P>
<P>
   For Bergman, his fourth career complete game was redemption for
a frustrating start five days earlier in Cincinnati, when he
allowed five runs, six hits and four walks in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very frustrated about how I pitched my last time out,''
Bergman said. ``I wanted to go out there today and have a good
game.''
</P>
<P>
   He was the beneficiary of several ground-ball outs that kept his
pitch count low. He needed just 99 pitches, one-fourth of those
during the first inning, and was aided by three double plays.
</P>
<P>
   When he walked into the dugout after the eighth inning, Dierker
approached and asked if Bergman wanted to stay in the game. Bergman
said yes and retired the Marlins 1-2-3 in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Down 1-0, the Astros tied the game on Hidalgo's fifth home run
of the season, off Brian Meadows in the second inning. Craig
Biggio's RBI single in the fifth put the Astros ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Then came four more runs in the sixth, three on one play, as the
Astros took command. Meadows (3-2), who had five strikeouts through
five innings, did the damage to himself, walking three Astros to
load the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Bako, who was hitting .191 for Class AAA New Orleans before he
was recalled Monday, had a two-run single, and Bill Spiers also
scored on the play when cutoff man Kevin Orie threw badly to third
base.
</P>
<P>
   Bako scored one pitch later when Meadows balked.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell and Bell continued a trend for the Astros with the
club's fifth back-to-back home-run performance _ in only 22 games _
tying the most in a season this decade.
</P>
<P>
   They also hit back-to-back home runs on five occasions during
the 1994, 1995 and 1998 seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Bagwell has hit six of his seven homers in the past 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   That's more than enough for Florida manager John Boles, who
first encountered the Astros' potent lineup during the second half
of 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're loaded,'' Boles said. ``The first three guys in their
lineup are pretty imposing and have been for a long time. What do
they call them, the Killer B's? I hate all three of them, but I
would like to have them. They're even better three years later.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 0135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
