<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 01:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0461 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      05-01 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-LOPEZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
John P.Lopez
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE WOODLANDS _ David Duval came knocking, but it didn't look like
anyone was home.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Dick and Jo Kidwell were home. They were just relaxing
in their den _ feet propped, faces windblown, trying to rest, doze
and recover from a long day of watching the Shell Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``Been out there all day,'' Dick Kidwell would say later. ``I
had no idea what was going on.''
</P>
<P>
   They should have opened the blinds.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Duval seemed ready to make a big run on the second day
of the SHO, the kind of awe-inspiring sweep through the back nine
that led him to the tournament championship a year ago, the
much-anticipated friendly course atmosphere treated Duval like it
did everyone on this day.
</P>
<P>
   Mysteriously. Mercilessly.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who was trying to figure out the confusing conditions on
virtually every shot Friday, was one stroke behind the leaders
heading to the 15th when he smacked his driver well to the left.
</P>
<P>
   It went miles left, seemingly. It went way, way left _ over the
fairway, over the left rough, over the river and through the woods,
over the out-of-bounds stakes until finally settling into the
Kidwells' back yard.
</P>
<P>
   And as the Kidwells relaxed, what ensued was a mad rush of about
500 or more fans, scurrying across the Kidwells' yard, squashing
their St. Augustine, spilling beer and tipping over potted plants.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd gathered around Duval's golf ball like it was a
campfire, moving ever closer, peeking between elbows and knees
trying to catch a glimpse of the ball. It was like a golfing
equivalent to a stampede, or a mosh pit at a Goo Goo Dolls concert.
</P>
<P>
   Several among the throng marveled at how Duval had just hit a
shot like we all have on some ill-fated Sunday afternoon escapade.
Some of them stood on the Kidwells' patio furniture trying to get a
better look at Duval's troubles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was watching it on TV,'' Dick Kidwell said. ``I had no idea
he was in our back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's where we put in the metaphor stuff:
</P>
<P>
   They all came a-knockin' Friday afternoon. Several of the best
golfers in the world came _ Duval, Vijay Singh, Tom Kite, Jeff
Maggert. But what they thought would be there in the second round
of the SHO wasn't home.
</P>
<P>
   It was supposed to be an easy layout, but it wasn't. It was
supposed to be like throwing yard darts at the TPC greens, but it
wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   The rough had been trimmed. The greens had been softened. The
players had been confident that scores would drop.
</P>
<P>
   But they were all windblown expectations, worn out by the end of
the day like the Kidwells, the greens, Duval and all those who
previously thought they would shoot record-setting scores at the
kinder, gentler TPC course.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was tough,'' said Duval, whose double bogey on No. 15 led
to a 5-under 139 total, good enough for a four-way tie for fourth.
``It was pretty obvious on the putting green that it was going to
be hard today.''
</P>
<P>
   It was. All the big hitters had trouble gauging the winds and
greens that dried quickly and became faster almost by the moment
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got to the point that the ball just wouldn't stop,'' said
Joey Sindelar, who still managed to share the second-round lead
with Hal Sutton at 8-under. ``We knew off the bat that we were in
for it.''
</P>
<P>
   And they were. Early in the day, John Daly struck a mammoth
drive on the par-5 13th but still decided to lay up after much
deliberation about the winds. Barely half a dozen players tried to
reach the 13th in two, with mixed results.
</P>
<P>
   Duval, who began his memorable charge to the 1998 title with an
eagle on No. 13, also laid up there Friday. And only moments after
Duval went into the Kidwells' back yard on No. 15, D.A. Weibring
tried to fight the wind with his approach over the water on No. 17.
He bounced it high off the bulkhead and into the wet stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Next up was Maggert, hanging on at 1-over for the day as the
shadows grew, trying to pull out another birdie. He bounced his
approach short and right and landed it only inches in front of the
bulkhead as the crowd gasped.
</P>
<P>
   They all gasped on this day. It was supposed to be easy, but it
wasn't. The red numbers were supposed to be bleeding off the leader
board, but the best anyone could muster was a pedestrian (for the
PGA, anyway) 68.
</P>
<P>
   The qualifying score for making it to the final two rounds was
supposed to be 1 under par, or maybe even 2-under. But it was
1-over.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was swirling out there,'' said Jeff Gallagher, who stands
one behind the leaders at 7-under. ``A lot of times, you'd think
you were into the wind but you'd be downwind. You definitely found
yourself playing on the defensive out there once in a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, they all found themselves in the water, or in the
rough, or maybe even in someone's back yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough day,'' Sindelar said. ``And if they don't water the
greens (Friday night), it's going to be tougher on Saturday.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
