<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PHILLIES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT PHILLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson wanted
to defy baseball logic. Closer Jeff Shaw was all for it.
</P>
<P>
   And in exchange for tempting fate, the Dodgers have a
season-long four-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   After putting the potential winning run on base with an
intentional walk _ a baseball no-no _ Shaw struck out Ron Gant in
the bottom of the ninth to preserve the Dodgers' 4-3 win over the
Phillies on Friday at Veterans Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers' fourth straight road win is their longest such
streak away from Chavez Ravine since they won five straight on the
road in August 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``My brain was telling me one thing and my emotions were telling
me another thing,'' Johnson said. ``You usually don't put the
winning run on. My brain won out _ but my brain also has too many
memories of (Gant coming through).''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson remembers Gant from their days together in Cincinnati.
These are different days. Gant fights himself at the plate and was
hitting .132 and has one hit in 13 at-bats with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   So when the Phillies pulled to within 4-3 on Scott Rolen's
two-run, two-out double off Shaw, Johnson strolled to the mound. He
proposed walking lefty Rico Brogna so the right-handed Shaw could
face the righty Gant.
</P>
<P>
   There was no debate.
</P>
<P>
   Gant struck out on three pitches. Shaw recorded his seventh
save.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's swinging at a lot of bad pitches right now,'' Shaw said.
``Once I got ahead of him I expanded the strike zone. Any time
you're in a ballgame and you have a guy struggling, you go after
him.''
</P>
<P>
   The tense moments of what was nearly Shaw's first blown save
didn't overshadow left-hander Carlos Perez's outing. In dire need
of a quality start, Perez (1-3) allowed one run in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   It was equally important Johnson showed confidence in Perez to
pitch past the sixth inning. Perez's first two starts ended with
seventh-inning collapses in which he allowed four runs and took the
loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking before getting to the mound what happened to my
first two starts,'' Perez said. ``I knew this time nothing was
going to happen, nothing was going to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Add a six-run, 32/3-inning fiasco that caused Johnson to skip
his spot in the rotation a week ago, Perez needed something good to
happen. Unlike his other outings, Perez was more successful deeper
in the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Phillies had runners in scoring position in each of the
first five innings but could only muster a run on pitcher Paul
Byrd's second-inning single. Perez retired the last seven batters
he faced.
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed speeds all night and threw a fastball for strikes
when we needed it,'' Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley said of Perez.
``He set the offspeed up with his fastball instead of vice-versa.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers built a 3-1 lead in the fifth inning against Byrd
(2-2) when Adrian Beltre singled in a run, Hundley scored on a wild
pitch and Beltre was safe at home on a fielder's choice.
</P>
<P>
   But it was Perez's ability to get out of the bottom of the
inning that catapulted him through the next two. The Phillies
loaded the bases with two outs. Phillies catcher Mike Lieberthal, a
Westlake High graduate, lined a pitch just foul down the left-field
line before hitting a pop-up foul to first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Carlos, at times, looked like he got a little tentative out
there, but that was a big one for him,'' said Johnson, who two
weeks ago questioned himself after allowing Perez to start the
seventh inning in Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have helped him out in the seventh with (Alan) Mills
if I had to,'' Johnson said. ``I was having Mills go along with him
(in the bullpen). Hundley said he was still popping the ball. Our
bullpen is somewhat short so I needed to get a quality outing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
