</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BELTRE LIVING UP TO PROMISE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ Los Angeles Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone
saw Adrian Beltre play for a week last season and decided the club
didn't need another third baseman.
</P>
<P>
   A month into the season, the only reason Beltre isn't running
away with the Rookie of the Year race is the Dodgers rushed him
into 77 games last summer, ruining that chance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he's one of the premier young players in baseball.
Beltre, 21, went 2 for 4 with an RBI in the Dodgers' 4-3 win
against the Philadelphia Phillies on Friday. It raised his average
to .355, and before popping out in the sixth inning he had hits in
six straight at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say anything about this guy,'' said Dodgers
left-hander Carlos Perez, wishing not to jinx the success. ``He's
young and I'm happy for him to get one or two hits. If you start
talking about it...''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, who had a career-high four hits Thursday in Milwaukee,
said there's nothing special going on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm seeing the ball well and hitting the ball hard somewhere
each time,'' Beltre said. ``I've had good swings and I'm getting
good pitches to hit and just swinging at them.''
</P>
<P>
   Beltre is flourishing hitting deep in the order, batting either
seventh or eighth. Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said he's not
ready to move Beltre into another spot in the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna possible for Monday: Johnson said rehabbing right-hander
Antonio Osuna could rejoin the Dodgers on Monday in Montreal if he
experiences no pain or stiffness in his elbow today.
</P>
<P>
   Osuna, on the disabled list since April 21 (retroactive to April
18) was scheduled to pitch Friday for Single-A San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   ``(It's) another big test, and if he can pass that test we'll
have him Monday,'' Johnson said. ``I still feel a little short (in
the bullpen).''
</P>
<P>
   However, questions linger whether Osuna can pitch the rest of
the season with a bone spur in his elbow. It's going to cause
Johnson to use him in more of a long-relief role than with Alan
Mills in a dual set-up role.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I have to modify the way I use him, I will,'' Johnson said.
``If I have to use him for more innings and give him more rest,
I'll do it that way. I'll take him in any role.''
</P>
<P>
   Extra hitting time: More than four hours before the first pitch,
Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley was taking extra batting practice in
hopes of working himself out of his offensive funk.
</P>
<P>
   Hundley entered the series hitting .148 (8 for 54), but maybe
the extra work helped. He broke an 0 for 15 drought with a fifth
inning single and was 1 for 3 to raise his average to .158.
</P>
<P>
   Despite saying Hundley was 50 or 60 percent when the season
began, Johnson said he's not worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not hurting, so if he's not hurting he's going to get
going,'' Johnson said. ``When you're out for a year and you miss
spring training, what the (heck). He's not Ted Williams.''
</P>
<P>
   There's also the issue of stolen bases. The Phillies had two and
Hundley has thrown out two of 24. During the three-game series in
Milwaukee, Hundley's dad, Randy, a former big-league catcher,
worked with his son. Dodgers coach Rick Dempsey, a former catcher,
also worked with Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``His timing's not there, mechanics are not there,'' Johnson
said. ``With Randy, Demper (Dempsey) and Todd, they'll get it
right.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
