A0464 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN     05-01 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD JUST WANTS TO PLAY ANYWHERE IN LINEUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ As far as Darin Erstad is concerned it makes
no difference where he bats in the Anaheim Angels lineup as long as
he plays.
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Terry Collins bumped Erstad from the leadoff spot
to fifth in the batting order. The caveat is that Erstad, playing
in place of Mo Vaughn at first, will return to the top spot when
Vaughn, currently getting at-bats as the designated hitter, returns
to the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just do what I'm told. Play wherever,'' Erstad said.
``There's not much difference between leading off or batting fifth.
Unless there's runners on you get pitched to pretty much the same
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Big difference: Tim Salmon, a notoriously slow starter, had a
great night at the plate Thursday in the Angels' 17-1 destruction
of the Toronto Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   Salmon went 2 for 5, scored a run, hit a home run and had two
RBI. Collins said Salmon, plagued by injuries last season, has
picked up some slack for the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim's stepping up,'' Collins said. ``His history has been that
of a slow starter. But, when we needed him to pick it up, he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Being free of pain has helped, Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's in great shape he feels good and he's glad to be back out
there,'' Collins said.
</P>
<P>
   Greene's day: Todd Greene took on duties behind the plate Friday
because Collins is convinced Greene is uniquely qualified to handle
starter Steve Sparks' knuckleball.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came down to of the three guys we have on this staff, the
one guy who can handle the knuckleball is Todd Greene,'' Collins
said. ``If Steve Sparks throws a quality knuckleball, (most
catchers) aren't going to throw anybody out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's in the dirt or knuckling like crazy, you got to
concentrate too much on catching that thing and if you are worrying
about guys stealing, they are going to run,'' Collins added. ``It's
that simple.''
</P>
<P>
   Konerko update: It was about this time last season that Paul
Konerko was hailed as the Dodger of the future. In fact, Baseball
America named him the No. 1 prospect in the Dodger system.
</P>
<P>
   But the 1999 season finds the former Dodger wearing a Chicago
White Sox uniform. That's just fine with him, even if cold and
windy Chicago nights take some getting used to.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best thing about getting back is getting out of the cold
and getting into some good weather,'' Konerko said.
</P>
<P>
   Konerko also likes the fact he's playing for a young team that
so far is holding its own in the competitive AL. Central. Going
into Friday's game the White Sox were in second place, four games
behind the Cleveland Indians and two-and-a-half games in front of
Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, the losses we have it's just been other teams beating
us,'' Konerko said. ``We're not giving away games. As long as we
can do that we'll be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Although he's batting just .197, Konerko wants to be a part that
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a couple of us, myself included who haven't been
playing up to our potential,'' he said. ``If we do that it will
make it even better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
