<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0031 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 02:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0465 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JAZZ-ROCKETS-HNS &LR;      05-01 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JAZZ-ROCKETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JONATHAN FEIGEN  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The Rockets were exposed. That's what made it hurt so much more
than even the embarrassing losses to the Clippers and Mavericks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   They were ready. They played hard. And next to the Jazz, the
Rockets looked like, well, the Clippers and Mavericks of the world.
For that matter, given the events and losses of the past two weeks,
that might insult the Clippers and Mavs.
</P>
<P>
   The Jazz almost toyed with its past rivals, who only a year ago
ran almost neck-and-neck in their playoff series. But when Utah
pulled away for an easy 91-78 win Friday night at Compaq Center, in
its fifth game in six days, the Jazz sent the Rockets reeling in
ways even the humiliating losses to the NBA's lesser lights could
not.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to right themselves before the playoffs begin a week from
today, the Rockets stood next to a Western Conference contender and
came up short.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is going to get psychological; we just played
terrible,'' Rockets forward Charles Barkley said. ``Everybody has
to look themselves in the mirror and say, `I (stink).'
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very disappointed and frustrated right now.''
</P>
<P>
   The feeling was mutual enough for the Rockets to hold a
20-minute postgame meeting. They had fallen into a tie with the
Lakers in their race for the home-court advantage in the first
round of the playoffs, but the Lakers hold the tiebreaker. But more
than that, the Rockets saw how far they are from being ready to win
in the playoffs on any court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're ready right now,'' coach Rudy Tomjanovich
said. ``But if we make a commitment and stay together and have some
positive goals, we can do it. The only way out of this thing is
growing and getting closer together. It's never too late.''
</P>
<P>
   When Friday's game seemed to be getting close, the Rockets
rallied several times only to shut down with time running out. The
Rockets had come back from as much as 15 down to within five
heading into the fourth quarter.
</P>
<P>
   They hardly had dominated that run back into the game, but they
scored 14 points in five minutes to end the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Scottie Pippen had taken a defensive rebound the length of the
court to set up Sam Mack for a 3-pointer, then drove from one board
to the other for a tough layup.
</P>
<P>
   But after putting themselves in position to get a win they had
to have, the Rockets missed their first eight shots of the fourth
quarter and four free throws.
</P>
<P>
   ``We missed some easy opportunities,'' Pippen said. ``We had the
opportunity when the game was close and weren't able to take
advantage of it. They know what to do at crunch time. We made
mistakes. We missed easy shots. We turned the ball over.''
</P>
<P>
   Hakeem Olajuwon missed a drive, a jumper and a hook, had a
turnover and missed two free throws. He finished with 28 points but
had to take 23 shots, making nine, to get there. Barkley missed a
jumper and finished with 10 points, his high against the Jazz this
season.
</P>
<P>
   When Barkley tried a 3, only to miss and end up forced to foul
Karl Malone on a breakaway, Malone completed a three-point play for
a 78-65 Utah lead with 4:11 left, finishing off the Rockets, who
still had not made a fourth-quarter field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Malone finished with 25 points, 13 rebounds and five assists.
Jazz point guard John Stockton had his customary 11 points and nine
assists, with just one turnover. And the difference between the
reeling Rockets and the rolling-again Jazz was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``They execute so well,'' said Antoine Carr, late of the past
two Jazz Western Conference championship teams. ``One thing we have
to learn, especially when it gets tight in the last five minutes,
we have to execute and do what the coach says, run the plays the
chief says. You can't have 12 chiefs and one Indian.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we can win, if we play like things really
matter. But I'm used to being aggressive every game. Right now,
we're coasting.''
</P>
<P>
   Brent Price hit a pair of 3s and Pippen, who finished with 15
points, hit one to stall the inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more troublesome than the meltdown that had put them
in this position, the Rockets began to play carelessly down the
stretch, as if giving up, at least for the night, on more than just
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like the way at the end of the game it got out of
hand,'' Tomjanovich said. ``Suddenly, we were just fouling guys in
the backcourt. It looked like we lost our poise.''
</P>
<P>
   It looked _ and after the game sounded _ as if they had begun to
lose their belief the mix could come together and work, hoping to
find that confidence in a team meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things are not going right, you see a lot of problems
compound,'' Olajuwon said. ``Things become more and more difficult.
When you're down on each other, you're making mistakes. We're in
that stage of the game. We know we can play better.''
</P>
<P>
   But better would not close the gap, and not just the difference
between the Rockets and the Jazz, owner of the league's best record
and nine consecutive regular-season wins against the Rockets. After
dropping five of their past six games, the Rockets have a long way
to go to match their level of play of a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel very strongly about our team,'' Pippen said. ``Even
though we're struggling on the court, we're very positive we have
what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   But it was a blind faith, the evidence impossible to find
elsewhere. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
