<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; For SATURDAY PMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are the top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for PMs of Saturday, May 1.
</P>
<P>
   The PMs news desk, 212-556-1927, opens at 7 a.m. Eastern Time.
To get story repeats before this hour call 212-621-1595 for reruns
on AP DataFeatures or 214-980-8305 or 8367 for repeats on UPI
DataNews.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL _ (Moved in ``i'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JACKSON (Belgrade, Yugoslavia) _ The three captive
American servicemen held by Yugoslavia talked on Friday with Jesse
Jackson while the chairman of the military court monitored the
questions through a Yugoslav army interpreter and a military
cameraman recorded their answers. They said that they are being
kept in separate cells, have no contact with each other or with
other prisoners in the same facility, and had seldom walked outside
their cells during their monthlong imprisonment. But they said they
are generally well-fed and have no medical problems. By Susan
Sachs. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MILOSEVIC (Washington) _ The Yugoslav leader, Slobodan
Milosevic, insisted in an interview released here Friday that
Yugoslavs were ``willing to die'' to defend their rights but at the
same time outlined what he described as a six point plan for
settlement of the war. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-APACHE (Washington) _ One night, maybe soon, the first
U.S. Apache helicopters are supposed to take off from a makeshift
base in Albania and fly into Kosovo to try to do what NATO's
high-flying jets have not done: eviscerate Yugoslavia's armored
forces. Such attacks carry enormous risk, though. And for that
reason President Clinton still has not approved their use in combat
in the Balkans. By Steven Lee Myers. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RAPE (Skopje, Macedonia) _ Sherife Alickaj, 18, is one of
a small group of ethnic Albanian women willing to say openly that
they were sexually assaulted by Serbian soldiers during the chaotic
exodus from Kosovo. By David Rohde.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-BOMB (London) _ A nail-bomb ripped through a gay bar in
London's Soho district Friday night, killing at least two people
and injuring 73 and leaving the city on edge after two other bomb
attacks this month in minority neighborhoods. The police said
Friday that they believed all three attacks were linked to extreme
right-wing groups. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-PROTEST (Beijing) _ Fearing that members of the Buddhist
Law movement might demonstrate again in coming days, China's
leaders issued a warning Friday morning to all government officials
and employees of state-run institutions not to take part in any
such protests. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   TERRORISM-REPORT (Washington) _ In what American officials
described as a move they hoped would ease relations with Iran, the
State Department dropped its designation of the Teheran government
as the world's leading state sponsor of terrorism. By Philip
Shenon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL _ GENERAL (Moved in ``a'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TENN-HEALTHCARE (Nashville, Tenn.) _ In one bold stroke,
Tennessee converted its Medicaid health benefits to managed care
five years ago and used the savings to cover people who couldn't
afford health insurance of their own or were too sick to qualify.
With 3 million people enrolled, its program, called TennCare,
became the most ambitious and generous government health plan in
the nation. But with TennCare's costs rising and Tennessee facing a
budget deficit, the program is facing retrenchment at the orders of
Gov. Don Sundquist. By Peter T. Kilborn.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-SHOOTING (Littleton, Colo.) _ Law enforcement
officials here acknowledged Friday that they did little to follow
up a complaint a neighbor made last year that one of the teen-agers
responsible for the killings at Columbine High School last week
``talks often of making pipe bombs and using them to kill numerous
people.'' By James Brooke. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-BACKLASH (Brookline, Mass.) _ It has always been
hard to be the one called a freak, geek, dweeb, weirdo. For many,
it just got a little harder. In scattered reports from around the
country, high school students who dress defiantly, or who are
computer lovers, or who qualify in any way as outcasts, say that
since the killings in Littleton, Colo., last week, they feel as if
they have become perceived not only as different but as threats. By
Carey Goldberg. With photo.
</P>
<P>
   COLO-SCHOOL-GUNS (Denver) _ Gathering here for their annual
convention just a day after Littleton, Colo., finished burying its
slain children, officials of the National Rifle Association on
Friday rejected any suggestion that the gun lobby was responsible
for the shooting rampage that left 15 people dead, and insisted
that they would stand fast against any new gun control. By
Katharine Q. Seelye. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON _ (Moved in ``w'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TRUCK-EMISSIONS (Washington) _ President Clinton has approved
strict federal rules to control pollution from the tailpipes of
automobiles and end the special treatment for sport utility
vehicles for the first time since federal emissions standards were
drafted in the early 1970s. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   HOFFA-TEAMSTERS (Washington) _ Even now, little more than a
month after taking office, the Teamsters president, James Phillip
Hoffa, still has a touch of ``I-can't-believe-this-happened''
amazement in his manner as he sits in the office his father once
used. By Steven Greenhouse. With photos.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BUSINESS DAY _ (Moved in ``f'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ America's extraordinary economic boom _
the second-longest so far in more than a century and a half _ shows
no signs of flagging. Despite a decline in auto production and
another sharp deterioration in the nation's trade balance, the U.S.
economy grew at a surprisingly robust 4.5 percent rate this winter,
the government reported. That is the sort of heady pace usually
associated with the first, not the eighth, year of an economic
expansion. By Sylvia Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   BROKERS-ANTITRUST (Washington) _ The Justice Department has
opened a broad antitrust investigation into the practices of some
of Wall Street's largest securities firms in setting rates for
initial public offerings, federal officials and defense lawyers
said. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MEDIAONE _ Disturbed by AT&AMP;T Corp.'s cable television ambitions,
America Online Inc. and Microsoft Corp. may back Comcast Corp. in
its fight against AT&AMP;T to acquire MediaOne Group Inc., the big
cable television carrier. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-INVEST (Tosno, Russia) _ The economic collapse confirmed
the worst corporate fears about Russia: It is too unstable to
operate here. Companies such as Pizza Hut and Hershey have pulled
out, and many that had considered entering Russia shelved their
plans. Yet a number of Western multinationals _ Caterpillar,
Nestle, Lucent Technologies and others _ are coping with the
economic crisis by settling deeper into Russia rather than pulling
out. By Neela Banerjee. With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ Signs that a bustling economy might finally
produce a long-feared bout of inflation sent stock and bond prices
tumbling Friday. But the spring revival of cyclical stocks was
still strong enough to push the Dow Jones industrial average to a
gain of 10.2 percent in April, the biggest monthly gain in more
than a decade. By Edward Wyatt.
</P>
<P>
   SMALL-STOCK-TRADING (Undated) _ In an attempt to combat
securities fraud among small over-the-counter stocks, the
Securities and Exchange Commission has proposed that brokerage
firms do more of the policing. The proposal has received a flood of
criticism from traders, investors and stock issuers. By Gretchen
Morgenson.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COMMENTARY (Moved in ``k'' category)  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   LEWIS-COLUMN (Jerusalem) _ One of Israel's notable achievements,
in the 50 years since the state was reborn, has been the
development of a respected legal system. The Israeli Supreme Court
is known for protecting the civil liberties of citizens. Its judges
are esteemed around the world. That achievement is at stake in
Israel's upcoming elections. By Anthony Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ENTERTAINMENT (Moved in ``e'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   MORAL-HAZARD (Undated) _ Rarely do dreary economic abstractions
become fodder for mainstream media accounts or occasional cocktail
party chatter as the concept of moral hazard has. By Timothy L.
O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   PATTERSON-RACE (Cambridge, Mass.) _ At times Orlando Patterson
seems to be mouthing the arguments of racial neoconservatives. An
African-American who teaches sociology at Harvard University,
Patterson asserts that problems in many black neighborhoods stem
less from white racism than from the breakdown of the black family.
In other moments, he sounds like a traditional liberal, insisting
slavery and the Southern sharecropping system are to blame for
breaking down the family structure. Such iconoclastic views have
helped turn Patterson, 59, into one of the most provocative
thinkers on the status of blacks today. By Steven A. Holmes. With
photo.
</P>
<P>
   COMICS-THREAT (Undated) _ Amid the nation's focus on violence
and video games, a look back at a time when when comic books were
said to be ruining America's youth. By Sarah Boxer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPORTS (Moved in ``s'' category) &LR;
</P>
<P>
   FBN-PATRIOTS-STADIUM (Hartford, Conn.) _ Five months after the
New England Patriots announced a startling plan to move to
Connecticut, the football team said Friday it was walking away from
the most lucrative stadium deal in professional sports now that
Massachusetts is willing to pay to keep the team.
</P>
<P>
   By Mike Allen.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-DERBY (Lexington, Ky.) _ Bob Baffert will take aim on
history with three horses in the 125th Derby: the entry of General
Challenge and Excellent Meeting, owned by Betty and John Mabee of
Golden Eagle Farm in California, and Prime Timber, owned by Marie
and Aaron Jones of Oregon. If he wins, he will become the first
trainer to win both races since Ben Jones won the Oaks in 1952 with
Real Delight and the Derby with Hill Gail. By Joseph Durso.
</P>
<P>
   RAC-DERBY-BET (Lexington, Ky.) _ At least for two minutes on
Saturday, Dallas Keen, Akiko Gothard, Dallas Stewart, Scotty
Schulhofer and Elliott Walden will be linked together in the 125th
running of the Kentucky Derby. Their horses have been lumped
together in the race's mutuel field. For horse racing aficionados
that means Churchill Downs oddsmaker Mike Battaglia determined
these five horses were the least likely to win in a crowded
20-horse field. For casual fans, however, that means a sort of
Sam's Club bargain opportunity. Think of it as buying in bulk _ a
$2 bet on No. 14 in the program brings five horses for the price of
one in one of the most wide-open fields in Kentucky Derby history.
By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-ATLANTA (Atlanta) _ The organizing committee for the 1996
Atlanta Olympics will release some of the files pertaining its bid
selection process for the Summer Games. By Jere Longman.
</P>
