<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 02:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0472 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-ONHOCKEY-BOS     05-01 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ONHOCKEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The finishing touch was a bellyslide, a
glorious, impromptu glide along the ice with arms stretched in
front of him.
</P>
<P>
   Anson Carter buried his goal and then rode the wave of his own
emotion, propelled in joy, finally gliding to a stop and being
piled upon by his Bruins teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Carter found the perfect wave, right here on Tobacco Road.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have my Fleet leap, but I save that for home,'' said Carter,
moments after sliding in his backhand at 14:45 of the second
overtime, lifting the Bruins to a 4-3 victory and a 3-2 series lead
over the Hurricanes Friday night at Greensboro Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played in the World Juniors, and one of my teammates, Martin
Gendron, slid just like that on his stomach. It's the first thing
that came to my mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``Something like that, you just do it on instinct. It's what
came to mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflexes and instinct begin to wane the longer overtime goes.
Legs turn to mush. The thinking process breaks down. What should be
an easy forehand tap pass can feel like moving a curling stone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a heavyweight fight out there after a while,''
said Carter. ``You pick your spots. You aren't trying for the
knockout punch. You jab, and stick your move.''
</P>
<P>
   But the knockout punch, the one that certainly now has the
'Canes leaning over the ropes, dazed and bewildered, came on a
Carter-Joe Thornton combination 1-2 punch. Carter fed to Thornton,
and Thornton returned to Carter, and with a dash across the crease
Carter soon would be sweeping in his winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I scored on him, I went forehand on him,'' said
Carter, thinking of his previous goal in the series against
Carolina goalie Arturs Irbe. ``Maybe that's what he was thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   In the back of his mind, Carter was thinking about rule No. 1
for the scorer: when on a breakaway, go with your best move. This
was not his best move. If he had been barreling straight in on
Irbe, perhaps he would have gone with his reliable forehand lift.
But here he had an angle, a move with a view, and the approach gave
him an option.
</P>
<P>
   Carter held his shot, kept cutting right-left across the front
of the crease, Irbe locking onto his approach and moving laterally
across his shaded blue patio.
</P>
<P>
   ``He tracked me right across,'' said Carter. ``But I saw an
opening, I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Right he was. Carter carried toward the left post, pulled the
puck to his backhand, and swept in the winner. Irbe was beaten to
the stick side, a spot that grew more vulnerable for the goalie as
the night progressed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe saw me,'' said Carter, who didn't have to holler for the
feed, Thornton knowing that his linemate was in full stride. ``I
passed to him, saw an opening, and hit the hole as hard as I can.
Joe made a great saucer pass over their guy and put me in full
stride.''
</P>
<P>
   Can one play, one goal, make a team? In the years ahead, will
Carter cashing in against the 'Canes define what the Bruins do, who
they are, as the new millennium approaches?
</P>
<P>
   There is no knowing.
</P>
<P>
   We remember the Big, Bad Bruins for Bobby Orr's goal against the
Blues in the '70 Cup finals. Orr, to Derek Sanderson, back to Orr.
Puck behind Glenn Hall. A Stanley Cup in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's goal didn't even clinch a first-round series. The
'Canes come to the Fleet on Sunday for Game 6, with a chance of
sending it back here for deciding Game 7 Tuesday night. But if
there is any stock to be put in momentum, in having one spirit
lifted and another one flattened, then Carter's goal could be what
makes a young team.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins have waited a very long time for something like this,
a huge goal, a big break, for fate to come and kiss them on the
head instead of kicking them in their arses. Admit it. When the
game rolled into the second OT, you had visions of Petr Klima
swirling in your head. You thought of power outages and
transformers blowing. You remembered the old Garden, the last train
on the Green Line, the 27 years without a Stanley Cup, the decades
of dreams demolished on the roads between Boston and Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   But for one night, with one sweet sweep, Carter's goal brought a
different ending. The Hub's hockey team hung in there, went long
into the night, and made the most of it.
</P>
<P>
   Carter slid, and slid, and slid.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we'd lost it,'' he said. ``There's no way I would have
slept (Friday night).''
</P>
<P>
   Carter came to the Boston dressing room a dejected man at the
end of regulation. He blamed himself for Sami Kapanen's goal with
1:45 left, the goal that forced overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was on the sideboards, and I was sleeping,'' he recalled.
``(Paul) Coffey jumped by me at the boards and helped keep the puck
in the zone. That's what led to the goal. It was my fault. I came
in here the goat. I felt awful.''
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two periods later, the goat would be the hero.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not my best move, either,'' said a jubilant Carter. ``I've got
another in my bag of tricks. But I'll save that for another time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
