<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0474 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS     05-01 0853
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
? 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Twists and turns. Momentum shifts. Crazy
bounces. A million highs and nearly as many lows. It was
nail-biting, edge-of-your-seat, crazy. It was vintage playoff
hockey.
</P>
<P>
   It took 94 minutes 45 seconds, and it wasn't decided until Anson
Carter took a pass from Joe Thornton and beat Carolina goalie
Arturs Irbe with a backhand shot to the stick side at 14:45 of
double overtime to give the Bruins a 4-3 victory in Game 5 Friday
night at Greensboro Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   Boston now has a 3-2 lead in the best-of-seven Eastern
Conference quarterfinal, and can wrap up the series with a victory
in Game 6 tomorrow night at the FleetCenter.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins were full of relief and the Hurricanes were full of
disappointment and regret over missed opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't want to go out there for another shift,'' said
defenseman Ray Bourque, who played 53:26 (57 shifts) out of a
possible 94:45. It was the most ice time he'd seen since Game 1 in
the Stanley Cup finals against Edmonton in 1990, a game that went
three overtimes. ``I didn't see it. I just had my head down and I
was trying to rest for my next shift. I got my head up and I see AC
going for a dive. It was a great feeling.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolina very nearly ended it much earlier at 5:14 of overtime
No. 2. Martin Gelinas had a wide-open net and Byron Dafoe was out
of position, and Bourque got back first. Gelinas hit the puck, it
popped up, Bourque tried to whack Gelinas's stick, and Gelinas hit
the puck again and it bounced out of his reach and out of harm's
way. It appeared that Bourque had saved it with the shaft of his
stick, but Bourque said no. His stick actually missed the puck as
Gelinas hit it the second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He double hit it,'' said Bourque. ``He hit it forward and then
he hit it backward. We caught a huge break. He had the whole net to
shoot at. I couldn't believe it. I've done that on the golf course
and then you look around and say, `Did I just do that?' He couldn't
believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   That play _ and Bourque's overall performance _ was special,
according to Carolina coach Paul Maurice. ``Ray Bourque played 52
minutes (last night),'' said Maurice. ``He actually took a shift in
goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The first two periods belonged to Carolina. Throughout the
series, the Bruins have had a hard time coming out of the gate. The
Hurricanes have come out flying, dictating the play. Too often, the
Bruins have been back on their heels initially and then finished
strong.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night was no exception. Defenseman Steve Chiasson gave
the Hurricanes a 1-0 lead on the power play at 3:49. Then Ray
Sheppard made it 2-0 at 15:19 of the second, and the Bruins
appeared to be in deep, deep trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the players that if we can't do better than this, we
might as well warm the plane up and get going, never mind the
period,'' said Burns.
</P>
<P>
   Bourque, too, was not happy. ``The first two periods we didn't
play too well,'' he said. ``We talked about going out and leaving
it on the ice and giving us an opportunity by going out and trying
to score one goal and get us back in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   And it was Bourque who scored it, starting the barrage of three
goals in a span of 1:52, causing a 180-degree swing. The Bruins
went up, 3-2, and it appeared until very late in regulation that
Boston wouldn't be touched.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's turnaround began in the first minute when Bourque beat
Irbe from the slot on a rebound of a Dmitri Khristich shot at the
34-second mark to pull Boston within 2-1. Only 1:03 later, with the
Bruins on the power play after Gary Roberts was called for boarding
Tim Taylor, sending him to the dressing room with a shoulder
injury, defenseman Darren Van Impe made them pay. He took a pass
from Bourque, dishing from the right point, and blasted a shot from
the left point that beat Irbe to the stick side inside the left
post.
</P>
<P>
   Then a neutral zone turnover less than a half-minute later by
defenseman Marek Malik sent the Bruins down the ice on a two-on-one
break. With only defenseman Glen Wesley back, left wing P.J.
Axelsson, flanked by center Jason Allison, scored an unassisted
goal when he beat Irbe with a shot into the top left corner for the
3-2 lead at 2:26.
</P>
<P>
   But then, bam! The Hurricanes tied it on a Sami Kapanen strike
with 1:45 left, sending the game into overtime. Kapanen took a
cross-crease pass from Roberts and beat Dafoe at 18:45.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams had chances in the first extra period. Carolina had
one at the 2:21 mark when Wesley rattled a shot off the crossbar.
Then came Gelinas's chance, and that miss set up Carter's heroics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to give the players credit, they really came out and
battled hard to get the go-ahead goal,'' said Burns. ``Then it's a
long overtime. Everyone fought hard. When a guy like Ray plays 53
minutes, that's a lot of time on the ice. He saved the game for us
for sure. Gelinas will probably have trouble sleeping (last night).
He certainly missed that one. But that's what overtime is about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
