<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 02:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CUSACK-FORGERY-NYT &LR;      05-01 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CUSACK-FORGERY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN FOUND GUILTY IN FORGING OF DOCUMENTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A former paralegal at a New York law firm was
convicted Friday of bilking investors of $7 million in a forgery
scheme involving more than 200 documents said to be in the
handwriting of John F. Kennedy.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence X. Cusack III was found guilty of creating the bogus
documents and then having them authenticated by experts. The most
explosive of the papers falsely linked Kennedy with Marilyn Monroe
and a Chicago mob figure.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack, who had insisted that the papers were authentic and that
he was innocent, appeared stunned as the verdict was read in U.S
District Court in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Denise L. Cote ordered that Cusack be confined to his home
in Connecticut until his sentencing on July 30. Cusack, 48, faces
up to five years in prison, but prosecutors said they would seek a
longer term because of the large sums lost to investors, the
misrepresentation of history and the tarnishing of Kennedy's
reputation. Cusack could also face millions of dollars in fines and
restitution orders.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack left the courthouse without comment. His lawyer, Robert
F. Katzberg, would say only that there would be an appeal.
</P>
<P>
   Cusack's scheme fooled more than 100 investors, prosecutors
said, as well as several journalists, whom Cusack tried to use in
an attempt to publicize the materials and enhance their value.
</P>
<P>
   The government had argued during the trial that money was
Cusack's motive, and that appeared to have had an impact on the
jury.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the dollar signs _ period,'' said George Spencer,
foreman of the jury, which deliberated for one-and-a-half days.
</P>
<P>
   Another juror, who refused to give his name, said: ``We went
through a lot of evidence, and it was clear the documents were
frauds.''
</P>
<P>
   In presenting their case, the prosecutors, Paul A. Engelmayer
and Peter G. Neiman, offered voluminous evidence showing that
Cusack's claim that the papers were genuine was historically
impossible.
</P>
<P>
   One document, for example, was purported to have been signed by
Kennedy and Marilyn Monroe in 1960, in the Carlyle Hotel in New
York. But one of Kennedy's secretaries, Janet Des Rosiers, whose
signature also appeared on the document, denied ever having seen
it.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Des Rosiers also produced the flight logs of Kennedy's
airplane, showing that on the date the document had was said to
have been signed, Kennedy was campaigning in West Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Engelmayer said in his summation that Cusack ``tried to hijack
history in order to feed his own extravagant habits, and support
his own quest for luxury.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors presented evidence that Cusack had been spending as
much as $50,000 a month on luxury cars and Gucci loafers.
</P>
<P>
   In Cusack's defense, Katzberg suggested that prosecutors were
focusing on Cusack's lifestyle because their case was weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder how many pairs of Gucci loafers does it take for
somebody to be guilty?'' Katzberg mused in his closing arguments.
</P>
<P>
   Katzberg said that the documents might be fakes, but Cusack had
not made them, and he sold them believing they were genuine.
</P>
<P>
   But John M. Reznikoff, an autograph dealer who was helping
Cusack market the papers, testified that Cusack had tearfully
confessed to him that he had forged the documents after Peter
Jennings, the ABC News anchor, had challenged the papers'
authenticity in an interview with him.
</P>
<P>
   Reznikoff said Cusack then started to pace around the room,
saying, ``Can't we just give all the money back?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
