<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0477 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LA     05-01 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS BEAT WHITE SOX
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Once again Mo Vaughn provided the spark.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of driving the Anaheim Angels to a win with his bat on
Friday night, it was Vaughn's body that got the big hit. It spurred
the Angels to a 3-1 win over the Chicago White Sox before 35,053
fans.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the eighth inning, the teams were tied at one. White
Sox starter Jaime Navarro walked the first two batters he faced --
Orlando Palmeiro and Randy Velarde.
</P>
<P>
   As Vaughn was due up next, White Sox manager Jerry Manuel pulled
Navarro and brought in reliever Bill Simas.
</P>
<P>
   Simas plunked Vaughn in the chest with the very first pitch, a
cut fastball. Vaughn started out to the mound, but was restrained
by umpire Durwood Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   The stands erupted. Fans who came to see the post-game fireworks
show, thought they might see some on the field. Instead Vaughn made
his way to first, loading the bases.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he didn't charge the mound because he didn't want to
risk a three-day suspension. He also knew his teammates would be
fired-up
</P>
<P>
   `When I see a guy on my team get hit, I'm trying to knock
somebody's head off,` Vaughn said. `I'm sure my teammates feel the
same way. `Whatever motivates you you use,` Vaughn said.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter, Tim Salmon took a Simas fastball to deep center
and sacrificed home Orlando Palmiero for the go-ahead run. With
Troy Glaus at the plate, Randy Velarde stole third. White Sox
catcher Brook Fordyce overthrew his attempted pick off and Velarde
came home for the third and final run.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn said he saw the pitch coming at him the moment it left
Simas' hand.
</P>
<P>
   `I seen it coming toward me and I was steaming,` he said. `I
just said to myself, `I'll take it and do what I got to do.`
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Simas said he wasn't aiming for Vaughn. The pitch
simply got away.
</P>
<P>
   `Anybody that knows the game, knows that I wasn't trying to hit
him,` Simas said. `After it happened the umpire told me not to
antagonize him, but he was staring at me and I'm not going to turn
my back on him and give him a chance to charge the mound.`
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the hot Angel bats that produced 29 runs in two
previous games cooled off a bit as the team came up with just 5
hits in the contest.
</P>
<P>
   Knuckleballer Steve Sparks, who started the game for the Angels
went 7 2/3 innings, the longest outing by an Angel starter yet this
season. Mark Petkovsek appeared in relief and got the win.
</P>
<P>
   Sparks gave up just five hits, while striking out four and
walking five. He threw 133 pitches.
</P>
<P>
   White Sox starter Jaime Navarro got the loss and dropped to 1-2
for the season.
</P>
<P>
   The two teams will meet again tonight in a 7 p.m. matchup that
marks the halfway point in a four-game series.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago scored first when former Dodger Paul Konerko, hitting
just .197 coming into the game, singled off Sparks with no outs in
the fourth in the fourth to drive in Magglio Ordonez. As the White
Sox leadoff hitter in the fourth, Ordonez reached on a single, then
stole second before scoring. Sparks worked himself out of the
inning by getting the next three batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Early on, Sparks seemed sharp. The first two batters he faced
went down easily. Things got rockier though after he walked Frank
Thomas and gave up a single to Ordonez. Luckily, Greg Norton flied
out to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   `I'm just happy with the way it turned out tonight,` Sparks
said. `This game was a good building block for me.`
</P>
<P>
   The Angel half of the inning was hardly more productive. With
one out Velarde went the opposite way and doubled down the right
field line.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn advanced him to third with a ground out. Salmon followed
that with a powerful shot to left, but it was caught at the warning
track by Chicago's Jeff Abbot.
</P>
<P>
   The Angel half of the second inning mirrored the first. Darin
Erstad reached on a double off the scoreboard in right center, but
his teammates were unable to advance him.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim threatened again in the fourth. Vaughn led off with a
sharp single to left. Then Salmon reached on a fielder's choice
that saw Vaughn cut down at second. Erstad and Glaus ended the
inning for the Angels with a pair of outs.
</P>
<P>
   Things began to brighten in the fifth. Anderson's 387-foot lead
off homer on a 2-0 pitch evened the game at one. Later in the
inning, Orlando Palmeiro got to first on a walk, but he was
stranded there when Velarde flied out.
</P>
<P>
   In the sixth, the Angels were back to stranding runners. With
one out, Salmon got aboard on a double to left. Erstad hit into a
fielder's choice sending Salmon to third. Glaus, the next batter,
flied out to center ending the inning. Manager Terry Collins
chalked up his team's early misfortune to good pitching by Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   `He was impressive,` Collins said. `We didn't drive in runs
because he pitched a good game.`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
