<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 02:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0478 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRI     05-01 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-NATO-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SAYS NEW BOMBING IS THE STRONGEST EFFORT YET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to add last graf with NATO comment on Yugoslav Defense
Ministry as bombing target.) (af) 
 By ELIZABETH BECKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO Friday night unleashed what officials
described as the most aggressive bombing in the five-week air war,
hitting Serbian tanks and armored vehicles in Kosovo and bridges in
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   It was the third day in a row of fierce attacks, taking
advantage of clear weather that forecasters expect to continue
through the weekend, according to the Pentagon. The Pentagon said
650 missions were scheduled for Friday, the most to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is about the best weather we've had since the operation
started,'' Maj. Gen. Charles Wald of the Air Force told a briefing
at the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   On another front, the State Department announced it would fly
the first of 20,000 Kosovo refugees to the United States next week.
</P>
<P>
   With the flow of refugees rapidly overwhelming resources in
Albania and Macedonia, Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
announced that the Clinton administration was changing the rules to
transfer refugees to the United States. The new rules would allow
the first 400 Kosovar Albanians to go directly to Fort Dix, N.J., a
former Army training base, for processing and immediate reunion
with families around the United States.
</P>
<P>
   In the last three days, 19,500 refugees have arrived in
Macedonia. The assistant secretary of State for refugee affairs,
Julia Taft, said the administration and private groups had received
offers from 45,000 people to provide housing and other assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Albanian-American families had already identified 1,800 refugees
who are their relatives and welcome in their homes, she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday night, the second day of the increased air effort,
NATO hit targets that included the Defense Ministry and Yugoslav
Army headquarters in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last night we took the battle back to the heart of Belgrade,''
a spokesman for the allied military command, Brig. Gen. Giuseppe
Marani, told a briefing in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   But Marani acknowledged that one bomb had malfunctioned and
missed its target in predawn strikes. Several civilian houses were
destroyed in the Vracar district, a mile from downtown, and
Yugoslav state media said at least four people had been injured.
</P>
<P>
   The Defense Ministry headquarters was hit for the first time, a
spokesman for the allies said, and an ammunition-storage area and a
television broadcasting antenna south of the city were also hit.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon announced that allied plans had also pounded the
Pristina airfield on Thursday night with 5,000-pound ``bunker
buster'' bombs, the debut of that weapon in the Balkan conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Wald said allied planes were more successful striking
surface-to-air missile and radar sites on Thursday night,
reflecting better information and familiarity with the battlefield.
``We're getting better and better intelligence,'' he said, ``and
it's accumulating.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Senate, Republican leaders moved to block a vote on a
bipartisan measure championed by Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., that
would instruct President Clinton to use ``all necessary force and
other means'' against Serbia. The foreign relations committee sent
the measure to the floor without a recommendation Friday.
</P>
<P>
   The majority leader, Trent Lott of Mississippi, and the minority
leader, Tom Daschle of South Dakota, will move to put off the
legislation on Monday, Daschle said.
</P>
<P>
   Lott and other Senate Republican leaders had considered a
alternative, a bill to require the president to seek congressional
approval before deploying ground troops. But the ill will generated
by a debate on the war in the House this week dampened the Senate's
enthusiasm for open argument, several senators said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to postpone without prejudice any further debate on
involvement in the Balkans,'' Daschle said. ``We'll save that
debate for another day.''
</P>
<P>
   That day may arrive when the Senate takes up a measure to pay
for the war during the week of May 10, several senators said.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., filed a suit Friday with a
bipartisan group of 16 other lawmakers that contended that just
Congress had the power to declare war and that the Clinton
administration was violating the Constitution by participating in
the Kosovo conflict without congressional approval.
</P>
<P>
   In Albania, Gen. Hugh H. Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs
of Staff, arrived Friday and visited 3,800 American troops, telling
them that the NATO air campaign was beginning to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO is conducting air operations over Yugoslavia both day and
night, virtually around the clock,'' Shelton said. ``Our military
strikes have taken a heavy toll on Milosevic's forces and his
security infrastructure.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Albright appeared with the chief prosecutor of the
International Tribunal for War Crimes in the former Yugoslavia,
Louise Arbour. Judge Arbour said she was promoting a more
aggressive plan for arresting those indicted for war crimes in
Bosnia as a deterrent to Serb troops' committing atrocities in
neighboring Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration has yet to agree to help make those
arrests, Judge Arbour said, adding:
</P>
<P>
   ``The time is absolutely critical to see a very robust action on
the outstanding warrants. I think that could have a very immediate
impact, would be the demonstration that we have the capacity to
investigate. And we have partners who have the political will and
the operational skills to execute arrest warrants, even in hostile
environments.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Arbour declined to comment on a report that she was
planning to leave her post as chief prosecutor. Officials say she
is the prime candidate for a seat on the Supreme Court of Canada, a
position that will be vacant in the summer.
</P>
<P>
   Human rights advocates and Clinton administration officials have
expressed concern that her departure would weaken the prosecutions
of war crimes at a critical juncture.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why Yugoslavia's Defense Ministry headquarters had not
been bombed before, a NATO spokesman, Jamie P. Shea, said: ``The
headquarters of the special police, which we attacked some time
ago, were a larger priority target. The Ministry of Defense is
important as well. It's really a question of trying to identify
locations which are the brain of these operations.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
