<SLUG> BC-BKN-VECSEY-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRAND SLAM ATMOSPHERE MERITS EQUALITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By LAURA VECSEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Yes, in tennis the men play best-of-five. Yes, those
matches can prove more grueling and more epic than ``Braveheart.''
And yes, if tennis players were paid by the minute, the men should
get more, since a women's singles match can last just a little
longer than an episode of ``Ally McBeal.''
</P>
<P>
   (Are we allowed to talk about the scorched-earth aces served in
men's matches, where a ``rally'' is anything longer than a service
winner? Or those times during men's matches when a player tanks an
entire set to conserve energy for the next one? Just asking.)
</P>
<P>
   But there is a bigger point to be made here.
</P>
<P>
   When the old guard at Wimbledon rejected a bid by the Women's
Tennis Association this week to dole out equal prize money between
the men and the women, they failed to recognize a basic, glorious
fact about their lawn party.
</P>
<P>
   The beauty of the Grand Slams is that four times a year _ on the
red clay at Roland Garros, on the grass at Wimbledon, in the heat
and cacophony of New York and down under in the sun of Australia _
the best tennis players in the world, men and women, gather for
very special championship tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   What makes a Grand Slam a Grand Slam is that men and women share
equal billing and are competing for the same prestigious, coveted
titles. The presence of everyone is what makes these fortnights so
intriguing and more than warrants equal pay.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, what's the real difference between $728,000 for the men
and $655,200 for the women? If it's just a matter of principle, of
thinking men deserve more, then the principle is downright
Jurassic.
</P>
<P>
   STAYIN' ALIVE: The Nuggets were fine guests of the city Friday
night. Nick Van Exel and Antonio McDyess let the Sonics and their
fans have a nice time at KeyArena, meaning the Sonics are still
alive with three games to go in this nutball NBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's Showtime on Sunday. And we do mean Showtime, since the
Los Angeles Lakers appear to have regained a little of their lost
luster after beating the Blazers and taking to heart Kareem
Abdul-Jabbar's constructive jabs.
</P>
<P>
   For the Sonic faithful, who want to see the fellas in the
postseason yet again, let's just hope there is no repeat of the
Sonics' national TV shellacking last Sunday at the Delta Center in
Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   FOR THE ROSES: Got to love the fillies in the Kentucky Derby. We
want to see Three Ring set the pace with early speed, although
we'll have to put money down on Bob Baffert's Excellent Meeting,
even if it's an exacta box with the big boys, Menifee and Prime
Timber.
</P>
<P>
   SPEED DEMON? Word is the Mariners are looking to add more speed
to their lineup even with the welcome addition (unless you're Butch
Huskey) of Brian Hunter _ Mariner left fielder No. 9,999 (or
something like that) since Ken Griffey Jr. took over in center
field.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, with Hunter at leadoff, does that mean we will never see
Lou Piniella pencil in a lineup that starts off with David Segui,
Edgar Martinez, Griffey and Jay Buhner?
</P>
<P>
   Boy, would that be a relief.
</P>
<P>
   WHY WORRY: When Stan Williams went to the mound Friday night
after Jeff Fassero gave up two home runs to Toronto in the third
inning, what do you bet the pitching coach told the Mariner starter
to chill out. What's a 5-3 deficit to a team that came back from
6-1 to win 22-6 _ and take center stage on ``SportsCenter'' for a
day?
</P>
<P>
   And lo and behold, Griffey comes through with his second grand
slam in two days to give the Mariners a win.
</P>
<P>
   JOSE CAN YOU SEE: Speaking of Mariner left fielders: It's always
good to see Jose Cruz Jr. in the Kingdome, no matter the color of
his uniform.
</P>
<P>
   OLYMPIC MESS: First, Johnson &AMP; Johnson announces it won't spend
money sponsoring the 2002 Winter Games in Salt Lake City. Then,
this week, the United States Olympic Committee's head marketing
man, John Krimsky, abruptly announces his resignation. Now the word
is that Salt Lake is shockingly behind its $850 million in
fund-raising _ thanks to the backlash over the International
Olympic Committee's goodie grab bag gluttony and Salt Lake's
willingness to grease palms, pocketbooks and bank vaults.
</P>
<P>
   Salt Lake's new Olympic marketing slogan should be: Brother, can
you spare a luge _ and about $300 million?
</P>
<P>
   THOSE TIMBERCUBBIES: Deep down, the Sonics are praying that
Minnesota continues its slide and falls out of the playoff picture.
The T-Wolves posted a win Friday night, making every one of the
Sonics' last three games crucial. At least last season, the Sonics
were actually in the playoffs before the T-Wolves almost knocked
them off.
</P>
<P>
   INSPECTING THE GOODS: Maybe the Sonics didn't know Billy Owens
would get injured when they signed the free agent, but there is a
scale somewhere at the Sonics' training facility, no?
</P>
<P>
   THE LONGEST YARD, BRONCO STYLE: John Elway's retirement
announcement is such old news, it's almost time for him to announce
his comeback.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Vecsey is a P-I columnist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
