<HEADLINE>
SONICS FLATTEN NUGGETS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ On his first touch of the game Friday night, Vin Baker
drew an offensive foul.
</P>
<P>
   He thought he was just being aggressive. So to prove his point,
the next time he received the ball, Baker whirled past two
defenders and dunked with two hands.
</P>
<P>
   Baker did what he had to do, and so did the Sonics, defeating
the Denver Nuggets 111-101 at KeyArena to keep their playoff hopes
alive.
</P>
<P>
   But all was not well with Baker, who returned from a deep bruise
in his right knee but played only six minutes off the bench.
</P>
<P>
   Baker is perhaps more frantic than anyone about this tiny fact:
The Sonics still need help to make the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics (23-24) remain in ninth place in the Western
Conference standings _ one game behind Minnesota and Sacramento
with three regular-season games left.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, the Sonics need to sweep their remaining games
and need Minnesota to lose twice in order to make the postseason.
The Timberwolves own the tiebreaker should they finish in a tie
with the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, that is what Baker reminded Sonic brass of after the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Furious about his lack of playing time, Baker met with Sonics
coach Paul Westphal, team president Wally Walker, co-captain Gary
Payton and Baker's agent, Eric Goodwin, immediately following the
game.
</P>
<P>
   That latest development kept the Sonics from opening the locker
room in a timely fashion for postgame interviews. Only a few
players were present when the locker room finally opened.
</P>
<P>
   No one would comment when they emerged from Westphal's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``The knee feels good and this is a crucial point of the
season,'' Baker said before the game. ``I feel better. I wouldn't
be on the floor if I couldn't play. I'm ready to give the team any
minutes I can.''
</P>
<P>
   In his postgame conference with the media, Westphal said Baker
was not in shape.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have liked to play him a little bit more, but
circumstances didn't really warrant it,'' Westphal said. ``I don't
think he looked sharp, but I give him credit for doing everything
he can to get out there and help us.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to As The Sonics Turn. The Baker saga comes one day
after Payton and those close to the All-Star guard went into damage
control for comments he made following Wednesday's 35-point loss at
Portland.
</P>
<P>
   Next up for the Sonics is a tough home game Sunday against the
Los Angeles Lakers on national television. Fortunately for the
Sonics, they finish with a pair of games in which they will be
heavily favored to win.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics play Dallas at home on Tuesday and conclude the
regular season Wednesday in Los Angeles against the Clippers.
Minnesota, meanwhile, ends its home schedule tonight against the
Clippers followed by road games at Houston and Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Sacramento has the easiest schedule of the three teams fighting
for the last two playoff spots. The Kings close with home games
against Phoenix and Vancouver and one road game, at Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to continue to win,'' Sonics guard Hersey Hawkins
said. ``That's all we're concerned about. ... If we just keep
winning, we'll be fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The way this season has gone, who knows if they will. Maybe they
won't.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they play the same as they did tonight, you know, passing
the ball around ... yeah, they can get into the playoffs,'' Denver
center Danny Fortson said.
</P>
<P>
   There was little doubt about whether the Sonics deserved to win
Friday night's game. They trailed only once _ 2-0 47 seconds into
the game. From there, the Sonics used a 17-5 run to take control.
</P>
<P>
   Behind a season-high 32 assists, the Sonics pummeled the Nuggets
with offensive balance. Detlef Schrempf's 28 points led six players
in double figures.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been playing out of position a lot, particularly with Vin
out of the lineup,'' Westphal said of Schrempf. ``Just this week,
he's guarded Karl Malone twice and Brian Grant and then Antonio
McDyess. He's really just done an amazing job.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics jumped in front 60-51 by halftime. Their biggest lead
was 83-67 with 2:53 left in the third.
</P>
<P>
   Denver cut the Sonics' 14-point lead to 100-95 with two minutes
left in the game. But Dale Ellis hit a 3-pointer, Schrempf made two
free throws and Hawkins made a short jumper to complete a 7-0 run
and remove all doubt from the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   NOTES: Backup point guard John Crotty did not play because of a
mild concussion he suffered during Wednesday's game at Portland.
... The team activated guard Drew Barry from the injured list to
replace Crotty in the lineup. James Cotton was placed on the
injured list with the stomach flu. ... The Nuggets are wearing
black patches on their uniforms to pay tribute to the victims of
the Columbine High School shootings. ... Baker decided he was ready
to play after a strong practice Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
