<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIFFEY'S SLAM IN 8TH LIFTS M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Ken Griffey Jr. lifted his arms in the air as he
rounded first base and smiled as he bounded into the Mariners
dugout. In April.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners center fielder is not one to show his emotions.
Maybe under a pile of jubilant teammates in playoff victories over
the New York Yankees, but not in games before school's out.
</P>
<P>
   This one was different. Griffey, owner of one career hit in nine
at-bats against nasty Toronto Blue Jays lefty Graeme Lloyd, came to
bat with the bases loaded and one out, trailing by two in the
eighth inning.
</P>
<P>
   He sent Lloyd's first pitch screaming toward right center, and
it had just enough lift to carry over the wall for a grand slam.
The slam was Griffey's second in two days, and the decisive blow in
an 11-9 Mariners win in the Kingdome Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just emotion from coming from behind,'' Griffey said.
``Anytime you come from behind, it gives the team a lift.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey, whose one prior hit against Lloyd was a homer, said he
didn't come up looking to hit the first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just trying to stay out of the double play,'' he said.
``That's the biggest thing in that situation, staying out of the
double play and giving your team a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Griffey became just the 18th player in baseball history to hit
grand slams in consecutive games. He has driven in 11 runs in his
past two games, a new Mariners record. His ninth home run of the
year moved him past Yogi Berra into a tie for 47th on the all-time
list with Johnny Mize, at 359.
</P>
<P>
   All three base runners who scored on the grand slam had been
walked by Jays reliever Robert Person, who had stifled a potential
rally an inning before with 96-mph heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a great arm,'' said M's outfielder Butch Huskey, a
former minor-league roommate of Person's who walked before
Griffey's blast. ``He just has control problems sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners' patience was as much the result of a conscious
effort as it was of one pitcher's wildness.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are working the counts better than we were earlier in the
year, and it's starting to show,'' said M's manager Lou Piniella.
``(Hitting coach Jesse Barfield) and I have talked about it and
preached it, and it pays dividends if you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Toronto was hurt far worse by walks than the Mariners. Starter
Jeff Fassero walked six, a Mariner high this season, but only one
of his free passes turned into a run. Fassero was hurt more by the
long ball _ he surrendered four homers, also a season high for an
M's pitcher, and lasted only 42/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Fassero said he was fighting himself with mechanical problems he
couldn't pinpoint. But he also was surprised the Blue Jays lifted
several good pitches _ a slider at the shoetops to Carlos Delgado,
a low fastball to Shawn Green, a fastball away to Jose Cruz Jr. _
over the fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought three of their hits were fly outs, and I watched two
go out and one go off the wall,'' Fassero said. ``It seemed like
pretty light air for this place. It seemed like it was a little
warm; I don't know if the heaters were on or what. But they can
swing the bats. They're definitely a low-ball hitting team. I've
learned that. Give them credit.''
</P>
<P>
   After Fassero departed, the M's got strong relief from winner
John Halama (1-2) and closer Jose Mesa, who converted his sixth
save in six chances.
</P>
<P>
   Before Griffey went to work, the Mariners' offensive hero was
Rafael Bournigal. The newly acquired shortstop drove in a run with
a sacrifice fly in the second and singled and scored in the fifth.
In the sixth, with a runner on, Bouringal poked a pitch down the
left field line for his third home run in 849 major league at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Bournigal's double-play partner, second baseman David Bell, left
the game after colliding with Toronto catcher Mark Dalesandro on a
double-steal attempt in the first inning. Bell was bloodied on the
play and needed eight stitches to close a gash on his chin that was
so deep, trainers could see his chin bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember being five feet away from him, and I don't remember
anything else until I was on the ground,'' said Bell, who was
thankful Dalesandro's mask had come off on the throw to shortstop
seconds before. ``I remember going, `What is he going to do?' And
the next thing I knew, I was out.''
</P>
<P>
   Aside from a headache, Bell said, ``I don't really feel that
bad.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
