<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DISSOLVES ON CONTACT 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   By the time the mayor of Rye, N.Y., was introduced, I had to
stop myself from yelling over to the blonde in black, ``Hillary,
turn back before it's too late!''
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Rodham Clinton, after all, could have been home in
Washington playing first lady. She could have been lounging in the
silk splendor of the White House residence. She could have been
asking a steward to pour her some white wine and commanding the
chastened president to massage her feet.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, she was being tortured at the kind of New York dinner
where the name ``Aaron Burr'' was the punch line _ repeatedly. At
the annual Democratic Jefferson-Jackson fund-raising banquet at the
Hyatt on Thursday night, Mrs. Clinton suffered through dozens of
introductions of minor state and local political figures and 14
speeches that felt like 1,400.
</P>
<P>
   She has another glamorous trip to Buffalo and Ellis Island
planned for this week.
</P>
<P>
   Yup. The lady definitely wants to be a senator. It was pretty
evident when she studied up on all New York's agricultural crops
and started referring to herself and the state as ``we.''
</P>
<P>
   But now it's undeniable. You could tell because she was laughing
at the jokes of Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver, most often
described in the press as ``funereal.'' You could tell because she
had put away her pastels in favor of the Manhattan uniform of
black. You could tell from the body language of Harold Ickes, who
was bounding around the ballroom with a cat-swallowed-canary grin,
rejected as White House chief of staff by one Clinton but relied on
as New York strategist by another.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, you could tell because she sounded more Bill than
Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's becoming her husband,'' said one former White House
official who knows her well. ``The evolution is now complete.''
</P>
<P>
   She started out in '92 promising ``Buy one, get one free,''
offering a team of two separate professionals with individual
strengths. She was all spine, where he was all flexibility. She was
an ideologue, where he was a shapeshifter. She was a ``we've got to
fight and jam it down their throats'' firebrand, where he was a
smooth-talking compromiser.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's her turn to try to be all things to all people. To
slide to the center. To bend that famous spine. She no longer
mentions a Palestinian state. She has revealed that she favors the
death penalty, ``with caveats.''
</P>
<P>
   Her after-dinner speech had little fire or even New York
politics in it. The pols were hoping for Rudy flambe. Instead of
red meat, they got polenta.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that we should have a national conversation about
and a national campaign against youth violence,'' a touchy-feely
Mrs. Clinton told the crowd. Like her husband, she now treats talk
as action and silence as a cause for horror. She thinks if you
listen to people, you understand them, and that everybody is right
in his or her own way.
</P>
<P>
   In a speech that dissolved on contact, she urged ``a broader
conversation about what kind of nation we are, what kind of people
we want to be ... how we're going to work out our disagreements.''
She called for a new millennial ``attitude'' forged from ``bringing
people of different backgrounds and points of view together to come
to some common agreement about what we should do for the common
good.''
</P>
<P>
   She concluded by saying she hoped that ``as we move forward in
the next several years in our political process, in all the large
and small ways we work with one another, we make common bonds with
one another, we reach compromise over all kinds of issues, we will
be guided by the overwhelming desire to play a positive role in
bringing people together to work on behalf of the kind of country,
state, city and, yes, world'' we want.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton began his presidency with a national conversation
and now Hillary is beginning her de facto Senate campaign with a
national conversation. If only she wouldn't. There is way too much
talk in this country, too much blather, too much media, too much
psychobabble.
</P>
<P>
   If she must have a national dialogue, she should make it about
how we cope with the schiziness of a president's wife running for
the Senate out of the White House. Or help us work through our
anger at the way the first lady is running a personal shuttle
service between Washington and New York, largely on our dime. Give
me some closure on that _ quick!
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
