</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS' FANS WILL ALWAYS HAVE 1969 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Ron Swoboda loves the look on their faces. Well into
middle age themselves, with the attendant wrinkles and gray hairs,
they get this silly gaping smile on their faces when they realize
who he is, what he was part of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lovefest, man,'' Swoboda said.
</P>
<P>
   Like a lot of us who think 1969 just might have been the most
bizarre year of our lives, or maybe of the century, Swoboda often
talks like a cast member of the musical ``Hair.''
</P>
<P>
   The language comes back: ``Blows me away.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoboda remembers the year when white people wore their hair
down their backs, and blacks wore their hair in ballooning Afros,
when astronauts walked on the moon and John and Yoko sang for peace
in Vietnam - when it was not quite clear the center would hold _
and somehow or other the Amazing Metropolitans won the World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's still a big deal,'' Swoboda said the other day. ``A big
doggone deal.''
</P>
<P>
   Thirty years have gone by, and it's maybe bigger than ever.
Every year, some team wins the Stanley Cup and the Super Bowl and
the NBA championship and the Final Four and the World Series and
the national college football championship and there are
celebrations in every ``Greatest Sports Town in This Country,'' to
say nothing of the now-obligatory videos and coffee-table books.
</P>
<P>
   Every championship, by definition, is historic. What the Mets
did in the year of Neil A. Armstrong and Jimmy Qualls and Richard
M. Nixon was unique. The Worst Team in the History of Baseball
turned around and won the World Series. You could - as Swoboda's
mentor, Casey Stengel, liked to say - look it up.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday in Shea Stadium there will be an old-timers' game, mixing
aging members of the Chicago Cubs, Atlanta Braves and Baltimore
Orioles, who still cannot believe it.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the old Mets will be there - the Glider, Buddy, Tug, Dr.
Ron, Cleon, Tommie, Sham, Krane, Tom Terrific. Children will
understand why that year was different from any other year.
</P>
<P>
   ``People remember,'' said Swoboda, himself 54, a baseball
broadcaster and businessman in New Orleans, and a living totem to
Mets fans of a certain age.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have gone on with their lives,'' Swoboda said.
``It's not like they are geeks with Mets jackets who live with
their moms. But the Mets mean something special to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoboda has had three decades to try to figure it out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were putting men on the moon,'' he said. ``We were killing
people in Vietnam. People were protesting and putting flowers in
their hair. If there was anything easy to hang on to, it was the
Mets. When we won the World Series, all things seemed possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we did was layered with other things,'' Swoboda added.
``The National League jilted New York when the Dodgers and Giants
left. The Mets came back with Casey covering up that they were
losing 100 games a year. In short order, we were winning 100 games
in a year. It was unbelievable, man.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoboda spanned the bad years and the amazing year. He was a raw
20-year-old outfielder in the spring of 1965, Rocky on and off the
field, but an observer. The old manager liked him because Swoboda
personified Stengel's dream of the new Mets - ``They ain't failed
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Swoboda recalled: ``I would sit and listen to him. It would
sound as if he was speaking in Stengelese, but all of a sudden I'd
say, `Hey, man, this guy is telling a parable - and it's aimed at
me!'''
</P>
<P>
   By 1969, Casey was a revered ancient, and Gil Hodges was the
manager. Casey once said Hodges could ``squeeze your earbrows
off,'' which was probably true, and only Rocky Swoboda, true to his
nickname, dared challenge him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're young and full of yourself, you do things you
regret,'' Swoboda said the other day. ``Gil sometimes made me feel
he was rubbing our noses in his authority, but that was me, that
was my fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one time early in 1969 he held a meeting and he
said, `You guys are professionals, you set your own curfew,' and
somebody suggested two and a half hours after the game, and Gil
said it was too long, and I popped up, `Gil, why don't you just
tell us?' I would do my thing like that. Why didn't I just shut
up?''
</P>
<P>
   Hodges squeezed the earbrows of an entire season, and Swoboda
made an epic catch in the World Series, and the Mets danced on the
moon. In the spring of 1972, Hodges, a cardiac patient, fell down
dead at 47. Swoboda, a Yankee by then, still wishes he had patched
it up a little more, but they are part of the same legend. Not all
championships are created equal. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 0940EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
