<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 09:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0494 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     05-01 0874
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TRAINING WITH THE INFLUENCE OF WHITTINGHAM  
 (EDITORS: COLUMN TO BE SUBBED AFTER THE KENTUCKY DERBY) 
</HEADLINE>
  jt) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The best eulogy Nick Zito could think of for
Charlie Whittingham was short and sweet, the antithesis of a
grizzled workaholic who plied his trade for 50 years, almost right
up until his death 11 days ago at the age of 86.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just knew he was a horse trainer, nothing else, and he
stuck to it,'' Zito said. ``He didn't try to be something else, an
entrepreneur, or an actor, like me.''
</P>
<P>
   Zito, raised in Queens, N.Y., in the shadows of New York's race
tracks, laughed sarcastically, having raised a subtext that has
become unavoidable in his beloved profession, one in which the
stakes for success have been raised, like it or not.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, D. Wayne Lukas had a run of six straight
Triple Crown victories and seven of eight, and then Bob Baffert
came along to win consecutive Kentucky Derbies the last two years,
along with the 1998 Preakness. Two striking, media-savvy profiles
were carved into the consciousness of a fading sport crying out for
a Rushmore of stars.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert came to Churchill Downs Saturday hoping to become the
first trainer to win three straight Derbies, add to his growing
reputation as the man with the silver hair and a golden touch. The
news media backside crowds flocked to Barn 33 this week, where
Baffert's three contenders _ General Challenge, Prime Timber and
the filly Excellent Meeting _ were housed for Saturday's 125th
Derby running. Lukas, with two less-distinguished horses, Cat Thief
and Charismatic, appeared earlier in the week to be inducted in
thoroughbred racing's Hall of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   In the expanding universe of entertainment and sports, from the
R-rated professional wrestling to the made-for-television X Games,
it makes perfect sense that celebrity trainers who look as if
they've stepped off a golf course more than out of a smelly barn
become the marketing rage. This is a sport where the horses tend to
sound alike and the jockeys, for all their courage and skill, are
existentially in supporting roles. Trainers are the college
basketball and football coaches of thoroughbred racing. They
represent the Program, the continuum, as the horses pass in and out
of prominence every few years.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any coincidence that Lukas, a former high school
basketball coach who counts Bobby Knight among his best friends,
insists that his growing stable of assistant trainers address him
as Coach? He refers to his ``system'' when he talks about all the
places he can't possibly be, and the men who implement his training
techniques at a half-dozen different tracks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach, the system works,'' he recalled one of his assistants
raving into the telephone after one recent victorious race.
</P>
<P>
   If the recent dominance of Lukas and then Baffert suggests
anything, it is that the next wave of aspiring super trainers had
better be part entrepreneur, part actor, anti-Whittinghams. They
had better be good recruiters, and jugglers, too. Trainers have
always served different masters, the way a college coach works for
the school and the shoe company, but the magnitude of these
conflicts is growing, based on the sheer number of horses required
to keep up with the Lukases and Bafferts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Horses break down, they don't train well, don't run well in
the Derby preps,'' Baffert said Friday, looking country-club cool
in customary shades before his Silverbulletday won the Kentucky
Oaks. ``You need a lot of them if you want to get here.''
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer realistic to stake one's Triple Crown season on
a horse or two, any more than it is enough for Mike Jarvis to count
on two or three recruits deciding on St. John's. You can't win, or
even be seen on horse racing's grandest stage, if you're not here.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm not mistaken, Charlie Whittingham came to the Derby
four times, won two and finished second once,'' said Zito. ``His
philosophy was don't come in here unless you've got a shot, and I
always believed the same thing. But there used to be, what, 4 Derby
preps and now there's 10. If you run strong in one of them, how do
you not come to the Derby?
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning, I thought they were creating too much hype.
I was thinking that if you if you have all this stuff going on
leading into the Derby, what are you going to do for the Derby?''
</P>
<P>
   At 51, this trainer who learned from the old school has grasped
the sport's new math. He spread several horses around the Derby
preps, and when the two he had the highest hopes for faltered, he
still had Stephen Got Even, winner of the Gallery Furniture Stakes
at Turfway Park in Florence, Ky., near Cincinnati, and Adonis, best
of what the racing people called a weak Wood Memorial in New York.
</P>
<P>
   He, too, came to Churchill Downs looking for his third Derby
winner, though not with the three-straight splash of Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can get all the glory,'' Zito said. ``I'll sneak in.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the Whittingham in him speaking, the old pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie never forgot where he came from,'' Zito said.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas and Baffert are where no trainer has gone before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
