<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 09:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RAC-TRACKS-FUTURE-NYT     05-01 0995
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-TRACKS-FUTURE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RACING MAKES THE WIDE TURN FROM TRADITION 
</HEADLINE>
   (Attn: Ind., Ohio, Fla., Calif., Ky.)  
(jt) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Beneath the twin spires of Churchill Downs,
where tradition and history were being served again Saturday in the
125th Kentucky Derby, the winds of change were rustling and maybe
even howling as thoroughbred racing groped for new business
alliances and mergers to save the sport from oblivion in the 21st
century.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the chief players in the trend toward consolidation are a
pair of former Marines who run race tracks 75 miles apart in the
heart of the bluegrass country where racing flourished as a way of
life long before casino gambling arrived.
</P>
<P>
   They are Tom Meeker, president of Churchill Downs and perhaps
the most aggressive strategist in racing, and Ted Bassett, chairman
of Keeneland Race Course in Lexington, who startled the purists
recently by allying his stately old track with gambling
corporations in a move toward rescuing Turfway Park in northern
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   On the West Coast, the trend has been accelerated by Frank
Stronach, the Canadian horseman who purchased Santa Anita last
year. But Meeker and Bassett have taken the Eastern establishment
by surprise with their moves in Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think you'll ever see slot machines or casino gambling
at our hallowed track,'' Bassett said with exaggerated emphasis in
a recent interview in Lexington. ``But if they come someday to
Kentucky, why not Turfway? And you will see a more intelligent way
for Keeneland to deal with its people.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeker, who recently led Churchill's moves to acquire Hollywood
Park in California and Calder in Florida, said that racing has no
choice but to pursue mergers in business.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at American business today,'' he said in an
interview at Churchill Downs, ``there are a number of things
forcing businesses to consolidate. In the 1980s, the motive was to
improve shareholder value. In the 1990s, companies have joined to
develop better platforms for their products, especially in
telecommunications and banking.
</P>
<P>
   ``In racing, we have moved from a little parochial business
where you did your business within 25 miles of your track. Now,
we're a national and even international market. We have an $8
billion simulcast market, interstate.''
</P>
<P>
   He seemed willing to defuse the issue of casino gambling, which
alarms many traditionalists who prefer racing as a way of horse
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, we support casino gambling,'' he said. ``But we don't
see it as an end-all. If it takes casino gambling to save the
business, we ought to get out of the business and get into a new
one. We see alternative gambling as part of the solution, but not
all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeker, a decorated officer who spent three tours of duty in
Vietnam and then returned home to Louisville to get his law degree,
became general counsel to Churchill Downs, and in 1984 succeeded
Lynn Stone as president. In the last few years, with racing
generally losing fans and business, he initiated a series of moves
that expanded Churchill's interests and startled the rest of the
racing world as it reached for new marketing strategies and
customers.
</P>
<P>
   Hoosier Park in Indiana was opened as that state's first
parimutuel race track along with its satellite betting facilities
in Fort Wayne, Indianapolis and Merrillville. Then Churchill bought
interests in Ellis Park and Kentucky Downs. And in recent months,
it bought Calder Race Course in Florida for $86 million, negotiated
to buy Hollywood Park in Los Angeles and reportedly opened talks
with Gulfstream Park in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   The moves came at a price. The board of directors authorized a
rise in the number of shares of stock to 50 million from 20
million, and obtained a $250 million line of credit. And the
company's stock lost about one-third of its value at one point. But
Meeker sees it all as part of the price of success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get some leverage, where we can get more money to
deliver a better product to our customers,'' he said. ``It's a
natural evolution. You'll join race tracks to strengthen their
balance sheets and acquire more capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It used to be that mergers had a bottom-line focus, and it
sent tremors through people. Now, you're looking at the top line: 1
plus 1 equals 3. You have to go into this with the philosophy that
you need to get more capital, not cut less fat.''
</P>
<P>
   He reflected, and said: ``Fifteen years ago, when I came here,
we'd open the gates. We were the only show in town. One business,
one product. Now, we have casinos right across the river.''
</P>
<P>
   Ted Bassett, who was a Marine officer in World War II, created
even more waves early this year when he joined the traditionalist
Keeneland track in Lexington with Harrah's Entertainment and the
Gtech Corp., which makes video lottery machines. For $37 million,
Keeneland took over operations at Turfway Park across the Ohio
River from Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   ``We realized that 10 years ago, only New Jersey and Nevada
allowed casino gambling,'' Bassett said. ``Today, 30 states allow
it. Harrah's has 19 casinos around the country. They have customers
logged in their computers. They know what people like, even what
they eat and drink. Why not use their customer-relations smarts? We
might learn something. And Gtech makes the best use of
technology.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Turfway has been on the block for two years, with no takers,''
he said. ``They run before each of our two meets, spring and fall.
So, why not take advantage of that and join the dates to keep the
horses running in Kentucky? The pool of talent is becoming
increasingly critical.''
</P>
<P>
   So is the financial dilemma that threatens to wipe out many
tracks in racing, especially small ones without Churchill's
resources or Keeneland's insight. But they at least have nudged the
trend to transform their business and survive into the next
century.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
