   OTHER NEWS:
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-ELECTIONS (Panama City) _ The Panama Canal is by far the
the most important issue looming over Sunday's presidential
election here, a contest between the son of Gen. Omar Torrijos, who
negotiated the Panama Canal Treaty with President Carter in 1977,
and the widow of a president ousted by the general. By Mireya
Navarro.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-TORTURER (Bangkok, Thailand) _ Cambodians know him as
the cruelest of the Khmer Rouge torturers, the author of such
directives as ``Use the hot method, even if it kills him'' and, in
the margin of a list of 17 children, ``Kill them all.'' In his own
mind, he is St. Paul, a persecutor who renounced his past and
became a Christian evangelist. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-SCARF (Istanbul) _ A newly elected deputy of Turkey's
parliament insists she will take her oath while wearing her Muslim
head scarf, a move likely to set off a confrontation with the
secular political establishment. By Steven Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   LONDON-BOMBING (London) _ British police officers sped to a
small Hampshire village southwest of London early today to arrest a
man they said may be involved in a wave of extremist bombings that
claimed two lives in a blast last night at a gay bar in Soho. But
the arrest failed to quell widespread anxieties among minority
groups that they may be the next target of what the police depict
as a hate-driven racial campaign by extreme rightists that has sent
tremors of nervousness across London. By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   CORSICA-VIOLENCE (Paris) _ Bombs and fires have long been common
tools for Corsica's separatists, but a recent explosion at a beach
restaurant appears to have been the work of the very crack police
squad that was created to stem the guerrilla violence. By Marlise
Simons.
