<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0079 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 12:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1293 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOREIGN-ECON-REVIEW-2     05-01 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOREIGN-ECON-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN ALLIES ARE FIERCE COMPETITORS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Late in the day on April 6, Energy Secretary Bill
Richardson showed up at the White House with some bad news for
President Clinton: The leakage of nuclear secrets from U.S. weapons
labs was far worse than anyone thought. The Chinese _ whose prime
minister was on his way to Washington _ may have obtained computer
codes that are the key ingredient for simulating nuclear weapons
explosions.
</P>
<P>
   It was the kind of chilling discovery that would make for a good
Washington thriller. But real life is more complex. In a speech the
next morning, Clinton said Americans do indeed have reason to worry
about China, but not only a muscular China with the latest weapons
technology. Americans have as much to fear, he argued, from a weak
China whose ailing banks and bankrupt enterprises could undermine
the world economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we've learned anything in the last few years from Japan's
long recession and Russia's current economic troubles, it is that
the weaknesses of great nations can pose as big a challenge to
America as their strengths,'' Clinton said. ``So as we focus on the
potential challenge that a strong China could present to the United
States in the future, let us not forget the risk of a weak China,
beset by internal conflicts, social dislocation and criminal
activity, becoming a vast zone of instability in Asia.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the starkest moment yet in what has emerged as the
central foreign policy conundrum in Washington: In an age when your
military adversary can also rank among your biggest trading
partners, and when your military allies double as your fiercest
economic competitors, does America want weak global neighbors or
strong ones?
</P>
<P>
   That question is increasingly the subtext of daily debate in
Washington, fracturing the Democratic and Republican parties across
unusual lines, trapping lawmakers and pundits in circular arguments
about where America's true interests lie. It helps account for the
crazy-quilt of U.S. foreign policy. And the problem is made more
complex by the fact that the world stage is crowded by weak states
_ countries that are jockeying for global influence while
struggling to keep from drowning in debt, self-doubt and rising
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   The Japanese, once masters of the art of converting
old-fashioned capital into political capital, have watched their
global influence decline faster than the price of an office
building in the Ginza. While Russia tries to flex old muscles in
the Balkans, it is submitting to the humiliation of having the
International Monetary Fund micro-manage its economy. (Last week,
spurred by fears that Moscow is feeling dangerously alienated from
the West, the IMF finally committed to $4.5 billion in new loans
for the nearly insolvent government, just enough to stave off
national default for another year or so.)
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese spies who may be tinkering with the nuclear codes
are probably thankful for the fact that, unlike millions of others
who toil for the state, their jobs are going to be around for a
while. And then there are the Europeans, who are slogging through a
war in Yugoslavia just at the moment that their economies are
slowing and their new currency, the Euro, has fallen 10 percent.
This was supposed to be the year the continent focused on becoming
the next great economic superpower, linked by a single currency and
a huge market. Instead, one European finance minister visiting
Washington last week moaned, ``We're spending all our political
energy on a 600-year-old problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extraordinary moment that perhaps we haven't seen
since the '20s, or at least since the days of the Marshall Plan,''
said Kenneth Courtis, the chief Asian economist for Deutsche Bank.
``You have the world economy flying on one engine _ the United
States. And almost everyone else is dealing from a weak hand.''
</P>
<P>
   You would think this would leave Washington filled with joy, and
often it does. After all, that single engine still has its
afterburners lit: The government reported Friday an astounding 4.5
percent annual growth rate in the first quarter, once again beating
virtually every forecast. It's hard to imagine any country
threatening America's sole-superpower status for decades. It's even
harder to recall that only a decade ago Washington was still
preoccupied with Japan's buying spree in Hollywood and on Wall
Street, and wringing its hands about the successes of Asian-style
capitalism.
</P>
<P>
   But the celebration of U.S. supremacy sometimes obscures the far
more complex risks of managing world affairs amid global economic
and political fragility. And the truth is that Washington is still
a lot more comfortable containing an easily identifiable enemy than
managing a system where cracks on one side of the globe can radiate
to the other.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem is that weakness comes in many forms. There
is Russian-style weakness, an inability of the state machinery to
make the country function, to keep control. Whatever temporary
pleasure Americans derived from watching the Russian military
threat fall apart has been tempered by the fear that economic chaos
has put its nuclear expertise up for sale.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the Cold War we knew that Russia's nukes were under
strict control, but we were terrified of the people controlling
them,'' said Michael Mandelbaum, a Johns Hopkins University
professor who has written about the new challenges of managing a
global system in which leaders are overwhelmed by the forces around
them. ``Now the fear about Russia is that nothing is under anyone's
clear control _ not the taxation system and not the
atomic-industrial complex.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   And then there is Japanese-style weakness, a subject President
Clinton will be carefully dancing around Monday as Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi arrives for an official visit. In Tokyo the problem
isn't a collapsing state; it's a chronic inability to get political
consensus, whether the issue is bolstering security in Asia or
remaking the world's second-largest economy.
</P>
<P>
   Obuchi will be arriving with the news that the lower house of
Parliament has finally passed legislation that would allow it, in
theory, to act like a real ally of U.S. forces should a military
emergency break out in the Pacific. But the bill was stripped of
several key elements, including one that would let Tokyo
participate in enforcing international sanctions, and the Pentagon
still fears that if North Korea lashes out, Japan may sit on its
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate concern is whether Japan's seven-year
recession is finally ending, as the Japanese insist. If not,
Japan's troubles could choke off Asia's fragile recovery and force
the United States to continue taking in a wildly disproportionate
amount of the world's exports. Sooner or later, that will cost
American jobs, which is why Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin warned
again last week that America's soaring trade deficits are ``not
politically sustainable.'' But in Japan's case, as in Russia's,
Washington has few levers to pull.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Washington is never quite sure with whom it should be
negotiating. Obuchi has scant control over the pace of Japanese
reforms. That power is in the hands of the country's scared
corporate heads, its much-criticized bureaucrats and its workers,
who are terrified by the rising unemployment rate and know that
they have few options if they lose their job.
</P>
<P>
   If Boris Yeltsin was once committed to reforming the Russian
economy, he has given it up. It is notable that ever since Russia's
currency devaluation and default on some of its debt last August,
the Clinton administration has cut back on providing free advice
about the wonders of making the transition to a market economy.
``It would only stoke their resentments further,'' one senior State
Department official said. ``We're wiser to shut up about reform.''
</P>
<P>
   But at least there is some agreement in Washington that a
stronger Japan and an economically stable Russia are in the
country's interests. Raise the subject of China, and it's a
different story. On Capitol Hill these days, China is once again a
power to be contained.
</P>
<P>
   The revelations of nuclear espionage bolster the arguments of
conservatives who say the Clinton administration has been blinded
by big business and big donors, and that it buried the evidence of
transgressions at Los Alamos because they threatened the policy of
engagement. Add their voices to those of human rights groups who
are horrified by China's recent crackdowns, unions that fear trade
deals, and Taiwan supporters who want more protection from the
mainland's missiles.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of the spectrum are Clinton and many of
America's China experts, who see 100 million jobless wandering the
Chinese countryside, failing state-owned enterprises and insolvent
banks that _ at the government's insistence _ keep those
enterprises afloat. And there are Russia-like symptoms: arms
proliferation, the rising power of organized crime, a military in
business for itself.
</P>
<P>
   The theory of integrating China into the World Trade
Organization _ the deal Clinton walked away from earlier this month
_ is that it would help the Chinese pull off the feat that the
Russians couldn't. It would force China to deal in a Western legal
system, to open up, to let a billion Web users bloom.
</P>
<P>
   A nice theory, but the reality is that Washington wants China,
like Russia, to be strong on Washington's terms. Washington wants
to encourage Chinese economic strength and discourage military
strength; it wants nations to independently find their own way to a
market economy _ as long as it runs strictly according to Western
rules.
</P>
<P>
   In short, Washington wants strong economies run by leaders who
will shrink their military power and act weakly beyond their
borders. But Washington is not likely to get what it wants.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1225EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
