<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1306 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WELFARE-MISSING-REVIE     05-01 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-MISSING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO BENEFITS, BUT NO JOBS: WELFARE'S MISSING-IN-ACTION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., Wis., N.J.)   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ They seem to be the disappeared, the missing, the lost
in action of the new welfare era.
</P>
<P>
   As more and more states track down former welfare recipients to
assess how their well-being has been affected by stricter
eligibility rules and more stringent work requirements, the
question of those not accounted for looms ever larger.
</P>
<P>
   The dimensions of the question are not trivial; the group of
people neither working nor on welfare amounts to more than
one-quarter of former recipients, state officials have said in
several preliminary reports.
</P>
<P>
   And in the information wars between advocates for the poor who
contend that recent welfare changes are too harsh and state
officials who present them as working well, the ``missing''
category is becoming a weapon that both sides seek to wield.
</P>
<P>
   There are two kinds of the unaccounted-for: those who simply
could not be found by trackers and those who have stayed off
welfare but are not working. Not on welfare but not working either?
What, then, are they living on? How do they survive?
</P>
<P>
   When Massachusetts issued its first detailed, long-term report
on how former welfare recipients seemed to be doing in mid-April,
Claire McIntire, the state's commissioner of transitional
assistance, immediately hailed as good news its findings that a
majority were working and only about 20 percent were back on
welfare.
</P>
<P>
   But her ``very first question'' to her staff, she said last
week, was, ``What is happening to the other 25 percent?'' So she
asked researchers to get back to her about how those who were
neither working nor on welfare were getting by.
</P>
<P>
   The answer was piecemeal. Of all the households that remained
off welfare, 75 percent had an adult member working, the
researchers found. The rest could be broken down like this:
</P>
<P>
   _ Just over 6 percent were in the process of re-applying for
welfare or other assistance;
</P>
<P>
   _ About 2.5 percent were getting some form of Social Security
payment;
</P>
<P>
   _ About 12 percent had been working in recent months but were
not at the time of the survey;
</P>
<P>
   _ The remaining 5 percent or so had other explanations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would not characterize them as missing,'' Ms. McIntire said.
``We know they're still around, and they have other means by which
they are supporting themselves and their families. And if they do
not, we want them to come back to us and we will help them get back
in the work force.''
</P>
<P>
   Such assertions draw vehement challenges from the advocates for
the poor who see the Massachusetts report more as cause to worry
than to rejoice. Unfamiliar with the official breakdown Ms.
McIntire had ordered internally, they had their own ideas of what
was happening with the missing 25 or 30 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``My guess is that some have probably moved in with former
spouses and boyfriends, of whom some are probably abusing them,''
said Randy Albelda, a University of Massachusetts economist, citing
the high percentage of welfare recipients who have suffered
domestic abuse. ``Some people are probably going underground and
doing illicit and illegal activities.''
</P>
<P>
   But basically, Ms. Albelda said, ``We don't know what's happened
to people, and it's going to get worse because the people who went
back on welfare will have no welfare to go back to'' now that time
limits in Massachusetts are kicking in. ``They're our missing,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The advocates also point out that the people who could not be
found at all for the survey, or refused to answer, are likely to be
worse off than those who answered, and that respondents were likely
to be less then honest because they were told that the information
they provided could be forwarded to their case workers.
</P>
<P>
   Around the country, there is a growing push to fill the holes in
the welfare puzzle. Jack Tweedie, who tracks welfare policy for the
National Conference of State Legislatures, said that, in the
simplest terms, the states made changes in their welfare programs,
their case loads dropped much faster than they had expected and the
immediate question became, ``What happened to those families?'' Two
key questions, he said, are, ``How many are working and how many
are in desperate circumstances?''
</P>
<P>
   That broad picture is now emerging. State reports have tended to
show that about two-thirds of former welfare recipients get jobs
and about one-fifth find themselves even poorer than before.
</P>
<P>
   So now, Tweedie and others said, efforts to track the families
that left welfare are getting more advanced, and officials are
beginning to ask follow-up questions about how former recipients
who have not found work are supporting themselves, and what exactly
are the barriers that keep them from getting jobs.
</P>
<P>
   In Wisconsin, said Jan Van Vleck, a state expert on post-welfare
tracking, the latest survey asked the question, ``If you have not
identified any forms of support, could you let us know how you are
living?''
</P>
<P>
   One way many are likely to be living, Tweedie noted, is by
depending even more on family than before. A New Jersey study of
certain former recipients, he said, found that as they were leaving
welfare, 38 percent said they planned to get a job; but only about
half of those people actually did. And just 23 percent said they
would depend on family support, but then a full 47 percent actually
did.
</P>
<P>
   The worry is that such family support may not be sustainable for
long, he said, because the families that former recipients depend
on are usually poor as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1250EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
