<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0091 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0543 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-NYT &LR;      05-01 0778
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITHOUT ELWAY, BRONCOS COULD BECOME ORDINARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There are excruciating draft day decisions, ones that keep
personnel men in the National Football League awake for days
afterward. And then there are the no-brainers. One day in 1983,
Ernie Accorsi had an easy choice to make. No advanced degrees
required.
</P>
<P>
   On the draft board of the Baltimore Colts, staring at Accorsi,
singing to him, was a baby-faced quarterback out of Stanford named
John Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the easiest decision I made in football,'' said Accorsi,
then the Colts' general manager and now the Giants' general
manager. ``It was like drafting Willie Mays.''
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi would pick Elway, then be forced to trade him to Denver
after Elway refused to play in Baltimore. Elway and Accorsi, one of
the smartest personnel men in football, would cross paths again.
</P>
<P>
   It was Elway who practically single-handedly beat Accorsi's
Cleveland Browns with the Drive in the 1986 American Football
Conference championship game. ``That's a game John will probably
always remember,'' Accorsi said, ``and one I would like to
forget.''
</P>
<P>
   The cannon-armed Broncos quarterback went on to one of the most
brilliant athletic careers in any sport, with five Super Bowl
appearances, including victories in the last two.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is one of those rare players who can change the course of a
team, and I think he changed the course of a league,'' Accorsi
said.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's career comes to an end Sunday, when it is expected he
will officially announce his retirement after 16 seasons. And in
retirement, Elway's impact could be just as great as it was when he
was on the playing field. Nature abhors a vacuum.
</P>
<P>
   So there will be a number of quarterbacks scrambling to fill the
void left by Elway, and plenty of teams hustling to take advantage
of what is perceived as a now weakened franchise in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   With Elway gone, the landscape of the division he dominated _
the AFC West _ is wide open. Elway's backup, Bubby Brister, was 4-0
in games he started in place of Elway last season, but because of
injuries, Brister has not played a full season since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping Brister healthy is the biggest challenge for coach Mike
Shanahan. If Brister goes down, the Broncos will be in trouble. The
second-year quarterback Brian Griese is not ready yet, and Chris
Miller, who signed on as a free agent during the off season, has
not played since retiring because of severe concussions in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge to the defending Super Bowl champions could come
from almost anywhere in the conference. In the AFC West, the
Seattle Seahawks have the talent, and a great coach in Mike
Holmgren, to beat the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest threat to Denver will probably come from the AFC
East, perhaps the most powerful division in football and one with a
stellar cast of quarterbacks. Buffalo has Doug Flutie, and
Indianapolis has a mature Peyton Manning and a vastly improved
defense. Miami has a motivated Dan Marino, since time is running
out for him to win a championship, and New England has Drew
Bledsoe, who would love to take over Elway's title as football's
most prolific passer.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has always beaten up on New England, especially at Mile
High Stadium, and Elway played some of his best football in those
games. When the Patriots heard of Elway's retirement, the team
probably broke open a bottle of Champagne.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are the team most prepared to knock off the Elway-less
Broncos. They almost did it in the AFC title game last season,
jumping to an early lead before being torched by Elway.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets have loaded up on free agents in the off season, to add
depth and firepower. One Jets player said he and other players have
talked frequently in recent days about how they are now the team to
beat.
</P>
<P>
   For the Broncos, the man in charge of keeping the barbarians
from storming the gate is Shanahan. The former coach of the year
still has lots of talent to work with in wide receivers Rod Smith
and Ed McCaffrey, tight end Shannon Sharpe and running back Terrell
Davis, who rushed for more than 2,000 yards last season.
</P>
<P>
   But Denver definitely loses something with Elway's retirement,
one element being a psychological edge. Teams knew that almost no
lead they earned was safe because in the wink of an eye, Elway
could come back. Brister, through no fault of his own, does not
inspire that kind of fear. ``It will be different for us, without
John,'' Shanahan said. ``There is no question that the Denver
Broncos will never be the same again.''
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the league, of course, isn't exactly misty-eyed.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
