<HEADER>
A0545 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYWOOD-FEUD-REVIEW     05-01 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-FEUD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S LATEST LIVE ACTION: RAGING BULLS, PART II 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD _ In the hierarchy of values in Hollywood, money
dominates. But no one likes to talk about it. While it's perfectly
normal to discuss marital infidelities, drug addiction, sexual
dysfunction and other intensely personal matters, money is,
curiously, not mentioned because everyone is so obsessed with it.
</P>
<P>
   But now two of the dominant players in town, Michael Eisner,
chairman of Walt Disney Co., and Jeffrey Katzenberg, who worked for
him for 10 years as chairman of Disney studios, are not only
talking about money _ they're publicly attacking each other over
it.
</P>
<P>
   Not one but two golden Hollywood rules have been broken. The
town is not only mortified but fascinated by the odd legal battle
now going on in a Century City law office as if passing a car wreck
on the 405. No one can quite believe it's happening.
</P>
<P>
   At one level, the issue is Katzenberg's contention that he's
owed at least $250 million, and perhaps double that, from Disney in
profits from projects he helped create from 1984 to 1994 including
``The Lion King,'' ``The Little Mermaid, ``Aladdin'' and ``Good
Morning, Vietnam.'' In 1994 he quit in anger when Eisner failed to
promote him to No. 2, president of Disney Co. Katzenberg went on to
found Dreamworks with Steven Spielberg and David Geffen. Disney has
acknowledged that Katzenberg deserves some bonus payment but
nothing close to the amount he's seeking.
</P>
<P>
   In short, the case pits two very rich moguls against one another
_ not exactly the stuff of high courtroom drama or even a good
movie.
</P>
<P>
   At another level, though, the Katzenberg-Eisner clash has
elements of almost Shakespearean drama. The two men, who were both
raised on Park Avenue in New York, were virtual brothers for nearly
two decades. Their fallout was personal, even destructive to
themselves. The case, said Katzenberg's lawyer, Bertram Fields, was
``about the personal animus of one man'' _ Eisner.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the case seems to be about the outsize animus of both men
toward one another, a raging hatred that has led them to break the
Hollywood code of behavior that decrees that no one talk about
money and no one hurl public abuse at each other. (Private abuse is
quite another issue.)
</P>
<P>
   Eisner and Katzenberg will, of course, survive the case and, no
matter what happens, will remain extraordinarily rich. But their
reputations, at least for the moment, are damaged by the case.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week, with Katzenberg on the stand, he was depicted
by the Disney lawyer, Louis Meisinger, as a studio executive whose
live-action films were $231 million in the red when he left the
company _ a sharp rebuke to Katzenberg.
</P>
<P>
   Disney also released letters that sought to diminish Katzenberg.
To assure his profits, Katzenberg wrote a letter that ordered
Fields to be ``an absolute killer.'' Following an acrimonious
contract negotiation in 1988, Katzenberg wrote Eisner: ``You've
been great. You've handled my crap with extraordinary patience and
understanding. I'm deeply appreciative and do love you for it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the hearing, Fields asked his client, Katzenberg, to confirm
that he received $100 million in compensation during his years at
Disney. Fields also asked if Eisner had received $1 billion during
the same period, and Katzenberg answered yes _ before retired Los
Angeles County Superior Court Judge Paul Breckenridge sustained
Meisinger's objection.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Eisner, who is scheduled to appear in court this
week, was depicted by Katzenberg and Fields as duplicitous. At the
same time Fields said that the Disney senior executive vice
president, Sanford Litvack, and Irwin Russell, a Disney board
member and Eisner's personal attorney, made misleading and false
statements about Katzenberg's contract. The three ``came up with a
story,'' said Fields. ``Each story is patently untrue. I don't say
that lightly.''
</P>
<P>
   In the clubby and highly secretive world of Hollywood's power
elite _ in which Fields himself is a member in good standing _ such
public accusations would have been unthinkable. Until now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1256EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 12:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1309 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOLLYWOOD-FEUD-REVIEW     05-01 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOLLYWOOD-FEUD-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOLLYWOOD'S LATEST LIVE ACTION: RAGING BULLS, PART II 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
