<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 13:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0547 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKE     05-01 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 The Week in Review  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Red Alert for America's Forests
</P>
<P>
   Red maples, long seen as the poor relations of the maple family,
are taking over America's Eastern forests.
</P>
<P>
   Once confined to swampy areas, red maples have gained a foothold
on drier upland soil, thanks to a decline in forest fires, which
have been suppressed during the last century. The fires used to
destroy the trees while sparing dominant species like oaks, with
their thick bark and deep, extensive root systems.
</P>
<P>
   The red maples, which can thrive under almost any set of upland
conditions, show remarkable aggressiveness and resilience, getting
the jump on other species by dropping their seeds in spring rather
than in autumn, and using chemicals in their leaves to repel gypsy
moths, which devour oaks and elms.
</P>
<P>
   Scientists have found that red maple saplings today tend to
dominate the carpet of young trees and shrubs under the forest
canopy, and when existing oaks and related species like hickory die
or are cut down, the red maples will replace them.
</P>
<P>
   It is hard to miss these arboreal invaders. Their foliage is
green in the summer but turns brilliant scarlet or crimson in the
fall. In the winter, the buds and many twigs are red. In the
spring, so are their flowers and the whirlybird seed pods that hang
from drooping red stems.
</P>
<P>
   If the maples succeed in driving out oaks, a variety of small
creatures, from birds to nut-eating animals to insects that live in
oak bark, will go with them. The result could be a less vibrant
ecosystem, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   One way to change the trend would be to restore fire to the
woods, as is often done today for conservation reasons. But the way
things are going, scientists say, the oaks and other species that
have dominated the region's forests for 10,000 years may one day be
lost in a sea of red.
</P>
<P>
   _ By WILLIAM K. STEVENS
</P>
<P>
   An Import That Japan Likes
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. This isn't another Viagra joke.
</P>
<P>
   The fact remains, though, that Viagra's wonders never cease. The
latest evidence? The pill has inspired Japanese bureaucrats to move
with, relatively speaking, lightning speed.
</P>
<P>
   Consider: the low-dose birth control pill has for years
dominated the contraceptive market in the United States and
elsewhere. Among industrial nations, only Japan failed to approve
it. The application has been languishing for a decade there _ a
molasses-like timetable that is apparently typical of the Ministry
of Health and Welfare.
</P>
<P>
   When these sober bureaucrats caught wind of Viagra, though, they
flew into action, giving it the go-ahead in a head-turning six
months.
</P>
<P>
   Could the difference have anything to do with the ministry
consisting of 198 men and 6 women? Absolutely, critics say. ``Japan
is a male-dominated society,'' said Tomoko Adachi, a Tokyo
gynecologist. ``Many Japanese women do not even want to have
Viagra.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, said urologist Takaaki Minami, ``Many women who have
gone through menopause say that Viagra will be a nuisance.''
</P>
<P>
   Nuisance or no, Japanese men are jubilant. Shigeharu Kobayashi,
an insurance executive, said, ``I'm 60 years old, but I think I'm
16.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By HUBERT B. HERRING
</P>
<P>
   Court Rejects Theory In Espy Prosecution
</P>
<P>
   With a narrow interpretation of the federal gratuity statute,
the Supreme Court made it substantially less likely that someone
could inadvertently cross the line between bestowing gifts on a
public official and committing a crime. The unanimous decision
rejected the theory behind an independent counsel's prosecution of
former Agriculture Secretary Mike Espy and of an agricultural
cooperative convicted of giving him tennis tickets and other items.
</P>
<P>
   The court said such gifts were illegal only if linked to an
``official act,'' hoped-for or accomplished; merely cultivating
good will is not a crime.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Justices to Rule on Tobacco
</P>
<P>
   It was far from a victory in the tobacco wars, but it was the
best the Clinton administration could hope for from the Supreme
Court. The justices agreed to decide whether the Food and Drug
Administration has the authority to regulate tobacco products as a
drug. While a ruling is perhaps a year off, the court thus kept
alive the prospect of federal regulation of smoking, which appeared
dead last summer when a federal appeals court ruled that Congress
had never given the FDA jurisdiction over cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   _ By LINDA GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   More Damage in Spy Case
</P>
<P>
   Government officials now say a scientist already suspected of
spying for China may have given away secrets to virtually every
nuclear weapon in America's arsenal. Mainly in 1994 and 1995, the
scientist, Wen Ho Lee, downloaded computer codes from a classified
system at the national laboratory in Los Alamos, N.M., and
transferred the data to a widely accessible computer network at the
lab, officials said. Senior members of Congress expressed outrage
over the government's failure to monitor Lee.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Eases Some Sanctions
</P>
<P>
   Trade sanctions were once a preferred method of punishing
nations linked to terrorism, like Iran and Libya. But a two-year
Clinton administration study has concluded that sanctions on food
and medicine tend to backfire, doing little to counter terrorism
while depriving innocent civilians. As a result, the White House
announced that as a general rule, food and medicine will be exempt
from sanctions. An early beneficiary will be Iran, which will
probably be allowed to import $500 million worth of U.S. grain and
sugar.
</P>
<P>
   _ By PHILIP SHENON
</P>
<P>
   Palestinian Delay on Statehood
</P>
<P>
   Backing down from a pledge that Israelis regarded as a threat,
Palestinian leaders decided against declaring statehood May 4, the
end of the five-year interim period set up under the Oslo peace
accord. Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat urged the Palestinian
Central Council to abandon the idea of pronouncing the West Bank
and Gaza Strip a Palestinian state less than two weeks before the
Israeli elections. He told the council that U.S. and European
officials, and some Arab leaders, had asked them not to make a
unilateral declaration at this sensitive moment in order to avoid
rupturing the peace process.
</P>
<P>
   The council will resume its talks over the fate of the state in
June.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1304EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
