<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0099 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0549 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VENEZUELA-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      05-01 1188
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR VENEZUELAN VOTERS, A NERVOUS HONEYMOON 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ He is a head of state now, no longer a
renegade colonel plotting a coup d'etat. At his insistence, a cowed
Congress has given him the authority to rule by decree, and voters
here last week convoked a Constituent Assembly that seems likely to
greatly expand his powers and term of office. But three months
after he was sworn in as president, Hugo Chavez continues to
perplex and unnerve Venezuelans, not to mention the rest of Latin
America.
</P>
<P>
   There is no denying that Chavez, a 44-year-old former
paratrooper who in 1992 led a bloody but failed attempt to
overthrow the elected government of this South American nation, is
the most intriguing political figure to emerge in the region in
years. His speeches, railing against privilege and corruption and
promising a peaceful ``social revolution'' that will redeploy
Venezuela's vast oil wealth to improve the lives of the masses,
have electrified a citizenry that had grown cynical and despondent
about the prospect of change.
</P>
<P>
   But Chavez has also engaged in behavior that can only be
described as bizarre coming from a head of state, and has
demonstrated little understanding of _ or patience with _ the
normal give and take of politics as conducted in a democracy. A
former associate who has broken with the president calls him ``a
Jekyll and Hyde'' figure with pronounced authoritarian tendencies,
and Chavez himself seems to take pride in baffling all who would
demand consistency, either intellectual or deportmental, from him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are designing something completely new here, and from the
ideological point of view I absolutely refuse, and will refuse to
the grave, to let myself be labeled or boxed in,'' he said
recently. ``I cannot accept the notion that politics or ideology
are geometric. To me, right and left are relative terms. I am
inclusive, and my thinking has a little bit of everything,
especially at this moment in which paradigms are being shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez's recent threats to dissolve Congress and the Supreme
Court, institutions he calls ``worm-eaten and decadent,'' and to
send his supporters into the streets can be viewed as an exercise
in bare-knuckles political brinkmanship. As tactics, they are
perhaps coarse, and summon unsettling memories of past military
strongmen in the region like Juan Peron. But they have proven
effective and are hardly surprising, given that Chavez came to
maturity in a military environment where orders were given and
obeyed.
</P>
<P>
   It is far more difficult to explain the friendly letter Chavez
wrote recently to the terrorist Carlos the Jackal, a Venezuelan
serving a life sentence in a French prison whose acts include
murder, hijackings and the kidnapping of OPEC oil ministers in
1975. Venezuela is a member in good standing of the oil cartel,
whose recent success in scaling back production to push up gasoline
prices could not have occurred without the cooperation of Chavez's
Government. But that did not prevent Chavez from addressing Carlos
the Jackal as a comrade in arms in the same unnamed cause.
</P>
<P>
   It is simply human solidarity,'' said Chavez, who was clearly
offended that his motives were being questioned when the existence
of the letter surfaced and there were criticisms of his conduct
here. ``I was in prison for two years, and I know it is
heartwarming when one receives a letter.''
</P>
<P>
   Though many of his public pronouncements have a left-populist
flavor, Chavez has discomfited the Jewish community and others here
by cultivating a friendship with an obscure Argentine writer,
Norberto Ceresole, who maintains the Holocaust never occurred.
Ceresole espouses a neo-fascist doctrine that calls for bypassing
political parties in favor of a ``leader-army-masses'' triangle,
and many observers claim to see traces of that philosophy in
Chavez's harsh attacks on Venezuela's two main political groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``He trusts no political party, not even his own,'' the
amorphous Fifth Republic Movement, said the ambassador of a
European country. ``He sees himself as embodying the desires of the
masses and having a direct link to them, and so his vision of
democracy sees no need for intermediaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration would surely prefer a more
conventional political leader in charge of a country that in recent
years has become the United States' principal source of imported
oil. Chavez was in fact banned from traveling to the United States
after the 1992 coup attempt. But the ban was lifted after he was
elected president in December, and he visited Washington before
taking office in an effort to patch things up.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that is past history,'' a State Department official said
earlier this year. But recently there have been signs of tension in
the relationship with Washington. Granted, the Clinton
administration expressed no objections to the referendum here, in
which more than 80 percent of voters endorsed Chavez's call for an
assembly to write a new constitution. ``The important point for the
United States government is that the process of reform move forward
in a democratic fashion,'' said White House spokesman Joe Lockhart.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, a visit by an assistant secretary of State
scheduled for late April was postponed indefinitely after
Venezuelan Foreign Minister Jose Vicente Rangel, a prominent
journalist who is well-known for his anti-American outbursts,
accused Washington of exerting ``elements of pressure'' to thwart
Chavez's efforts to transform Venezuelan society. What drew
Rangel's wrath was the latest of numerous U.S. statements
expressing support for Chavez so long as he respects ``democratic
parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, whatever autocratic ambitions Chavez may harbor
are constrained by countervailing institutions and a balance of
powers that has been put in place during more than 40 years of
democracy. But the constituent assembly, which is scheduled to
begin six months of deliberations in July, is likely to change all
that, and Chavez maintains that, despite a recent Supreme Court
ruling to the contrary, the 131-member assembly will have the power
to dissolve the legislative and judicial branches of government.
</P>
<P>
   To amused applause, a satirical revue that has been drawing
packed houses here since shortly after Chavez was elected suggests
that his long and increasingly frequent speeches on television need
subtitles to explain what he really means. Venezuela, a comedian
remarks, is living through a ``state of transition,'' which he
defines as ``going from one mess you know to another that is
completely unknown.'' When he says that, though, the response is
not applause, but nervous laughter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
