<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-STRATEGY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WAR IN BALKANS STRETCHES PENTAGON'S RESOURCES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The war in the Balkans is stretching the Pentagon's
longstanding global strategy, which calls for dedicating enough
forces to the Persian Gulf and the Korean peninsula to fight and
win wars in both places at the same time.
</P>
<P>
   In early April, the Navy shifted its only aircraft carrier in
the western Pacific, and its 75 combat jets, out of the region
indefinitely to help wage the Yugoslav campaign. The Pentagon
briefly suspended enforcement of the no-flight zone over northern
Iraq when fighter-bombers and radar-jamming planes were dispatched
to the air war.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon's fleet of refueling planes has been spread so thin
that President Clinton last week ordered the first of 33,000
reservists called up to sustain round-the-clock bombing runs. And
the Air Force general who commands U.S. combat planes says the
military is running dangerously low on its most potent cruise
missiles and satellite-guided bombs fired from B-2 bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is going to be really touch and go,'' Gen. Richard Hawley,
head of the Air Combat Command, said last week.
</P>
<P>
   Dealing with two full-blown regional military crises at the same
time has been a centerpiece of Pentagon planning since the end of
the Cold War. The strategy calls for waging two overlapping ``major
theatre wars.'' That has meant conflicts in the Persian Gulf and on
the Korean peninsula.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody anticipated we'd be doing a war in Europe,'' said
Zalmay Khalilzad, a Pentagon official during the Bush
administration. ``In the midst of Kosovo, should something develop
in both the gulf and North Korea, there would have to be some
extremely tough choices made.''
</P>
<P>
   For a decade, critics have derided the strategy's underlying
assumptions, dismissing the likelihood of two simultaneous wars and
the idea that a shrinking American military could move large
amounts of weaponry and materiel quickly enough to a far-flung
second front.
</P>
<P>
   But with the Balkans conflict intensifying, and allied forces
waging a low-grade air war in northern and southern Iraq, the
strategy does not seem so far-fetched anymore.
</P>
<P>
   If a crisis arises on the Korean peninsula, Pentagon officials
have put scores of bombers and fighter planes in the United States
on alert to fill in for forces sent to Yugoslavia. The aircraft
carrier Constellation in San Diego, not due to sail to the Pacific
until June, is on 96-hour notice to deploy earlier, if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq and North Korea have shown no signs of trying to exploit
NATO's preoccupation with the Balkan crisis, American intelligence
analysts say. Nonetheless, Pentagon officials are anxiously
watching both countries.
</P>
<P>
   Gen. Henry Shelton, the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
told Congress last month: ``Suffice it to say that what we have
going right now in Kosovo is a major theater war worth of air
assets. It has strained the force in the Pacific theater.''
</P>
<P>
   The strains would worsen if the United States and its NATO
allies reversed their opposition to invading Kosovo with ground
troops. In that event, 100,000 to 150,000 American soldiers could
be needed.
</P>
<P>
   These worries have prompted grumbling from some senior regional
American commanders, and top officers at the military's Joint Staff
in Washington, about the impact of a request from Gen. Wesley
Clark, an army general and NATO's military commander, for 300
additional American aircraft and more bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone kind of looks at this saying, `You got to be
kidding,''' said one senior Air Force general. ``Clark has
advertised this to be a major regional war, and he's making the
prophecy come true. It seems to be a lot of aircraft for the amount
of air space he's got.''
</P>
<P>
   An Air Force munition ship normally based at Diego Garcia in the
Indian Ocean, which supplies aircraft bound for the gulf or the
western Pacific, was ordered diverted last week to the
Mediterranean to supply the war effort there.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force also risks running out of its prewar supply of
some 900 joint direct attack munitions, the satellite-guided bombs
dropped off the B-2 bomber, before the next scheduled shipment from
the manufacturer in May, Hawley said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon had already said it had fewer than 80 of its
3,000-pound cruise missiles that are launched off B-52 bombers.
Congress approved an emergency request to convert 92 nuclear-tipped
cruise missiles to conventional payloads, but even so, those will
not be ready before the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Joint Chiefs of Staff are closely watching the strains the
Yugoslav campaign has put on forces earmarked to defend the gulf
and Korean peninsula. The burden is especially heavy on limited
numbers of highly specialized reconnaissance, surveillance and
radar-jamming planes, as well as the transport ships and planes
that would have to rush American forces from one conflict to
another.
</P>
<P>
   The fighting in Yugoslavia, Shelton says, now means there is a
much higher risk that any second regional war would be protracted,
with significant casualties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they both happen bing, bing, that's the worst case,'' said
an officer on the Joint Chiefs of Staff, who said virtually all
American peacekeeping, humanitarian and training exercises would be
sharply reduced or canceled.
</P>
<P>
   Many congressional Republicans, who have long complained that
the administration has shortchanged the military's budget at the
same time it piled on new humanitarian or peacekeeping operations,
now say the United States should curtail its involvement in
overseas missions, reverse the decade-long trend of a shrinking
military, or both.
</P>
<P>
   Today's 1.4 million-member active-duty military is two-thirds
the level of the Cold War armed force of the 1980s. Since then,
demands on the Army, Navy and Air Force from overseas missions have
increased by 300 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The time has come that we should pull out of some of these
commitments or enlarge the force and better equip them,'' said Rep.
Floyd Spence, R-S.C., who heads the House Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Some military commanders say the war in Yugoslavia will only
worsen this strain. ``We are seeing an increase in stress on the
forces left behind in the states, those that would augment next,''
said Hawley. ``They are seeing a decline in readiness and I expect
that will become more aggravated the longer this operation
continues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1323EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
