<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0561 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-HUNGARY-2TAKES     05-01 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-HUNGARY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON CONFLICT'S FRONT LINE, HUNGARY FEELS ANXIETY
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUDAPEST, Hungary _ At night, Attila Chikan's mother, a woman in
her 70s whose generation recalls World War II, hears the bombers
over Yugoslavia, even though, her son says, ``from where she lives,
it's physically impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   For the generation of Chikan, 55, Hungary's economics minister,
the war over Kosovo is a sharp contrast to memories of vacations in
Yugoslavia in the 1970s, when Tito's reform Communism inspired
restless young Hungarian economists.
</P>
<P>
   The minister, a professor of economics, is also in touch with
students. That generation, he said, ``doesn't understand the war,
from the point of view of rationality.''
</P>
<P>
   In less than a decade, Hungary has gone from a front-line member
of the old Warsaw Pact in a Cold War to being a front-line state in
NATO's first hot war, and the experience is straining the nation of
10 million _ politically, economically, militarily, and
individually.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the first NATO tankers began flying from Hungary, and
attack aircraft will soon use its air bases for their sorties. A
sense of anxiety hangs over Hungary, a sense of support but not
enthusiasm for the war, and even that is not felt uniformly through
the generations of a nation that persistently finds itself sitting
astride the fault line between East and West. The war erupted less
than two weeks after Hungary, Poland and the Czech Republic joined
NATO. Hungary's willingness to aid the war effort has angered
Russia, its former ally.
</P>
<P>
   A visit to Moscow by the Hungarian foreign minister was canceled
and Moscow recalled its ambassador for consultations.
</P>
<P>
   The war threatens the Hungarian economy, which only recently
began recovering from the financial shock of last year's Russian
economic meltdown and which is faced with slowing growth in western
Europe, now its major trade partner.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary, its people are quick to point out, is the only NATO
state bordering Yugoslavia, and there are misgivings over the fate
of the Hungarian minority in Serbia's Vojvodina region, north of
Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   Vojvodina Hungarians, some fleeing military conscription in
Yugoslavia, others uncomfortable with the regime of President
Slobodan Milosevic, are fleeing to Hungary.
</P>
<P>
   They are joined by a wave of Serbs, not impoverished masses like
many of the Albanians from Kosovo who have flooded Albania and
Macedonia, but middle class people and members of the political
opposition, disillusioned after years of peaceful dissent as much
by NATO's bombs as by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Sztojan Vujicsics, a Hungarian writer of Serb descent (in some
of his writings he uses the Serb spelling of his name, Stojan
Vujicic), said Hungarians are intent on fulfilling their
obligations to NATO. ``But they don't want to destroy
Serb-Hungarian relations, which are very ancient,'' he said. ``The
war will end, with all its consequences. But neighbors are
neighbors, and we will continue living here.''
</P>
<P>
   After five weeks of airstrikes, with NATO appearing to stumble
politically and militarily, he said, ``a dilemma is arising both
among intellectuals and the common people.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There is rising anxiousness,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Like many in this corner of Europe, Vujicsics' family reflects
Hungary's complex historical weave. In the 17th century, his
forebears fled Turkish expansion in Serbia. Ever since, his family
has remained here, in the heart of a sizable Serb community. Now he
welcomes the latest wave of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Otto Horvath is the son of Hungarians from Novi Sad, in northern
Yugoslavia. Shortly after the bombs began falling there, he and his
wife left for Budapest, where he has family. They managed to cross
the Yugoslav border on a technicality involving a German visa
Horvath had obtained for academic purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hungarian is his mother tongue, Horvath, 32, speaks
fluent Serbian. Indeed, in 1987, when he was barely 20, his first
thin volume of Serbian verse was awarded Yugoslavia's most
prestigious young poets' prize.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hungary could have been an intermediary,'' he said, over
coffee, with bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   He is no friend of Milosevic, but the bombs, he said, are
destroying civil society in Yugoslavia. ``The land is destroyed,
there is no money, no economy,'' he said. He does not intend to
return when the war ends.
</P>
<P>
   Compared with Yugoslavia, Hungary is flourishing, and he and his
wife quickly found work teaching. Like some other Yugoslavs, ethnic
Hungarian and not, they have found the Hungarian government fairly
uninterested in their lack of citizenship.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, growth here was 5.1 percent, and at least 4 percent
is expected this year, double the rate in western Europe. The
Budapest stock market, battered last summer by the Russian crisis,
has sprung back.
</P>
<P>
   Yet when Laszlo Koszonits, managing director of Mahart,
Hungary's river shipping company, looks out over the Danube from an
office a block away, he sees that it is empty of ships. Earlier
this month, NATO bombs destroyed bridges over the river in Novi
Sad, paralyzing traffic on one of Europe's longest inland
waterways, a vital artery for the Balkans, central Europe and
Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four ships and 24 barges _ 20 percent of our total capacity _
are stranded,'' he said. Revenues this year are projected to be a
third to a half lower than last year's $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cruise liners no longer ply the Danube from Vienna to the Black
Sea, hurting tourism. The Dunaferr steelworks, down-river at
Dunaujvaros, is scrambling for alternative carriers for the iron
ore it hauls up from the Black Sea and the steel rolls and sheets
it ships out, said Mihaly Schneider, the marketing director, at an
increased cost that makes the steel less competitive.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, said Koszonits, `'the West paid to destroy those bridges,
and the West will have to pay to rebuild them.''
</P>
<P>
   Hungarian officials fear the war's effects on tourism, which
accounts for 9 percent of the economy. And Moscow's anger could
lead to cuts in oil and gas supplies, which come mainly from
Russia, and would cost more to replace.
</P>
<P>
   While NATO membership has increased Hungary's attractiveness to
foreign investors, the effect could be neutralized if investors
perceive the war-torn region as inherently unstable.
</P>
<P>
   There are no signs this is happening yet. Nokia, the Finnish
phone company, is building a big research center here, and the
German car maker, Audi, plans a $600 million factory. But the
longer the war lasts, the greater the risk becomes. ``I think it
grows exponentially, because of the increasing mistrust of this
area.'' Chikan said.
</P>
<P>
   Tamas Wachsler, the state secretary in the Defense Ministry,
said Hungary has sent a 35-member medical team to Albania, and its
military planes are airlifting food and other supplies for the
refugees there.
</P>
<P>
   But to protect its minority in Yugoslavia, Budapest has told
NATO that Hungarian troops will not get directly involved in the
war, and that there is no way Hungary could be used as a staging
base for a NATO ground invasion of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to avoid Hungarians under the NATO flag fighting
against Hungarian conscripts under the Yugoslav flag,'' Wachsler
said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jozsef Kasza, the ethnic Hungarian mayor of Subotica, the
largest Hungarian city in Yugoslavia, recently warned Hungary's
prime minister, Viktor Orban, against ``toying with the fate'' of
the Vojvodina Hungarians.
</P>
<P>
   With the expulsion of the Kosovar Albanians, said Wachsler, the
Hungarians are Yugoslavia's last minority, ``which is of primary
concern to the Hungarian government, obviously.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, there are no signs that Belgrade is moving
against the ethnic Hungarian minority. Indeed, Hungarian newspapers
have reported promotions of ethnic Hungarian officers in the
Yugoslav Army, in an apparent bid for loyalty, although Wachsler
said he could not confirm this.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys in Hungary show 55 percent of the people supporting the
airstrikes, and 75 percent backing NATO membership, up from 60
percent at the time of accession in March. Yet two-thirds back the
ban on using Hungarian troops in action.
</P>
<P>
   With the dismemberment of the old Hungary by the Trianon Treaty
of 1920, Hungarian minorities remain not only in Yugoslavia, but
also in Slovakia and Romania. Governments in both those countries
now include Hungarian ministers. More than anything else,
sensitivity to minority rights appears to steel Budapest's resolve
in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Janos Martonyi, the foreign minister, said that ``patience and
determination'' were required.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the end, we cannot allow it when a government decides to
massacre one part of its population based on religious or ethnic
issues,'' he said. At the end of World War II, he said, ``there was
fundamental agreement that that could never happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to understand that NATO just cannot lose,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
