<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 13:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0564 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TRANSPLANTS-5TAKES-AR     05-01 1169
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRANSPLANTS-5TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS LOOK AHEAD TO AN ERA OF NONESSENTIAL TRANSPLANTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ky., Calif., Mass., N.J., Fla., Ohio, Wash., Mo., Pa., Iowa,
Wis., N.C., Vt. , Ga., France, Australia, Canada, Ecuador, England,
Germany, South Africa, Italy, Spain)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Transplant surgeons who once concentrated on vital organs like
hearts, livers and kidneys are branching out, transplanting an
array of body parts with surprising success, and possibly heralding
a day when tissues not essential to life are routinely given to
others.
</P>
<P>
   To the astonishment of many experts, the two men recently given
new hands in Lyon, France, and Louisville, Ky., are progressing
well, without rejection crises. With less publicity, surgeons
elsewhere have successfully performed experimental knee, larynx,
trachea, femur, nerve and muscle transplants.
</P>
<P>
   The newer transplants are believed to be few _ no central
organization keeps a tally and there is no way to know how many
people would benefit from them if they prove successful in the long
term.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as word of the early successes spreads, doctors are
beginning to stretch their imaginations. Leading transplant
surgeons envision a future where they can put new faces on burn
patients; give a woman new breasts, or even a uterus; transplant
penises; and reconstruct jaws and neck tissues for patients with
cancer, gunshot wounds, dog bites or accident injuries.
</P>
<P>
   But the new, non-vital transplants raise disturbing ethical
questions. With rare exceptions, transplant recipients must, for
the rest of their lives, take powerful anti-rejection drugs, whose
side effects include increased risks of infection, diabetes, cancer
and other conditions. Who should decide if the risk is worth the
reward? Who should pay for the procedures? If they prove effective,
will people be willing to donate their tissues for nonessential
operations?
</P>
<P>
   ``This is second only to cloning as an ethical issue,'' said Dr.
Rollin K. Daniel of Newport Beach, Calif., who was part of a team
that performed experimental hand transplants on baboons in the
1980s at McGill University in Montreal.
</P>
<P>
   The new transplant operations are generally experimental and
must be approved by an ethics committee before they are carried
out. Many of the newer procedures failed when they were tried years
ago. Improvements in surgical techniques, drug therapies and tests
to monitor rejection crises have paved the way for the revival, but
until scientists learn more about the new procedures, no one can be
sure whether they will revolutionize medicine or end up as
footnotes in medical history.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, though, a few doctors in fields like orthopedics and
transplantation who were not aware of each other's work have begun
sharing information, learning about advances in other specialties
and trying to apply them to their own fields.
</P>
<P>
   Some surgeons are expressing tempered excitement at the
explosion of possibilities. Success with the hand transplants, for
example, could even lead to radical procedures like face
transplants in a burned child, said Dr. John H. Barker, head of the
Louisville team's research program.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are tickled to death just because we can now give something
that looks like a jaw back to somebody,'' Barker said. ``But it
does not look very cosmetically pleasing at all.'' With the new
transplants, ``we could tackle things that are very difficult to
reconstruct, like the tongue,'' he said. ``There is nothing that
you can steal from anywhere in the body that will make a tongue.''
</P>
<P>
   Transplants are being considered as new treatments for disease.
For example, researchers are testing whether a thymus transplant
can restore an immune system destroyed by the AIDS virus.
</P>
<P>
   But beyond the thrill of breaking new medical ground is an issue
that gets far less attention: How to manage rejection of a
transplanted tissue that is not essential for life in an otherwise
healthy person. The underlying assumption is that the drugs can be
stopped, the donor part can be amputated, and the patient's health
will not have been significantly harmed. But some critics question
how well such a patient's body would respond after having been
immunosuppressed for long periods.
</P>
<P>
   For life-saving heart, liver and other organ transplants, ``you
can always justify upping the doses of the medication because the
alternative is death,'' said Daniel, the Newport Beach surgeon.
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue here is: Are you ever justified to put a patient's
life at risk on an on-going basis with immunosuppression just to
justify a quality of life transplant?'' Daniel said. ``If suddenly
the transplants start failing, who will be there for the patient?
At what point are you going to draw the line to ask: `How much
damage have you done?' and say that it is not worth a life to save
this transplant?''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Ramon Llull, a plastic and transplant surgeon at the
University of Pittsburgh who went to Germany to learn about knee
transplants, argues that non-vital transplants could be worth the
risk. Immunosuppressing drugs are used to treat some cases of
non-life-threatening conditions like psoriasis and rheumatoid
arthritis, he pointed out. ``If so, why can't we use the same
therapy for nonessential transplants?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Review boards vary in their willingness to approve human
experiments. But once approved, it is the patient who decides
whether to accept the risks.
</P>
<P>
   Patients' views should be given more weight in deciding whether
to proceed with an experimental operation, said Dr. Thomas E.
Starzl, the surgeon who in 1963 performed the world's first liver
transplant. ``The relationship between doctors and patients is too
much like that of a warden in a prison,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In time, the costs of the new operations could become a point of
contention. For now, most of the transplants, which can cost
$200,000 and more, are experimental, require long periods of
supervised rehabilitation, and are financed by private research
funds, often with time donated by doctors. If the operations become
standard, it would be up to insurance plans as to whether they
would be covered, as transplants of vital organs generally are now.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the uncertainties, patient demand drives much of the
effort. There are plenty of patients who say they are willing to
take large risks to get a new hand, joint or voice to restore their
physical and psychological well-being.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say you can live without a voice,'' said Dr. Marshall
Strome, who gave a patient a new larynx in Cleveland in January
1998. Yet, he said, ``One of the first candidates was a gentleman
who had been 10 years without his larynx following cancer and, as
president of the Lost Voice Club, was telling people how easy it is
to live after having a laryngectomy.''
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   HANDS
</P>
<P>
   The first hand transplant _ performed in Ecuador in 1964 _ was a
dismal failure, rejected in two weeks. Thirty-four years later,
last September, an international team of surgeons in Lyon announced
they had given another man's hand to a 48-year-old Australian,
Clint Hallam. Surgeons in Louisville, Ky., did the same on Jan. 24
for Matthew Scott, 37, of Absecon, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   The operations were undeniably feats of surgical virtuosity,
requiring the joining of nerves, muscles, bones and so on. But in
interviews, other transplant experts sounded more appalled than
impressed.
</P>
<P>
   The ``operation is dangerous and irresponsible,'' said Susan E.
Mackinnon, a plastic surgeon at Washington University in St. Louis
who has done research on nerve transplants for 20 years. She added:
``All it's going to do is save a limb, it's not going to save a
life. I wouldn't save a limb for immunosuppression for life.''
</P>
<P>
   At Washington University, Mackinnon contended, the ethics
committees that govern experiments with humans would have rejected
a proposal to do a hand transplant without more compelling evidence
of success in animal experiments. Other critics contend that the
teams should have started with patients who lost both hands because
they had the most to gain in a successful experiment.
</P>
<P>
   The surgeons who performed the hand transplants reject such
criticism. They proceeded with great care, they said, noting that
ethics committees at two separate institutions approved the
operations.
</P>
<P>
   The head of the Louisville team, Dr. Warren C. Breidenbach, said
his surgeons devoted three years to preparation, including
experiments in which they gave pigs new limbs for up to four
months, at which point they killed the animals to study the
transplantation. Moreover, he said, even before seeking surgical
candidates, they announced their intent to perform the procedure
and solicited comment at scientific meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Both patients are gaining strength and function in their new
hands. But it will be at least a year from the transplant before
either man can learn what degree of sensation and other nerve
function will return. Since the transplant, relations between
Hallam and his doctors have become strained, and Hallam said in an
interview that he is planning to hire his own team of physical
therapists to speed up function of his new hand.
</P>
<P>
   On April 12, Scott, who lost his hand more than 13 years ago in
a fireworks accident, threw out the first ball at the Philadelphia
Phillies home opener. Last week, Scott left Jewish Hospital in
Louisville to return to his job in paramedic management and
teaching at a community college. He now can grasp thin objects such
as a poker chip from a table; turn a door knob; use a computer;
pick up a glass to drink; and hold hands with his young sons, a
hospital spokeswoman said. He will continue supervised physical
therapy in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   Even at best, the new hands will never be the same as the
natural hands, the transplant surgeons said.
</P>
<P>
   Were it not for the novel work of a German surgeon, it is
unlikely that Hallam and Scott would have new hands.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1996, the surgeon, Dr. Gunther O. Hofmann, transplanted
a knee to an accident victim who otherwise would have undergone
amputations or walked with a rigid leg.
</P>
<P>
   That patient, and three other men after him, sought knee
transplants and accepted the risks of immunosuppression drugs
because they wanted to continue to be athletic.
</P>
<P>
   Now the men, aged 17 to 47, have resumed working, surfboarding
and participating in other sports, Hofmann said in an interview
from his clinic in Murnau, near Munich.
</P>
<P>
   Like hand transplants, the knee operations involve transplanting
several types of tissue at the same time _ arteries, veins, bone,
bone marrow, cartilage, ligaments and muscle. Unlike the hand, they
do not involve skin and nerves.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Hofmann, who said his clinic is the largest
trauma center in southern Germany, was a critical factor in the
decision to proceed with the hand transplants.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann's team, which also has performed three experimental
femur transplants, has established strict medical criteria for
selecting patients for knee transplants ``because we are aware of
the problems with a non-vital transplant,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Only people who have destroyed their knee joint and knee cap and
lost the ability to straighten a leg are eligible. The injury must
have occurred within the last six months. The team will not operate
on any candidate for an artificial knee joint or other procedure to
repair or reconstruct the joint.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Hofmann estimated that he would have performed 50 knee
transplants by now, except for difficulties in finding enough
donors.
</P>
<P>
   The four men who received new knees have varying limitations in
movement, but all are vastly better off than without a transplant,
Hofmann said.
</P>
<P>
   One, a German dentist, has resumed full-time practice in Spain.
A second, Elmar Deugebauer, works for UPS in Germany and does heavy
lifting. ``He should not, but he does,'' Hofmann said. The two
other men, who had to change careers because of their injuries, are
in business school. One had had 30 operations before the knee
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Llull, the plastic and transplant surgeon at the University of
Pittsburgh who went to Murnau to examine the knee patients, said he
was ``astonished'' when he visited Hofmann's clinic. ``They had
fabulous results,'' Llull said.
</P>
<P>
   The UPS worker was so enthusiastic about the surgery that he
drove 700 miles to show off his knee to Llull, who had the patient
walk up and down stairs. The only abnormality he detected was
slight swelling, Llull said.
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann said he was not aware of any other group that has
attempted knee transplants, in part because few orthopedic surgeons
have had experience with transplant surgery. ``Everyone is waiting
for the first five-year results of our program,'' he said, because
``we have had problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Hofmann was referring to a fifth transplant patient, a
32-year-old woman who had undergone two major operations that
failed to reconstruct her damaged knee. She suffered two severe leg
infections, which Hofmann's team thought it had controlled before
performing the knee transplant. But three weeks after she began
taking the anti-rejection drugs, the infection recurred. To beat
the infection, she had to stop taking the immunosuppressant drugs,
but her body then rejected the new knee. With no working knee
joint, she will walk with a rigid leg.
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Each year, millions of people worldwide benefit from the most
successful of all transplants _ blood transfusions. Tens of
thousands can see through new corneas or benefit from bone and
cartilage transplants used in knee, hip and other orthopedic and
reconstructive surgery.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979, Dr. Claus K. Herberhold of the University of Bonn took
the success with cartilage transplants a step further, performing
the first trachea transplant in an adult.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, more than 130 people have been given windpipes to
replace tracheas that were narrowed or malformed from birth
defects, destroyed in accidents, or scarred after having breathing
tubes in the windpipe for long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   No failures have been directly related to the operation,
Herberhold said. It has given the gift of normal breathing to
people who used to feel like they were trying to breathe through a
straw. Still, largely because the initial reports were published in
German, it was almost 20 years before a trachea transplant was
performed in this country, by Jeffrey P. Jacobs of All Children's
Hospital in St. Petersburg, Fla.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs only learned of the technique because he had gone to
London to train in heart surgery with Dr. Martin Elliott at the
Great Ormond Street Hospital. In 1994, Elliott, who had heard from
colleagues about Herberhold's work, modified the technique for a
5-year-old patient. Instead of making a horizontal incision in the
neck to reach the trachea, as Herberhold did with adults, Elliott
made a vertical incision and split the breast bone to reach the
lower end of the child's trachea. Meanwhile a heart-lung bypass
machine maintained the child's circulation and breathing.
</P>
<P>
   As with cartilage transplants used in orthopedic surgeries, the
trachea, which is made of fibrous cartilage, is treated with
chemicals to destroy foreign materials known as antigens that could
trigger rejection reactions. The tissues are transplanted without
their blood supply, which also lowers the risk of rejection.
</P>
<P>
   The transplanted cartilage acts as a sheathing to allow it to
merge with the body's own cartilage. A plastic stent is temporarily
inserted to prevent collapse of the trachea.
</P>
<P>
   In the first few weeks, cells from the recipient start growing
along the inside lining of the new trachea. The cells have
hair-like projections that help brush away infectious agents and
particles that trickle down the trachea. With time, the new trachea
appears normal when doctors use a tube to look at it. The
transplanted cartilage does not seem to grow. But because the
long-term growth potential of donated trachea is not known,
surgeons use an oversized trachea just to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   After Jacobs returned to Miami, in September 1996, he and
Elliott performed the first trachea transplant in the United
States, on a teen-age girl. With the permission of federal health
officials, Elliott brought a donor trachea from England.
</P>
<P>
   Until her operation, the girl had severe breathing problems and
often could not go to school. ``The operation turned the girl's
life around,'' Jacobs said. Now she plays volleyball and softball.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs said he has done three additional cases, plans a fourth
this week, and that three surgeons in Boston, Iowa City and
Philadelphia each has done a tracheal transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Tissue banks in Miami, London and Bonn now collect tracheas.
Herberhold said he was working with a company, Biodynamics, in
Erlangen, Germany to make tracheal cartilage more widely available.
THE LARYNX  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tim Heidler was going about 40 miles an hour on his motorcycle,
eager to get to a firefighting class in 1978, when he ran into a
cable strung between two trees. The cable severed his esophagus,
crushed his larynx and caused serious internal bleeding. Surgeons
operated for eight and a half hours, and were forced to leave him
with a permanent hole in his windpipe.
</P>
<P>
   In recovering, Heidler developed hepatitis, and a
life-threatening staphylococcal infection nearly led to amputation
of his legs. After two years and 27 operations, he was released
from the hospital, but he could not speak on his own.
</P>
<P>
   About two months after the accident, Heidler began using an
electric voice box, or electrolarynx, a device also used by
thousands of accident victims and laryngeal cancer patients. But it
was hard to use. ``People were trying to figure out how you're
talking and were not paying attention to what you are saying,''
said Heidler, now 40 years old and living in Duncansville, Pa. ``It
has that robotic voice to it, and you almost have to watch the
person's lips to understand.'' When on the telephone, he said,
``People just think they are talking to a computer, and they just
don't pay any attention.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Heidler heard a news report about a trachea transplant
in a young girl. A friend, a nurse, wondered whether something
similar could be done for him and learned that Dr. Marshall Strome,
a Cleveland surgeon, had conducted 12 years of research on animals
to develop a larynx transplant.
</P>
<P>
   The only other laryngeal transplant ever performed was a partial
one, on a 62-year-old man with laryngeal cancer in Ghent, Belgium,
in 1969. The man spoke, but he died of the cancer soon after.
</P>
<P>
   On Jan. 3, 1998, as Strome removed the dead man's larynx, he was
not sure it would fit Heidler because it was much larger and shaped
differently than his patient's.
</P>
<P>
   The operation took 12 hours. Because of the injuries and repairs
made 19 years earlier, Strome had to transplant the larynx and a
group of adjacent tissues. They included 70 percent of the throat
and two glands in the neck: the thyroid and parathyroid. He also
connected a key nerve, known as the recurrent laryngeal nerve, on
one side. The one on the other side had shriveled and could not be
found at surgery, Strome said.
</P>
<P>
   Strome told his patient it would be six weeks before he would
let him use his new voice. But three days after the operation,
Strome said he ``couldn't stand it any longer.'' He strolled into
Heidler's room, put a glove on to cover the hole in Heidler's neck,
and said: ``I want you to breathe out and say hello or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Heidler said that with his head and neck so swollen, he thought,
``no way.'' But though the words were raspy, he was speaking again.
``Hello,'' he said. ``Hi, Mom.'' By last summer, Heidler was
singing. More recently, he has sung hymns in church, but cannot get
high tones yet.
</P>
<P>
   His words are clear, though still a bit raspy. But vocal quality
depends not just on the larynx but also on the size and shape of
the mouth, throat, sinuses and so on. So Heidler's voice resembles
neither that of the donor (a singer whose voice is preserved on
tape) nor Heidler's old one.
</P>
<P>
   Because Strome is working in uncharted waters and the only
information comes from animal experiments, he is not sure how much
he can lower the dose of immunosuppressant drugs, which he would
like to do to decrease the risk of infection. Reflecting on his
role as a human guinea pig, Heidler said, ``The only difference
between me and the rat is I can talk and the rat can't tell you how
it feels.''
</P>
<P>
   Strome said he had five patients who want a new voice. But they
cannot afford the $200,000 estimated cost, and insurance companies
will not pay for the experimental procedure.
</P>
<P>
   Debates over the ethics are valid, Strome said. ``But what about
the folks who don't want to live their life without a voice?'' he
said ``Shouldn't they have the opportunity to have it done, if they
understand the risks?''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   Susan Mackinnon's harsh criticism of hand transplants largely
reflects her experience with the nerve transplants that she does to
help repair injuries in young people.
</P>
<P>
   Her approach is unusual because she aims to produce a temporary
transplant. The donor nerve is used to form a scaffolding to bridge
a missing segment of nerves, which is intended to last long enough
for the recipient's body to regenerate its own nerves. That usually
occurs at a pace of about an inch a month.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, the recipient takes the standard immunosuppressive drugs
for the time it takes for the nerve to regenerate _ about two years
_ not for the lifetime required in other transplants. Then the body
can safely reject the donated nerve.
</P>
<P>
   Nerve transplants are intended to avoid amputation of a limb.
Mackinnon, who is a professor of plastic and reconstructive surgery
at Washington University in St. Louis, said she has been very
strict in selecting the eight recipients of the nerve transplants
that she has been performing since 1988 when she worked at the
University of Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   The recipient's nerves were damaged accidents. Their ages ranged
from 3 to 26 years.
</P>
<P>
   One transplant failed, showing that ``even a small nerve can
reject,'' Mackinnon said.
</P>
<P>
   In repairing severed nerves, Mackinnon first tries to join the
ends, or fill a gap by taking a piece of nerve from the leg or
elsewhere in the patient's body.
</P>
<P>
   But some injuries require larger sections of nerve than the
patient can spare. It is in such cases that Mackinnon has used
nerve transplants to bridge the gap temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it appears a transplant of a spinal cord is beyond
reach because it contains thousands of nerve connections.
</P>
<P>
   The human nerve transplants are born out of Mackinnon's 20 years
of research on regeneration and immunology on rats and primates.
Mackinnon first performed a peripheral nerve transplant on a human
in 1988, and she then waited five years before doing another
``because nerves grow slowly, and it takes a long time to know
what's going on,'' she said. With experience, she has found that
for unexplained reasons cooling the nerve for a week improves the
outcome.
</P>
<P>
   Her technique has been picked up by doctors at Baylor College of
Medicine in Houston and at Children's Hospital in Boston. In the
summer of 1997, they were considering a similar transplant on a
girl who had severe nerve damage in her arm. A few hours after she
celebrated her first birthday, the girl's father suddenly died. The
girl's doctors, led by Dr. Joseph Upton, took nerves from the
father's arms and legs and gave them to his daughter. She is
``doing fantastically well,'' Upton said, but cautioned, ``it will
take time and growth to more objectively determine the degree of
function provided by the transplant.''
</P>
<P>
   On April 13, doctors at Baylor took a nerve from a father's leg
and a week later transplanted it into his 1-year-old son to repair
a paralyzed hand. The doctors are hopeful that the boy will have
hand sensation and movement in a year.
THYMUS  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Scientists are trying to broaden the uses of transplants in
treating disease and are focusing on AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The thymus is a gland deep in the neck and upper chest that
helps regulate immune function. Usually, the gland is largest in
childhood and shrinks with age.
</P>
<P>
   Pediatricians first performed thymus transplants, apparently
successfully, in the late 1960s to treat babies who were born
without a thymus from a rare condition called DiGeorge syndrome.
However, experts say they cannot completely interpret the results
today because of the inadequacy of the tests used to detect
DiGeorge syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, researchers experimented with thymus transplants
for AIDS patients, using thymus discarded during infant heart
surgery.
</P>
<P>
   Rather than transplanting the gland, Dr. Richard Hong at the
University of Wisconsin developed a technique to transplant thymus
into muscle. Doctors at five medical centers in the United States
conducted a trial involving 50 adult AIDS patients. But the thymus
therapy failed. Hong has since found that transplanting pieces of
donor thymus in the omentum (an apron of fat that covers the
intestines) is easier than into muscle in children with DiGeorge
syndrome.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Hong, now at the University of Vermont in Burlington,
teamed with Dr. Andre J. Nahmias of Emory University in Atlanta to
do experimental thymus transplants in four children dying of AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   The transplants were performed before the introduction of the
more effective anti-HIV drug combinations. Three of the four thymus
transplant recipients died of AIDS. But the first recipient, a boy,
improved and is doing well.
</P>
<P>
   As newer research shows that a shrunken thymus remains more
active later in life than previously believed, scientists are
focusing more on the damage that HIV, the AIDS virus, does to the
gland. Nahmias said his team is continuing thymus transplants in
monkeys in the belief that the transplants might have a beneficial
role among the substantial number of AIDS patients in whom the new
drug cocktails fail.
</P>
<P>
   Nahmias said he was ``convinced that up to 15 percent of adults
have HIV that hits the thymus and kills off the cells, and that
leaves nothing else but a thymus transplant to replace them.''
</P>
<P>
   Duke University scientists have used a variant of the technique
to transplant thymuses to five adults with AIDS. But in each case,
the thymus was rejected, although all five are alive. The approach
is also being tested by researchers in Australia.
(MORE) nn
</P>
<P>
   MUSCLE
</P>
<P>
   Heart transplants may be routine these days, but surgeons are
trying other twists on muscle transplants that show promise for
reconstructive surgery after cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Treatment for skin cancer had left James Crook, 56, with a
5-by-5 inch area of bare skull in 1996. Doctors at Washington
University in St. Louis wanted to use Crook's own muscle to cover
the area, but they could not because earlier surgery limited the
potential donor sites, and heart failure made him too high a risk
for surgery. So gauze covered the exposed skull for two months
while Dr. Timothy R. Jones, a plastic surgeon, searched for a
muscle donor.
</P>
<P>
   Crook was an unusual candidate for a muscle transplant because
he was already taking immunosuppressant drugs to preserve a donor
kidney. The first kidney transplant failed after one and a half
years due to a viral infection. But a second transplant had worked
well for four and a half years. The skin cancer was a common
complication of the anti-rejection drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   After finding a suitable donor, Jones took the deceased's
muscle, put it on the bare area of the scalp, and connected blood
vessels in the muscle and Crook's neck. Then the surgeons took skin
from Crook's leg to cover the bare scalp.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't need the muscle to function as muscle, but to
provide a blood supply to nourish the skin while it healed over the
bare skull,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we cared about was that the muscle transplant would allow
the overlying skin to stay healthy, and we doubted that Crook would
mount much of a rejection to the donor muscle,'' Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   But even rejection of the donor muscle would have benefited
Crook because a chronic rejection reaction can produce blood vessel
growth and scar tissue that would anchor the skin. If so, the skin
would live because it was Crook's tissue and it would be nourished
by the growth of blood vessels.
</P>
<P>
   The muscle transplant succeeded, but Crook's heart condition
worsened and he died about 18 months later.
</P>
<P>
   FUTURE  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In 1967, Dr. Christiaan N. Barnard in South Africa became the
first to successfully transplant a human heart and set off a me-too
fever among cardiac surgeons around the world. Experience soon
taught surgeons greater respect for the complexity of overcoming
the immune system's power to reject donated tissue. But now the
excitement about the hand transplants has some surgeons planning
similar transplants at their own centers.
</P>
<P>
   The next world first in transplant surgery could come from Rome,
where a plastic surgeon plans to apply to health officials to
transplant a penis. The surgeon, Dr. Nicolo Scuderi, said that
three people have requested a penis transplant. Two are women who
want sex change operations. The third is a man who had his penis
amputated in a sex change operation to become a woman but who now
wants to return being a man.
</P>
<P>
   It is not known whether the recipient of such a transplant would
be capable of having an erection.
</P>
<P>
   With this as with other procedures, critics say contend that
researchers are moving faster than animal experiments justify. Wait
a few years, they say, for perfection of strategies now being
studied in hopes patients will escape lifetime immunosuppresant
drug therapy.
</P>
<P>
   For example, scientists are studying chimerism, a common
reaction to transplantation in which there is two-way traffic:
cells from donor tissue migrate to the recipient's skin, and the
patient's own cells migrate to the transplanted tissue. They can
persist in harmony for years. A hope is to manipulate the chimeric
reaction to reduce the risk of rejection reactions.
</P>
<P>
   Some strategies involve taking cells or tissue from a donor,
treating it in a laboratory, and then injecting the material into
the recipient to prime the recipient's body to later accept a real
transplant.
</P>
<P>
   Another strategy involves bolstering a recipient's immune
defenses to counter rejection such as by developing antibodies
against one or more antigens. Antibodies are proteins that the body
forms to defend against triggers in foreign tissue known as
antigens. The hope is that the specially developed antibodies will
block recognition of specific antigens and allow the recipient's
body to tolerate a graft.
</P>
<P>
   For all her caution, Mackinnon, the Washington University
surgeon who criticized the hand transplant, foresees a new era.
``We are quite close to dramatic changes,'' she said.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
