<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REJECTED SUITORS SAY BELICHICK WILL SUCCEED PARCELLS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It appears that the Jets' defensive coordinator, Bill Belichick,
was much more popular in recent months than most people knew. As
teams began firing their head coaches during the off season,
Belichick's name was among the first they turned to on their
Rolodexes, as he quietly became one of the most pursued men in the
coaching derby.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the fact that he is not leaving the Jets may speak volumes
about the future plans of Belichick and his boss, Coach Bill
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Several National Football League team officials, speaking at
length for the first time about their pursuits of Belichick, said
they believed he could have had almost any open coaching job he
desired. But Belichick rebuffed all advances.
</P>
<P>
   Nine head coaches were hired after last season, and based on
interviews last week with officials of a majority of those teams,
Belichick was either the leading candidate or among the top three
candidates for almost every job. The only two teams not interested
were the Baltimore Ravens (the owner, Art Modell, had a rocky
relationship with Belichick when both were in Cleveland) and the
expansion Browns.
</P>
<P>
   Why are Belichick's actions so revealing? Team officials say
that when they contacted Belichick or a representative, they were
told that Belichick was grateful for the interest but that the plan
was for Parcells to coach the Jets for one last season and then
Belichick would take over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was told pretty much point-blank'' that Belichick was going
to coach the Jets after this coming season, said one general
manager.
</P>
<P>
   There has long been speculation that Belichick would take over
as coach next season for Parcells, who is also the general manager.
But the words of these team officials, all of whom spoke on the
condition of anonymity, seem to take the idea beyond speculation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, two league officials said Belichick received a $1
million bonus from the Jets this off season. Those officials
believe the bonus was given so that he would not leave the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   When Belichick will actually take over the Jets depends on
Parcells, who can be both predictable and hard to figure out.
Parcells may be set to retire, but what would a tough loss in a
conference title game next season do to his thinking? Would it make
Parcells, a great competitor, want to come back for another try?
</P>
<P>
   Belichick is one of the most intriguing coaches in the game. In
Cleveland, where he amassed a 37-45 record, he was seen as a
brilliant tactician who lacked the people skills to deal with the
news media and other members of the Browns' organization.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Belichick's reputation for having a great football mind has
grown, to the point where some executives believe he is among the
smartest coaches in the game. Concerns about his sometimes gruff
personality have apparently eased. Teams that checked out Belichick
were told that most Jets players loved to play for him; and NFL
officials know the stories of how Belichick will lock himself in a
room and break down film for hours.
</P>
<P>
   If Belichick and the Jets were to part ways in the near future,
he would be the most attractive coaching candidate around, the way
Mike Holmgren was after he left the Green Bay Packers.
</P>
<P>
   But Belichick probably will not be going anywhere. One reason is
that Belichick would most likely be given the same amount of
control that the owner, Leon Hess, has given Parcells. That is an
attractive reason to stay.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Belichick would inherit a franchise on the rise. While it
is true that the Jets sacrificed a chunk of their future, in draft
picks, to get Parcells from New England _ the Jets did not have a
first-round pick in this year's draft _ Parcells will leave the
Jets in great shape over all.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets are definitely the team to watch next season. Parcells
has made a number of personnel moves geared toward making it to a
Super Bowl immediately, and the team's road to a championship got
easier with the retirement of Denver Broncos' quarterback John
Elway. It is hard to believe that Bubby Brister will be able to
approach the level of excellence Elway sustained for so long in his
career.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is definite: Belichick would rather plan a game
against Brister than Elway.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing a Shock Absorber
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Chris Miller, who left the NFL nearly four years ago
because of multiple concussions, is now the third quarterback with
the Broncos behind Brister and the second-year player Brian Griese.
This time, though, Miller is taking extra precautions.
</P>
<P>
   Next season, he will use a specially designed helmet that
absorbs shock better than the helmets he used when he played with
the Atlanta Falcons and St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is major concern about Miller's health, and the
Broncos plan to watch him closely.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1337EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
