<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SOME, CLOSING THE DEAL CAN BE TOUGH GOING 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the last three outs that determine if a manager will
whisper those three little words to his closer. Not that the relief
pitcher is looking for his manager's love, but he does want his
respect, as well as that of his teammates' and that of his team's
opponents. The best way to get all of that is to get the last three
outs. But it's easier said than done.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not that easy,'' Bruce Bochy, the San Diego Padres'
manager, said. ``By far it's the toughest three outs to get.''
</P>
<P>
   The past couple of weeks have demonstrated that more vividly
than most stretches of the season. Nearly everybody who is anybody
in the closing business failed in trying to save a game, including
Trevor Hoffman, who last season had Bochy cooing 53 times in 54
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, you're shocked,'' Bochy said of Hoffman's
uncharacteristic failure against the Mets last Wednesday, ``but it
happens so quick there's no time to agonize.''
</P>
<P>
   Called on in the ninth inning to protect a 3-2 lead, Hoffman
gave up a leadoff single to John Olerud, and Mike Piazza crashed
the next pitch over the right-field fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to get that first guy,'' said Hoffman, generally
considered the best in his business. ``I just didn't make quality
pitches on either batter I faced. It showed. Two hits, two runs,
game over. There's no room for error.''
</P>
<P>
   With that performance, the 31-year-old right-hander matched his
blown save total of last season. This failure was worse, however,
because the Padres lost. Last season, when he squandered a 4-3 lead
over Houston on July26, he allowed the Astros only to tie the game.
The Padres won it in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   Saves have their critics. There are those who feel a save is
given too generously and say that some managers help their closer
pad his save total by bringing him in with a three-run lead when a
save is highly likely. Bobby Thigpen had such assistance from Jeff
Torborg, the Chicago White Sox manager, when he established the
major league record with 57 saves in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Bochy acknowledged that a closer falls into some easy save
opportunities and said, ``At times it can be a little misleading.''
But he added, ``He's going to have to get some tough ones, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting on his blown save, Hoffman said: ``A lot of people
don't put a whole lot of credence on saves. But it's not so much a
given. Games are important late. You never really know the
importance of those last three outs until you need them. Yet they
dictate how your club goes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres won the first game of the series, and Hoffman
suggested that had he held the second-game lead, they might have
carried that momentum into the third game Thursday and won that as
well. Instead, they lost two of three.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, John Wetteland turned a 6-5 Texas lead into a 7-6
Yankee victory in the ninth inning. Two days earlier, Wetteland's
eminently capable successor with the Yankees, Mariano Rivera,
allowed Toronto to score the tying run in the ninth. The Yankees
won in the 10th.
</P>
<P>
   That same day Mike Timlin, Baltimore's closer (with the Orioles,
that term might be an oxymoron), took a 10-8 lead over Oakland and
gave up a game-losing three-run home run to Tony Phillips.
</P>
<P>
   Closers are sometimes asked to maintain ties in the top of the
ninth, giving their teams a chance to win in the bottom half of the
inning. Last Sunday, as Rivera and Timlin lost leads, Roberto
Hernandez of Tampa Bay and Ugueth Urbina of Montreal were assigned
to maintain ties, and both failed.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez gave up two runs for a 6-4 Seattle victory;
Philadelphia scored four runs against Urbina and, after the Expos
rallied for two runs, won by 8-6. Ten days earlier, Rivera failed
to keep his team tied, allowing the Orioles two runs and a 9-7
victory, and just the other day Billy Wagner of Houston made a 5-5
score disappear by allowing Arizona to score five runs in the
ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Urbina had a shaky week. Six days before the tie game, he
relieved against Colorado in the ninth with a 10-8 lead and the
Rockies scored three runs and won, 11-10.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Beck of the Chicago Cubs and Jeff Montgomery of Kansas City
also encountered double-barreled trouble recently. Beck blew
ninth-inning leads on successive days against Milwaukee, the Cubs
losing the first game in nine and winning the second in the 10th.
The Royals lost to the Chicago White Sox and the Anaheim Angels
when each team scored three ninth-inning runs against Montgomery.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a special pitcher, a special mentality,'' Bochy said.
``You've got to be tough for two reasons. You have to get the outs,
and if you don't, you have to be ready to go the next day.''
</P>
<P>
   And with recent developments indicative of the life of a closer,
sometimes the next day doesn't turn out any better.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
