<HEADER>
A0575 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-     05-01 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 UNDATED: any better.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rojas Brings Up the Rear
</P>
<P>
   If closers are not immune to rude treatment, neither are other
pitchers. Before last Thursday, only one American League pitcher,
Justin Thompson of Detroit, had been battered for seven runs in one
inning, the Yankees wreaking havoc on the young left-hander on
April 11.
</P>
<P>
   But on Thursday another young pitcher, Roy Halladay of Toronto,
and Heathcliff Slocumb of Baltimore each gave up seven runs in one
inning, Halladay in the first inning, Slocumb in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The inning turned out to be Slocumb's last with the Orioles;
they released him the next day. As for Halladay, who in his first
20 innings this season had not permitted an earned run, Andy Sheets
of Anaheim hit a grand slam for the last four runs against him.
</P>
<P>
   The same day, Mel Rojas, the relief pitcher who did not like
pitching in New York, found that working for Detroit isn't so great
either. Returning to Seattle after being traded to the Tigers,
Rojas was rocked for the last five runs in the Mariners' 11-run,
fifth-inning eruption, then for six more runs in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Griffey Jr. brought the scoring to a climax against Rojas in
the fifth, swatting a grand slam, then produced the sixth and final
run in the sixth with a solo homer.
</P>
<P>
   The 11 runs Rojas gave up recalled Chan Ho Park's feat for the
Los Angeles Dodgers April 23 against St. Louis. Park also gave up
11 runs _ but in one inning, the historic one in which Fernando
Tatis slugged two grand slams.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn Against Johnson
</P>
<P>
   If good pitching is supposed to beat good hitting, why does Tony
Gwynn have more hits against Greg Maddux (35), Tom Glavine (28) and
John Smoltz (28), Atlanta's throttlesome threesome, than against
any other active pitchers?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think because those guys are around the plate more than
anything,'' Gwynn said. ``I always give them the benefit of being
the guy in charge. I'm like a counterpuncher. I try to counter what
they do. They're all around the plate, so you know you don't have
that far to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Johnson is another story. Gwynn, a left-handed batter,
wishes the left-handed pitcher were fictional, but once this season
and once last he has seen the reality that is Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denny Neagle is a guy I never saw the ball off of,'' Gwynn
said, discussing the pitchers who have been most difficult for him.
``He was always No.1, but I think he's getting bumped. Having faced
Randy Johnson twice, I have not sniffed the ball off of him yet.
He's punched me out four times in eight at-bats, not counting the
playoffs, which makes it like 6 in 14.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, 36 hits from 3,000 (through April 30) seldom strikes out.
While Johnson struck him out twice last Sunday, Gwynn has struck
out only four other times in 85 (through April 30) times at bat
this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've only struck out three times in a game once,''
Gwynn said, recalling a game against the Dodgers' Bob Welch about a
dozen years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Referring to Johnson, Gwynn said: ``The first two times up I
punched out and it was 0-2 the third time. It's hard not to panic.
It's hard not to say, `Well, I guess this is going to be the second
time.' But he ran a fastball in on my hands and I beat it into the
ground. I was like, `Yeah, I hit it, I put it in play.' That's the
first time in a long time I was satisfied just to put the bat on
the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   But Gwynn also felt that Johnson could have struck him out for
the third time if he had wanted to. All he had to do, the San Diego
star said, was throw a slider instead of a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   In his previous at-bat, Gwynn said, Johnson threw a slider, the
likes of which he had not seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I swear it broke that much,'' he said, holding his hands a few
feet apart. ``When I started to swing, I thought I was on it and it
just kept on going, and I struck out again. When you face Randy
Johnson, everybody talks about his heater, but it's his slider
that's hard to hit. It's got tilt, that kind of an angle, and it's
got that much break.''
</P>
<P>
   Oldest Trick on Henderson
</P>
<P>
   Rickey Henderson was able to laugh about it afterward in the
Mets' clubhouse, and that was just as well because it was humorous.
Donne Wall, a San Diego relief pitcher, picked him off first base
last Thursday, and he did it by first faking a throw to third,
where Rey Ordonez stood, then turning and throwing to first. It's a
move that rarely works, but it got the game's greatest base
stealer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know he had that move,'' Henderson said. ``I usually
know he has it. I saw him motion and I just had my mind made up I
was going to go. The weakest play of all got me. In a way it
embarrassed me. The oldest trick, the weakest play in the world got
you.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
