<HEADER>
A0580 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NIRELAND-KILLINGS-ART     05-01 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIRELAND-KILLINGS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ULSTER LAWYER'S KILLING CASTS SUSPICION ON POLICE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By WARREN HOGE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST, Northern Ireland _ Earlier this year, Rosemary Nelson,
a prominent civil rights lawyer, spoke at a ceremony honoring a
colleague whose killing in 1989 has long symbolized the danger of
practicing criminal law in Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   Now, her portrait shares space with his on a memorial mural in a
Belfast housing project.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nelson, 40, was killed March 15 by a bomb placed under her
car. The service she had led Feb. 12 marked the 10th anniversary of
the shooting death of Patrick Finucane at age 39.
</P>
<P>
   The two cases bear sinister similarities, chief among them the
charge by legal and human rights groups here and in the United
States that British security forces and the local police, the Royal
Ulster Constabulary, made them targets for killers by accusing them
of sectarian sympathies, threatened them with death through their
clients and may have colluded with the Protestant paramilitary
groups responsible for the two killings.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations, the European Parliament and concerned U.S.
members of Congress have joined the legal and rights organizations
in calling for an independent investigation into the deaths. And
Britain has come under increased pressure to end the emergency
regime that governs law enforcement in Northern Ireland under which
suspects are denied the legal rights common to other Western
societies.
</P>
<P>
   As often occurs in sectarian killings in Northern Ireland, Mrs.
Nelson and Finucane (pronounced Fin-OOO-kin), were killed
deliberately in the apparent safety of their own homes.
</P>
<P>
   Gunmen burst in on the Finucane family during Sunday lunch and
fired 14 shots into his body as he sat at the dining room table
with his wife and three children. The magnet bomb that killed Mrs.
Nelson was placed under her sedan while it was parked in her
driveway, and the explosion that killed her occurred on her street,
50 yards from the school where a sister was teaching and the
youngest of her three children, Sarah, 8, was on a recess break.
</P>
<P>
   Groups like the Belfast-based Committee for the Administration
of Justice and the New York-based Lawyers Committee for Human
Rights that have investigated the Finucane case over the years
turned up evidence that members of the Royal Ulster Constabulary
told Protestant paramilitaries that he was a militant for the
Catholic cause, that police knew of the plot to kill him and did
nothing to stop it, and that one of the Protestant underground
group's most notorious killers was a British agent.
</P>
<P>
   A month before the 1989 killing, Home Secretary Douglas Hogg,
Britain's top law enforcement officer, had told the House of
Commons in London that some Belfast lawyers were ``unduly
sympathetic to the cause of the IRA,'' an inflammatory charge in
the combustible politics of Northern Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever been charged in the case. Britain has conducted
two confidential judicial investigations and says it is unwilling
to reopen the case without new evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``No lawyer in Northern Ireland can forget what happened to
Patrick Finucane nor dismiss it from their minds,'' Mrs. Nelson
told a Congressional subcommittee in Washington last September.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations Special Rapporteur on the Independence of
Judges and Lawyers, Param Cumaraswamy, studied the consequences of
the Finucane killing last year and concluded that his death had had
a ``chilling effect'' on lawyers here. ``Solicitors informed the
Special Rapporteur that the murder led them either to give up
criminal practice entirely or to alter the manner in which they
handled terrorist-related cases,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In a separate report on the police in Northern Ireland, the
United Nations official said that the Royal Ulster Constabulary had
in general ``engaged in activities which constitute intimidation,
hindrance, harassment or improper interference.'' He expressed
particular concern that the police regularly ``identified
solicitors with their clients and their clients' causes as a result
of their discharging their functions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nelson opened her practice in Lurgan, 18 miles southwest of
Belfast, only a month after Finucane's death. She did not set out
to represent people involved in the conflicted province's sectarian
clash, but she found them coming to her after being turned away by
other lawyers.
</P>
<P>
   One case she took on was that of Robert Hamill, 25, a Catholic
man who was beaten to death by a mob of 30 men as he walked through
Portadown, a Protestant stronghold, in May 1997. She then
challenged the arrest of a man detained in the killing of two
policemen in Lurgan in June 1997, and succeeded in gaining his
freedom. She became most widely known for taking up the cause of
the residents of Garvaghy Road, a street intersecting Catholic
housing projects on the outskirts of Portadown that is the scene of
annual violent encounters over the insistence of the Protestant
Loyal Orange Order to conduct its traditional parade there.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   She began to get regular death threats in the mail and over the
phone, and clients told her repeatedly that police officers
interrogating them told them she was a paramilitary herself and
that she would be killed. They said police officers told them that
a disfigurement on the side of her face had come from an IRA bomb
she had been carrying. In fact, it came from an operation to remove
a birthmark.
</P>
<P>
   In Northern Ireland, people suspected of ``terrorist'' activity
can be detained for up to seven days without charge and cannot have
access to their lawyers for the first 48 hours. Lawyers are barred
from that week's questioning. It was during such periods of
detention, Mrs. Nelson told various investigating bodies, that
officers made their menacing comments about her to her clients.
</P>
<P>
   She also said she was roughed up and insulted by police officers
during the Garvaghy Road march of July 1997 when, as the lawyer
retained by the residents, she sought explanations from ranking
policemen.
</P>
<P>
   The Independent Commission for Police Complaints took up her
reports of death threats and completed its report nine days after
her death. The panel is known for seldom finding fault with police
practices, but it listed 16 ``serious concerns'' about the Nelson
inquiry. These included statements that police officers were
hostile, evasive, disinterested and uncooperative, that one arrived
for a hearing late and inebriated, that others read from prepared
statements and that some police witnesses showed an ``ill-disguised
hostility to Mrs. Nelson.''
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the sensitivities of the Nelson killing, Sir Ronnie
Flanagan, Chief Constable of the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
announced the day after her killing that the investigation would be
led by a constable from England and aided by the U.S. FBI.
</P>
<P>
   The Belfast-based Rosemary Nelson Campaign, the international
rights groups that have been monitoring the treatment of lawyers
here and the U.S. congressmen are insisting on an investigation
that will be international, armed with subpoena power and
completely independent of the Royal Ulster Constabulary. Even
though 14 of the investigating squad are not from the constabulary,
the 40 other members are, which may deter witnesses from coming
forward.
</P>
<P>
   The Northern Ireland peace settlement of last April called for
an end to emergency powers in the province and created a Human
Rights Commission, a Criminal Justice System Review and an
Independent Commission on Policing, headed by Christopher Patten,
the last British governor of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Nelson expressed fear over the continuing death threats but
felt that testifying openly before investigating panels here and
abroad would offer her protection.
</P>
<P>
   Her killing was ``not just an attack on the peace process,''
said Paul Mageean, legal officer of the Committee for the
Administration of Justice, where Mrs. Nelson was a board member.
``It was an attack on the whole notion that you can make change
through peaceful, legal means.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
