<SLUG> BC-TURKEY-SCARF-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATOR'S HEAD SCARF UPSETS TURKISH TABOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By STEPHEN KINZER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ISTANBUL, Turkey _ When Turkey's newly elected Parliament
convenes for the first time Sunday, it may face its first crisis
even before members take their oaths of office.
</P>
<P>
   A newly elected deputy from the Islamic-oriented Virtue party,
Merve Kavakci, says she will insist on taking her oath while
wearing her head scarf. That would probably lead to a confrontation
with the political establishment, which is strongly secular.
</P>
<P>
   The head scarf has become an inflammatory symbol in Turkey.
Powerful military and civilian leaders consider it a sign of
religious militancy and anti-secular beliefs. Some women, however,
say their scarves are simply an expression of fidelity to Islam and
have no political implication.
</P>
<P>
   Turkish women are free to wear their head scarves in public, but
are not allowed to do so in courtrooms, at public universities or
at official gatherings. Ms. Merve will be the first woman to seek
to wear one in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Bulent Ecevit has sent emissaries to leaders of
the Virtue party in an effort to head off a confrontation Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want there to be any tension when Parliament opens,''
Ecevit said. ``She can cover her head as she wishes in her private
life and in her private work in Parliament, but when she is in the
parliamentary chamber or in committee rooms, we expect her to
conform to established rules and traditions.''
</P>
<P>
   Virtue party leaders have said they are unable to overrule Ms.
Merve's decision. ``She gave the election authorities a picture of
herself in a head scarf, and they did not object,'' said one of
them, Abdullah Gul. ``It is up to her.''
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Ms. Merve, 31, said wearing the scarf is her
democratic right.
</P>
<P>
   ``If people who campaigned for democracy at their campaign
rallies were real democrats, they wouldn't be trying to block me,''
she said. ``Banning head scarves is a form of pressure. It shames
all political parties. If the deputies maintain their opposition to
head scarves, in the next election they will be buried at the
polls. I'm not going to take off my head scarf, and I'm not going
to resign.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Merve is one of two women elected to the new Parliament who
wear head scarves. The other one, Nesrin Unal, a member of the
rightist Nationalist Movement party, has said she will remove hers
when in Parliament.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to serve the people,'' Ms. Unal said. ``I don't
want a confrontation over the head scarf issue. That would create
tensions that would harm Turkey.''
</P>
<P>
   The central event Sunday was to have been President Suleyman
Demirel's decision about which political leader he would ask to
form Turkey's next government. But it is universally assumed that
he will give the job to Ecevit, and attention has been focused
instead on the prospect of a clash over Ms. Merve's head scarf.
</P>
<P>
   The first session of Parliament is traditionally presided over
by the oldest deputy, in this case 86-year-old Ali Reza Septioglu.
By coincidence, Septioglu was in the same position when Parliament
convened in 1991 and another female deputy, Leyla Zana, caused
pandemonium when she sought to take her oath in Kurdish instead of
Turkish.
</P>
<P>
   Septioglu ordered Ms. Zana removed from the chamber. She was
later arrested, tried and imprisoned on charges of supporting
separatism.
</P>
<P>
   Although Septioglu has not said precisely what he will do
Sunday, he has asserted that he ``will apply what the law
demands.''
</P>
<P>
   Debate over the head scarf reflects one of the fundamental
conflicts in modern Turkey. For years, Turkish leaders have warned
that allowing full political freedom here would plunge the country
into chaos by giving separatists and religious fundamentalists the
chance to spread subversive doctrines. But others say Turkey has
matured politically and is stable enough to survive the expression
of all points of view.
</P>
<P>
   The issue was unexpectedly brought to the top of the political
agenda earlier this week when the country's senior judge, Ahmet
Necdet Sezer, called for repeal of laws restricting freedom of
expression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
