<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 14:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0585 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOLS-WORSTEVER02-C     05-01 1634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOLS-WORSTEVER02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Columbine shootings harken back to Bath school bombing
 &HT;    By Steve Bennish
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATH, Mich. _ On a faultlessly beautiful May morning in 1927 _ a
day so beautiful it seemed to embody all the hopes of spring _ a
failing farmer named Andrew Kehoe decided the time was just right
to murder every child he could in this small village just north of
the state capital of Lansing.
</P>
<P>
   In a pair of dynamite explosions prepared in advance with
diabolical precision, Kehoe managed to kill 45 people, including
himself, and nearly destroy a school building with hundreds of
pounds of alarm clock-rigged dynamite he had secreted in the
school's sub-basement. Another 60 people were injured, some left
permanently disabled.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps a half-hour after the first explosion _ a detonation so
powerful that you could hear it 60 miles away in Mount Pleasant _ a
weirdly grinning Kehoe tooled up to the disaster scene in his newer
model Ford Model T pickup truck, beckoning Bath Consolidated School
Superintendent Emory Huyck to approach. Dozens of elementary school
students were already dead or dying nearby and rescue workers
feverishly tried to save those still trapped in the collapsed
school. Kehoe then executed his final act of wild, murderous rage,
detonating the truck packed with dynamite and shrapnel and killing
himself, the superintendant and two bystanders.
</P>
<P>
   Before Oklahoma City, before Littleton, Colo., before the latest
wave of bizarre, terrorist-style schoolhouse killings shook the
foundations of an American cultural landscape awash in violence,
there was the horror of Bath, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Today the incident is so faintly remembered and obscured by time
that major U.S. newspapers including The New York Times erred when
initially describing the Littleton, Colo., high school massacre as
the deadliest school slaughter in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, only a handful of elderly residents are alive to recall
Kehoe's bizarre wrath. All say there are no easy explanations.
</P>
<P>
   The 1920s were an era without today's familiar suspects _
ultra-violent Hollywood revenge fantasies, blood-engorged computer
games, and firearm glorification.
</P>
<P>
   But there were ominous hints to Kehoe's madness, hints that made
Kehoe something other than just another brooding Midwestern farmer
squeezed by a fast-approaching Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The date was May 18, 1927, just days before lucky Lindbergh
conquered the Atlantic Ocean. Kehoe, local farmer, prickly school
board treasurer and meticulous handyman who always wore a clean
shirt, was about to make history. Until a fuel-fertilizer bomb in
1995 destroyed the Alfred P. Murrah federal building in Oklahoma
City and killed 168 people, Kehoe's actions would stand as the
worst single act of peacetime terrorism in American history.
</P>
<P>
   Critic turned terrorist
</P>
<P>
   Today Bath Twp., pop. 6,387, remains a rural hamlet little
changed in 72 years. Kehoe's once model farm is nothing but open
field and woods. In a quiet corner of the modern Bath School stands
a display case containing fragile memories of what is known as the
``Bath School Disaster.'' A few photographs, newspaper clippings, a
school child's autograph book, portraits of child victims. Just
across the street is a park where all that remains of the old
school is the preserved cupola with American flag flying, some
concrete benches, a memorial plaque and lingering memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's history and you hope to learn from it,'' said Barb
Wilkins, 57, who helps her husband Gene run the museum. In light of
recent events, she reflects, ``it seems the wrong people are
learning too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Barb's mother, Lillian Reed, lost all her teeth in the
explosion. She was 13. ``It gives you chills from head to toe,''
Wilkins said.
</P>
<P>
   Local histories for sale in Bath _ notably the 1980 book,
``Mayday. The History of a Village Holocaust'' by Grant Parker, and
``The Bath School Disaster'' by M.J. Ellsworth _ paint Andrew Kehoe
as a familiar enough Midwestern type: something of a loner, born to
a large, prosperous Tecumseh Irish-Catholic farm family, one of 11
children his father had with three wives.
</P>
<P>
   Kehoe showed an early fascination for mechanics and electricity,
taking courses at Michigan State College in East Lansing. For some
time, he worked as an electrician in the St. Louis area before
returning to Michigan. In 1912, he married Nellie Price, also from
a large Irish farm family.
</P>
<P>
   Seven years later, the couple purchased an 80-acre farm in Bath
from Nellie's uncle's estate for $12,000. But farm product prices
were plunging and to add to the plight, locals in 1921 approved a
property tax hike to fund consolidation of the area's one-room
school houses into a single handsome two-story school district
building for 314 students.
</P>
<P>
   The tax hike on Kehoe's smaller-size 80-acre parcel took its
toll. Kehoe made his last mortgage payment that year. He would
remain in default to the estate's executors, a fact unknown to
local neighbors who saw in Kehoe a community leader. Residents,
many still sore at the tax hike, elected the handsome, blue-eyed,
steel-haired man to the school board in 1924 to represent them.
</P>
<P>
   Like a duck to water, Kehoe took to the job of board treasurer _
a role critics hoped would suit him and keep school spending in
line.
</P>
<P>
   As an added bonus, Kehoe's technical skills made him an everyday
sight at the school. His frugality extended to voluntarily fixing
for free anything mechanical that went wrong. It gave him
unrestricted access to the school _ a fact that in hindsight sent
chills down the spines of survivors. Also in ominous hindsight,
Kehoe seemed more happy when tinkering than farming. He showed a
cruel streak, shooting a neighbor's fox terrier who barked
persistently.
</P>
<P>
   Kehoe became an energetic school board squabbler. He tried
unsuccessfully to eject the strong-minded Army veteran
superintendent and then tried to cut his vacation time. He
successfully cut annual payments to the janitor. Kehoe pointedly
eyeballed the school's bus driver when he daily passed by the Kehoe
farm on his appointed rounds, timing him with a pocket watch. The
busy treasurer seemed to take particular pride in personally
handing out checks on payday. Meanwhile, he seemed to lose interest
in his farm as the politics of the board and community seemed to
turn against him. In the spring of 1926, he lost a run for township
clerk.
</P>
<P>
   Later that year, Kehoe's wife's family began foreclosure
proceedings. By this time, Nellie Kehoe, plagued by ill health,
spent much of her time hospitalized. Kehoe began taking out-of-town
trips, buying hundreds of pounds of explosives. The 55-year-old
Kehoe eventually amassed perhaps 600 pounds of a World War I
concoction called Pyrotol.
</P>
<P>
   No one guessed how he planned to use it.
</P>
<P>
   Day of rage
</P>
<P>
   By mid-May, Kehoe had packed the sub-flooring and crawlspaces of
the school with enough explosives to kill everyone there. He set
the alarm clock detonator for 9:45 a.m. _ a time well after school
began. Willis Cressman, 87, recalls seeing the familiar fix-it man
at the school at the start of the day, taking note of the entering
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw him that morning,'' Cressman recalled. ``He greeted us
and smiled at us.''
</P>
<P>
   Kehoe returned to his farm after stopping at the post office to
mail a package containing his meticulous accounting of school
finances, including a lengthy explanation of a 22-cent discrepancy.
By the time explosions rocked the school, it's believed Kehoe had
already murdered his wife. Back at the farm, Kehoe triggered
explosives he had packed into farm buildings. The farm exploded in
a tremendous roar. His wife's charred body was found the next day
amid the rubble. Kehoe had dumped her in a hog chute. Seeking to
have the final word, he attached a carefully stenciled wooden sign
to a farm fence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Criminals are made, not born,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   Wanda Cushman, 83, was 11 when her school blew up. She didn't
hear the explosion. She only felt it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The papers went up on our desk and then everything went. I
blew high in the air....and came down more or less. My hair was
full of plaster.''
</P>
<P>
   She recalls a scene of utter panic, with parents frantically
looking for their children. One little girl's body hung lifeless
from a coat hook on a door. ``Parents were crying and almost crazy
looking for their children,'' she said. ``We had no idea what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, perhaps because of a wiring glitch, 504 pounds of the
explosives planted at the school didn't detonate and were later
removed by authorities.
</P>
<P>
   When Kehoe drove up to the schoolyard for his grand finale, he
realized his plot had only gone so far and he'd succeeded in
destroying only a portion of the school that he hated.
</P>
<P>
   When Kehoe detonated his truck, startling the confused crowd
with yet another terrifying explosion, Willis Cressman, then 17,
was only 70 feet away. ``I knew it was time to get out of there,''
he recalled. He had hurt his feet badly jumping from the second
floor of the school after the explosion. He limped home but was
otherwise unharmed. Body parts were hanging in trees and nearby
cars were in flames, he recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Chester McGonigal, 87, was in the 10th-grade that year. ``We had
40 funerals in two days,'' he said. ``Saturday and Sunday, the
roads were packed. It was an awful thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For locals here, the massacre at Columbine High School rekindled
memories of that spring day in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   The town's pharmacist, Brian Stoddard, said sales of books about
the disaster have picked up sharply in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've sold about 25 in the past week,'' he said. ``It's not
forgotten.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
