<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO CONFLICT
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-JOVANOVICH _ NEW YORK _ A Q-and-A with Vladislav
Jovanovich, Yugoslavia's representative to the United Nations.
(Alexander, Cox News Service). 20. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-SERBS _ PARMA, Ohio _ The sun from a clear spring morning
shines on this well-kept Cleveland suburb and ignites the brilliant
color of the stained glass windows in. Sava Serbian Orthodox
Cathedral. Christ himself in luminous bloom along the southeastern
wall dominates the stout architecture of the eastern rite temple.
But He fails again this Sunday to brighten a preoccupying
somberness. America is at war with Serbia, which for the people of
St. Sava means their home is at war with their homeland. As they
have seen it portrayed by NATO, the U.S. and the media, the complex
and bloody history of the Balkan Peninsula, where Serbians defied
authoritarian rule in both World Wars to stand with America and its
Allies, has been simplified into the political equivalent of an
afterschool special. Good versus evil. Here, in one of America's
largest colonies of American Serbs, they want to tell the
complicated version of the fight over Kosovo and show how unfair it
was for NATO to choose sides in a decades old conflict burdened
with a record of atrocities by both. They are desperate advocates
for peace, but they feel ensnared in the portrait of their
nationality as aggressive, unyielding and wrong. (Montgomery, Cox
News Service) 25. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EUROPE _ PARIS _ The 19 NATO members and their two dozen
partners of the alliance left Washington last week following the
50th anniversary summit after putting forth an image of ``European
unity'' over the U.S.-led NATO bombing of Yugoslavia. But that
unified front may be just that, a front. We talk to people in
cities, towns and villages in Western Europe to gauge how much
unity there really is toward the bombings. (Roughton, Cox News
Service). 40. WITH PHOTO. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   EUROPE-DATA _ Data for a map showing contribution of each NATO
country to the bombing cause plus maybe a blurb on how each stands
with all this.
</P>
<P>
   (Roughton, Cox News Service). 30. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   HAITI-TROOPS _ PORT AU PRINCE, Haiti _ In February, Gen. Charles
Wilhelm, commander of the U.S. Southern Command, recommended
pulling U.S. troops out of Haiti. Not only have they failed to
bring the hoped-for stability, he said, but they are in danger from
the very people they are supposed to be protecting. Yet the troops
remain. As President Clinton tries to rally support for a
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, it would be embarrassing for the
administration to accept the general's call for a pullout. We spend
a day with the 500 or so U.S. troops that quietly continue a
five-year U.S. occupation of Haiti. The impoverished nation still
resents the last U.S. incursion, a 19-year occupation that ended 65
years ago. Just last fall Haiti's Parliament passed a law to make
the presence of foreign troops illegal. In Washington, members of
Congress also are questioning the U.S. presence, which costs $22
million a year. They say the money is a waste since most of it goes
to protect the U.S. troops. (Emling, Cox News Service). 30. WITH
PHOTOS (by the Palm Beach Post). MOVED
</P>
