<P>
   KOSOVO-PEACEKEEPERS (Brussels) _ Russia appears to be moving
towards agreeing to a U.N. Security Council resolution that would
authorize an armed international military force in Kosovo to allow
refugees to return even if Yugoslavia continues to refuse one, NATO
officials said Saturday. While Russia continues to say publicly
that it would veto any Security Council resolution with a
peacekeeping force that did not have the consent of Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic, NATO diplomats said there was
movement behind the scenes in Moscow if not yet in Belgrade. By
Craig Whitney. (Scheduled to move by 2:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news
file.)
</P>
<P>
   N.C.-BANK-ROBBERS (Charlotte, N.C.) _ Even though bank robbery
has been declining nationwide, the crime has become remarkably
common here. The state's banks, credit unions and savings
institutions were robbed 289 times last year, a 38 percent jump
from 1997, one of the highest increases in the country, according
to the FBI. In bank robberies per capita last year, North Carolina
was near the nation's highest, with 38.9 for each million people.
By contrast, such populated states as Illinois had only 21 per
million and New Jersey 11. By David J. Morrow. (Moved under 'a'
news file)
</P>
