<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 14:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0592 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PANAMA-CANAL-NYT &LR;      05-01 0993
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANAL'S FINAL RETURN COLORS VOTE IN PANAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MIREYA NAVARRO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY, Panama _ The ``Trautenbels,'' a 484-foot cargo
ship, was ushered from the Pacific Ocean into the Panama Canal by
tugboats, and by two electric towing locomotives into a water lane.
Steel gates snapped shut, enclosing the ship in a chamber, inside
which it was lifted by rising water, a process repeated twice more
at different points for a voyage up to 85 feet above sea level,
across mountains now flooded by artificial lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Panama Canal is a fascinating feat of engineering, a
U.S.-made 50-mile passage that carries more than 13,000 ships and
190 million tons of cargo a year between two oceans. At the end of
this year, the United States will permanently relinquish the canal
to Panama _ along with about $4 billion worth of property.
</P>
<P>
   The canal and the prospects for an economic boom based on the
property Panama will inherit are by far the most important issue
looming over Sunday's presidential election, a contest between the
son of Gen. Omar Torrijos, who negotiated the Panama Canal Treaty
with President Carter in the late 1970s, and the widow of a
president ousted by Gen. Torrijos. The winner, whose tenure is
constitutionally limited to one five-year term, will preside over
the Dec. 31 handover.
</P>
<P>
   The canal is so hallowed that the candidates, locked in a tight
race, agreed that it could not be the subject of electoral
mudslinging.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Panamanians' fervent desire to use the handover to
help eradicate high unemployment and poverty rates and help this
country of 2.8 million people toward a brighter future.
</P>
<P>
   The next administration faces the challenge of disposing of the
valuable real estate the United States is leaving and replacing the
jobs and income earned from the U.S. bases, which has run to as
much as $350 million a year. It must also operate the canal, which
brings about $545 million a year in tolls, oversee its expansion
and prevent deforestation of the watershed.
</P>
<P>
   Polls showed the election to be a close match. In Panama's
clique-ridden politics, Martin Torrijos, 35, is trading heavily on
the memory of his father, who died in a 1981 plane crash. And his
opponent, Mireya Moscoso, 52, is the widow of Dr. Arnulfo Arias,
who was elected president three times and deposed by the military
each time, the last only days after taking office in 1968, in the
military coup that installed Torrijos.
</P>
<P>
   Although both have been active in the political scene in the
'90s, each has sparse experience in government. Their political
platforms have broad similarities. Both oppose privatization of
certain state-owned services and promise honest government in a
country with scant tradition of same.
</P>
<P>
   Torrijos has served as deputy minister of government and Justice
in the administration of the current president, Ernesto Perez
Balladares, and is the candidate of the governing Democratic
Revolutionary Party.
</P>
<P>
   Both Panamanians and Americans have fears that future
governments may divert canal money for their own benefit, and
Balladares did little to assuage them when he packed the Panama
Canal Authority, the agency that is supposed to govern the canal's
operations starting next year, with relatives and cronies.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the governing party have also been allowed to rent,
with an option to buy below market value, some of the best of the
reverting properties.
</P>
<P>
   Public outrage over the actions was cited here among the factors
leading voters last September to reject a constitutional amendment
that would have allowed him to serve a second term.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Panama Canal was completed in 1914, the bulk of its
revenue has usually been invested in maintenance and modernization.
While the handover of the 569-square mile U.S. canal zone has been
seamless so far _ 95 percent of its more than 7,000 employees are
Panamanian, working under a Panamanian administrator _ there is
great uncertainty about the fate of the valuable property that
comes with it.
</P>
<P>
   Only about 4,000 Americans, mostly Army and Air Force personnel,
remain of the 10,000 military personnel once stationed here. When
they leave at the end of the year, Panama will be left with the
task of somehow transforming the U.S. military's property into the
centerpiece of a longed-for bonanza.
</P>
<P>
   If all goes according to the plans, or dreams, then barracks,
hospitals, schools, airstrips, churches, houses, offices and
manicured lawns will become private housing, hotels, a university,
sports centers, and industrial parks at the center of an envisaged
export boom that will see ports teeming with new trade.
</P>
<P>
   Already, $1 billion has been invested by Panama and other
countries, from Spain to Taiwan, mostly in tourism and
maritime-related services, Panamanian officials say. The old School
of the Americas, for instance, where Latin American military
officers trained, is turning into a luxury hotel. Part of the
Albrook Air Force Station has been sold to American former canal
workers for a retirement community of 147 families.
</P>
<P>
   But most of the really valuable property _ nine military bases _
will only be transferred over the next eight months. The future of
that real estate hinges on the ability of Panama to attract more
investors, said Nicolas Ardito Barletta, administrator of
Interoceanic Region Authority, created in 1993 to manage the
property reverting to Panama.
</P>
<P>
   ``The property is going to be worth what we make it produce,''
Barletta said. Some properties that have already reverted are
fallow and deteriorating, even as others are being developed.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the economic questions posed by the handover, some
Panamanians worry about losing the U.S. military, whose presence
has served as a deterrent against incursions by Colombian
guerrillas. Now, the border with Colombia will be guarded only by
police, for Panama has no army.
</P>
</TEXT>
