u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PEACEKEEPERS-2     05-01 1018
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PEACEKEEPERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NATO SEES MOSCOW EASING ITS STANCE ON PEACEKEEPERS IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By CRAIG R. WHITNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BRUSSELS, Belgium _ Russia appears to be moving toward agreeing
to a U.N. Security Council resolution that would authorize an armed
international military force in Kosovo to allow refugees to return,
even if Yugoslavia continues to refuse one, NATO officials said
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   While Russia continues to say publicly that it would veto any
Security Council resolution with a peacekeeping force that did not
have the consent of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic, NATO
diplomats said there was movement behind the scenes in Moscow if
not yet in Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the information I have is that they are prepared to accept
a force under those conditions,'' a senior NATO official said.
``They have said privately that they would participate.''
</P>
<P>
   The official said the allies had not yet heard from Viktor
Chernomyrdin, the Russian special envoy to the Balkans, since
Chernomyrdin's six hours of talks with Milosevic on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In a statement timed to coincide with his meeting with the
Russian envoy, Milosevic said in an interview made public on Friday
that he might be willing to accept a U.N. contingent in Kosovo, but
he dismissed the idea of a ``force'' and rejected any notion of
NATO troops on Yugoslav soil. NATO rejected his proposals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Belgrade shows concrete and constructive intentions which can
become a basis for further progress,'' Chernomyrdin said in Moscow
on Saturday, although he left Belgrade with no sign of a change in
the Yugoslav position. Chernomyrdin said Saturday that he would
talk with Vice President Al Gore about his talks in Belgrade and
would travel to France and London next week.
</P>
<P>
   NATO's fresh hope of constructive Russian involvement in the
Kosovo crisis comes after the reopening last weekend of the special
diplomatic channel between Gore and Chernomyrdin, who had
established ties before Chernomyrdin was dismissed as Russia's
prime minister last spring.
</P>
<P>
   After Russia's president, Boris Yeltsin, suggested reactivating
the channel in a telephone conversation with President Clinton last
weekend, Clinton decided to send Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott to Moscow, a NATO official said. Talbott briefed NATO
officials here Thursday on the results of his soundings.
</P>
<P>
   The view from NATO now, according to one senior official, is
that with all of Yugoslavia's neighbors now supporting allied
bombing to stop Milosevic's campaign of repression of the ethnic
Albanian majority in Kosovo, Russian support for a Security Council
resolution under chapter seven of the U.N. charter would be a clear
signal to Belgrade that it could not hold out any longer.
</P>
<P>
   Chapter seven allows the international organization to send
peacekeeping forces into areas of conflict even when the combatants
do not consent.
</P>
<P>
   ``The moment chapter seven is approved, the situation for
Milosevic is completely changed,'' the NATO secretary-general,
Javier Solana, said in an interview with The New York Times on
Saturday. ``Then there would be the beginning of a negotiation, and
the deployment of a peacekeeping force.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an isolated country now,'' Solana said of Yugoslavia and
its leader. ``Serbia used to be a country surrounded by friends. If
the Russians go to the Security Council, that would lift the final
block. And everybody, including Russia, is absolutely convinced
that without troops on the ground, this problem has no solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana also said that he expected that NATO ambassadors would
soon approve a plan to allow allied warships in the Adriatic to
board and search oil tankers and other ships making oil deliveries
to Yugoslav ports, further depriving Yugoslav military and police
forces of the fuel they need to carry out their operations.
</P>
<P>
   But, Solana said, with a petroleum embargo on Yugoslavia by all
15 European Union countries in effect since Friday, and 90 percent
of the rest of the oil-producing world also declaring a halt to
deliveries there, the NATO ship inspections would be mostly
symbolic.
</P>
<P>
   Only Russia among major oil-producing countries had so far not
agreed to stop oil supplies, Solana said. Most Russian oil to the
Balkans is delivered through a pipeline to Slovenia, and Slovenia
has agreed to the embargo. In Moscow, Chernomyrdin said Russia
would ignore any embargo not approved by the Security Council, but
officials there said they were unaware of many deliveries of
Russian oil to Yugoslavia by ship.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the economic pressures on Yugoslavia, Clinton on
Saturday toughened sanctions to bar most trade with its Serb
republic. Previous sanctions had barred the sale of arms and
restricted financial transactions.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to oil, the new executive order would also prohibit
sales of all other goods except food and medicine. Sales to
Yugoslavia's republic of Montenegro, whose government has leaned
toward NATO, would be exempted.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said the sanctions would ``diminish the Belgrade
regime's ability to continue its campaign of repression and
defiance, while allowing needed supplies to reach victims of its
reckless and brutal conduct.''
</P>
<P>
   With clear weather over the Balkans, allied warplanes are flying
about 600 missions a day. Heavy bombing overnight destroyed nine
radio and television transmission towers across the country and
seven highway and railroad bridges, spokesmen said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied aircraft also bombed tanks, armored personnel carriers,
command centers, fuel dumps, mortars and artillery, and military
airfields in Kosovo, according to Col. Konrad Freytag, a spokesman
for the allied military command.
</P>
<P>
   ``The military radio relay network is essential to Milosevic's
ability to direct and control the repressive activities of his army
and special police forces in Kosovo,'' Peter Daniel, a NATO
spokesman, said. ``Every day, because of this, Milosevic is less
and less able to stay in touch with his forces and keep them
supplied.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Allied military spokesmen said Saturday that they as yet had no
information to offer on a report from Yugoslavia that 23 passengers
had been killed Saturday afternoon when NATO bombs hit a bus in
Kosovo, in the town of Luzane, 12 miles north of the capital,
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The command also said that rebel Kosovo Liberation Army forces
in Kosovo were putting up ``strong resistance'' to the Yugoslavs in
a corridor along a road near Suva Reka, north of Prizren in the
southern part of the province.
</P>
<P>
   With the bombing now in its 39th day and every prospect that it
will continue, with more than 1,000 allied warplanes, right into
summer, the allies hope that Russian pressure on Yugoslavia will
finally get Milosevic to the negotiating table.
</P>
<P>
   But Russia has not yet said publicly that ground troops are
needed to solve the problem in Kosovo, although it had agreed to be
part of an international peacekeeping force led by NATO if
Milosevic had accepted the peace plan for Kosovo that was worked
out in Rambouillet, France, this winter.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, NATO countries have said they hoped to get Russia to
use its influence on Belgrade to get Milosevic to agree to withdraw
his military and police forces from Kosovo, and let peacekeepers in
to allow more than a million Kosovo Albanian refugees to return
home.
</P>
<P>
   Now it is clear that while NATO continues to bomb, it expects
Russia to use leverage of its own on Belgrade by letting Milosevic
know that Russia, too, is ready to support the imposition of a
peacekeeping force in Kosovo to stop the continuing violence
against civilians there.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO's expectation also reflects the fact that if increased
bombing and diplomacy cannot bring Milosevic to accept reason, the
alliance has no other option readily available.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's not reasonable, we'd have to enter in force. For that
to happen, we'd have to damage the country much more than we have
done,'' a senior official said. Asked what would happen if
Milosevic decided to take his country down with him under the
bombing, like Adolf Hitler in World War II, the official said, ``I
cannot see that happening.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials say there is no doubt in any allied country about
the need to keep bombing until Milosevic agrees to let the refugees
return to Kosovo. ``We have to reverse the ethnic cleansing,''
Solana said. ``The people who have been forced out need to return.
For that, you need a secure environment, and for that you need
international troops, and you need Serb forces to withdraw. This is
the objective.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked whether the allies all still believed that bombing alone
could bring about that result, Solana said: ``We think at this
point, yes. You have to keep bombing until the brain of the whole
operation, which is Milosevic, is convinced that it is time to
stop.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We had the leaders of 19 NATO countries at the summit in
Washington, plus 40 countries in the European-Atlantic Partnership
Council, all agreed that this is the moment when the international
community should say this kind of behavior at the end of the 20th
century is unacceptable,'' Solana said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The summit was very important,'' Solana continued. ``I think
that Belgrade maybe expected that the coalition would not hold, but
the leaders are absolutely committed to the policy. We will
succeed, there's no doubt about that. This has to be the real end
of the old era.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
