<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR O'NEAL AND IVERSON, SCORING TITLE TAKES A BACK SEAT TO
PLAYOFFS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Shaquille O'Neal and Allen Iverson were recently asked what
it would mean to win the National Basketball Association's scoring
title, each responded in an unselfish, thoughtful manner, the kind
that makes coaches proud and footwear executives queasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``That means nothing to me,'' O'Neal said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked if winning the most valuable player award mattered,
he added: ``That doesn't mean anything to me, either. Just winning.
Right now, my team ain't winning, so nothing else matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Iverson said: ``If it happens, it happens. But I want to win
games. I want to get to the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   In six games over the next four days, the two young stars _ who
by virtue of their talent, force and flair have been enlisted to
carry the NBA into the post-Michael Jordan era _ can kill an
outdated perception they dubiously share. It is the one that says
O'Neal and Iverson are more about themselves than their teams. To
dispel it, all they have to do is occasionally pass and, most
important, win.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, O'Neal was averaging 26.3 points a game
for the Los Angeles Lakers; Iverson was averaging 26.2 points for
the Philadelphia 76ers. They were neck and neck, and it would be
natural for the game's most powerful big man and its most
breathtaking point guard to dominate the ball in their respective
teams' final three regular-season games.
</P>
<P>
   As the final games on Wednesday approach, one can almost hear
the players' entourages egging them on.
</P>
<P>
   The league can only hope that the two players first listen to
their own words about putting winning ahead of self. O'Neal's
Lakers are battling the Houston Rockets for home-court advantage in
the first round of the Western Conference playoffs. In their final
three games, the Lakers travel to Seattle Sunday, play host to
Dallas on Monday and finish with Portland at the Great Western
Forum on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Iverson's 76ers could finish anywhere from fifth to eighth place
in the Eastern Conference, depending on how they do at Detroit
Sunday, at Charlotte on Tuesday and at home against Detroit on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their teams need those victories more than O'Neal and Iverson
need points to assure themselves of an individual honor.
</P>
<P>
   With the exception of his nearly two-year hiatus, Jordan led the
league in scoring from the 1986-87 season through last year. O'Neal
has already won the scoring title once, averaging 29.3 points a
game at Orlando during the 1994-95 season when Jordan was playing
baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Individually, they have nothing to prove. O'Neal's only job
should be to dominate a game on defense and help his team resurrect
a disappointing season.
</P>
<P>
   Feuds with Coach Larry Brown aside, Iverson has been awesome. In
the MVP voting, he will most likely finish in the top five. He
almost made his first appearance on David Letterman's show last
Wednesday, only to be bumped at the last minute by Dustin Hoffman.
It would be understandable if Iverson's head were spinning. But he
should take time to reflect on these last three games of a
resilient season for the 76ers.
</P>
<P>
   Now, if both teams shore up their playoff seedings and nothing
is at stake on Wednesday, then a bit of showtime is in order. And
for what it is worth, O'Neal probably has an edge based on the fact
that neither Seattle nor Dallas believes in defense.
</P>
<P>
   Controversial Call for Knicks
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Knicks expected any favors, but they were as
shocked as anyone Wednesday night when Referee George Toliver
whistled Allan Houston for a controversial dead-ball foul in the
final seconds of a game New York would go on to lose, 76-73, to the
Hawks.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is that call a rarity in the league, it is never seen
when a team is holding a 1-point lead in the final seconds of a
game. Toliver's call led to one free throw and helped prevent the
Knicks from tying the game when Latrell Sprewell hit a running
3-pointer with 1.2 seconds left.
</P>
<P>
   Privately, team officials were irate for other reasons than
merely bad officiating. When Toliver was relieved of his duties as
an NBA official nearly two years ago _ another casualty of the
Internal Revenue Service's crackdown on league referees who
downgraded first-class tickets to coach fares and pocketed the cash
_ the Knicks helped him out financially.
</P>
<P>
   They called Toliver and asked him if he would like to referee
scrimmages during the team's post-season training camp in
Charleston, S.C. Toliver, confined to home detention as part of his
sentence, gladly accepted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a lot, but we helped him out,'' said one team
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``We didn't do it
with the idea he would repay us during the season if he ever got
his job back. That's ridiculous to even think that way. We just
thought he was a good guy and we needed an official.'' Chicago
Comes Up Empty
</P>
<P>
   For the first time since 1969, neither the Bulls nor the
Blackhawks are headed toward the post-season in Chicago. If Madison
Square Garden is likely to be dark and empty for most of May and
all of June, think about those poor souls who used to inhabit the
United Center.
</P>
<P>
   While the Knicks struggle to the make the playoffs and try to
provide their owners with some sort of dividends after the Rangers
faltered, Michael Jordan's old team mercifully ends its rebuilding
season on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Nine years after their first title, the 12-35 Bulls are about to
finish with the worst record in the Eastern Conference. And it is
not only the fans who are suffering.
</P>
<P>
   ``There goes that Walt Disney World vacation for the family,''
said Tyrone Jackson, a United Center security guard who worked the
Jordan detail for seven years, including three seasons at the old
Chicago Stadium. ``We'll have to figure out something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Bulls' championship run began, Jackson has been able
to take his wife, Lynn, and their three children _ Brittany, age
10, Donald, 8, and Tyrone Jr., 6 _ on annual vacations. Having made
$80 for each playoff game at the United Center _ roughly $2,000 in
extra income each post-season _ he misses Jordan, Scottie Pippen
and friends more than most.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be glad if he had stayed another year,'' Jackson said.
``At least we'd be working. The air stays clean around the
neighborhood. Everything just smells better.''
</P>
<P>
   Not all in the Windy City are still mourning. Bill Gleason, the
76-year-old sportswriter for The Daily Southtown, said most
observers had been resigned to the Bulls' having a dreadful season.
A third-generation White Sox fan, Gleason added that many of
Chicago's teams had essentially prepared Bulls fans for the
letdown.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nothing more than Chicagoans expected,'' Gleason said.
``We are accustomed to that kind of thing here. We don't get as
goofy about it as New Yorkers do.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
