<HEADER>
A0607 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MD-BASEBALL-DISCRIM-A     05-01 0845
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MD-BASEBALL-DISCRIM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHURCHGOERS' DISCOUNT CREATES RIFT AT BALLPARK
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(DW)  
By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HAGERSTOWN, Md. _ Out here in western Maryland, more than an
hour's drive from any big city, diversions are where you find them.
For decades, area residents have enjoyed a fair share of them
watching minor league baseball in Municipal Stadium, a tidy little
ballpark of 4,600 seats on the edge of town.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the stadium is home to the Hagerstown Suns, a Class
A affiliate of the Toronto Blue Jays. The Suns pass the summer
playing teams in the South Atlantic League with names like the
Greensboro Bats, the Hickory Crawdads and the Savannah Sand Gnats.
</P>
<P>
   Often, though, a baseball game is not enough to entice fans,
even with modest ticket prices of $7, $5 and $3. So, like
executives of minor league teams elsewhere, Winston Blenckstone,
the Suns' owner, counts heavily on promotions, like Little League
Home Run Derby Nights in June when the Suns play the Asheville
Tourists, and Seat Cushion Giveaway Night for an August game with
the Piedmont Boll Weevils.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more popular specials in recent years has been Church
Bulletin Day. Each Sunday that the Suns play at home, up to six
family members get in for a total of $6, provided they have a
bulletin from their church. It is the team's way, Blenckstone said,
of promoting family values, and typically 100 fans with bulletins
show up on those days.
</P>
<P>
   But now, the offer is under assault as religious discrimination,
an accusation that leaves Blenckstone scratching his head in
bewilderment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Minor league baseball is all about promotions,'' he said last
week, as a game with the Augusta Green Jackets was about to start.
``If you take away one kind, who's to say someone else won't object
to Little League Night or Senior Citizen Night or Scout Night?''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge came after Carl Silverman, 43, a professed
agnostic from nearby Waynesboro, Pa., who occasionally attends Suns
games, brought his two young daughters to a game last year on
Easter Sunday. Silverman asked for the discount afforded
churchgoers and was refused. He thought that was wrong, inasmuch as
the city of Hagerstown owns the stadium, and he took his case to
the Maryland Commission on Human Relations.
</P>
<P>
   The commission investigated and found ``probable cause'' that
the promotion violates state antidiscrimination laws. Silverman and
the team were given a hearing date, June 28, before an
administrative law judge to determine if the team is violating the
law.
</P>
<P>
   ``It irked me that if you bring a church bulletin, you are
treated better,'' Silverman said. ``You get a better deal.'' He is
asking only that the team discontinue the church-bulletin
promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Silverman, who was born Jewish, describes himself as an agnostic
and free thinker who ``rejects all religion as being a brand of
mental illness.'' He also describes himself as a ``house dad,''
caring for his children while his wife, who was reared as a
Lutheran but does not practice the faith, works as a pharmacist.
</P>
<P>
   The case against the team is only the latest of Silverman's
efforts to separate matters of church and state. Several years ago,
he waged a successful battle with his local school district to keep
the Gideons from distributing Bibles throughout the public schools,
and he forced the state of Pennsylvania to remove crosses from two
state parks.
</P>
<P>
   In challenging the Suns, he has won the help of the American
Civil Liberties Union, which has agreed to represent him at the
hearing. ``Not many facts are in dispute,'' said Dwight Sullivan,
one of Silverman's lawyers. ``It all boils down to whether the
discount offering, which was made at a public facility, is a form
of religious discrimination.''
</P>
<P>
   After operating minor league teams for 13 years with no
complaints, Blenckstone said he was astonished that a state agency
might judge him to be discriminating. The team, he said, used a
liberal interpretation of the promotion, accepting bulletins from
synagogues and mosques, as well as churches.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we say church, we mean any house of worship,''
Blenckstone said. ``We're just trying to tie in the assets of the
community with family values. I don't think there's anything
unhealthy about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverman disagreed. ``They're claiming any house of worship,''
he said. ``That still discriminates against atheists, agnostics,
humanists, pagans and lots of others, even Christians who do not go
to church.''
</P>
<P>
   Silverman insisted it was strictly a matter of principle. Asked
about a sign in front a restaurant near the stadium that offered
drink specials to women on ``Ladies Nite'' each Wednesday, he said:
``I'm not out to fight other people's battles. I'm interested in
what violates the law, the religious aspect, in particular. If
other people want to fight other battles, great. The Church
Bulletin Day is my battle.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
