u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHER-AR     05-01 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHER-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA PLAN WOULD GIVE VOUCHERS FOR STUDENTS AT BAD SCHOOLS TO GO
ELSEWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (bl)  
 By PAMELA MERCER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ORLANDO, Fla. _ Asked to write his name, Johnathan Rodriguez, a
lanky first- grader at the Orlo Vista Elementary School here, bent
over his desk and seized his pen with the intensity of a surgeon
about to use a scalpel.
</P>
<P>
   He had no trouble with the Johnathan, but when it came to
writing Rodriguez, he got stuck after the o. Teresa Sanders, his
teacher, completed the word for him.
</P>
<P>
   This lesson would normally have little meaning for anyone other
than Johnathan. But in Orlo Vista, the ability of Johnathan and his
schoolmates to write and read could seal the fate of this and other
public schools across the state.
</P>
<P>
   Orlo Vista is one of four schools that the Florida Department of
Education has listed a being critically low performing. Last year,
less than the required 33 percent of its students scored higher
than average in nationally standardized reading and mathematics
exams, and less than a third got a passing grade in a writing
program. If this year's test results, which are expected in the
summer, show that students have again failed to meet state
standards, the Education Department could mark Orlo Vista itself
with an ``F.''
</P>
<P>
   The grade is far from symbolic. Under a plan known as the A plus
education package, approved by the Legislature, Florida will offer
students from public schools that fail to meet its standards two
years in a row a chance to study in a private or public school of
their choice. Students opting to change schools will receive
vouchers worth about $4,000.
</P>
<P>
   The plan will also allow the state to effect sweeping changes in
a school that fails just one year. State education officials will
have the authority to change the curriculum, dismiss or retrain the
principal and staff, and provide financial aid.
</P>
<P>
   Precise guidelines of the A plus education package, which has
been a top priority for Gov. Jeb Bush since taking office last
January, have yet to be drawn up by the state Education Department.
Yet the plan has drawn criticism from public school officials here
who fear that they might lose their best students, and the money
that follows them, to private schools that are not held accountable
to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Sandwiched between a main street and a side street, Orlo Vista
Elementary is set in a low-income neighborhood of small bungalows
and spottily paved roads. Patricia Ramsey, the school's principal,
estimated that 90 percent of the students come from families whose
incomes are below the poverty level. To measure the ability of such
a student body through standardized testing, she said, is to ignore
the gaping holes that their disadvantaged background has ripped in
their education.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have the same raw material coming in the door of
every school, it's not like a manufacturing company and at the end
of the process we can do quality control and say, `This passes'''
Ms. Ramsey said. ``Looking at where a child comes in the front door
and how far a school takes them, how much they grow _ that's what I
want to be held accountable for.''
</P>
<P>
   To be sure, by many measures, Ms. Ramsey and her staff have had
to struggle. Originally built to have 400 students, Orlo Vista now
has 700. To accommodate the extra children, trainer-style
structures have been erected as makeshift classrooms in the
school's small grounds, depriving Orlo Vista of its playground.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast is served at the school for the students that do not
get any at home. And language and mathematics difficulties aside,
even kindergarten can prove a challenge for children who, teachers
say, fail to receive even the most basic instruction at home. ``A
lot of times we have children here that do not know colors,'' Ms.
Sanders said. ``A lot cannot label parts of their bodies, they
don't know zoo animals.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition, keeping track of the students progress has been
difficult, for Orlo Vista has a turnover rate amongst the student
body of 50 percent every year, compared with an average of 31
percent for the state at large.
</P>
<P>
   So how to gauge the progress of the students, particularly when
only the fourth grade at Orlo Vista took the tests that put the
school on the state's critically low performing list?
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Ramsey laughed bitterly. ``It's like testing water,'' she
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
