<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-CUMMINGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALTER J. CUMMINGS, APPELLATE JUDGE SINCE 1966, DIES AT 82  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Conn., Fla., Mass., Wash.)   By WILLIAM H. HONAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge Walter J. Cummings, who at 36 became the youngest
solicitor general of the United States and went on to be one of the
longest-serving federal appellate court judges in the nation's
history, died on April 24 at Northwestern Memorial Hospital in
Chicago. He was 82 and lived in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1966, Cummings was named by President Lyndon B. Johnson
to the U. S. Court of Appeals for the Seventh Circuit, in Chicago,
and served until his death. In his nearly 33 years on the bench,
Cummings wrote more than 2,700 opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the judge's more notable opinions was one in 1972
reversing an action by Judge Julius J. Hoffman of U.S. District
Court in the ``Chicago Seven'' case. Hoffman had cited some of the
defendants in the case for contempt of court in the tumultuous
trial that came to symbolize the domestic disruptions that erupted
in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1970, all the defendants were found not guilty of charges of
conspiring to incite a riot two years earlier, during the
Democratic National Convention in Chicago. But five of them were
found guilty on a lesser charge of crossing state lines with the
intent of inciting a riot.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman's courtroom became a raucous setting in which the
defendants and their lawyers were repeatedly excoriated from the
bench while the defendants, among them Abbie Hoffman, David
Dellinger and Jerry Rubin, sneeringly referred to Hoffman as ``
Magoo.''
</P>
<P>
   The judge ordered another defendant, Bobby G. Seale, a leader of
the Black Panthers, to be bound and gagged after Seale called him a
``pig'' and a ``racist.''
</P>
<P>
   Reviewing the trial, Cummings found that Hoffman's conduct was
``deprecatory and often antagonistic'' toward the defense, and
ordered a new trial before a different judge.
</P>
<P>
   Although some counts of contempt were eventually upheld against
the defendants, no fines or sentences were ever imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Cummings also participated in important decisions
requiring steel companies to stop polluting Lake Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   In writing judicial opinions, the judge was concerned about
matters of tone and style. Dissenting from the majority opinion in
a 1993 case holding that the Boy Scouts of America may exclude
applicants who refuse to swear that they will carry out their
``duty to God,'' Cummings declared that although the majority might
have reached ``the correct result,'' it had done so ``in a most
unfortunate fashion by imparting a stingy and narrow reading'' to
the applicable statute.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Joseph Cummings was born in Chicago on Sept. 29, 1916, to
wealth and social position. His father, Walter J. Cummings Sr., was
a railroad-car manufacturer, the first head of the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp. and chairman of the Continental Illinois National
Bank &AMP; Trust Co., now part of BankAmerica.
</P>
<P>
   The younger Cummings attended the St. Albans School in
Washington and the Chicago Latin School, and received his
bachelor's degree from Yale University in 1937 and his law degree
from Harvard University in 1940.
</P>
<P>
   Rejected by the armed services in World War II because of poor
eyesight, he became an assistant to the U.S. Solicitor General in
1940, and later was a special assistant to the Attorney General.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, he practiced law in Chicago until 1952, when he
was chosen by President Harry S. Truman to be solicitor general,
making him the youngest to hold that post. In 1953, after Truman
left office, Cummings returned to private practice in Chicago; the
next year, he was named to the appellate court. He served as chief
judge of the Seventh Circuit from 1981 to 1986.
</P>
<P>
   In 1946, he married Therese Murray, who died in 1968. Cummings
is survived by three sons, Walter J. Cummings III of Chestnut Hill,
Mass., Keith Murray Cummings of West Palm Beach, Fla., and Mark
Farrell Cummings of Chicago; a brother, Edward, of Washington, and
two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
