<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STEELE-TRIAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL TO BRING BACK MANY PLAYERS IN CLINTON SCANDAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALEXANDRIA, Va. _ In a federal courtroom here Monday, Kenneth
Starr's prosecutors will begin the trial of the first and only
person to be charged with a crime related to the sprawling sex and
perjury investigation that led to President Clinton's impeachment.
</P>
<P>
   Although Starr's prosecutors took sworn testimony from at least
111 people, including Monica Lewinsky and Linda Tripp, the
defendant in this case is a little-known Richmond woman named Julie
Hiatt Steele, whose role in the matter is so peripheral that her
name does not appear in the Starr Report.
</P>
<P>
   Besides being an odd epilogue, Ms. Steele's trial offers another
chance for many of the scandal's main players to be heard yet
again. The witness list includes Ms. Lewinsky; Mrs. Tripp; Kathleen
Willey, the former White House volunteer who accused the president
of making an unwanted sexual advance, and Michael Isikoff, the
Newsweek reporter who wrote the first comprehensive story about the
Lewinsky investigation. On Friday, the judge presiding over the
case refused to quash subpoenas seeking Isikoff's notes and
testimony and unpublished material from Ms. Willey's March 1998
interview with the CBS News program ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele is charged with lying in an affidavit and statements
to investigators about her knowledge of whether the president had
made an unwanted sexual advance to Ms. Willey. She had described
this knowledge to Isikoff and later denied it.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview in April, Ms. Steele, 52, said that Starr's
prosecutors were vindictively trying to punish her for refusing to
verify Ms. Willey's account and ``help them prove'' that the
president had groped Ms. Willey just outside the Oval Office in
November 1993. If convicted, Ms. Steele, who is divorced and has an
8-year-old adopted son from Romania, faces a maximum of 35 years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think this is about either one of us,'' Ms. Steele
said in an interview Friday. ``It's about Ken Starr overreaching
and doing everything he can to get the president. I got in the
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Ms. Steele's defense team, led by a Washington lawyer,
Nancy Luque, will try to portray Starr as an overzealous prosecutor
who singled out Ms. Steele after she criticized Starr's motives in
televised interviews. Ms. Luque said that Starr's prosecutors tried
to threaten the legality of Ms. Steele's adoption of her son, Adam,
and that prosecutors asked Ms. Steele's adult son, her brother and
others about the adoption.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy to put Starr and his motives on trial was used with
success by Susan McDougal's defense lawyers in her recent trial in
Little Rock, Ark. Ms. McDougal was acquitted of obstructing justice
in April. Prosecutors charged Ms. McDougal after she refused to
cooperate with Starr's grand jury investigating the Arkansas
financial dealings of Clinton and his wife, Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele testified at Ms. McDougal's trial about her view of
Starr's tactics, and her story apparently helped persuade some
jurors that Starr was determined to get the president.
</P>
<P>
   It is unlikely, however, that the judge presiding over Ms.
Steele's trial will allow defense lawyers to attack Starr. Judge
Claude Hilton of U.S. District Court in Alexandria has told the
lawyers that he will not allow the trial to veer away from the
facts that are central to the charges.
</P>
<P>
   In a motion to dismiss, Ms. Steele's lawyers accused Starr's
office of seeking an indictment ``based solely upon a credibility
test between Ms. Steele and Kathleen Willey.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It did so fully aware of Ms. Willey's record of lies and
misrepresentations in connection with the Jones vs. Clinton case,''
the motion contended.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele said: ``I'm being prosecuted for calling a liar a
liar and Ken Starr knows it and he has covered it up every step of
the way. It is despicable. It is a great injustice.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that blunt outspokenness that infuriated Starr's
prosecutors late last year, Ms. Luque said in court papers. Defense
lawyers intend to introduce letters that show that Starr's
prosecutors had considered Ms. Steele a witness, not a target, of
their inquiry last summer, according to court records.
</P>
<P>
   David Barger, a prosecutor in Starr's office who will try the
case, did not return telephone calls in late April. A spokesman for
Starr, Edward Page, said that the local rules prohibited him from
commenting on any aspect of the case. In his congressional
testimony in November, Starr angrily denied that his prosecutors
did anything inappropriate in their investigation of Ms. Steele.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele's refusal to back up Ms. Willey's account of an
encounter with the president was apparently a big factor in Starr's
decision not to include information about Ms. Willey in his
impeachment report to the House of Representatives in September.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele initially told Isikoff, the Newsweek reporter, that
Ms. Willey told her of the alleged sexual advance just after she
said it happened. But Ms. Steele later disavowed that account and
gave an affidavit in the Paula Jones sexual misconduct lawsuit
denying that Ms. Willey had ever told her of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Ms. Willey's encounter with the president, Ms.
Steele said that she had spoken with Ms. Willey about the incident,
but that Ms. Willey ``never said anything to suggest that Clinton
made sexual advances toward her or otherwise acted inappropriately
in her presence,'' according to an affidavit she signed on Feb. 13,
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele later said that she had claimed knowledge of the
incident only as a favor to Ms. Willey, who she said had asked her
to lie to Isikoff to corroborate her account. Since then, she has
repeatedly refused under oath to confirm Ms. Willey's account.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has denied that he ever made a sexual advance to Ms.
Willey, both in his grand jury testimony and in his deposition in
the Jones case.
</P>
<P>
   It appears from some of the documents in the court file that
Starr's prosecutors may try to prove that Ms. Willey was groped by
the president inside the White House. They have entered into
evidence the videotape of Clinton's grand jury testimony, as well
as a transcript of his testimony in the Paula Jones lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Gecker, the Richmond lawyer who represents Ms. Willey,
did not return phone calls in late April. Several weeks ago, he
said that Ms. Willey would have no comment before the trial.
</P>
<P>
   The trial could hinge on jurors' judgment of the credibility of
the two former friends from Richmond, Ms. Willey and Ms. Steele,
whose friendship began, just as it ended, with threats and hurt
feelings.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1978, Ms. Steele and her husband moved to Richmond
and entered into a contract to buy Ms. Willey's four-bedroom
Colonial-style house for $117,000. But 12 days before Christmas,
the Willeys broke the contract and Ms. Steele sued for breach of
contract. The lawsuit was dropped after Ms. Steele and Ms. Willey
became friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the only person I knew in Richmond,'' Ms. Steele said.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have ammunition that could raise doubts about the
other's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   In early 1998, Ms. Willey, who is steeped in debt, tried to sell
her story of her encounter with the president to a book publisher,
and to The Star, the supermarket tabloid. She also wrote a series
of flattering letters to Clinton after the alleged groping
incident, but she has said that she maintained communication with
the president because she wanted a job in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Steele says she told a lie to Isikoff on Ms. Willey's
behalf, and she has conceded that it was a mistake to sell a
photograph of Ms. Willey and Clinton to The National Enquirer for
$7,000. Prosecutors suspect that she no longer supports Ms.
Willey's account because she is trying to help the White House.
</P>
<P>
   But she called that laughable, saying that she never voted for
Clinton and that she comes from a family of Republicans. ``My
mother had volunteered for Nixon's campaign in Kentucky,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Although their friendship has ended, Ms. Steele and Ms. Willey
have crossed paths several times around Richmond. In September
1997, Ms. Steele said, Ms. Willey confronted her at the Ukrops
supermarket and ``started yelling and screaming at me.'' It was
shortly after Ms. Steele had sold the photograph to the tabloid.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Ms. Steele says, she wishes their friendship had ended long
ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I regret that every single time she did a terrible thing to
me, I forgave her,'' she said. ``I confused forgiving and
forgetting. I was right to forgive, but I was wrong to forget.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
