<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for May 2,
1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York Times News
Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A slow-moving storm will gradually move away from the Southeast
coast, but clouds and some showers will linger near the shoreline
from North Carolina to Georgia. Gusty winds from the northeast
combined with overcast skies will keep temperatures far below the
seasonal average. Clouds will dissipate during the day over the
interior Carolinas and Georgia as drier air arrives on northerly
breezes. Farther west, the interior Southeast will have abundant
sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Expansive high pressure will promote another day of plentiful
sunshine from the northern Mississippi Valley to the Northeastern
states. Breezes from the south will boost afternoon temperatures
far above seasonal levels from the Great Lakes to the eastern
Dakotas. Most of the Northeast will be mild, but midday and
afternoon sea breezes will keep coastal areas cool.
</P>
<P>
   Showers and thunderstorms will be common from central Texas to
the western Plains and central Rockies. A jet stream disturbance
moving northeast from the Texas panhandle will enhance the risk of
strong thunderstorms from western Nebraska to the Red River Valley
in Texas and Oklahoma. High wind gusts and hail will accompany some
of the storms.
</P>
<P>
   Showers will precede a front as it moves from eastern Montana to
the western Dakotas. Behind the front, brisk onshore winds will
bring cool and showery weather to the Pacific Northwest, especially
near the coast and Cascades. Meanwhile, most of the Southwest will
be drier and milder than recent days with ample sunshine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Seeds of Drought
</P>
<P>
   The seeds of summer drought are often planted in the spring.
April was the driest on record in Mobile, Alabama, a reflection of
exceptional dryness in much of the Southeast. The Northeast, where
Boston had its second driest April, also had areas of sparse
rainfall. Reliable predictions for those areas of the nation that
will have drought this summer are impossible. Patterns of spring
rainfall can markedly alter the drought probabilities, but, in many
past years, areas that have been unusually dry at the start of the
growing season have greater risk of summer drought. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
