<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-EASTNOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Anderson wants jersey retired at Georgia Tech
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kenny Anderson says he doesn't like looking up to the
rafters at Georgia Tech's Alexander Memorial Coliseum and not
seeing his name and number among the retirees. Graduation is a
requirement if you want to have your number hanging and Anderson,
now with Boston, says he is equal to the task.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to graduate,'' he said. ``I'm planning on getting
back into it this summer. I'm serious about it. I'm going to try to
graduate. I'm about 50 credits short (of a degree), but I want to
do it. That's not my reason to graduate, but that's the rules.''
</P>
<P>
   Ticking off the names of the famous, he notes, ``They got (Matt)
Harpring, (Tom) Hammonds, (Mark) Price, (John) Salley, but no K.A.
And that bugs me.''
</P>
<P>
   Knicks' big Achilles
</P>
<P>
   Madison Square Garden President Dave Checketts acknowledges the
severity of Patrick Ewing's Achilles is such that it might be best
to shut him down until next season. ``I threw it out just to say,
`Is it worthwhile resting him now?''' Checketts said. ``But I think
in Patrick's view, if he can help us, I think we have to have it.
I'm not giving up on the season when I say this, but Patrick needs
a good off-season when he's not sitting at the bargaining table and
doesn't have that load on his mind. He needs a good off-season of
conditioning and getting ready to play.''. . . Wes Unseld talked to
Dave Cowens about the Wizards' job. Ex-Hawks guard Doc Rivers also
spoke to Unseld. . . . Mike Fratello cannot opt out of his
Cleveland deal until July, 2000 but isn't unhappy with his job.
</P>
<P>
   The `Junk Yard Dog'
</P>
<P>
   Jerome Williams is tearing it up in Detroit. In six starts, he
has averaged 14.8 points and 11.8 rebounds and made 37 of 58 shots.
``If I play 30 minutes and don't get at least a double-double, then
that's not JYD basketball,'' said Williams, also known as the Junk
Yard Dog. He had 21 points, 14 rebounds, 7 assists against Boston.
``I told my father that I would get 15 rebounds. I was one short.
He said he wouldn't get his haircut until I got 15. Now he is
walking around my house with an Afro. I know my mom is mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruining of the Bulls
</P>
<P>
   Averaging 81 points and shooting under 40 percent, the Bulls
have their worst offense since the early 1960s. Theirs is also the
biggest drop-off for a championship team. After losing Bill
Russell, the Celtics went from 48 victories to 34. The worst
single-season drop was San Antonio's, from .720 in 1995-96 to .244.
Last year, the Bulls were .756. Should they lose all their
remaining games, they would be 12-38 for .240.
</P>
<P>
   Shortened season urged
</P>
<P>
   Pat Riley says the ideal NBA season would be 60 games. ``People
would have rest. Injuries would be cut down. The commissioner
definitely doesn't want to hear that, but that would be an ideal
schedule. This has tested everybody, and the commissioner is aware
of that. Of course, then he would say, `Pat, would you take a
22-game pay cut?'''
</P>
<P>
   And how would Riley respond? ``I don't get paid by the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
