<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-WESTNOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Duncan not ready for long run with Spurs
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Tim Duncan is not going to commit himself long-term to
the San Antonio Spurs. Not yet, anyway.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs concede he won't sign an extension this off-season
because of the franchise's cloudy future.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan says he hasn't thought about his contract status, but
admits the arena issue is a major factor.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs had one arena proposal _ a tax-increment financing
project with a local school district _ killed prior to the season.
City and Bexar County officials are expected to reopen talks with
Spurs chairman Peter Holt after the mayoral election. The Spurs
would like some movement by November. A poll commissioned by the
Spurs last year said 70 percent of San Antonio residents were
opposed to building an arena with a sales tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a lot of it. A whole lot of it,'' Duncan said. ``I love
San Antonio. It's a great place for me. If we're going to be here,
what kind of team are we going to have? A lot of different factors
go into it.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to have some great guys around you. You want to have
great fan support. A stadium is a big part of it. A practice
facility is a big part of it, but it's not the most important
part.''
</P>
<P>
   A lot of Jazz
</P>
<P>
   Jazz owner Larry Miller is upset about the rip from Isiah Thomas
last Sunday on NBC in which Thomas called Miller's tirade against
Portland's Greg Anthony ``classless and tasteless.'' Miller said
Thomas' comments were a factor in him being disciplined by the NBA.
Miller, who sits at courtside, has had run-ins with a number of
players, including Dikembe Mutombo. He was fined $10,000. ... With
the season winding down and his team struggling, Utah coach Jerry
Sloan says, ``It seems to me every game is like a playoff game now.
Hopefully, our players realize that.'' No love in L.A.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Jerry West on the Shaquille O'Neal-Kobe Bryant rift:
``It's not dislike, it's just a jealousy. I saw that same sort of
thing while sitting in a locker room with Elgin (Baylor) and Wilt
(Chamberlain).'' When Chamberlain read that remark, he ripped
ex-teammate West. ``When something big comes up, such as problems
with (Dennis) Rodman, the man (West) disappears.'' Chamberlain also
defended Bryant: ``Kobe is taking the brunt for every problem they
have; he has become their whipping boy, and that's wrong. A lot of
his mistakes are just the exuberance of youth. If he makes a
sensational play and they win, he's great. But if they lose, then
he's a hot dog. That's not fair.''
</P>
<P>
   Ready and able
</P>
<P>
   When Portland hammered Seattle 119-84, Damon Stoudamire played
his best game since coming to the team last season, scoring 31
points. He made 14 of 21 shots and added six assists.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I set my mind to it, I'm capable of doing that,''
Stoudamire said. ``A lot of people forgot that I averaged 20 points
in this league (with Toronto). This is something I used to have to
do all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
