</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFC-FUTURE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Elway's retirement puts pressure on Jets
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ When Vinny Testaverde teed off at the Cadillac/NFL
Golf Classic in Clifton, N.J., last spring, he was an unemployed
quarterback hoping the next telephone call might bring a contract
offer.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked down the first fairway at the Upper Montclair
Country Club on Monday, though, the New York Jets quarterback was
carrying more than a 7-iron on his right shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   In a conference that will be reshuffled by the retirement of
John Elway, a reborn Testaverde and his teammates suddenly carry
the pressure of being anointed the club most likely to supplant the
Denver Broncos as AFC champions next season. It is a mantle,
Testaverde said, worn tentatively.
</P>
<P>
   ``Talk isn't going to win anything,'' Testaverde said. ``A year
ago, we felt we were ready to make a move. But as much as we talked
about being a Super Bowl caliber team, we weren't sure of
ourselves. Now that we've been to the (conference title game), we
know what we're capable of accomplishing. But I'm sure there are
plenty of teams, with John out of the equation now, who feel the
same way.''
</P>
<P>
   The end of Elway's 16-year career hasn't resulted in the kind of
desperation among Broncos officials that might have happened before
Terrell Davis' arrival in 1995. But many people think that the
Broncos' chances for a first-ever Super Bowl three-peat have been
diminished.
</P>
<P>
   As the news of Elway's retirement spread last weekend,
bookmakers in Las Vegas changed the Broncos odds for winning their
third consecutive Super Bowl from 7-2 to 4-1, with Minnesota
becoming the favorite. One of the New York tabloids noted that
Elway's retirement, ``had handed the AFC crown'' to the Jets.
Another cited the pressure Jets coach Bill Parcells will face in
what figures to be his final season.
</P>
<P>
   But the Jets, who have acquired several key veterans this
spring, aren't the only team that should benefit by Denver's loss.
</P>
<P>
   Players in Jacksonville, Miami and New England all said the
retirement could have a leveling effect. The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution checked with 10 coaches or general managers,
and the Jets and Broncos got four votes each as favorites in the
AFC, and the Jaguars got two.
</P>
<P>
   ``The natural reaction when a great player leaves is to assume
there's going to be some backsliding by his team,'' Jaguars coach
Tom Coughlin said. ``We'll have to see. Because of free-agency,
there's so little continuity anyway that it seems like you are
always starting over. Last year is rarely indicative anymore of
what this year will be. People will play Denver differently now,
but the Broncos will play differently, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Broncos players like to refer to their offense as a ``well-oiled
machine,'' but everyone is wondering if the attack will be as
strong without Elway. Miami coach Jimmy Johnson suggested that the
difference will be more psychological _ positively for the
opposition and perhaps negatively for the Broncos.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fourth quarter, (teams) might not be looking over their
shoulders as much,'' he said, referring to Elway's trademark
late-game comebacks. ``Sometimes, if you believe a team is
beatable, then it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Bubby Brister, the vagabond quarterback who will replace Elway,
was 4-0 as a starter last season. He said on Tuesday that he
expects to see plenty of eight-man fronts as defenses concentrate
on stopping Davis to make Denver pass. Coach Mike Shanahan and
several Denver players have been outspoken and unified in their
support of Brister. But Brister, two years younger than the
38-year-old Elway, remains an unproven commodity. He has not
started more than four games in a season since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Former Atlanta starter Chris Miller, journeyman Jeff Brohm, and
second-year player Brian Griese will back Brister. In the last
three seasons, Brister, Miller, Griese and Brohm have combined for
four starts, 193 attempts and 11 touchdown passes. And Denver is
financially strapped, because owner Pat Bowlen subscribed to the
play-now-and-pay-later approach with Elway, annually restructuring
his contract to help create room under the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Elway will cost Denver nearly as much in retirement as he did
when he was playing, counting $3.9 million against the team's cap
next season and $5 million in 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Jacksonville wide receiver Keenan McCardell said that Elway's
retirement ``was not like Michael Jordan's,'' and said the Broncos
will remain the team to beat as long as Davis is running.
</P>
<P>
   But Jets tailback Curtis Martin spoke for most of the league
when he summed up what might befall an Elway-less team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's too bad for them,'' Martin said. ``And good for all the
rest of us.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
