<HEADER>
A0642 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-NHLNOTES02-COX     05-01 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sabres make obvious clear: Hasek won't be a Thrasher
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the first official setback in the Thrashers'
attempt to accrue talent, Buffalo general manager Darcy Regier
tipped his hand on the Sabres' protected list for the upcoming
expansion draft.
</P>
<P>
   He's keeping Dominik Hasek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to help get him to Atlanta,'' Regier said,
laughing. ``Maybe he'll end up there some day, but as long as I'm
here, it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   After Hasek, the NHL's closest thing to a one-man franchise, led
the Sabres to a four-game sweep over Ottawa in the first round of
the playoffs, Thrashers general manager Don Waddell jokingly
wondered if Buffalo would expose the goalie. Sure _ right after
Philadelphia serves up Eric Lindros, Colorado offers Peter Forsberg
and Wayne Gretzky decides to make a comeback because he always
wanted to be a Thrasher.
</P>
<P>
   Ottawa dominated the play in Game 1 (shots: 41-15) and outshot
Buffalo by an average of 14 per game in the series. But Hasek
limited the Senators to six goals on 162 shots (.963 saves
percentage) and frustrated Ottawa's young forwards. ``You don't
have to be a genius to figure out the difference,'' Senators coach
Jacques Martin said.
</P>
<P>
   Not fan of 2-ref system
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia coach Roger Neilson escaped a fine despite publicly
ripping the league and the two-referee system. Neilson became
incensed when the Flyers were called for two minor penalties by
separate refs on the same play in Game 4 against Toronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``A referee is the guy who's in charge of the game _ he can't
split it up with somebody else,'' Neilson said. ``There's two
things you never want to know: One is how they make hot dogs, and
the other is what goes on in the NHL office.'' ...
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Gary Bettman is saying little about the half-dozen
racial incidents that have targeted black players in recent years,
most recently the unproven allegation that Toronto's Tie Domi
called Philadelphia's Sandy McCarthy the ``N'' word. ``Obviously,''
Bettman said, ``if there are things we need as a league and if
teams need to discuss things with their players in consultation
with the players association, that's something we have to look
at.''
</P>
<P>
   McCarthy on Domi's denials: ``He's like a rat trying to hide.
He's a little weasel. He has to tell the truth _ if he's a real
man.''
</P>
<P>
   Etc.
</P>
<P>
   Dallas defenseman Shawn Chambers after playing 56 minutes, 21
seconds, nearly a complete regulation game, in the Stars'
triple-overtime win over Edmonton: ``I couldn't even get excited. I
saw the pile of players celebrating the (winning) goal. I just
turned and went the other way to (goalie) Eddie Belfour.'' It was
Belfour's third triple-overtime game. ... The NHL might soften the
crease rules in the off-season to something akin to ``no harm, no
foul.'' As an example, a skate in the crease would not negate a
goal if an official thinks that the offensive player did not
interfere with the goaltender. ... Washington has told goalie Rick
Tabaracci he won't be back. ... Chicago center Alex Zhamnov thinks
No. 36 makes him look too slow so he's switching to 13 next season.
Honest. ...If Boston or Toronto should advance to the finals
against Detroit, it would be the first meeting of Original Six
teams for the Stanley Cup in 20 years, since Montreal beat the New
York Rangers in 1978-79. ... There were eight third-period
comebacks in the first 23 playoff games, equaling the number in the
entire 1998 post-season.
</P>
<P>
   Thrashers update
</P>
<P>
   Montreal assistant coach Dave King, a candidate for the
Thrashers' head coaching job, is considering an offer for the top
job with Jokerit, a team based in Helsinki, Finland. But Waddell,
the Thrashers GM, isn't concerned: ``If we lose (a candidate)
because of other opportunities, it would be unfortunate. But we
won't lose anybody we're really hot on, and at this point we're
lukewarm on all of the candidates.'' ... Ottawa's quick exit might
have hurt the potential candidacy of Senators' assistant coach Mike
Murphy. ... The Thrashers will host ``NHL Breakout '99,'' a street
and in-line hockey tournament, May 8-9, at Whitewater in Marietta.
Entry information is available at area ice and roller rinks and
sporting goods stores. ... Waddell expressed no doubt that Philips
Arena will be completed in time for next season as he accompanied a
few media members on a tour the other day. Not that the Thrashers
need any extra motivation to have their arena finished, but they
would be fined $15 million by the NHL if it's not. ... With the
NHL's decision to retire Gretzky's No. 99 league-wide, the
Thrashers pulled off this rarity: retiring a uniform number before
they ever assigned one.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
