<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 15:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BILLFISH02-COX     05-01 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BILLFISH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Florida official says national plan to save billfish inadequate
 &HT;    By Willie Howard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ A plan to protect billfish in the
Atlantic Ocean, announced Monday by the National Marine Fisheries
Service, will do ``absolutely nothing'' to reduce billfish
mortality or to rebuild overfished billfish populations, the
chairman of the NMFS billfish advisory panel said this week.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Nelson, executive director of Florida's Marine Fisheries
Commission and chairman of the panel that advises NMFS on billfish,
said the plan fails to significantly address the bycatch, or the
unintended catch, of sailfish and marlin by commercial longliners
who use rigs 30 to 40 miles long containing thousands of hooks.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at blue and white marlin and sailfish, 94 percent
of the mortality is from longline bycatch,'' Nelson said.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. commercial fishermen are not allowed to land or sell
billfish. But because they can't select which fish will bite their
longline hooks, billfish are unintentionally caught and killed.
</P>
<P>
   The National Coalition for Marine Conservation has asked the
NMFS to restrict longlines to 10 miles in length and impose a
six-hour maximum soak time. If longlines were pulled and checked
more frequently, NCMC says, hooked billfish would be more likely to
be alive when released than if the rigs are left in the water for
long periods of time.
</P>
<P>
   NMFS spokesman Gordon Helm said the agency, an arm of the U.S.
Department of Commerce, is studying longline length restrictions
and soak-time limits.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a living document,'' Helm said of the fishery
management plan for Atlantic billfish, an outgrowth of the 1996
Sustainable Fisheries Act, which requires federal regulators to
identify overfished stocks and develop plans to rebuild them.
</P>
<P>
   ``These plans might as well be written by commercial
longliners,'' said Mike Leech, president of the International Game
Fish Association, which represents recreational anglers.
</P>
<P>
   Plans approved this week, which take effect June 1, do limit the
number of longline fishermen, something the commercial fishing
industry has wanted for years. They also forbid longline fishing
during the month of June in a section of the ocean off New Jersey
to protect bluefin tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Other measures include:
</P>
<P>
   _ A three-fish-per-person daily bag limit on Atlantic yellowfin
tuna for recreational anglers.
</P>
<P>
   _ A one-shark-per-vessel recreational bag limit and a 4 1/2-foot
minimum size limit on several species of coastal sharks, not
including 19 shark species already protected by no-take rules.
</P>
<P>
   _ Voluntary education workshops for both commercial and
recreational anglers on several species of highly migratory fish in
the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   The NMFS had proposed closing a small portion of the Atlantic
off Florida to longline fishing for three months to protect
juvenile swordfish, but that part of the plan is being
reconsidered.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed closure off Florida is expected to go back before
the Department of Commerce after public hearings this summer.
Meanwhile, the longline industry is pushing for a buyout plan that
would result in large time and area closures for longline fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Nelson Beideman, executive director of the New Jersey-based Blue
Water Fishermen's Association, which represents 160 operators of
longline fishing vessels, said his organization is working with
Congress on a plan for the government to buy some 60 longline
vessels, for $15 million. In exchange, much of the Atlantic ocean,
from North Carolina to the Florida Keys, would be closed year-round
to longline fishing.
</P>
<P>
   Beideman said the buyout and Atlantic closure, along with a
half-year closure in a portion of the Gulf of Mexico off the
Florida Panhandle, would reduce by 47 percent the unintended
killing of juvenile swordfish and longline billfish mortality by 24
percent.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
