<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-FEATURE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Celtics miss on promise, playoffs
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the jockeying for playoff positioning and the race
for the final postseason spots goes down to the NBA's final
regular-season days, a group of teams must feel like the creepy
neighbor who wasn't invited to the party.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone expected the Chicago Bulls to be excluded from the
fray, what with the gutting by general manager Jerry Krause. But in
Boston, Cleveland and New Jersey _ where much was expected this
season _underachievement has been the order of the year.
</P>
<P>
   In this shortened season with wide-open prospects, the Celtics,
Cavaliers and Nets have floundered in disturbing fashion. Injuries
have played a part, particularly in Cleveland, but injuries, we're
told so often, are a part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   From the start, Rick Pitino's Celtics hardly resembled the team
that won 35 games last season. They were young and expected to be
better, but instead they've been awful. Pitino's pressing scheme
essentially is an all-or-nothing system, and it mostly resulted in
blowout defeats.
</P>
<P>
   Among other problems, which include Antoine Walker being booed
by home fans, point guard Kenny Anderson was hardly the factor
Pitino expected when he traded promising Chauncey Billups for the
former Georgia Tech star. Anderson's plight epitomizes this year's
Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel good about my career,'' Anderson said. ``I'm an
underachiever, as far as what my potential was when I was coming
out of high school, college. I feel I've underachieved. It's not
over, though, so there's a light at the end of the tunnel.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been more down for the Cavaliers, a team of which much was
expected, what with the return of four rookies who received
significant minutes last year. The best of the lot was center
Zydrunas Ilgauskas, who went down with a broken foot a month into
the season. Point guard Brevin Knight and guard Derek Anderson both
missed time with injuries, too. And so, coach Mike Fratello is
liable to have his first sub.-500 season since he coached the
1984-85 Hawks to a 34-48 mark. Meanwhile, it's been ugly all season
for New Jersey, a team picked by some to win the Atlantic Division.
Instead, the Nets got John Calipari fired as they stumbled through
the season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
