<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBA-NOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Malone shows no remorse By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The longer Karl Malone plays, the more he opens
himself up to criticism as a dirty player. An unrepentant dirty
player.
</P>
<P>
   The latest evidence against the Utah Jazz forward came last week
when he clocked Phoenix center Joe Kleine with an elbow to the face
that took plastic surgery and 30 stitches to close. If that had not
been bad enough, Malone said later, after claiming that he didn't
mean to bloody Kleine, ``That's the way I play, and that's the way
I'm going to play as long as I'm playing.''
</P>
<P>
   He offered no apology. That left Suns coach Danny Ainge
incensed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl showed zero remorse,'' Ainge said. ``All he's done is
bash Joe and Luc Longley. All he does is play dirty and show no
remorse for the players he leaves injured on the floor.''
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Malone injured Longley's knee when he leaned on
the Phoenix center and then kicked him. Longley missed seven games.
Last year, Malone knocked out San Antonio's David Robinson and
guard Elliot Perry with elbows to the face. Malone once fractured a
bone in the face of the late Derek Smith with an elbow and bloodied
Isiah Thomas with an elbow.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge cited that history as a pattern. ``If this was the first
time Karl had done it, you could excuse it,'' Ainge said. ``You
never know which Karl Malone is doing the talking, anyway. Is it
the one who says he's never playing in Utah again? Or is it the one
who is crying at the podium after re-negotiating his contract _ for
the fifth time? You might as well call him Sybil.''
</P>
<P>
   PHIL'S NIGHT
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls will raise a banner Wednesday at the United Center for
former coach Phil Jackson, who quit after last season and six NBA
championships in eight years.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan is expected to attend, along with presidential
hopeful Bill Bradley, among others.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jackson has spent much of his time on the
motivational speaking circuit and aiding Bradley's quest for the
White House. He probably will coach next season and have his choice
of jobs from New Jersey and Washington _ who have interims at the
helm now _ and possibly New York and the Lakers, depending on how
those teams finish.
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan's purchase of the Charlotte Hornets apparently
imminent, Jackson probably would get a call from his former player,
too, although Paul Silas has made a strong bid to keep the job.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS UP
</P>
<P>
   To the Spurs. After a slow start, Tim Duncan's squad has been
brilliant and poses as much a threat as anyone in the playoffs _
despite David Robinson's demise.
</P>
<P>
   THUMBS DOWN
</P>
<P>
   To the Lakers' Kobe Bryant. A sinking ship hardly needs a
20-year-old to argue with his coach about a defensive assignment,
as Bryant did with Kurt Rambis last week. Might Kobe be getting too
big for his britches?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
