<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONDON-BOMBING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUSPECT HELD, OVER BOMBING IN LONDON: FEAR PERSISTS 
</HEADLINE>
  (kd) 
 By ALAN COWELL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British police officers sped to a small Hampshire
village southwest of London early Saturday to arrest a man they
said may be involved in a wave of extremist bombings that claimed
two lives in a blast Friday night at a gay bar in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   But the arrest failed to quell widespread anxieties among
minority groups that they may be the next target of what the police
depict as a hate-driven racial campaign by extreme rightists that
has sent tremors of nervousness across London. Representatives of
London's Jewish groups said worshipers may be searched at
synagogues and Jews would patrol some areas to watch for suspicious
activities. ``We are concerned, but I hope that the precautions we
have put into effect will stop anything happening,'' said Mike
Whine of the British Board of Jewish Deputies.
</P>
<P>
   More than 70 people were wounded when the bomb _ the latest in a
series of attacks _ exploded at the Admiral Duncan pub. The police
said they were linking the Soho blast to earlier attacks on
Londoners of African-Caribbean descent in Brixton, south London,
two weeks ago Saturday, and a second blast last weekend in Brick
Lane, east London, which has a large Asian population. Six people
were described by hospital authorities Saturday as in a critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
   A person asserting to represent a shadowy right-wing extremist
group calling itself the White Wolves called a London radio station
to take responsibility for last night's attack.
</P>
<P>
   The three attacks have left London jittery. The police cordoned
off an area in the district around Victoria station, a main railway
terminus, Saturday after a further scare but there was no immediate
word on whether a bomb had been found.
</P>
<P>
   The timing of the bombings remains mysterious. When the first
bombs went off in Brixton and Brick Lane, some Londoners concluded
that they were in protest of an official inquiry that unearthed
police racism in investigations of the killing of a black
teen-ager, Stephen Lawrence, by a gang of white youths who have
escaped punishment. Since then, though, the bombers' activities
seem to suggest a broader, neo-Nazi agenda aimed at the same groups
vilified by Hitler and the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Over all, five people have now been arrested but two were
released on bail. The arrests follow the release by the police of
images from a closed-circuit television camera that recorded a
young white man in a baseball cap apparently surveying a busy
market area in Brixton two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good likeness for the video still,'' a police
spokesman said of the man seized when scores of officers burst into
a modest, semi-detached house on a quiet residential street in
Cove, Hampshire, on the southwest outskirts of London near
Farnborough at 2 a.m. Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Neighbors told reporters that the police ordered them to leave
their houses as officers raided the three-bedroom house where, a
police spokesman said, ``combustible materials'' were found.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the suspect shared the house with another man
and a woman and had lived there for about a year. The man was said
to be in his early 20s. A police spokesman said the man had been
arrested ``in connection with the Brixton and Brick Lane bombs,''
but did not say whether the man was also suspected of involvement
in Friday's attack on a sunny, summery evening in Soho.
</P>
<P>
   The police raid stunned the quiet village. ``It's shocked us
all,'' Olive Gibbs, a 73-year-old who lives two doors away from the
man who was detained, told the British Press Association. ``It's
such a quiet place and there has never been anything like that
happening here.''
</P>
<P>
   Sharon Wells, a 34-year-old mother of two who also lives nearby,
said: ``We used to let our children run around but I'm going to
ship them out today. We've heard that the house is a bomb
factory.''
</P>
<P>
   While little is known about the White Wolves group that asserted
responsibility for Friday night's blast _ and has also been linked
to the previous two _ investigators say their name suggests
neo-Nazi links, and some newspaper reports have said they are
connected to similar extremists in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The White Wolves are said to be an offshoot of Combat 18 _ which
takes its name from the position of Adolf Hitler's initials in the
alphabet _ itself a violent breakaway from rightist political
organizations. Some groups reported a letter sent to some of them
before the Brixton bomb that told Jews and ``nonwhites'' to leave
Britain by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jews and nonwhites who remain after 1999 has ended will be
exterminated,'' the letter said. ``When the clocks strike midnight
on 31 December, 1999, the White Wolves will begin to howl and when
the wolves begin to howl the Wolves begin to hunt. You have been
warned. Hail Britannia.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
