<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Overworked pitching a problem for Indians
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ As the Cleveland Indians fight the urge to fit
themselves for their championship rings, a detail plagues them as
they rush off toward October. It's their pitching staff. It's an
autumn disaster waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   With the majors' best record entering the weekend, Cleveland has
a starting staff that continually failed to get through the middle
innings. A suspect bullpen, supposedly addressed with offseason
acquisitions, already has been overworked. As the postseason is all
about pitching, the Indians are riding for a fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the rate we're going,'' manager Mike Hargrove said,
``(relievers) Paul Shuey, Steve Reed and Mike Jackson are going to
end up with 120 appearances each.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not Shuey. Forced to work three consecutive games in
Boston last weekend, he tore a hamstring and might miss most of
May. What's puzzling about that trend is that Cleveland's staff had
been considered one of the AL's soundest. Now the club is obsessed
with soaring pitch-counts.
</P>
<P>
   In a four-game span last week, Cleveland starters threw 136
pitches in the first inning alone, an average of 34 per man, when
even half that total is above the norm. Where pitching coach Phil
Regan targets a nine-inning game between 117-120 pitches, both Dave
Burba and Jaret Wright would average 151 pitches per nine innings
at their current rate; Doc Gooden would be up to 197.
</P>
<P>
   ``Guys are throwing too many pitches early,'' Regan said.
``They're pitching themselves out of games.''
</P>
<P>
   That spelled ruin for a bullpen that blew a league-high 23 saves
last year. Over the winter, the Indians dealt for Ricky ``Don't
Call Me Ricardo'' Rincon and Jerry Spradlin. Closer Jose Mesa, Doug
Jones and Eric Plunk, who had a combined 4.64 ERA as Indians last
season, were jettisoned, and the club even picked up Mark Langston
when San Diego cut him and made him a reliever.
</P>
<P>
   The changes have improved nothing. Shuey is down, Rincon is
sitting out a month with a a bad elbow, and Langston's availability
is limited because of a bone spur in his left elbow. Closer Jackson
is fighting muscle strains on both sides of his rib cage. Spradlin
was so bad he was dumped on San Francisco for some middling
prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Now the bullpen is populated with suspects Paul Wagner and Rich
DeLucia.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the Indians are scoring by the bushel simply
because they have to. The pitching staff gave up five or more runs
in eight of the first 21 games, while the bullpen blew three save
chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked a lot about pitch counts the last few days, Regan
said. ``Guys have to keep their pitch counts down and stay in games
longer to give our bullpen a break.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Chad Ogea, the only active pitcher to win a World
Series game for the Indians, is 2-1 in Philadelphia, has worked
into the seventh in three of his first five starts and hasn't
exceeded 100 pitches yet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
