<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0652 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-NRA-ART-N     05-01 1226
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-NRA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THOUSANDS MOUNT PROTEST AS NRA MEETS IN DENVER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Idaho, Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE and JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ As more than 7,000 protesters demonstrated outside, the
National Rifle Association held its annual meeting in a hotel
ballroom here Saturday, rallying defiantly against calls for
restricting guns after the school shootings in nearby Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   More than 3,000 people crammed into a room set up for 2,000 for
the association's meeting, which had been scaled back from three
days to one after the Littleton shootings, in which 15 people died.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Charlton Heston, the actor who is the president of the
organization, the pro-gun group had spurned calls from state and
local politicians and others to scrap its convention out of respect
for those killed just 10 miles away in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, they observed a moment of silence for the
victims. Then the Colorado secretary of state, Vikki Buckley, a
Republican, delivered a rousing defense of the constitutional right
to bear arms.
</P>
<P>
   Of the killings in Littleton, Ms. Buckley said: ``Guns are not
the issue. Hate, what pulled the trigger of violence, is the
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who would run the NRA out of town need to look at our
own children who are engaging in irresponsible sex and having
children they cannot take care of,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Raise as much heck about that as you did the NRA and you will
have saved more lives in five years than are taken with guns in a
century,'' she declared to sustained applause and a standing
ovation.
</P>
<P>
   Outside, protesters held signs denouncing the event and the
group.
</P>
<P>
   ``Denver doesn't want NRA blood money,'' read one sign, as
protesters walked somberly from the state capitol to the hotel
singing ``We Shall Overcome.'' Another sign read, ``Cradle
children, not Uzis.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I am embarrassed that I was not involved in this earlier,''
said George Flynn, a protester and the father of a Columbine High
School student who was not harmed in the attack. ``It took
something like this to wake me up, and I am ashamed of that.''
</P>
<P>
   But convention participants were unapologetic.
</P>
<P>
   Clem Potelunas, a civil engineer, drove his pickup truck from
Idaho Falls, Idaho, for the gun meeting. ``We're here to show
solidarity for what we believe in,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Wayne LaPierre, executive vice president of the rifle
association, followed Ms. Buckley with a more subdued policy
speech. He said that the Littleton shootings had left a vast
misimpression of where the rifle association stood on several
issues.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre emphasized that ``the real problem is unprosecuted
criminal access to guns,'' a statement that brought much applause.
</P>
<P>
   But his very modest nods to anything that hinted at concession
were greeted coolly.
</P>
<P>
   For example, LaPierre said: ``We believe in absolutely gun-free,
zero-tolerance, totally safe schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials said that the group had never gone on record as saying
there should be absolutely no guns in schools. LaPierre said that
anyone who took a gun to school should be expelled.
</P>
<P>
   LaPierre also said the association supported trigger locks as
long as they were voluntary, not mandatory. The association has
been at odds with gun manufacturers over this point, with most
manufacturers now routinely outfitting new weapons with such locks.
The rifle association's position may seem like the smallest of
steps, especially since the locks can easily be removed and do not
have to be put back on again. But as recently as a year ago, the
association would not have said, as LaPierre did Saturday, ``We
support and encourage the distribution, development and use of
safety locks.''
</P>
<P>
   In Littleton, law enforcement officials continued to investigate
the shootings. On Friday, the parents of one of the killers, Dylan
Klebold, met for several hours with investigators at their lawyer's
office.
</P>
<P>
   But The Denver Post reported Saturday that the parents of Eric
Harris, the other killer, had said through their lawyer that they
would talk to police only if granted total immunity from
prosecution. Their lawyer, Benjamin Colkitt III, was not reachable
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Jefferson County sheriff, John Stone, has said that a search
of the Harris house on the evening of the shooting found a
sawed-off shotgun barrel and bomb-making materials fully visible in
Eric's bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   Randy Brown, who reported to police last year that his son,
Brooks, had been threatened by Eric Harris on the Internet,
rejected comments by the sheriff's office that the authorities had
not contacted the Harris and Klebold families because the Browns
had requested anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is beyond ludicrous,'' Randy Brown told The Denver Rocky
Mountain News. ``We took the complaint to them with the kids'
names. We wanted them to be arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We asked them if they could keep our name out of it, act like
they found it on their own, so we didn't have to worry about Eric
killing Brooks,'' Brown said. He added that investigators had never
telephoned to say that they had had problems gaining entry to Eric
Harris' Web site.
</P>
<P>
   In the angry atmosphere following the shootings, there have been
bomb threats to the hotel where the NRA members met Saturday and
death threats to families of the two suspects. Doug Dean, a state
representative from Colorado Springs, who sponsored a bill this
spring to loosen rules on the granting of permits for concealed
weapons, has said that he has received so many telephone threats
that he may leave politics. Dean, a Republican, is the State House
majority leader.
</P>
<P>
   Reflecting a continuing jumpy mood, high school absenteeism
spiked on Friday, fueled by Internet rumors that there would be
trouble on April 30, the 54th anniversary of Hitler's death.
</P>
<P>
   Denver has not been immune to the rash of bomb threats that have
plagued schools around the nation in the last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Arvada police arrested a 34-year-old woman with a
history of run-ins with school administrators over the treatment of
her son.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Thomas, the Jefferson County district attorney, quoted the
woman, Faye Rae Holt, as saying in a recorded message on Wednesday
on the attendance telephone line for Pomona High School: ``There
goes your students. There goes your school. This is not a joke.''
The bomb threat forced a two-hour evacuation of the school
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, on a hill in Clement Park overlooking Columbine, as
many as 300 people an hour visited memorials to the victims. Last
Tuesday, Greg Zanis, an Illinois carpenter whose father-in-law was
murdered in 1996, drove here and erected 15 crosses.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday afternoon, Brian Rohrbough, whose son Daniel, a
15-year-old freshman, was murdered in the shootings, uprooted and
carried away two crosses that carried the names of the two killers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not an issue of closure, this is an issue of right and
wrong,'' Rohrbough said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23 people injured in the shootings, four remained in
hospitals Saturday, two in serious condition and two in fair.
Protests against violence and in sympathy with the victims were to
take place Saturday in 25 countries.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
