</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SLEEPYHOLLOW-GM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLEEPY HOLLOW AND DEVELOPERS PREPARE FOR LIFE AFTER GM 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SLEEPY HOLLOW, N.Y. _ General Motors is almost done taking apart
the massive plant here where it made 11 million cars. As workers
cart off chunks of steel and long ribbons of aluminum in the shadow
of the Hudson highlands, this village is beginning to feel less
like a factory town and more like a river town.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are vistas opening up that no one has seen for the last
100 years,'' said Mayor Philip Zegarelli. ``It's like a curtain
rising.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of the communities along the Hudson River in
Westchester County, Sleepy Hollow is in the delicate process of
de-industrialization. Up and down the county's 50 miles of
riverfront, towns are reclaiming land where chemicals were
processed, sugar refined and ovens, carpets and wire made. Towns
are finally turning years, even decades, of talk into action, with
parks, marinas and housing in the works.
</P>
<P>
   For years, factory workers and residents here, along with local
and state officials, fought the closing of the General Motors
plant, which at its peak employed 5,000 people and provided half
the taxes in the village. But when the plant shut three years ago,
the village, in a gesture that signaled the end of an era, changed
its name from North Tarrytown to Sleepy Hollow.
</P>
<P>
   Now, General Motors is reviewing proposals for its property from
three developers, including Donald Trump. The company says it hopes
to select a plan by the fall. All three call for a mix of housing
and commercial space, and under the village's recent rezoning,
there is the potential to create a village within a village _ 1,900
apartments that could nearly double Sleepy Hollow's population of
8,300.
</P>
<P>
   Because the 97-acre parcel is Westchester's largest developable
tract along the Hudson, and is at a point where the Metro North
train tracks are inland, giving the land riverfront access that
provides magnificent views, its transformation is stirring
excitement and anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   Struggling business owners envision throngs of shoppers.
Residents dream of strolling along a public esplanade at the
Hudson's edge. Village officials look forward to restoring the tax
base. But environmentalists and some of the village's residents say
the plan could choke the village with traffic. And elected
officials are feeling pressure to find just the right balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The orientation of the site toward the river is fantastic,''
said Zegarelli. ``By the same token, you want to be careful that
whatever proposals come up don't swamp the village, either. It's
such a huge undertaking _ you really can't blow it.''
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, construction will not begin for at least a few
years. Once General Motors selects a developer, the plan will be
subject to an environmental-impact study. One hurdle is poor access
to the parcel; only one road, the village's main street, Beekman
Avenue, leads directly to the site from Route 9.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists and residents are particularly concerned about
traffic. The mayor believes that rezoning carried out under the
previous administration allows far too many residences, which could
mean traffic problems.
</P>
<P>
   Others have raised questions about pollution on the property.
Residents remember when you could tell which colors the cars were
being painted by looking at the Hudson. But General Motors
considers this a ``relatively clean site,'' because it was an
assembly plant, said Phyllis Riina, a real estate manager for the
company. Oil contamination was found in the area of the paint shop,
she said, but cleanup work, which entailed removing soil, was
recently completed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the state Department of Environmental Conservation
reviewed the company's records to determine whether the property
should be added to the state's Superfund program for polluted
sites. An agency spokesman, Samuel Thernstrom, said there was ``no
evidence to suggest that hazardous waste had been disposed of on
the site.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are construction difficulties. Part of the site is
landfill, and General Motors expects that builders will have to
drive pilings into the ground to support new structures.
</P>
<P>
   There are marketing challenges as well. The surrounding
neighborhood includes Sleepy Hollow's most modest housing, as
wealthy residents had no interest in living next to a
2.5-million-square-foot factory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You do have some tacky older buildings, and you're going to
see that,'' said Elio De Cecchis, the owner of De Cecchis Realty
here. ``You are certainly going to exclude some people who can't
overcome'' that sight.
</P>
<P>
   Village officials are eager to see the property return fully to
the tax rolls. The Board of Trustees ran out of money in April and
had to borrow $500,000 until the fiscal year ends at the end of
May.
</P>
<P>
   The financial troubles are the result of a long-simmering
dispute with General Motors. The company is relying on an
assessment valuing its property at $12 million, which resulted from
an agreement made with the village before the auto plant closed.
The village is insisting on valuing the land at $44 million, based
on a reappraisal, and officials are not cashing any tax payments
until the matter, which is in court, is settled. Last year, the
dispute forced the village to lay off seven employees, including
two police officers.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear what development proposals General Motors is
considering. The company will not divulge the names of the
developers, but Trump has said that he is a contender. He is vague
about his plan, saying only that it calls for mostly housing and
shops. (The zoning would also allow a hotel.) As for concerns about
housing density and traffic, Trump said: ``It's a big site. We're
going to come up with a better way to enter the project.''
</P>
<P>
   Some residents are skeptical, however. They say traffic is
already a problem. ``You come out here on Beekman Avenue at 3
o'clock, and you can't move,'' said John Masias, 73, who worked at
the GM plant for 32 years. ``Personally, I don't think they should
have any apartments because of the congestion. The town's too
small.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are worried about tipping the socioeconomic scale toward
the rich, even though Mayor Zegarelli says he will insist that any
development include moderately priced housing for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The village now is economically diverse, with large gracious
homes in the verdant Philipse Manor section and plain multifamily
housing downtown.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm concerned about gentrification,'' said Stuart Siegel, an
IBM computer scientist who lives in a rental building. ``If Trump's
involved, it could raise the rents on existing apartments.''
</P>
<P>
   But everyone, it seems, looks forward to regaining access to the
Hudson River, which broadens out in the vicinity of Sleepy Hollow
to one of its widest points. On a recent overcast day, a lone
Canada goose floated on the river's gray surface by the General
Motors plant, as welders cut through a building facade, sending out
showers of sparks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a river town,'' said Bruce MacDonald, 42, who was
snapping photographs of the scene. ``But sometimes you don't feel
that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
