<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 15:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0658 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH02-COX     05-01 1672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush's absence in key state rubs voters the wrong way
 &HT;    By Ken Herman
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANCHESTER, N.H. _ Here's John Kasich learning how to mush a
dogsled in Laconia. There's John McCain on the cafe and barber shop
circuit in Portsmouth. On Saturday, Lamar Alexander opened a new
headquarters here.
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole has been through. Ditto Dan Quayle, Gary Bauer,
Steve Forbes and Pat Buchanan. And many of them will be back
tonight for the New Hampshire GOP's grandly named ``Vision for the
New Millennium'' banquet.
</P>
<P>
   But where, some from the Granite State are asking, is George W.
Bush, the front-runner in absentia?
</P>
<P>
   Tonight, as his rivals speak, some of Bush's influential New
Hampshire backers will be on hand, without a candidate but with a
``Coming Attractions'' display pushing Bush like he is going to be
the feel-good hit of the summer. For now, that _ and sign up party
activiststs _ is about all they can do.
</P>
<P>
   The New Hampshire primary is nine months away, but activists and
voters here expect candidates to show up early and often. They
always do, a tradition that magnifies Bush's absence.
</P>
<P>
   By autumn, Bush probably will have been here enough to make
voters forget his late arrival. For now, however, it's turning off
some folks and turning them toward other presidential contenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know enough about George Bush,'' said Bob Coffey, a
Newmarket business consultant who likes his politics on the
hand-to-hand level. ``I'm not sure he is really wanting to be
president.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he'll be here soon, shortly after the Texas
legislative session ends May 31. Not soon enough, Coffey says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He does get time off. We all get weekends off. All of these
other guys are coming up here on weekends. I don't see why he can't
make a trip up here every once in a while,'' said Coffey, who had
Kasich at his home two weeks ago and is leaning toward backing the
House member from Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   In nearby Bedford, state Rep. Kathleen Flora is getting similar
bad vibes about Bush. She has given up on him. Later this month,
she'll participate in a news conference featuring state and party
leaders backing McCain.
</P>
<P>
   It's a decision she reached after taking close looks at McCain,
Alexander, Dole and Quayle. Bush, out of sight, was out of mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not paid attention to George W. Bush,'' said Flora,
``and the reason for that is he has not been here and has not made
himself known. I didn't feel like he was all that interested in the
whole thing.''
</P>
<P>
   She is not impressed with Bush's line about having work to do in
his current job before looking for a new one.
</P>
<P>
   ``He could have come up on the weekends,'' she said. ``I think
he has just absolutely been invisible. ... I haven't heard what he
stands for, and I haven't seen what he has done, and I haven't seen
the interest that he supposedly has for winning the presidency.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the undercurrent of dissatisfaction about Bush's
absence, he is well-armed to get a full-blown campaign up and
running as soon as he is ready. He has far more money than the
other candidates (save perhaps for the self-financed Forbes), and
his organization here boasts the top names. Sen. Judd Gregg, owner
and operator of the state's best GOP network, is a Bush
co-chairman, as is former Gov. Steve Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   Gregg scoffs at the notion that Bush's late arrival could become
a problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``The response to him has been very strong and hasn't been
tempered in any way by the fact that he said he can't get to New
Hampshire until the Legislature is out,'' he said. ``I've told
people he will be here with enthusiasm and with energy, pursuing a
very hands-on, I'm-here, ask-me-your-questions campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush charm, money and machinery will kick in to bolster poll
numbers that already put him atop the field here. A Franklin Pierce
College poll conducted April 22-27 for WNDS-TV of Derry, N.H.,
showed Bush with a commanding lead.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, slowly but surely giving up the guise of a guy who is
merely thinking about running, began papering New Hampshire last
year with ``keep your powder dry'' letters to folks with
long-standing ties to his family.
</P>
<P>
   His only face time in a state whose voters crave it came April 8
in a live interview on Manchester's WMUR-TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``I intend to come up to New Hampshire and begin a grass-roots
campaign,'' he said. ``I understand that New Hampshire is retail
politics, and I look forward to coming up there to shake as many
hands as I can, look people in the eye and tell them where my heart
is.''
</P>
<P>
   That will begin June 14 in Manchester, where Bush will be the
featured speaker at the New Hampshire Federation of Republican
Women's annual Lilac Luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   And when he gets here, the game will change for the others who
have been here for months and, in some cases, years. The goal is to
emerge as the candidate who can move to the head of the class if
the frontrunner stumbles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a race to be the anti-Bush,'' a top Alexander strategist
said Saturday as the ex-Tennessee governor headed door to door.
</P>
<P>
   Barbara Russell, who quit as assistant state GOP chair to sign
on with the Bush team here, knows her guy is running ahead, but
also knows there is some crankiness about his late arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are candidates in on a weekly basis. Some days you see
several,'' she noted.
</P>
<P>
   Russell spun Bush's absence as a source of anticipation, not
frustration. ``There is a lot of excitement about being able to see
him and hear him and ask him questions. Up here, we like to see and
touch and interact,'' she said. ``Many people have signed on. Many
more are very anxious to take him for a test drive.''
</P>
<P>
   She believes Bush's friendly style will play well with New
Hampshire voters, once he gets there. She also thinks Bush is
scoring points by sticking to his commitment to make the Texas
Legislature his top priority.
</P>
<P>
   ``He proves he is a man of his word, loyal to the voters of
Texas,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Grafton County GOP Chairwoman Nancy Merrill admires that but
didn't let it stop her from signing on elsewhere. She couldn't wait
for Bush to get here. She has signed on with McCain, who has been
here several times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing Senator McCain helped me to make my decision,''
Merrill said. ``I always liked his record, and something happens in
New Hampshire that's wonderful when you can listen to the
candidates, not just sound bites.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The absence of the other candidate may have been a factor to
me,'' she said of Bush, adding, however, ``I know a good many
voters up here are solid Bush supporters even though he hasn't been
here yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush backers such as Russell understand the value of being here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen Forbes help someone on with their coat. I have
seen Alexander move very easily and graciously through crowds.
Kasich moves through a crowd with a little more animation. He
connects in a different way with people. Elizabeth Dole, with her
warm smile and Southern accent, just charms people,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Frequent fliers
</P>
<P>
   Being here also shows you care, according to McCain backer Nancy
Merrill, who thinks June may be a little late for Bush's debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is a sense that he doesn't think New
Hampshire is important. I just think there is probably a little
frustration that he hasn't been here so people could actually hear
him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The others have been heard, some for years. Buchanan is making
his third race here. Alexander holds an annual summer lobster bake
that has grown into one of the state's biggest events (1,300
lobsters in 1997, 2,500 in 1998).
</P>
<P>
   After his Saturday door-to-door tour, Alexander said he knows
many New Hampshire voters are months away from picking a favorite.
But he is sure he is scoring points with his frequent visits.
</P>
<P>
   What's the peril for a candidate not due here until June 14?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we're about to find that out,'' said Alexander. ``The
peril is you might not be seen as ready to be president. I think
people like to size you up and chew you over. ... It's one thing to
be a governor. Going from being governor to being president is like
going from the playground to the NBA finals, and the people of New
Hampshire know that.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Forbes spent $5 million on TV ads. Dole is well-known
from her husband's campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is a familiar name, if not face, from his father's
campaigns. But the most recent one, 1992, is a fading memory to
many folks.
</P>
<P>
   The newcomers in the field have worked to keep their names in
the papers in recent weeks. McCain showed up to chat with the
breakfast crowd at Cafe Brioche in Portsmouth and shake hands at
John's Barber Shop and the Federal Cigar newsstand.
</P>
<P>
   It's the kind of campaigning that counts here, according to
Kasich, who talked about the hands-on factor after his klatch at
the Coffey house last month.
</P>
<P>
   ``You let people poke you and look you in the eyes and smell you
and find out whether they like you or not,'' he told local
reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Kasich was back again this weekend as part of his grand, but
simple, plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``My strategy is to come here and bug them about every weekend,
which I've been doing about every weekend,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   There is evidence that he is approaching saturation. The first
question after his Friday night speech came from a local reporter
who showed up a bit late.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything new?'' the scribe inquired.
</P>
<P>
   All of the candidates get voter and media review when they come
through, including the scrutiny of the conservative and influential
Manchester Union-Leader, which backed Buchanan in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is clear that Governor Bush has the name and the
bankroll,'' editor-in-chief Joseph McQuaid wrote recently. ``But he
won't be making his first New Hampshire campaign appearance until
June, at which time New Hampshire voters will be able to begin
comparing and contrasting him with many other candidates.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
