<HEADER>
A0659 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONGRESS-MILK-PRICES-     05-01 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-MILK-PRICES-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONGRESS MULLS PRICING PLAN FOR NORTHEAST MILK PRODUCERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JAMES DAO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a fight pitting farmers' incomes against
consumers' pocketbooks, Congress has begun a fierce debate over
legislation that would allow dairy farmers in New York, New Jersey
and other states to charge more for milk.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would enable New York and New Jersey _ as well as
Maryland, Delaware and Pennsylvania _ to join the six New England
states in the Northeast Interstate Dairy Compact, a two-year-old
federally sanctioned cartel that sets a minimum wholesale price for
milk sold in the region.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation, which would also authorize Southern states to
create their own compact, would almost certainly raise prices at
the cash register by a few pennies a gallon, and perhaps much more.
</P>
<P>
   With 157 sponsors in the House and 39 sponsors in the Senate,
the bill is well on its way to winning the 218 House votes and 51
Senate votes it needs for passage.
</P>
<P>
   But consumer groups and businesses that process milk have led a
vigorous lobbying campaign against the measure, contending that it
would hurt the elderly and the poor. Anti-tax groups have also
opposed the bill, saying it would have the effect of imposing a
milk tax on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   On the other side, environmentalists have joined farmers in
asserting that the measure would help small dairy farmers stay in
business, keep the region's milk supply steady and prevent the sale
and development of pasture land. And Southern conservatives have
locked arms with Northern liberals in supporting the bill, saying
that, for the dairy industry at least, government regulation might
be OK after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The federal government already sets minimum prices for fluid
milk,'' said Rep. Asa Hutchinson, R-Ark., who is a lead sponsor of
the bill. ``I just want to improve the regulatory system.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate is immensely important to farmers like Tom A. Borden,
a part owner of O.A. Borden &AMP; Sons Farms in Washington County,
N.Y., 30 miles north of Albany. A sixth-generation dairy farmer who
is distantly related to the founders of Borden Foods Corp., Borden,
44, said the legislation would increase his annual income by
several thousand dollars, enough to cover part of his property
taxes and equipment costs. Most important, he said, it would ease
his anxieties about the roller-coaster milk market by guaranteeing
a minimum level of revenue from his 160-cow herd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything that makes us healthier will make it more appealing
for the next generation to take on the business,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Augustine Carson, 74, a retired postal worker from Harlem
who tries to drink a quart of milk each day to combat her
arthritis, said she feared that the legislation could end up
squeezing her already tight budget. ``If I had to pay more for
milk, I'd have to cut down on other things,'' Ms. Carson said. ``I
know farmers work hard and have to make a little more money, but
can't it come from some other source?''
</P>
<P>
   The debate on Capitol Hill will be strongly colored by regional
alliances, as the South and Northeast unite against the Midwest,
and possibly the West, where farmers contend that dairy compacts
will hurt their sales. Some urban legislators, including those from
New York City, are also expected to oppose the bill.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is particularly significant to New York state, the
nation's third largest milk producer. Under immense pressure from
the state's 8,300 dairy farmers _ down from 14,200 a decade ago _
Gov. George Pataki pushed a measure endorsing the compact through
the Legislature last year by tying it to a pay increase for the
lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, the state's senators, Charles Schumer and Daniel
Patrick Moynihan, both Democrats, support the federal bill.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would allow New York, New Jersey and Maryland _ whose
legislatures have endorsed the compact _ to join the Northeast
compact immediately. Delaware and Pennsylvania could also join once
their legislatures approve it. And it would make the Northeast
compact permanent. Because the system was controversial, the
compact was devised as a test and is scheduled to go out of
business Oct. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen Southern states, including Texas, Florida and Georgia,
would also be authorized to create a separate regional compact.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government has been regulating the milk market since
the Great Depression, and continues to set wholesale prices for
drinking milk in most regions. It does not set prices for milk used
for cheese, ice cream and other dairy products.
</P>
<P>
   But the government has been scaling back price supports since
the 1980s, causing wholesale prices to fluctuate more. In April,
for instance, the price paid to farmers for drinking milk in New
York plummeted to 99 cents per gallon from a record high of $1.50,
which would cause the average farmer's monthly revenue to drop by
thousands of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   (MORE
</P>
<P>
   Farmers say that such wild changes have made it difficult to
plan or get bank loans. They also say that declining consumption,
coupled with increased productivity, have kept milk prices
relatively low. The compact is intended to address both problems by
setting prices that are steadier, and generally higher, than the
federal price.
</P>
<P>
   Under compact rules, farmers receive the higher of the two
prices. When the federal price goes above the compact price, as it
did happen late last year, the compact price goes out of effect,
until the Federal price is the lower one. The compact price is set
by a 26-member commission appointed by the governors of the six New
England states.
</P>
<P>
   As is often the case on Capitol Hill, the debate has featured a
battle of worst case scenarios.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents contend that in states that join the Northeast
compact, milk prices will rise by 20 cents to 40 cents per gallon.
Higher prices, they say, will reduce sales, causing even more small
farms to go out of business. The real beneficiaries from the
arrangement, they maintain, are large farms, which would receive
most of the additional revenue from higher prices. Such critics say
the government should try to emphasize benefits for small farmers
by using tax cuts or aid programs that could reduce their utility
bills, property taxes and feed costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am all for helping small farmers in our state, but this
appears to be just helping big producers,'' said Rep. Carolyn
Maloney, a Democrat representing Manhattan and Queens who said she
is likely to vote against the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Proponents say that the Northeast compact has raised retail
prices only a few cents a gallon and that increases above that have
resulted from market forces. While the compact may require milk
processors to pay more for milk, those increases will not
necessarily be passed on to consumers, they say. And they assert
that without the compact, small farms will continue to fail,
causing supplies to decline and prices to rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't do this, many small farmers will go out of
business and then milk production will be in the hands of a few,''
said Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, a Republican from Utica who is pushing
for the legislation. ``And then you'll really see prices go up.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters also note that the Northeast compact has exempted
school lunch programs and the Women, Infants and Children nutrition
program for low-income families from paying the higher milk price.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy economists say both sides have been guilty of
exaggeration.
</P>
<P>
   Several economists say the Northeast compact has had a smaller
effect on prices than the critics had predicted. Although prices in
the six New England states rose sharply in the first month of the
compact, July 1997, they fell back slightly and then leveled off.
In Massachusetts, for instance, retail prices jumped by 30 cents a
gallon, to $2.89 in July 1997, but fell to $2.69 a month later, and
remained near that level for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It achieved what it was supposed to do, which is to provide
some price stability,'' said Bob Cropp, an economist with the
University of Wisconsin. He estimated that the compact had
increased retail milk prices by about 10 cents a gallon.
</P>
<P>
   Economists also questioned the central premise of the bill's
supporters: that compacts will help small farms avoid being bought
out by larger ones. ``This does precious little to prevent the
structural change that is going on in the dairy industry,'' said
Andrew Novakovic, director of Cornell University's dairy markets
and policy program.
</P>
<P>
   Dairy farmers say the legislation, while far from ideal, is the
best thing available. And, they say, they need it urgently. ``We
can't shut the cows off and wait till next year,'' said Eric Ooms,
a dairy farmer in Columbia County, N.Y.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1553EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 15:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0661 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INMATE-NYT &LR;      05-01 0436
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INMATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMATE   WINS LAWSUIT FOR $100,000 IN RETALIATION CASE 
 (DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An inmate who claimed that he had been harassed and
discriminated against because he complained about corruption at
Sing Sing state prison has been awarded $100,000 in damages by a
federal jury.
</P>
<P>
   The inmate, Ronald Maurer, 49, filed a handwritten lawsuit three
years ago in U.S. District Court in Manhattan, claiming that he had
been improperly disciplined and placed in segregated housing
because he alleged that a high-ranking correction officer was
discarding inmates' grievances.
</P>
<P>
   The jury award, handed down Wednesday, was believed to be one of
the largest in which a prisoner charged systematic retaliation,
said David Marriott, an associate at Cravath, Swaine &AMP; Moore, the
firm that took over the case last fall.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer was first incarcerated in 1990 at the prison in Ossining,
N.Y., for first-degree robbery of $100 from a Westchester
convenience store.
</P>
<P>
   Marriott described his client as a model inmate who was
college-educated and a devout Muslim.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer had an unblemished disciplinary record for five years and
was housed in the less restrictive honor block. He became active on
the Inmate Grievance Resolution Committee, according to the
lawsuit. In May 1995, he filed a grievance alleging that a sergeant
on the committee was throwing away copies of prisoners' grievances.
Marriott said that he was then written up for a spate of false
violations.
</P>
<P>
   In one instance, he was accused of trying to organize a strike
against double-bunking, a practice in which two inmates are housed
in a cell intended for one. The lawsuit claimed that the defendant,
Lt. Robert Patterson, had concocted the charge, held a hearing and
then orchestrated discipline against the inmate.
</P>
<P>
   Maurer was then sent to an isolated housing unit known as ``the
box,'' where he served 210 days, the lawsuit said.
</P>
<P>
   A superintendent at the prison later exonerated Maurer, who was
transferred to Attica state prison.
</P>
<P>
   Patterson could not be reached for comment Saturday. Court
records show that his lawyer, Nancy Lynn Eisenstadt, an assistant
attorney general, argued that he knew nothing of Maurer's
accusations that inmates' grievances were being discarded, and
therefore could not have been retaliating for them.
</P>
<P>
   But the jury found that the lieutenant had violated Maurer's
constitutional rights. It decided that Maurer should receive
$25,000 for suffering and $75,000 in punitive damages. The state
plans to seek a new trial, Marriott said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
