<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0664 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONN-STADIUM-NYT &LR;      05-01 1273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONN-STADIUM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STADIUM LOST: HOW ROWLAND'S BIGGEST COUP BECAME HIS WORST DEFEAT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn., Mass.)   By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. _ When the owner of the New England Patriots
flew to Hartford to visit his sweetheart deal for the last time on
Thursday, he did what he had always done, according to Connecticut
officials: He asked for something more.
</P>
<P>
   The owner, Robert K. Kraft, wanted 30 more days to decide
whether to honor his pledge to move the Patriots to Hartford. He
had until Sunday to withdraw from the deal without a penalty _ an
escape hatch his lawyers had insisted on inserting into the
229-page contract. After that date, he could be liable for damages
of as much as $100 million to Connecticut, which had agreed to
build him a free stadium in return for a 30-year lease, larding the
deal with extras and guarantees that made the deal the richest in
the history of sport.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. John G. Rowland, who had been bleeding politically ever
since Massachusetts business and political leaders agreed Tuesday
on a package of subsidies to keep the football team in Foxboro, had
had enough. He refused the extension three or four times over the
course of a tense four-hour meeting in the Capitol, according to
aides who were in the room, and said that if Kraft did not renounce
the Massachusetts overture, Connecticut would kill its stadium
deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get back to us by 5 o'clock tomorrow,'' Rowland said,
according to his aides. ``You owe us at least that much.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You give me till tomorrow night, I'll give you an answer,''
Kraft replied, according to a Patriots executive. With a dozen TV
cameras waiting outside the office, the men began drafting a vague
statement about the meeting. According to the Connecticut camp,
Kraft then said, ``You mean we're not going to get an extension?''
</P>
<P>
   The governor just glowered.
</P>
<P>
   It was the final insult in a quick hitch that had gone bad
almost immediately after that triumphant day in November, when
Kraft told Rowland at the packed announcement ceremony, ``You're in
the red zone, and we're giving you the ball.''
</P>
<P>
   The deal's undoing seems sure to fuel the arguments of those who
have preached caution for cities and states as bidding wars for
sports franchises have escalated, and threatens the political
future of Rowland, a moderate Republican who has been mentioned as
vice-presidential material.
</P>
<P>
   At a funereal news conference Friday night, Rowland tried to
make sport of the damage to his image, saying, ``I'm not sure I had
that much of a national reputation to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft beat the governor's deadline by less than an hour,
announcing late Friday afternoon that he was killing the deal with
Connecticut because he could not be assured that the stadium, which
was to be built on a riverside site with a host of environmental
problems, would be ready for play in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland thought he had had the upper hand. But instead, he was
about to suffer the biggest embarrassment of his governorship.
Supporters contend that he should have started saying no to Kraft a
long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday, a Patriots executive said Kraft was
sorry to have hurt Rowland and admired his courage. But the
executive said the state shared the blame. While the team insisted
on having the stadium ready for play in 2002, Rowland could promise
only his best effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bargained for a deal, and the deal couldn't happen,'' the
executive said. ``That's life in the big city. We did negotiate a
hell of a deal, but the overriding thing for us was being settled
in a new football stadium by 2002 so we could compete in the
National Football League.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Patriots executive, Rowland said at one point,
``You're telling me that for one year you'll walk from a billion
dollars? I just don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   The executive said, ``He just didn't know us.''
</P>
<P>
   Now the team is back where it started, with an outmoded stadium
that Jonathan Kraft, the owner's son and a team vice president, has
described as an overgrown high school football field. Massachusetts
officials say they plan to court the Krafts aggressively between
now and May 25, the date of a National Football League meeting,
when team owners are scheduled to debate the Patriots' relocation
options.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts offer was brokered by executives of the NFL,
who wanted to keep a team in the Boston television market. But in
an interview Friday night, an executive close to Robert Kraft
dismissed the Massachusetts package with an expletive, so the terms
of any new Foxboro deal are in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   What is much more certain, according to Democratic and
Republican politicians, is that Rowland, who at 41 is the nation's
youngest governor, will need fancy footwork to recover politically
from having exposed his city and state to such a crippling setback
in morale.
</P>
<P>
   Business leaders in Hartford said that financing for any
downtown redevelopment would be much more difficult to get now that
the centerpiece of the city's hopes is gone. The many Connecticut
legislators who signed onto the stadium deal can now be expected to
bring much harsher scrutiny to any proposal from the governor. The
demonization of Kraft in the Connecticut media began immediately
Friday night, with one television station illustrating its stadium
story with a full-screen image of a donkey with Kraft's head pasted
on.
</P>
<P>
   The front page of The Hartford Courant Saturday, which had the
headline ``Dear John . . .,'' included a column called ``They
Burned Us, The Dirty Rats,'' which called the pullout ``the most
withering and subversive attack by a major sports league on a
single city in American history,'' and described Kraft as ``no
better than a common tenement rat.''
</P>
<P>
   The state has vowed to sue Kraft, asserting that he colluded in
the Massachusetts negotiations, which was barred by his contract
with Connecticut. A Patriots official said Kraft played no role in
the talks with Massachusetts. Rowland said the state would also sue
the NFL, alleging that it undermined Connecticut's contract with
the Patriots.
</P>
<P>
   While the lawsuits may deflect some of the heat, Rowland has one
major problem. His dealings with the Patriots were littered with
warning signs that the team might pull out. The governor himself
said in frustration at Thursday's meeting, according to his aides:
``You have nothing in this game. The risk is all ours.''
</P>
<P>
   The tone was set when Kraft and Rowland were originally
negotiating the deal. The team asked the state to guarantee that
all 66,000 seats in the $375 million stadium would be sold. He did
not quite get that, but the state agreed to pay for enough seats to
insure him a perpetual profit, the element of the deal that made it
the most lucrative in sports. With the free stadium in hand,
according to both sides, Kraft then asked for a free practice
center. He did not quite get that, but the state threw in a $15
million subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   Just last week, according to Rowland's aides, the Patriots faxed
a statement to the state demanding that the team be absolved from
any lawsuit over the Massachusetts negotiations, even though no
accusation had been made. The governor scheduled the Thursday
summit.
</P>
<P>
   Just as Rowland wanted the team to refuse the Massachusetts
deal, Kraft wanted to be reassured that the stadium would be ready
by 2002. That date already represented a delay in the state's
original promise, which had been silk-screened along with Patriots
logos on T-shirts legislators held up as they approved the deal:
``Connecticut 2001: A Football Odyssey.''
 &UR;  &LR; 
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
