<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REFUGEES-580&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES RESIST MOVING FROM UNSAFE BORDER TOWN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ About 100,000 Kosovo refugees remain in this
crumbling border city, and the local authorities, fearing Serb
attack, are intent on forcing them to move on to safer areas in
Albania.
</P>
<P>
   But most are reluctant to leave, especially to go to places that
could be worse than Kukes, a battered city normally of 20,000 that
is straining under the crush of so many people.
</P>
<P>
   Relief agencies, which encourage but do not force refugees to
move from unsafe border areas, have been stuck in the middle. But
during the last week they tried a new tack _ taking refugee leaders
to visit safer regions so they could see conditions there for
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   The idea was that they would report back to the refugees and
encourage them to move voluntarily before the local authorities
force them out.
</P>
<P>
   That would clear the city and make room for additional refugees,
who continue to arrive.
</P>
<P>
   But the results of the first visit by refugee leaders to another
site were not encouraging.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned, they were mobbed by refugees who feared the
future and craved information. At one camp, the leaders described
conditions in and around Peshkopi, a five-hour drive from here on
bad roads where 3,000 refugees could be resettled in public
buildings and with host families.
</P>
<P>
   The leaders had trouble persuading anyone to move. The refugees
did not like the idea that no more than six people could be settled
in each house, because that would break up the families of many
Albanians from Kosovo where families of 10 are not unusual.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees did not like being moved away from doctors and food
readily available in the tent camp where they have been living for
a month. They could not obtain assurances that host families would
not demand rent. Many refugees have no money, because they were
robbed by Serb forces before they crossed the border from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   And most of all, they found insufferable the idea of being
forced to move once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``We move here, and then they force us to move there, as though
we were rabbits being hunted by a dog,'' said Mehmet Dervishi, 58,
who comes from Kosterc.
</P>
<P>
   For two weeks he and his family have been living in a tent
provided by Greece. ``They will have to send the army to take us
out of here,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees is trying to find a
middle ground that will satisfy local authorities but will also
protect the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Concern for their safety has grown since Serb rockets exploded
just outside Kukes two weeks ago. The rockets were presumably aimed
at a camp of the guerrilla Kosovo Liberation Army, which recently
opened an office here and is openly meeting Western journalists,
dropping any pretense of not having a presence in Kukes.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials also say they believe that when NATO orders the
Apache anti-tank helicopters in Albania into combat against Serb
forces, an advance base will be established near here or that the
helicopters will travel through this corridor, drawing Serb fire
that could fall on Kukes, 10 miles from the border.
</P>
<P>
   Buses have been available for weeks to take refugees to other
regions. But they often they sit half-empty, waiting for enough
refugees to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Salih Kajtazi, 70, fears that in some distant place away from
the relief agencies, he will be forced to pay for food or shelter,
and he does not have any money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those who had money have already left,'' Kajtazi said. ``Those
without money are here.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   A spokesman for the United Nations, Jacques Franquin, said local
authorities were applying intense pressure on refugees to move and
were ready to use local laws to force them to leave, though they
had agreed to wait a short while.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got them to agree to delay the process until the assessment
visits by refugee leaders are complete,'' Franquin said.
</P>
<P>
   Shaip Hajdari, 37, was one of those who went on the first
inspection. He came back and told other refugees that conditions at
Peshkopi were much better than in Kukes. He said refugees who found
a vacant house or apartment there would receive about $1 a person
per day, as well as meals and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   He said that those who stayed with host families, as a majority
would be expected to do, would not receive stipends. Instead, the
host families would receive allotments of food and other supplies
to be shared with the refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't go because I have a tractor and also a very large
family that could not be accommodated,'' Hajdari told the refugees
after returning. ``But I think you should go.''
</P>
<P>
   His suggestion was rejected when he told the refugees that
authorities had taken him to places where refugees were already
living _ in a warehouse, an old hotel and a gymnasium _ but not to
places where new refugees would be sent.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd standing in the mud was unconvinced that they should
leave. ``If I have to,'' Dervishi said, ``I will go up to the
mountains and eat grass. But I won't leave here for that place.''
</P>
</TEXT>
