<HEADER>
A0666 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-2TAK     05-01 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRISONERS-2TAKES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILOSEVIC SAYS HE WILL FREE CAPTURED U.S. SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A photo of Jesse Jackson with Steven Gonzalez moved
Friday. Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204 or 1927.) 
(mk) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia said Saturday that he would free three captive American
soldiers on Sunday after a lobbying effort by the Rev. Jesse
Jackson, who urged NATO to reciprocate by immediately halting
further airstrikes and opening negotiations on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Complete details about the transfer of the soldiers were still
being worked out, according to Yugoslav officials. But Jackson said
it was likely that the three soldiers would be taken by car or bus
from Belgrade to the Croatian border early Sunday, a trip of about
an hour and a half, and then flown by U.S. military aircraft to an
air base in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   ``Miracles do happen,'' said the Rev. Joan Campbell, general
secretary of the National Council of Churches and part of the
19-member interfaith delegation that joined Jackson in the appeal.
``Jesse Jackson made a very powerful and profound case about what
this would really mean.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who organized the trip to Belgrade despite attempts by
senior Clinton administration officials to dissuade him, said he
believed that Milosevic was ready to talk seriously about how to
meet NATO's basic demands for an end to Yugoslav violence against
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo and for the deployment of an armed
international peacekeeping force in the province.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson said he would take a letter from the Yugoslav president,
expressing this willingness to negotiate, back to Washington to
give to President Clinton, but he stressed to Milosevic that his
delegation had no authority to negotiate or make promises about
NATO's reaction to the release of the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman, said,
``We have now seen the comments from Rev. Jackson and his
delegation, and obviously we welcome the soldiers' release.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson spoke briefly by telephone on Friday to Sandy Berger,
the White House national security adviser, and called again
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is expected to travel to Europe later this week, and may
meet the released prisoners there. But White House officials were
wary of responding to their release until it actually occurs.
</P>
<P>
   The White House did not immediately react to Jackson's
suggestion that NATO suspend airstrikes.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson urged NATO to show good faith by halting, at least for
the moment, the continuous bombing raids over Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there will a bombing halt,'' he added, noting that the
three soldiers remain in the hands of the Yugoslav military, in a
military building. ``How ironic it would be, how tragic, if now as
they are ready to come home, they would be hit tonight,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The three soldiers _ Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, 24, of Los
Angeles; Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone, 25, of Smiths Creek, Mich.,
and Spc. Steven Gonzales, 21, of Huntsville, Texas _ were captured
on March 31 while on patrol along the border between Kosovo and
Macedonia. The Yugoslav authorities have maintained that they were
inside Yugoslavia when they were seized.
</P>
<P>
   The soldiers have been kept in isolation and received their
first visits from outsiders only last week, first from
representatives of the International Red Cross and on Friday from
Jackson, congressman Rod Blagojevich, D-Ill., and two journalists.
</P>
<P>
   News of the impending release came after Jackson and three of
his companions met for more than two hours Saturday with Milosevic
in a session that participants described as alternately bombastic
and warm, encouraging and frustrating.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, accompanied by three of the religious leaders who
traveled with him to Belgrade, said he had repeatedly urged
Milosevic at the meeting to move beyond a recitation of Yugoslav
grievances over the NATO bombing and to free the soldiers as ``a
bold diplomatic move.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yugoslavia wants the three Americans to be seen as the moral
equivalent of those killed in the bombings,'' Jackson said after
returning to his hotel from his meeting at the presidential palace.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of a softening of Yugoslav attitudes came immediately.
Nine of the clergy were permitted to meet with the three soldiers
without the presence of the Yugoslav army officers who monitored
the interviews on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said the men were relaxed and smiling, but were worried
about having their hopes for release raised.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the three servicemen, the American leaders were
called to the office of the Yugoslav foreign minister, Zivadin
Jovanovic.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down, and there was the tea and the coffee and all
that,'' Campbell said. ``Then he just brings out this sheet of
paper and says, `It is my pleasure to tell you that the request you
made to President Milosevic' _ and then he took this very deep
breath _ `well, it has been decided that the prisoners will be
released to you and Rev. Jackson.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Jackson, who has ended nearly every official meeting here by
gently commanding Yugoslav officials to join hands in prayer, spent
about half an hour alone with Milosevic, in an office and then in
the shade of the palace garden.
</P>
<P>
   During that time, when he was out of earshot of both his own and
the president's companions, he said he appealed to Milosevic as a
politician who might gain by making an unexpected and perhaps
unreciprocated gesture. ``We chose to meet in a room for about 30
minutes to get into details as raw as we could about the advantages
of taking the risk for peace,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   But in all their public meetings in Belgrade _ with Patriarch
Pavle of the Serbian Orthodox Church, with government officials and
with representatives of other Christian, Jewish and Muslim groups _
the American clergy have heard no criticism of Milosevic and only
the faintest acknowledgment of Kosovo refugees' accounts of rape,
killing and forcible expulsion at the hands of Yugoslav forces.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they have heard a blanket condemnation of the NATO
bombing operation and found that their arguments received no
coverage in the Belgrade media.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the time, it was Milosevic talking,'' said Nazir Uddin
Khaja, president of the board of the American Muslim Council.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like the great lie _ you repeat it so long you believe
it,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Khaja, an internist from Los Angeles who made the journey to
Belgrade over the objections of many in his organization, said he
thought long and hard about whether he wanted to be one of the
group's emissaries to the meeting with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew I'd have to shake his hands, and I was thinking about
how blood-soaked his hands are,'' he said. ``But I felt, especially
as an American Muslim, we have to be present on the platforms for
peace, for justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Another participant in the meeting, the Rev. Leonid Kishkovsky,
said Milosevic appeared to take seriously the group's warning that
NATO and the United States are committed to a prolonged bombing
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did make the point that the military logic is inexorable,''
said Kishkovsky, the ecumenical officer of the Russian Orthodox
Church in America. ``And there, I believe, there was strong
listening.''
</P>
<P>
   He said Milosevic appeared to understand that the Jackson
delegation was not a signal of a change in NATO or U.S. policy. ``I
think he was astutely reading it, that we are here on our own, not
discouraged or encouraged by our government, but nevertheless not
hostile to our government,'' Kishkovsky said. Families of the
prisoners were excited but cautious at the news Saturday. Tricia
Stone, the wife of Sgt. Stone, plans to fly to Germany to meet her
husband if he is released. ``She is praying, and she is hopeful,
and she is packed and ready to go in case it is,'' said her
stepmother, Lisa McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``We want to believe it. We'll know it's true when we
hear it from the Pentagon.''
</P>
<P>
   At the Los Angeles home of Andrew Ramirez's father, the fence
was bedecked with three American flags, about two dozen yellow
ribbons and some yellow silk roses.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Carcano, 42, a cousin, said over the fence, ``We've
always been hopeful that all three of the guys would be released,
but until it's official, until we actually see it, we're not going
to get too excited.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
