<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 16:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0702 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-JORDAN-HORNETS02-     05-01 2023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-JORDAN-HORNETS02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jordan's comeback may be with ownership
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few days after Christmas 1996, as Michael Jordan sat
in the visitors' locker room at the Omni before the Chicago Bulls
played the Hawks, he was asked about buying an NBA franchise
someday. He frowned. Jordan the businessman has built a vast
portfolio that includes car dealerships, restaurants and golf and
sneaker companies. The notion of owning a team in the league he
dominated and raised to unprecedented heights, however, did not
appeal to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``No way,'' Jordan said then. ``I have better things to do with
my money. I don't need the headaches of dealing with players who
want money before proving themselves. Nah, no way.''
</P>
<P>
   Turns out, there was a way. Barring some surprise that Jordan
and his representatives find unworkable, the retired legend soon
will become the only African-American to become co-owner or
majority owner of an NBA team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long time coming,'' said Buck Williams, former NBA
player and Players Association president. ``It's much needed in a
predominantly black league.''
</P>
<P>
   Even back when he proclaimed no interest in purchasing a team,
Jordan did acknowledge that something was wrong with a league made
up of about 80 percent African-American players but no owners.
``That's something that should be addressed,'' he said then. ``No
doubt about it. It's a serious issue. I will support anyone who
wants to try to be the first, any way I can.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's not for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Because Jordan has said little publicly about his interest in
the Hornets, what happened to change his position is unknown. He
said in a recent statement that he would be ``fulfilling a personal
and business challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, as he did in becoming the most prolific player in
NBA history, Jordan is primed for a historical and unprecedented
move that would bolster a league in need of his presence in any
fashion.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all the things that Michael has done for the NBA, that
would be a fitting scenario for him now,'' said Eddie Johnson, a
longtime NBA player now with Houston. ``I knew he would not be able
to stay retired from basketball. He would have to come back some
way or another, just as Magic Johnson and Larry Bird have done.
This would be an excellent way.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan would pay about $80 million for half of the Hornets, a
team that has been in turmoil under George Shinn, the current
majority owner who may bow out of an active role. Shinn's
tight-fisted spending has hurt the roster, and a pending sexual
assault lawsuit and a messy divorce have hurt his image. A
Jordan-Shinn partnership would be strange in that sense. While
Shinn is beset by publicized personal problems, Jordan works
diligently on keeping a clean image.
</P>
<P>
   NBA commissioner David Stern, eager to have Shinn removed from
control and to make his sport the only one with at team that is 50
percent-owned by an African-American, planted the idea of Jordan
hooking up with the Hornets. Jordan's ownership almost certainly
would create financial resources for a new arena in Charlotte. Its
12-year-old facility soon will be the league's oldest without
undergoing recent renovation, and it has just 12 luxury boxes and
no club seating.
</P>
<P>
   And beyond Charlotte, Jordan's involvement could generate
interest from other African-Americans _ particularly former players
_ to step into an owner's role. ``Owning an NBA team,'' Stern said,
``is a good means for former players who've made a lot of money to
go into business together in a business they know about.''
</P>
<P>
   Stern has been pushing for minority involvement in team
ownership for three decades, ever since he was a lawyer in the
NBA's front office. In 1989, he put African-American businessmen
Peter Bynoe and Bertram Lee together with owners of the Denver
Nuggets. The two bought the Nuggets but a year later had to sell.
</P>
<P>
   Lee apparently was more flash than cash and even got evicted
from a downtown Denver apartment he rented. ``They were not as
economically strong a group as I thought,'' Stern said. ``And that
might not be fair to Peter. But he did sell for a profit.''
</P>
<P>
   Since then, ex-players Magic Johnson (Los Angeles Lakers) and
Isiah Thomas (Toronto) bought parts of franchises, although Thomas
has since sold his 8 percent share and Johnson retains only 5
percent. Actor Bill Cosby has a 3 percent share of the New Jersey
Nets. None has had final say on personnel decisions, as Jordan
would.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need more black owners, and there has never been one of
real significance yet,'' said Charles Barkley, Houston forward and
Jordan's friend. ``We need more black coaches, too. Black coaches
are like UFOs. You have sightings of them every now and then. Black
owners are even more rare. There have been other blacks to try to
own an NBA team, but they didn't have enough money to stick with
it. Michael would break that cycle.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of black ownership has been a matter of money more than
of race, Stern says. ``I think there should be minority ownership
in the NBA _ and I've been pitching it for 30 years _ for every
origin, color and gender,'' Stern said. ``I don't believe there are
any barriers except for putting up the money. This is about
capitalism, not race.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the price tags are high. A team like the Hornets, who
entered the league in 1992 for $32.5 million, is valued now at $160
million. Not many people have that kind of money.
</P>
<P>
   Neither has any minority gained at least a half-share of an NFL
or major-league baseball team, though four blacks and one Hispanic
own portions of a baseball franchise. Bob Johnson, president and
CEO of Black Entertainment Television, is wealthy enough, and he's
interested in becoming an NBA owner. The problem for him is finding
a team.
</P>
<P>
   ``And then it's the matter of, even if you had the money, do the
owners want you in the league?'' Johnson said. ``Michael Jordan
will be accepted by any league, so he clears that hurdle. It's a
challenge for African-Americans, but there are very few who can
afford it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob Johnson has been chasing a franchise everywhere,'' Stern
said. ``Bob's a value-purchaser. He's worked very hard and is quite
successful. But he will not overspend for an NBA franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's about what it comes down to now. ``The time to get
into ownership for African-Americans was when the league was first
created,'' Johnson said. ``As the league grew, we were left out of
the equation, weren't able to be serious players. And it continues
to be difficult, with the appreciation of the teams.'' Before Magic
Johnson bought a small piece of the Lakers, he was interested in
the Minnesota Timberwolves, up for sale in 1994. He called on
Minneapolis record-producing stars Jimmy Jam and Terry Lewis and
singing sensation Janet Jackson to form a bid team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a natural fit for Jimmy and Terry,'' Johnson said.
``They're from there and they love the NBA. For me and Janet, it
would have been business.''
</P>
<P>
   Jam welcomed the idea. ``Actually, the owners at the time
contacted us,'' he said. ``And we were interested, because we love
basketball and we didn't want the Timberwolves to be moved, which
is what was being talked about. ``
</P>
<P>
   The real motivation, Jam acknowledged, was ownership of the
arena to tie into his music business. The deal fell through when
the parties could not agree on a price and Magic Johnson got an
irresistible offer from Lakers owner Jerry Buss.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never a dream of ours to be NBA owners,'' Jam said.
</P>
<P>
   Although the players union would disagree, Stern points out that
owning an NBA team is not an automatic money-maker. He said some
owners would rather have skipped this entire season and cut their
losses than play under the old collective-bargaining agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look at the numbers,'' Jam said, ``and owning an NBA team
is tough to make money. But if you own the arena, then you have the
suites, the naming rights and 160 open dates. If you take advantage
of that, then the arena is being used and it's a viable thing. If
not . . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``See, in the African-American communities, there's not a Paul
Allen (of the Portland Trail Blazers) who can go and build an arena
and buy a team out of his pocket. Having that team and that arena
doesn't affect anything he does.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us,'' Jam said, ``it has to be about putting 10 people
together to make it happen. So, in that regard, I think the void of
African-American ownership is economics more than race-driven.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan left the league as no one has before _ winning his final
game on a last-second jumper in the NBA Finals. Many people thought
he would not be able to resist one more run as a player. But he
has, and he's on the verge of becoming linked with the league
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just like with Magic, Bird or myself, I think Jordan should
always have a connection to the NBA,'' Isiah Thomas said. ``It just
makes sense, business-wise, and in other ways. For Jordan to have
no connection to the league would be a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan chose the Hornets because of his strong allegiance to
North Carolina, his home state, and because of Shinn's willingness
to sell. He could have purchased a small piece of the Bulls, the
team he led to six NBA championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that he would make a good owner,'' Bulls owner Jerry
Reinsdorf said. ``He is good at everything he does. Michael is very
bright and has very good insight into things that he focuses on. So
I'm sure he would be a plus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I once asked Michael if he thought that when he had finished
playing he would want to be part of (the Bulls') ownership group,''
Reinsdorf said. ``That wasn't an offer. I asked him if he'd like to
be. He said no. He said that he didn't think that he would enjoy
being an owner because he thought that he would not be tolerant of
players. And that was it. It was a 30-second conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan, who made an estimated $45 million annually from
off-the-court activities while he was playing, conducted a much
longer meeting at his New York restaurant last month with Charlotte
lawyer John Fennebresque. Fennebresque, who heads the city's arena
committee, left impressed by Jordan's acumen, interest and
charisma.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him that his involvement would make (a new arena) a lot
more likely,'' Fennebresque said. ``I said, 'We need money and we
need your stature.' He is very interested. He loves North Carolina.
He wouldn't move here, but he would spend a significant amount of
time here. He wants to be very involved in the management of the
team.''
</P>
<P>
   With Jordan in the wings, the Hornets have made a serious
playoff push after trading all-star Glenn Rice to the Lakers for
Eddie Jones and Elden Campbell. Injured forward Anthony Mason will
be back next year. By then, Jordan's presence could lure more
talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, I would play for Michael,'' said Scottie Pippen, a
former Jordan teammate and now a forward for Houston. ``I played
with him for 10 years. So I know I can play for him. He'd want to
do the same thing I'd want to do. And that's win. He would make a
good owner.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also could be a magnet for other roles. Pippen predicted
that Phil Jackson, formerly of the Bulls, would be Jordan's first
choice as coach.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said, ``If he offered me a job to help him run the
franchise in some way, I would love to join him.''
</P>
<P>
   Jordan is so beloved that he could be North Carolina's governor,
if he wanted to. In the African-American community, he has been
criticized for not being outspoken on issues of race. But, as he
did on the court, his ambition is to lead by example.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't have to say, 'Look, I'm an African-American NBA
owner,''' veteran Indiana guard Mark Jackson said. ``By doing it,
he's leading the way, showing that it's something African-Americans
can do. That's what role models do.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NBA needs more than one African-American owner. But you've
got to start somewhere, and Michael Jordan's a great one to get it
started.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
