u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-N     05-01 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DEVILS, A FEEL OF THE ROAD AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Friday night's 4-3 victory over the Pittsburgh Penguins
guaranteed the New Jersey Devils at least one more home game in the
Stanley Cup playoffs, perhaps as many as 13 more in the
Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   This means more nights in hotels, even when the game is at home,
a team tradition that has been slightly relaxed this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's pretty comfortable with what we're doing,'' said
cach Robbie Ftorek, who added that he is not too concerned that ``a
couple of the single guys'' might have different opinions.
</P>
<P>
   Even a telephone call can be a distraction on the afternoon of a
game, Ftorek said, and distractions are unwelcome during the
two-month tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Of course the Devils spent Saturday night in a hotel. They were
in Pittsburgh preparing to play the Penguins this afternoon in Game
6 of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils held a 3-2 lead in the best-of-7 series. A victory
Sunday would advance them to face the Buffalo Sabres. A defeat
would mean Game 7 at home on Tuesday _ and back to a ``home'' hotel
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   In recent seasons, under coach Jacques Lemaire, the Devils spent
many nights in hotels during the playoffs, even on nights in New
Jersey that did not precede games. Lemaire and general manager Lou
Lamoriello liked to keep their athletes under close watch, if not
lock and key.
</P>
<P>
   Although many hockey teams stay in hotels before home games in
the later rounds of the playoffs, few did it as often or as early
as the Devils. Even on the road, they seemed isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Last spring, in the first round against Ottawa, the top-seeded
Devils stayed at a hotel that was far from downtown and the wicked
ways of the Canadian capital. The hotel was closer to the arena,
they were told. After they were upset by the Senators, a few Devils
gave the impression that defeat was a release from captivity.
</P>
<P>
   Without speaking against Lemaire's methods or challenging the
authoritarian ways of Lamoriello, Ftorek has loosened things up a
bit. On the road, at least in the first round, his team has stayed
in downtown hotels in Pittsburgh. At home, they are allowed to live
in their houses or apartments except on the nights before games.
</P>
<P>
   Ftorek said he talked this over with Scott Stevens, the captain,
who discussed it with other veterans. Ken Daneyko, one of the team
seniors, said the current hotel policy is fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a little different and I think it's great,'' Daneyko
said. ``It's so you can rest and focus on the game and get away
from home. It's a sacrifice. You have to put your families aside.
But players with kids might not get as good a rest at home. We're
doing it less than in the past. You don't want to get too mentally
tired from focusing too much on every game. But, the night before
the game, I totally agree with it and I think most of the guys do
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Jason Arnott, who used to play in Edmonton, said the Oilers did
not use hotels at home, so the Devils' way was an adjustment.
Arnott, one of the single Devils, said: ``We usually accumulate in
one room and just hang out. It's good for the team and the
camaraderie. We have a team breakfast and get ready for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik, who is married, said he wasn't sure how much he was
supposed to talk about hotel policy. ``We get to go home, we get to
go home, we get to go home,'' he said, with a smile. ``I think the
mood is good. That's what matters.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he misses his wife, Holik said: ``I always do.''
</P>
<P>
   Holik set up both of Randy McKay's goals Friday night. After the
game, both men greeted family members in the lobby and left
Continental Arena with them.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Bombardir, married with an infant son, discussed the team
hotel policy in previous seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's always the worry,'' he said, ``if you're staying in
hotels too much, and all of a sudden you're worrying about not
seeing your children and your wife, and you're not comfortable in
there. I think going in there the night before is just fine for us.
It works well.''
</P>
<P>
   Two Devils bachelors, Patrik Elias and Petr Sykora, combined on
Sykora's goal Friday that put the team ahead to stay. Afterward,
Sykora said: ``It doesn't bother me to be alone at home or at the
hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias, who is engaged to be married, said: ``The last couple of
years, it didn't work out.''
</P>
<P>
   Elias said that letting players go home, except on the nights
before home games, ``is better for the married guys to be with
their families.''
</P>
<P>
   When asked whether he would prefer to spend more time with his
fiancee, Elias paused and chose his words carefully. ``This is
Lou's and the coach's decision,'' he said, ``and we've got to
follow that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
