<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0732 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LASVEGAS-MAYORAL-NYT &LR;      05-01 1275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LASVEGAS-MAYORAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWYER OF COLORFUL CLIENTS TRIES TO ADD LAS VEGAS TO LIST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Nev.)  (ART ADV: A photo is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(DW) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAS VEGAS _ In 35 years as a criminal lawyer, Oscar Goodman has
won cases for clients like Meyer Lansky and Anthony (Tony the Ant)
Spilotro. He has won acquittal for a surgeon accused of molesting
female patients under anesthesia, defended a federal judge against
impeachment charges and a man accused of murdering another federal
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had the alpha and omega of law,'' Goodman said last week
from his green marble-floored office here, surrounded by
autographed pictures from clients and admirers as diverse as LaToya
Jackson, Mike Tyson, Mike Wallace and Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah.
</P>
<P>
   But now Goodman, or ``The Big O,'' as he is known to friends, is
running for mayor. ``It's the first time in my life when I'll be on
the inside trying to do good and keep the government honest,'' he
said. ``I intend to treat Las Vegas as my primary client, with the
same passion I've had for all my less popular clients over the
years.''
</P>
<P>
   Since he declared his candidacy in March, Goodman has treated
voters like jurors, arguing his case _ including a plan to charge
developers' fees to finance civic improvements _ with populist
persuasiveness. Contrary to the oddsmakers' early assessments,
polls show him heavily favored to place first in a crowded
nonpartisan primary election on Tuesday, if not win the outright
majority that would avoid a June 8 runoff and make him mayor on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be so appropriate for that city if Oscar became the
mayor,'' said his friend Nicholas Pileggi, the writer and the Las
Vegas demimonde who co-wrote the screenplay for Martin Scorsese's
movie, ``Casino,'' in which Goodman unabashedly played himself.
``He's a really genuine person,'' Pileggi said.
</P>
<P>
   Pileggi, speaking by telephone from New York, added: ``He's a
true defense attorney in the best sense of the word, his own little
Civil Liberties Union. It would be great.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone in this city, which has worked hard to reinvent
itself as a family-friendly resort in which mob rule is a distant
memory, is so excited at the prospect of a Goodman reign. When he
announced his candidacy, The Las Vegas Review-Journal ran an
editorial headlined ``Anybody but Oscar,'' which described Goodman
as a ``barrister to butchers'' and said he ``carries so much
baggage he could be skycap of the century at McCarran International
Airport.''
</P>
<P>
   His clients have been colorful, to say the least. He kept
Spilotro, the Chicago mob's man in Vegas, out of jail despite
accusations that he had killed 22 people. Eventually, Spilotro's
body was found in an Indiana cornfield.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, a bearded, bespectacled 59-year-old father of four,
mostly takes the criticism in stride. But he has also hit back with
a television commercial featuring testimonials to his fairness and
integrity from old adversaries: the former head of the local
Organized Crime Strike Force, a former agent of the Federal Bureau
of Investigation and a former U.S. attorney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'll grab the City Council and the good old boy system and
he'll shake it pretty hard,'' the former U.S. attorney, Lamond
Mills, a Ronald Reagan appointee and a prominent Mormon in the
state, said in an interview. ``I think that would be a hoot. My
conservative friends say to me, `What about the image?' But the
fact of the matter is, people don't come here to go up to the
Mormon Temple. They come to gamble. I think he'll add to the
pizazz.''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman, a Democrat, is one of nine candidates scrambling to
fill the seat being vacated by Jan Jones, who announced this winter
that she would not seek a third term. Goodman's two leading
opponents are Arnie Adamsen, a City Council member, and Mark Fine,
a developer. They each trailed him by more than 10 percentage
points in a poll published last week in The Review-Journal.
</P>
<P>
   With a reporter in his office, he cheerily fielded a phone call
from the city's reigning casino mogul, Steve Wynn, who had called
to confide the results of a private poll that showed Goodman within
striking distance of 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying as hard as I can,'' Goodman said into the phone,
adding, ``I learned everything from you, Steve. I'm dead serious!''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman has a populist, libertarian streak that appeals to a
town that, despite its explosive growth, retains a frontier air,
said Michael Bowers, a professor of political science at the
University of Nevada at Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is still sort of wide open and there's a strong kind of
libertarian streak that runs through the whole state,'' Bowers
said. ``At the same time, there's a sense of people coming here and
starting over, leaving their past mistakes behind them, and so
people are less judgmental than they would be in many other
cities.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor here is relatively weak, one of five equal votes on
the City Council. Much of the power over planning and zoning rests
with the county, which controls the unincorporated area of the
famous Strip, where most of the new casinos have been built. But
Goodman says he will use the bully pulpit to its limits.
</P>
<P>
   In early appearances, Goodman showed some lack of familiarity
with the city budget and policy, and he has been impolitic enough
to acknowledge in the past that he is personally sympathetic to the
idea of decriminalizing drugs and legalizing prostitution, though
he insists that, whatever his beliefs, ``as mayor, I would never do
anything that would embarrass Las Vegas.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a prosecutor, Goodman grew up in Philadelphia and
graduated from Haverford College and the University of Pennsylvania
Law School. Goodman and his wife, Carolyn, arrived in Las Vegas in
1964, ``with $87 between us,'' he said, on the advice of a Las
Vegas police officer he had met on a case as a clerk at the
Philadelphia district attorney's office. Early on, he decided that
he could be in the world of casinos and night clubs, but never of
it, if he wanted to succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand, here I was a 23-year-old kid coming
out to Damon Runyonville, and everybody I saw was a character,''
Goodman recalled. ``There were guys with nicknames which described
them. There was Wingy, who had one arm, the Midget, Hunchy. I mean,
every night it was a dream come true for somebody who loved O.
Henry stories and Damon Runyon stories, and my wife said, ``Wait a
minute, two things: You can't be your client, you've got to be a
cut above your clients in order to have credibility, and you have
to be like Caesar's wife, you've got to be above reproach, because
there is nothing they would rather do than get you.'''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman never gave prosecutors anything to get him on, though in
1994 he paid a $50,000 fine and risked jail time for refusing to
give the government payment records from a reputed mobster, Natale
Richichi, on the grounds that to do so would violate lawyer-client
privilege. He turned over the records when his client gave him
permission and the government threatened to bring criminal contempt
proceedings that could have led to disbarment.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman has another inviolate rule: He never represents
informers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He thinks of them as rats,'' Pileggi said. ``But he has never
taken on the aura of these people. I think he truly loved Spilotro,
one of the most vicious killers you can imagine. Now you'll never
convince Oscar of that. When he was around him, he was a total
gentleman.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
