<SLUG> BC-KNICKS-PRACTICE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS' SEASON IS HANGING IN BALANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Mass., N.C., Fla.)   By STEVE POPPER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ Jeff Van Gundy has peeked at the scoreboard,
spun the dial on the satellite dish and even sat at the breakfast
table with his wife, Kim, and figured out the playoff
possibilities. While it is still possible for the Knicks to finish
anywhere from the fifth spot in the Eastern Conference all the way
down to the 10th spot, the math has boiled down to a seemingly
simple equation: if the Knicks can win two games, they will be
assured of a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know we've got to win two tough games against three tough
teams,'' Van Gundy said Saturday after the Knicks finished their
workout at SUNY-Purchase and prepared to fly to Indiana to face the
Pacers on Sunday afternoon. ``... We need two wins, but the
schedule is definitely not in our favor about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The magic number for the Knicks to clinch a playoff berth is
two; any combination of two Knick victories and Charlotte Hornet
losses puts the Knicks into the postseason. With games in Indiana
on Sunday, against Boston on Monday and then against the Miami Heat
on Wednesday, Van Gundy knows that it will not be easy for his team
to get two victories by itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks can clinch a berth on Sunday, if they win in Indiana
in the afternoon and Charlotte loses at Miami that night. The
Hornets finish with games against Philadelphia on Tuesday night and
at Boston on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   But before they concern themselves with any of the
possibilities, the Knicks are trying to focus solely on their own
task.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody says we've got to win two out of three,'' Chris
Childs said. ``We've got to win one _ Sunday. Then we'll think
about Boston after that game. Everybody is up and ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   But part of the problem for the Knicks is that everybody is not
up and ready to go. Marcus Camby practiced Saturday and will play
Sunday with a sore right shoulder. But Childs and Patrick Ewing did
not practice, and the Knicks will be unsure until game time if
either can play.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy sounded doubtful about whether Ewing, who has a sore
left Achilles' tendon, would be ready. He returned to action on
Thursday night against Philadelphia after sitting out the previous
three games, but reinjured himself in the third quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last game, he played 21 minutes and I was going to put him
back in, but he said that he couldn't go back in,'' Van Gundy said.
``He didn't look good the other night and that was off of six days'
rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying `didn't play well.' I'm saying he didn't look
like he did against Charlotte, where the time off had served him
well and he had a bounce in his step. If he can't be productive and
effective, there's no sense putting him in.''
</P>
<P>
   Childs was hopeful that his bruised right knee was recovering
quickly enough that he would be able to play. But even if the leg
responded to treatment, Childs said that he had not slept more than
an hour or two in the previous three nights, both from the pain and
the worry that the injury was something worse than it turned out to
be.
</P>
<P>
   Van Gundy has tried to dismiss the notion of resting Ewing
during these final three games, in preparation for the post-season.
He has also resisted speculating on possible playoff positioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our first goal is only to get there, because we're a long way
from getting there,'' Van Gundy said. ``We have by far the most
difficult schedule. I just want to get there. They know we're not
there yet, but they should feel good about where they're at, what
they've done over the last five games, because they've played very
well. But they know that we need two wins.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
