A0737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT &LR;      05-01 0870
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-KOSOVO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE LOGIC OF KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, May 2: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unless there is an unexpected diplomatic breakthrough, the war
in Yugoslavia promises to extend into the summer, if not beyond. As
the American people brace for a sustained military campaign, they
deserve a clearer account of America's goals from President Clinton
and of how the national interest would be served by achieving them.
Anyone who doubts the demand for a plain and compelling rationale
for the war need look no further than the House of Representatives,
which last week stunned Washington by refusing on a tie vote to
support the NATO air offensive.
</P>
<P>
   Though partisan maneuvering by the Republicans was partly
responsible for the unfortunate outcome, the deadlocked House was a
symbol of national ambivalence that Clinton cannot afford to
ignore. The problem is not that Clinton has failed to outline
military and political objectives for Kosovo. He has done so in
some detail. But he has so far failed to connect those aims with
larger U.S. interests in a way that convinces a majority of his
countrymen that war with Slobodan Milosevic is warranted and may
have to be waged for months.
</P>
<P>
   Impeachment scars have left Clinton and House Republicans wary
of each other, but the White House must work more closely with
Congress if it wants to build support for the war. Republicans, for
their part, should cease probing for political advantage on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After 40 days of bombing, the military and political picture in
Kosovo has changed in ways that the White House and NATO did not
fully anticipate. As a result, some clarification and redefinition
of purpose are required.
</P>
<P>
   One of the original objectives of the air war _ protecting the
ethnic Albanians in Kosovo from Yugoslav aggression _ has proved
unrealistic and unattainable. Each day brings a new wave of
bedraggled refugees to Albania and Macedonia, and with them stories
of unspeakable abuses and killing by the Yugoslav forces in Kosovo.
Gen. Wesley Clark, the NATO commander, has acknowledged that
alliance missiles and bombs cannot stop the bloodletting. Even if
NATO wanted to send a ground force into Kosovo, which it does not,
it would take two or three months to assemble the troops and
weapons, more than enough time for Milosevic to finish his ethnic
cleansing.
</P>
<P>
   That unpleasant fact means that this war is now being fought
primarily over the future of Kosovo, a cause that is harder to
define and more difficult to sell to Americans than the defense of
innocent civilians under brutal attack. It is also a cause that
will be difficult, though not necessarily impossible, to advance
with air power alone.
</P>
<P>
   The goals Clinton has enunciated for Kosovo are honorable and
desirable. They include the return of the refugees, the restoration
of a high degree of political autonomy for Kosovo and the creation
of a secure environment in which Yugoslav forces could no longer
threaten ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   To gain the support of the country, Clinton has to place those
aims in a broader framework. We believe that freedom, human rights
and the preservation of a civilized society are critical principles
bound up in the conflict in Kosovo, and that Milosevic's effort to
drive the Balkans into a new dark age must be resisted. While
Yugoslavia does not present a military threat to the rest of
Europe, and unlike Iraq cannot impede the flow of oil, its
genocidal assault on Kosovo cannot go unanswered.
</P>
<P>
   With the Cold War over, the country needs to devise a new
calculus for determining when its security is threatened and the
use of force is warranted. Kosovo is a test case. If the United
States and its NATO allies are prepared to let a tyrant in the
Balkans slaughter his countrymen and overrun his neighbors with
hundreds of thousands of refugees, other combustible regions of
Europe may face similar upheavals. History teaches that instability
in Europe inevitably hurts the United States, and can produce
larger conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Just how Washington and its allies defend these interests in the
Balkans will depend on military and diplomatic developments in the
weeks ahead. The application of air power, which is now crippling
the Yugoslav economy, may eventually force Milosevic to seek peace.
The bombing must be given time to work. The option of an invasion
should be kept open, if only to pressure Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   There may also be diplomatic progress now that Russia is trying
to broker a deal and may be ready to back an armed international
peacekeeping force in Kosovo. While Clinton's peace terms should
shape a settlement, there may be space within them to work out an
accord. NATO has already offered more flexible terms for a
cease-fire and Milosevic has given a little ground on allowing
peacekeepers in Kosovo when the war ends. His demand that it be
unarmed or only lightly armed is unacceptable.
</P>
<P>
   But whatever course Clinton chooses, the country must be
satisfied it is worth the sacrifices that may be required. If
Clinton hopes to prevail in Kosovo, he will first have to secure
the support of the American people and of Congress.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
