A0738 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-PARANOI     05-01 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-PARANOIDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: WHEN THE `PARANOIDS' TURN OUT TO BE RIGHT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BRENT STAPLES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Black Americans live shorter lives than whites and are more
likely to suffer stress-related maladies like high blood pressure,
which contributes to stroke and heart attack. The medical
profession has yet to list ``racism'' as a cause of death.
</P>
<P>
   But some social scientists now see tension related to
discrimination as a health hazard on par with smoking and a
high-fat diet. Among the day-to-day acts of discrimination that
shadow African-Americans, none are more stressful or dangerous than
those committed by police, some of whom treat black people as
criminals until proved otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   The situation is largely invisible to whites, many of whom see
the complaints as a function of what writer Norman Podhoretz once
described as ``paranoid touchiness'' among black people.
</P>
<P>
   Not all whites hold the Podhoretz view, of course, and the
current police scandals in New York City and New Jersey are
broadening the vantage point on this problem. When these sagas are
over, millions of white people who thought black people paranoid
will have substantial insight into a nightmarish reality that
whites barely glimpse but that black people live through day after
day.
</P>
<P>
   After years of lies, New Jersey admitted that the state police
targeted black motorists _ on the basis of race alone _ for drug
searches along the New Jersey Turnpike. Taking a page from the KGB,
troopers even recruited motel workers to spy on patrons who spoke
Spanish or paid in cash on grounds that such people might be ``drug
couriers.''
</P>
<P>
   State legislative hearings by New Jersey's black and Latino
caucus have provided chapter and verse on how these policies were
carried out. Former state troopers testified that barracks bulletin
boards were once strewn with racial epithets and that troopers used
racist banter over the radio, describing cars with black drivers as
``buckets of coal.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the most telling testimony came from a black dentist,
Elmo Randolph, whose gold BMW was stopped more than 100 times over
four years as he drove from his home in Bergenfield to his office
in East Orange. Troopers continued to harass him even after they
had identified him as a dentist, which suggests that the stops were
a game to be played at African-Americans' expense.
</P>
<P>
   When Randolph refused to let police search his car, they seized
his license and made him wait on the side of the highway for 20
minutes. Randolph finally sold the BMW.
</P>
<P>
   The New York City Police Department denies using ``racial
profiling,'' but a recent story in Crain's New York Business raises
questions. The newspaper interviewed 20 black professionals _
including corporate presidents _ who told harrowing stories of
being singled out and humiliated by police, usually for driving
expensive cars.
</P>
<P>
   Earl Graves Jr., the president of Black Enterprise magazine, has
been stopped twice over the last year in his Lexus and told Crain's
earlier this month that black men driving luxury cars were `` a
recipe for disaster'' _ meaning that encounters with the police
often turn violent, with the black person ending up dead.
</P>
<P>
   This kind of harassment has deepened racial alienation among
affluent black people who had hoped against hope that money would
let them blend in at last and become regular Americans. But instead
of fading into the crowd, they have become an ever more popular
target for police departments in New York City and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Black families of all income levels bear a heavy burden in
anxiety, worried that fathers, sons and husbands may one day be
picked off by police officers who mistake them for criminals.
</P>
<P>
   The recent events in New York and New Jersey are proof that
African-Americans who were thought to be paranoid are in fact being
singled out for disproportionate police attention, even when they
break no laws. Mayors and governors who permit this practice will
have themselves to blame when the damage suits reach into the
billions and the racial climate is irreparably poisoned.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
