A0739 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-GORDON-NYT &LR;      05-01 0397
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GORDON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
C. GORDON, EXPERT ON LAW OF IMMIGRATION, DIES AT 93  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Md., Calif.)   By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Gordon, a son of immigrants who became the general
counsel of the Immigration and Naturalization Service and the
founding author of the 20-volume treatise Immigration Law and
Procedure, died Wednesday at Bay Medical Center in Panama City,
Fla. He was 93 and lived in Potomac, Md., and Panama City.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was a seminal figure in modern immigration law.
``Immigration Law and Procedure,'' which he published starting in
1959, is the principal reference in the field, widely cited in
court opinions and scholarly articles. He continued to publish
supplements and updates to it until he was 88.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before him, there was really no complete guide,'' said a
longtime friend, Maurice A. Roberts, retired chairman of the Board
of Immigration Appeals at the Justice Department. ``His book was
like an encyclopedia, and it gradually expanded as the law
expanded.''
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was born on Oct. 12, 1905, in New York City, the son of
immigrants from Eastern Europe. He attended the City College of New
York and graduated from New York University Law School with honors
in 1927.
</P>
<P>
   He spent several years in private practice before joining the
Immigration and Naturalization Service in 1939. He stayed for 35
years, rising to general counsel in 1966.
</P>
<P>
   During his tenure at the immigration agency, Gordon argued eight
cases before the Supreme Court. ``He was known as a liberal and
someone in favor of a more open, fairer immigration policy,''
Roberts said, but sometimes he had to argue positions with which he
disagreed.
</P>
<P>
   In one such instance, three decades ago, Gordon lost the case of
Afroyim vs. Rusk, in which the Supreme Court ruled that a
naturalized citizen cannot lose his citizenship against his will by
voting in a foreign election.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving the agency in 1974, Gordon went into private
practice and founded a Washington law firm, Gordon &AMP; Bryant. During
those years, he filed lawsuits challenging the interdiction of
Haitian refugees at sea and restrictions on Iranian citizens during
the Iran hostage crisis. He retired in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Anne; a son, Michael Gordon of
Potomac; a daughter, Ellen Gittel Gordon of Los Angeles, and two
grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1742EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0741 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-PROSECUTOR-2TAKES-     05-01 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-PROSECUTOR-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`A ROUGH YEAR' TARNISHES PROSECUTOR'S REPUTATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RONALD SMOTHERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEWARK, N.J. _ When Patricia Hurt was appointed just over a year
ago as the Essex County prosecutor, the accolades were quick to
pour in. She was the first black woman to hold the job, and as a
Republican in an overwhelmingly Democratic county, she brought what
many considered a refreshing mix of law-and-order conservatism and
social advocacy.
</P>
<P>
   That seems a very long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   State and federal authorities are now looking into charges that
three people were beaten by officers in the course of separate
investigations conducted by her office; local officials are
accusing her of wasting taxpayers' money on luxury office
appointments, like a $120 leather wastebasket, and unjustified
salary increases; and some current and former employees of the
office are suing her for what they contend is age and gender
discrimination when Ms. Hurt promoted her personal favorites.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, some employees have complained that she
occasionally used her assistants to help with personal errands, in
one case picking up her, her family members and an aide from the
airport after a vacation in South Carolina. Through an aide, Ms.
Hurt denied the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   The criticism has grown louder in the wake of the furor over how
her office handled the April 8 murder of an Orange policewoman. Ms.
Hurt charged with murder and kept in custody for six days a man who
had a strong alibi, who passed two polygraph tests and who was
later cleared.
</P>
<P>
   According to people close to the office, Ms. Hurt refused to
free the man, Terrance Everett, despite the urging of senior
investigators. And when the suspect was finally cleared, she
expressed no regret for what her office had done.
</P>
<P>
   The case cost the prosecutor her top deputy, Patrick Toscano,
who resigned in protest. But just as critically, it cost her a huge
measure of respect.
</P>
<P>
   For many people in the legal community, Ms. Hurt's determined
refusal to apologize publicly to Everett, marked the end of what
had been a fairly buoyant honeymoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happened to him was horrible, and had it continued he
would have faced the death penalty,'' said Alan Zegas, a veteran
defense lawyer in Essex County. ``She should have apologized, and
by not apologizing her conduct reflects poorly on her office and on
her as prosecutor, and from what I have heard has caused morale in
the office to deteriorate along with her credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps most prominent among the new chorus of detractors is
Essex County Executive James Treffinger, who once counted Ms. Hurt
among his most trusted aides when she was his deputy county
executive and who once liked to take credit for pressing Gov.
Christie Whitman to appoint her as prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Now he sees her as distant and autocratic. While she once basked
in the light of television cameras with an airy and engaging
manner, she has grown more defensive and reluctant to take
questions from reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It perplexes and frankly saddens me that there has been such a
remarkable change,'' said Treffinger, who this week called for an
investigation into some of Ms. Hurt's recent spending in the
prosecutor's office. ``I can only speculate that the change is due
to the tremendous powers conferred on her by the office of
prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   Through most of last week, Ms. Hurt refused to grant an
interview to discuss the controversies. But Friday, in an impromptu
hourlong session in her office, she parried accusations of
mismanaging the office and exhibited some of the resilience and
toughness that close associates said had long been her traits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is an awesome responsibility to sit in this chair, and the
decisions that are made are made on so many different bases,'' Ms.
Hurt said. ``But I am trying to get this office ready for the 21st
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded and visibly buoyed by supportive staff members during
the interview, she said she would not try to take on the criticisms
of her office one by one, but termed them unfair. At one point she
expressed fear that the criticism, and the pressure to respond to
it, was affecting the kind of compassion for crime victims and the
community outreach that she has tried to make the hallmark of her
tenure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a call from the mother of Robin Moses,'' she said,
referring to e a 33-year-old woman from Orange who disappeared last
September. ``She said, `You aren't going to forget about my
daughter, are you?'''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt said that with all the decisions she had to make daily,
there were bound to be mistakes and those who disagreed with her.
But many of the mistakes and grumbling were more the result of not
having enough money to pay competitive salaries, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Brunell, Ms. Hurt's deputy first assistant prosecutor,
echoed the concerns about low salaries and insufficient resources
and added that Ms. Hurt's additional efforts to reach out to the
community had probably further strained the office while making her
``extremely popular'' with the staff.
</P>
<P>
   Thad Givens, her acting chief of investigations, pointed to the
long hours that many employees were working. ``If they didn't like
her, we would have had a rebellion by now,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Givens also responded Saturday to the charge that she had used
her staff to meet her and family members at the airport. He
acknowledged that investigators from the state attorney general's
office had been in Newark on Friday to look at records after
receiving an anonymous complaint about the incident. But he
explained that office investigators were sent to the airport
because Ms. Hurt had been the object of threats from a fugitive
that her office was seeking. He added that she had been accompanied
during her vacation by an office investigator for security reasons.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As for the charges of brutality that have drawn state and
federal investigators to the office, Ms. Hurt denied any wrongdoing
by her staff, while friends and longtime supporters outside the
office said she was being unfairly blamed for police actions over
which she has no control. And they said that much of the criticism
is aimed at her because she is overturning ``the old boy network''
by appointing women and members of minorities to top posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We tend to catch a little more flak as African-Americans
coming into a position such as Pat has,'' said Hadren Simmons, a
longtime friend and a founder of Concerned Black Republicans of New
Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Hurt's detractors are both black and white, Republican
and Democrat. Veteran black investigators in her office who were
either demoted, reassigned or forced into retirement during her
first months in office were among those who filed a lawsuit
charging her with age discrimination.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Hurt, 42, took office in January 1998, she was given
the reins to the largest and busiest prosecutor's office in the
state, in New Jersey's second most populous county after Bergen
County. And she quickly caught people's attention with her
aggressive efforts to solve more than a dozen slayings of
prostitutes. She formed an unusual task force of detectives to gain
the confidence of women who would otherwise be hiding from the
police and spoke of her desire to protect vulnerable segments of
society.
</P>
<P>
   She also hired the mother of Megan Kanka as a part-time
spokesman for the office, traveling around the county explaining
``Megan's Law'' to educators and community groups. She put up
billboards urging people to help fight drugs and sharpened the
office's focus on victims.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt also seemed intent on shaking up some of the old
personnel traditions, moving quickly to force out several senior
people. Some of them were replaced with less-experienced employees
and with women.
</P>
<P>
   She named an old friend and child abuse investigator in the
office, Priscilla Corcoran, as her deputy chief of investigations,
and elevated two lawyers, Sara McCardle and Siobhan Teare, to top
supervisory posts.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, the quick personnel moves created the impression
among some staff members of an office in chaos. ``Lists would
appear transferring people, 15 or 20 at a time, in ways that made
no sense,'' said one veteran investigator. ``Then a few weeks later
those changes would be quietly rescinded because they hadn't
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Some employees also accused Ms. Hurt of playing favorites in
managing her staff. One example they cite is that of Leshia Rosa,
who lives in Ms. Hurt's home in Montclair and who Ms. Hurt terms a
``tenant of mine.'' Ms. Rosa is an investigator in the office and
she often serves as Ms. Hurt's driver. Their friendship goes back
to 1995, when Ms. Rosa got a county job as a $19,000-a-year
juvenile detention officer. When Ms. Hurt became county prosecutor,
Ms. Rosa was appointed to the $58,536-a-year investigator's job,
according to county personnel records.
</P>
<P>
   When Ms. Hurt first came onto the scene in Essex County she was
referred to many simply as ``Bobby's daughter,'' a reference to her
well-known, much beloved father, Robert Hurt, a former teacher at
Newark's Montgomery Street school, who had been a standout point
guard with an awesome leaping ability when he played basketball at
Orange High School in the late 1940s.
</P>
<P>
   She is the oldest of three children of Edith and Robert Hurt.
She attended Montclair High School, where she was president of her
junior and senior classes. At graduation in 1974, she won the
Montclair High School Award, given to a student who stands out for
both their leadership and academic performance.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt attended Elmira College in upstate New York, and after
graduating in 1978 she enrolled in Howard University Law School in
Washington. With a law degree, Ms. Hurt returned to New Jersey and
worked as a law clerk for a Hudson County Superior Court judge and
later as a prosecutor in Hudson and Essex counties.
</P>
<P>
   From 1989-1992, she was Newark's chief municipal prosecutor, and
in 1992 she entered private practice, handling real estate
transactions and divorces while teaching paralegal studies part
time at Montclair State University.
</P>
<P>
   Harold Edwards, who with Simmons founded Concerned Black
Republicans of New Jersey, said that Ms. Hurt had long been a
political rarity _ a black Republican in a county where the
overwhelming majority of black voters are Democrat. But she had not
been active in politics until 1994, when he and Simmons, persuaded
her to run for county registrar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had approached others to run, but Pat was the only one who
saw the vision we had,'' said Edwards, who was then the vice
chairman of the Essex County Republican Party. ``Jim Treffinger was
running for county executive, and the party was trying to be
inclusive and empower black people.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Ms. Hurt lost to a black woman running on the
Democratic ticket, Treffinger won against a fractured Democratic
party. It was generally believed, Simmons said, that Ms. Hurt had
helped bring along some black voters to seal that victory.
Treffinger hired her as his deputy county executive.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was one of my most trusted senior management people, and I
had the utmost confidence in her,'' said Treffinger, adding that he
could always depend on Ms. Hurt for level-headed advice.
</P>
<P>
   At about the time that Prosecutor Clifford Minor stepped down,
Treffinger was heading into a re-election campaign that would pit
him against former Newark Mayor Kenneth Gibson. In what many saw as
a calculated bid to attract black support, Treffinger, who is
white, urged Whitman to appoint Ms. Hurt as the next prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Hurt's first few months in office attracted positive
headlines, the problems were not far behind. In September two of
Ms. Hurt's appointees ran into trouble. Ms. Corcoran, whom she had
named deputy chief of investigations, and Capt. Durrell Dunson, a
newly arrived recruit from the Newark Police Department, were
implicated in the brutalizing of a suspected drug dealer during a
raid. The case is now before a grand jury, and Ms. Corcoran has
resigned while Dunson is on restricted duty.
</P>
<P>
   The incident also led to the resignation of Edward Malia, the
man whose appointment as chief of investigations Ms. Hurt had
announced along with Ms. Corcoran's on the day she was sworn in.
</P>
<P>
   September turned even worse for Ms. Hurt when she and Ms. Rosa
were stopped for speeding in the Prosecutor's official car on the
Garden State Parkway. The incident led Ms. Hurt and her lawyer to
suggest that the white state trooper who stopped her was engaging
in racial profiling and should be investigated by the governor.
While Ms. Hurt later retracted that charge, she continued to insist
that she had not been treated respectfully in the incident.
</P>
<P>
   October brought the filing of the age and gender discrimination
lawsuit by the current and former employees. Also at that time the
white state trooper whom Ms. Hurt had accused of racial profiling
announced that he would sue her for slander and defamation.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Hurt's biggest problem began on the night of April 8,
when Joyce Carnegie, a police officer in the small town of Orange,
was gunned down while looking for a robbery suspect. Less than two
days after the killing, local police had arrested Terrance Everett,
a 24-year-old man with a criminal record who fit the description of
the killer and whose picture was identified by several witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   But to some of Ms. Hurt's top aides, it became clear within
hours of his arrest that he was not the killer. Yet Ms. Hurt pushed
ahead with her case against Everett, arraigning him on a murder
charge and bringing him before television cameras with bruises and
a black eye that he said he suffered from police abuse while being
arrested. And in the meantime, investigators failed to interview a
key alibi witness until five days after Everett was arrested.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't all. Because of investigators' doubts about
Everett, officers continued to look for suspects even while Everett
was in jail. A day after his arrest, officers arrested a
27-year-old man who also fit the description of the officer's
killer. That man, Earl Faison, died in police custody; the
authorities have not explained how he died.
</P>
<P>
   Federal and state investigations are now being conducted in both
cases, and Ms. Hurt's office is facing civil action as well.
Lawyers for Everett say they intend to file suit alleging false
arrest and brutality, while Faison's family is also considering
legal action.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Hurt continues to say little about the investigation into
Officer Carnegie's death, other than that she was comfortable with
how it was handled. ``I do not intend on answering each of the
criticisms,'' she said Friday, ``except to note that they are
unfair.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came the announcement late last week that the attorney
general's office was auditing her handling of funds forfeited by
drug dealers and the allegations by Treffinger that she was
misusing money and spending extravagantly.
</P>
<P>
   Asked Friday if it had been a rough two weeks, Ms. Hurt managed
a smile and replied:
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a rough year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
