<HEADLINE>
CATAMARAN SAILOR PLOTTING THE REVENGE OF THE TOMATO  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va., Fla., )   By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For Hans Meijer, a multihull sailor from Virginia Beach, Va., a
tomato is anything but a piece of fruit. It has got him into
trouble twice now in ocean racing, and both times, he has had to
head for the beach. Not a good place for tomatoes.
</P>
<P>
   So what is this circuitous connection between a tomato and
sailing? Sponsorship in the Worrell 1000, an annual catamaran race
1,000 miles along the East Coast, from Fort Lauderdale, Fla., to
Virginia Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Meijer, a competitor in that race for the last two years, has
named his 20-foot catamaran, Pomodoro, Italian for a tomato. (The
boat's name comes from Pizza Pomodoro, the restaurant that Meijer's
sister owns in London.) Each time he has sailed under that name, he
and his teammate have been forced to abandon their little beach
cats at Cape Hatteras, along a rough-and-tumble stretch of ocean
off the North Carolina coast.
</P>
<P>
   This year, the 38-year-old Meijer hopes things will be
different. The event, scheduled to begin next Sunday off Fort
Lauderdale, is expected to include 13 two-man teams. Meijer plans
to sail with Brian Lambert, 33, from Fort Walton Beach, Fla., as
crew. They will wear a specially made T-shirt to charge their
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a picture of a tomato on the front,'' Meijer said, ``a
mean, vicious tomato with blood running from its fangs. It has
green vines for hands, and they are wrapped around the lighthouse
at Cape Hatteras.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Meijer's catamaran dismasted in rough seas 14 miles off
the coast. It took two Coast Guard vessels to pick up Meijer and
his crewman.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, his multihull's front crossbeam cracked. Near shore,
a huge wave picked the boat up like a skillet under an
egg-over-easy and dumped the boat right-side-up on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   Meijer landed on a deserted island off Hatteras last year. It
was another 23 hours before his shore crew picked him up from the
remote fishing camp on the deserted island off Hatteras. A
fisherman had given them plates of spaghetti and Scotch to get them
through to the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Meijer's failure to get around Hatteras has been niggling at him
all the while.
</P>
<P>
   ``The race is unfinished business,'' Meijer said in a telephone
interview last week. ``The challenge of sailing 1,000 miles is
something I've got to do. It's been a dream for some time.''
</P>
<P>
   So, this year Meijer and Lambert will wear tomato T-shirts that
issue a challenge to Hatteras: ``You're mine in '99.''
</P>
<P>
   For Meijer, the race has become a mission. For others, the
Worrell 1000 is a way of life. Randy Smyth, a sailmaker from Fort
Walton, has won the 15-year-old competition three times. Smyth, now
44, keeps coming back despite the race's grueling reputation.
</P>
<P>
   Its format calls for 11 seaside stops before the race finishes
May 21 in Virginia Beach. While mostly competing by day, the
sailors must also negotiate two evening stages. It means that
instead of a hotel bed, they are pinned to their catamaran's open
trampoline all night. The sailing is wet. Synthetic dry suits
replace all standard yachting gear. Eating is usually sandwiches
squashed in plastic wrap tied to the forestay. Navigating is tricky
near Hatteras, which is known as a Graveyard of the Atlantic).
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look toward shore from miles out, you see what
appears to be the skyline of a built-up city,'' Michael Worrell, a
co-founder of the race, said recently. ``But as you get closer, it
is really ocean swells coming together, and waves break straight up
into the air.''
</P>
<P>
   That doesn't seem to bother Smyth. ``You're kind of going out
there blindfolded,'' he said. ``If you're afraid of things like
waves and shoals, it could be daunting. But to me, it's a building
block in which you learn from past experiences.''
</P>
<P>
   So last year when a fierce northeaster barreled into the coast,
demolishing four catamarans and canceling Leg 11, from Cape
Hatteras to Kill Devil Hills, N.C., 10 of the 21 boats were forced
to pulled out. But Smyth got through it by going into the beach and
taking off the boat's jib before heading to the shoals. His boat's
reduced sail area allowed him to head up the shore in control as
other teams were being tossed in the steep surf.
</P>
</TEXT>
