<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-TURKEYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: SEASON OPENS FOR TOMS, BUT WATCH OUT FOR THOSE HENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the days grow longer and warmer, wild turkeys in New York
state are responding to ``the force that through the green fuse
drives the flower,'' and hunters count on this to reduce the male's
ability to notice that danger is nigh.
</P>
<P>
   Only adult males, also called toms or gobblers, may be shot
during the state's May 1-31 spring turkey season, which takes place
in all of the state north of the Bronx-Westchester county border.
</P>
<P>
   The season opens when most hens, already impregnated, are on
their nests. In a further effort to avoid the killing of hens by
mistake, the hours for the spring season are from a half-hour
before sunrise to noon. The nesting females tend to stick with
their brooding duties until that hour, but sometime during the day
they have to leave their nests and forage for food.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, the fully camouflaged spring hunter hies himself to
a likely spot in the woods and yelps as if he were a hen turkey
seeking to be serviced. The usual calling device for this is a box
call with a swinging lid. Some hunters use a diaphragm call that is
held in the mouth; its advantage is that it leaves your hands free
to hold your fowling piece and reduces hand movements. But it has
less range than a box call and is more difficult to use properly.
</P>
<P>
   A gobbling call is occasionally used in an effort to convince a
tom that another male has invaded his territory, a call to arms, if
you will. On rare occasions, novice hunters have stalked another
hunter who is gobbling. There is no need for this kind of nonsense.
Experienced hunters know that it is almost impossible to stalk a
wild tom successfully. The rule of thumb when spring turkey hunting
is, once you start yelping, to let the birds come to you.
</P>
<P>
   The spring hunter is after gobblers that are striving to mate
with every receptive hen around. Once so served, the hens turn to
egg-laying and nesting. The toms, meanwhile, remain inflamed.
Hard-put to find release, the male turkey sometimes races nonstop
through the trees and puckerbrush toward a hunter's yelp, but this
is not usual.
</P>
<P>
   If you are not an expert, it is best to call as few times as
possible, perhaps a few times every 20 minutes if the bird is
coming at you. Turkeys have marvelous hearing, and one sour note is
often all it takes to spook them. Their eyesight is also superb.
</P>
<P>
   The need for the nimrod's virtual immobility was brought home to
me many years ago when I went on my first spring turkey hunt. Paul
Updike and I ensconced ourselves on a hardwood ridge in the
Catskills where he had heard gobblers during preseason scouting.
Early on, a distant gobbler responded to his box call, but nearly
two hours went by before the bird came within shotgun range. It
circled around behind us and I froze.
</P>
<P>
   Paul inched himself around in order to be facing the bird. He
was in an awkward and contorted position, but dared not move any
more because his quarry was running back and forth through the dry
leaves. After 20 minutes, during which I saw nothing, Paul fired.
</P>
<P>
   Immediately after the shot he lay writhing on the forest floor,
shouting to me to get the bird. For an instant I thought that his
shotgun had exploded, injuring him; then I realized he was
experiencing a charley horse of magnificent proportions.
</P>
<P>
   I retrieved the turkey, a handsome gobbler of about 20 pounds
that was stone-hammer dead, and brought it back to Paul, who by
that time had stopped thrashing about. It was then that he told me
that turkeys are tough and that many toms believed to be dead have
escaped. Dogs are allowed in fall turkey hunting in New York state,
but not in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Hard winters do not reduce turkey populations as much as cold,
wet springs. Reproduction was down last spring, says Glenn Cole, a
state wildlife biologist, and that was reflected in a reduced
hunter kill of the birds in the fall of 1998. The hunter take in
the spring of 1998 was more than 9,000, about normal in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   The daily spring limit is one tom and the spring season's limit
is two. Both a hunting license and a special turkey permit are
needed to hunt the birds in New York state. The permit is also good
for the fall turkey season, when any turkey is legal game.
</P>
<P>
   Although most hens will be on their nests, a few are always
wandering about and they sometimes respond to the hunter's yelping.
Thus hunters must be certain of the sex of the bird. Males have
highly visible beards hanging from their chests. Only a few hens
are so adorned. The head of the gobbler is red, white and blue; the
hen's is a muted blue-gray. The gobbling, strutting, wing-dragging
and fanned tail approach of the tom is highly distinctive.
</P>
<P>
   Only shotguns or bow and arrow may be used for turkey hunting in
New York state. The shotshell pellets may be no larger than No. 2
or smaller than No. 8.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible to learn the art of spring turkey hunting on your
own, but you will progress a lot faster if you can go out with an
experienced hunter your first season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
