<P>
   HAITI-TROOPS _ PORT AU PRINCE, Haiti _ In February, Gen. Charles
Wilhelm, commander of the U.S. Southern Command, recommended
pulling U.S. troops out of Haiti. Not only have they failed to
bring the hoped-for stability, he said, but they are in danger from
the very people they are supposed to be protecting. Yet the troops
remain. As President Clinton tries to rally support for a
peacekeeping mission in Kosovo, it would be embarrassing for the
administration to accept the general's call for a pullout. We spend
a day with the 500 or so U.S. troops that quietly continue a
five-year U.S. occupation of Haiti. The impoverished nation still
resents the last U.S. incursion, a 19-year occupation that ended 65
years ago. Just last fall Haiti's Parliament passed a law to make
the presence of foreign troops illegal. In Washington, members of
Congress also are questioning the U.S. presence, which costs $22
million a year. They say the money is a waste since most of it goes
to protect the U.S. troops. (Emling, Cox News Service). 30. WITH
