<P>
   SCHOOLS-WORSTEVER _ BATH, Mich. _ Before Oklahoma City, before
Littleton, Colorado, before the wave of bizarre, terrorist-style
school house bloodbaths shook the foundations of an American
cultural landscape awash in techno-violence, there was Bath,
Michigan. There, on May 18, 1927, just days before lucky Lindbergh
conquered the Atlantic, a man described variously as homicidal
farmer, angry school board treasurer and meticulous handyman,
detonated hundreds of pounds of explosives he had secreted in the
subflooring of the local school, blowing 45 people - mostly
elementary school children - into oblivion. The small town just
outside Lansing was never the same. Today the incident is so little
remembered that major U.S. newspapers including the New York Times
erred when describing Littleton as the mostly deadly school
incident in American history Simmering, lonely hate and targeting
children for mass murder are nothing new. The angry farmer did his
deed because he resented increased taxes for the school. (Bennish,
Dayton Daily News), 30-40. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   STARWARS-PARTY _ DENVER _ 30,000 hard-core Star Wars fans invade
Denver for the first ever Star Wars celebration and we are there.
By Saturday, people will have a clear idea of what's cool and
what's not. Cummings will rendezvous with people from the Dayton
area at mid-day to compare notes on the Celebration, on the Star
Wars night life, etc. Will attempt to hook up with a photog at
about noon to shoot one or two local types whooping it up. Also
should have some accounts of major events such as the appearance of
the guy playing Darth Maul. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News). 25. ETA
7 p.m. EDT. WITH PHOTOS (from Grand Junction).
