<HEADLINE>
ON MAY 1, A SPRING BREAK FOR PENT-UP NEW YORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A big fat dose of spring was reported to have arrived
in earnest throughout this city Saturday. And just about everywhere
you looked, the evidence was rather compelling.
</P>
<P>
   In Times Square at 8 a.m., there was Cindy Crawford, warming up
packs of numbered runners for a jog to Central Park to raise money
for women's health issues. Not long after, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
went bowling in Bryant Park to kick off a pro bowling tournament
and raise awareness of himself. And in neighborhoods across the
rest of the city, New Yorkers kicked off the first real spring
weekend this year under a gorgeous, cloudless blue sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably as good a weekend as there has been in the
spring,'' declared Fred Gadomski, a meteorologist at Penn State
University who predicted Saturday's ``abundant sunshine'' and
70-degree temperatures would last through Sunday. ``This has, no
doubt, got people's hormones flaring up.''
</P>
<P>
   In healthy ways, mostly.
</P>
<P>
   In Brooklyn, cherry blossoms bloomed to great fanfare, and
environmentalists fished for toxic bass. In Harlem,
philanthropically minded souls restored a school playground. The
weather did, indeed, have something to do with that. ``You always
think this is the last day it's going to be like this,'' said Greg
Cirota, 31, a New York University film student, as he strolled
through a Lower East Side street fair. ``But then I realize it's
the first.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps no patch of Manhattan was put to greater or more diverse
springtime use than Washington Square Park, onto which pot-loving
hippies, child-toting yuppies and domesticated donkeys
simultaneously converged, each with a separate agenda. On the
southeast corner, hundreds of people gathered for the Million
Marijuana March to chant slogans advocating the legalization of
smokable hemp. About 100 feet away, Pink Ink Art and Motion, a
visual-arts company, offered children's tours through a psychedelic
playground of colored fabric tents and tunnels.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, about 40 protesters from the Global Sweatshop
Coalition parked in front of a Kmart at Astor Place and chanted:
``Hey, hey. Ho ho. Sweatshops have got to go.''
</P>
<P>
   On 143rd Street in Harlem, the mood was more altruistic as more
than 100 volunteers from the New York Junior League renovated a
playground at PS 194. ``Just watching everyone helping out here,
it's better than Tom Sawyer,'' said city Parks Commissioner Henry
Stern, who insists on being called ``Starquest'' when on official
parks business. Supervising the volunteers sweeping away nails and
glass, painting and repairing playground equipment, Starquest said,
``This will be one beautiful playground.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn was no less resplendent. At the Brooklyn Botanic
Gardens, a weekendlong Cherry Blossom Festival drew hundreds of
floralists, kindergartners and pensioners alike. ``There's no place
prettier in the world than this spot,'' said Joan Asher, 56, of
Brooklyn, breathing in the sweetened air between two rows of cherry
trees Saturday morning. ``This whole place just recharges my
battery.''
</P>
<P>
   As children played in the thick lawn around her, Dorothy Duan,
81, immigrant from China, gave a Tai Chi demonstration to anyone
who cared to watch. ``The blossoms remind me of my home town in
China,'' Ms. Duan said. ``I always try to come here around blossom
time.''
</P>
<P>
   About a mile east, in Williamsburg, the springtime subject at
hand was fish. About 50 people gathered along a garbage-strewn
section of East River bank for a ``fish-in,'' sponsored by the New
York chapter of the Sierra Club, to draw attention to the
pollutants in the river that have kept striped bass more or less
toxic for decades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to come here as a kid, but I don't remember ever
catching anything back then,'' said Andrew Dassaro, 36, a subway
conductor who spent the morning with a fishing line cast into the
river beside his nephew Thomas, 6.
</P>
<P>
   There was other evidence of full-tilt spring action _ Upper West
Side residents planting flowers in tree boxes; pet-store clearance
sales on cat leashes and dog beds, to name two _ but spring in New
York would not be quite right without its sine qua non signature:
German tourists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, they're walking through Strawberry Fields,'' said a
tour bus driver standing beside his rig on 77th Street and Central
Park West, waiting for a pack of Germans to return. ``It's really
nice out here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
