<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEGRAM HAS HIS DAY IN THE OAKS INSTEAD 
MONEY MATTERS 
IT'S THE PLACE TO BE 
RIDERS RULE THE DAY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., Wash.)  (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Mike Pegram didn't feel bad that he would be
merely a spectator at the 125th running of the Kentucky Derby. The
owner of last year's winner, Real Quiet, could have entered
Silverbulletday but decided he had a more important title to
defend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was the owner who had the most fun last year,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not only because he won the grand race. Pegram, the owner
of 22 McDonald's franchises in Washington state, brought a casual
attitude along with a party posse to his first Kentucky Derby. His
fashion statement over a week of high style remained consistent:
jeans and no tie.
</P>
<P>
   He and his friends, many of whom he grew up with in nearby
Princeton, Ind., were mainstays in the late hours. They preferred
an ever-present beer cooler over the tony parties. Pegram's good
friend, trainer Bob Baffert, made a point to carry the colors of
the everyman. In fact, it was Pegram who persuaded the California
trainer's to switch to thoroughbreds and bankrolled it.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't leave horse racing's biggest week empty-handed.
Silverbulletday, his championship filly, proved she was one of the
best of her generation by rolling to an easy two-length lead as the
1-9 favorite in the prestigious Kentucky Oaks on Friday. She picked
up the $341,620 purse to push her earnings over $2 million and give
Pegram a rare Oaks-Derby double.
</P>
<P>
   He also stayed for the big race Saturday and played with Baffert
and his entourage. ``That's what friends do,'' Pegram said.
</P>
<P>
   Money Matters
</P>
<P>
   The 125th running of the Kentucky Oaks broke attendance records
for the fifth year in a row. The more than 101,034 people, however,
didn't break the betting record for Oaks day. The on-track handle
was $10,339,112, short of 1998's $10,359,724
</P>
<P>
   Here's the breakdown of the record $1,186,200 purse for the 1999
Kentucky Derby: The winner earned $886,2000; second place,
$170,000; third, $85,000, and fourth, $45,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's the Place to Be
</P>
<P>
   Even with the late scratch of the Dubai-based Aljabr, the
19-horse field exceeded the average for Derby starters in the 1980s
and 1990s. In the past two decades, an average of 16.7 horses
started the race. In the 1960s and 1970s, Derby fields averaged
13.75. Most trainers expect future Derbys to fill the 20-horse
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure you'd rather have 12 or 13 horses, but this is the
biggest show in our sport,'' said Nick Zito, who brought Adonis and
Stephen Got Even here. ``You can't tell your owners, `You can't
bring your horse here.' If it's a good horse, they want to come and
be a part of this phenomenon. It's the place to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Riders Rule the Day
</P>
<P>
   In a big Derby field, jockeys are even more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy who can see an eighth of a mile ahead is going to win
this race,'' said the trainer D. Wayne Lukas, who had Mike Smith
riding Cat Thief and Chris Antley on Charismatic. ``He'll be making
early moves and planning late ones.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert said the jockeys would decide who had a chance to
win as they went around the first turn. ``There's a lot of banging
and a good rider will bring his horse through and in position to
win,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert was relying on last year's winner, Kent Desormeaux, to
do that in guiding the filly Excellent Meeting. Gary Stevens rode
on her entry mate General Challenge, with David Flores on Prime
Timber.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
