<HEADLINE>
UPSIDE-DOWN WORLD OF INTERNET STOCKS MAKES LITTLE SENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Would you like to know how crazy this stock market is? Really?
Naw, you wouldn't. It will only make you cry if you've been brought
up to believe in the precepts of value investing.
</P>
<P>
   Still want to know? OK, here goes. The Wall Street Journal on
Tuesday had a story showing how far the stock market has gone in
divorcing itself from reality. The article was pegged to a study by
a Morgan Stanley Dean Witter analyst, and revealed the secret of
how to make money investing in the depressed small-company sector.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Penney's research revealed that if you had bought the
stocks of companies in the Russell 2000 index expected to lose
money this year, you'd be making a killing.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 comprises small companies, usually defined as
those with a market value under $1.5 billion. This means it
includes many Internet-related stocks. As of April 23, Penney
noted, your portfolio would have been up 24.2 percent if you had
invested in the 190 companies expected to either post losses this
year or, at best, have no profit.
</P>
<P>
   But, as they say on the hard-sell commercials, that's not all.
If you had invested in the 1,494 Russell 2000 companies forecasting
a profitable year, your portfolio would be down 1.1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The paradox results from the Bizarro World of Internet stocks.
Get this: Doubleclick, an Internet marketing enterprise,
anticipates a loss of 43 cents a share this year, but its stock was
up more than 670 percent. SportsLine USA, an Internet sports
information company, is pegged by analysts to lose $1.92 a share,
but has scored a 170 percent gain on its stock.
</P>
<P>
   Compare this madness to some of the more spectacular value plays
in the Russell 2000 lineup. Papa John's International, a
pizza-delivery operation, has racked up 20 straight quarters of
year-over-year growth exceeding 20 percent. Despite this remarkable
five-year record, the stock is down 8 percent. This is ``quite
remarkable,'' said an analyst who tracks the stock. Yes, indeed, in
more ways than one.
</P>
<P>
   If that fails to bring tears to your eyes, here's another
Bizarro World refugee. Specialty Equipment, which is doing a
land-office business selling its wares to McDonald's restaurants,
has consistently beaten earnings expectations and has been buying
back its own stock. Nevertheless, ``no one cares,'' said an analyst
who follows the company. Its performance lags those of the major
market indexes.
</P>
<P>
   All of this brings to mind the recent observation of an analyst
who mused that some Internet companies were managed as if the
executives in charge didn't want to make a profit. This is no
accident, he contended, because Internet entrepreneurs are afraid
if they generate profits, they'll be judged by investors and
analysts like traditional companies. His point was put into
perspective by America Online's recent experience. Its stock got
hammered after per share quarterly earnings came in nearly triple
what Wall Street expected.
</P>
<P>
   What does this insanity tell us? For one thing, it tells us that
Internet stocks have been the place to be in recent months. In a
less salubrious context, however, it also reminds us that the
madness of crowds historically brings those crowds to grief.
</P>
<P>
   Caveat emptor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
