<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ripken retirement near
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken's back trouble is nothing new. He has successfully
fought off a disc problem in recent seasons with a program of
special strengthening exercises. But with his late father's illness
preoccupying his winter months, Ripken let the exercises slip,
which slowly delivered him to the disabled list once camp opened.
</P>
<P>
   Although he pledged to keep his condition ``private'' as he
tries to restart his season, Ripken is waiting for a series of
cortisone injections to take effect while he works the muscles
around the area. But without improvement, retirement becomes not
just an alternative but a certainty.
</P>
<P>
   ``People make decisions all the time,'' Ripken said, ``and this
is a time in my life when I have to look hard at my injury
situation, evaluate that and the whole career and make decisions
and make judgments. That's life, and that's what we do. ...
</P>
<P>
   Boston second baseman Jeff Frye suspected it would cost him his
job when the Red Sox signed Jose Offerman, and he was right as
Frye, while praising manager Jimy Williams, said, ``If I'm not good
enough to be the starting second baseman on a particular team,
maybe I shouldn't be on that team.''
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of seats at Comiskey
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox might wind up with the worst attendance in the
majors, which puts a smile on the mess in Montreal. Crowds at
Comiskey averaged under 13,000 through the first 10 games. Last
weekend's series with Detroit drew a three-day gate of 36,471,
which doesn't even match the Sunday crowd crosstown at Wrigley
Field, where the Cubs played the Mets before 39,265.
</P>
<P>
   The year before the strike, the White Sox won 94 games while
drawing 2.6 million fans. This year's projection is between 1.5
million and 1.6 million, despite the attraction of Frank Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've hit bottom,'' said Rob Gallas, the team's vice president
for marketing. ...
</P>
<P>
   Torii Hunter, rookie center fielder in Minnesota, has crashed
into the wall three times chasing fly balls, including a
homer-saving catch this week. ``I probably run into 20 a year,'' he
said. ``I've been knocked out about 10 times. Actually, probably
more, but I can't remember all of them.'' ... Kansas City's Johnny
Damon was able to keep his consecutive-games streak alive at 180
after his wife delivered twins during an off-day last week. Damon
entered the weekend hitting .211.
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Roster ramifications in Seattle
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's acquisition of outfielder Brian Hunter from Detroit
means two things: The Mariners' search for a lead-off hitter
reached the critical stage, and someone else is going to have to go
from the roster.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter's .298 on-base percentage was lowest in the majors last
season. He becomes the special project of hitting coach Jesse
Barfield. After the Mariners demoted reliever Brett Hinchliffe to
open a spot, the team has been left with 10 pitchers. Butch Huskey,
John Mabry and Matt Mieske are all left fielders and one is on the
way out. ...
</P>
<P>
   Two years after the 50-year celebration of Jackie Robinson's
major-league debut, Texas shortstop Royce Clayton is the only
active player to make a contribution to the Robinson Foundation,
setting up a college endowment with a $100,000 pledge. ... Angels
manager Terry Collins is discounting trainers' reports that
shortstop Gary DiSarcina's broken arm might be healed before the
All-Star break. ``Nothing is etched in stone,'' Collins said.
``I've been etching stuff in stone, and it keeps falling on my
head, so I'm not going to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
