<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fast pace for Atlantan Barrett
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _
</P>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Atlantan Michael Barrett finally has forced Montreal manager
Felipe Alou to play him daily at third base, a decision that
numbers Shane Andrews' days with the Expos. Barrett, the 1995
first-round pick out of Pace Academy, entered the weekend hitting
.344 with three homers and 12 RBIs while splitting time between
third base and catcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barrett is learning to play in the big leagues, and it isn't
fair to have him alternating from one position to the other,'' Alou
said. ``I don't think there is any question about Barrett being
able to play third base, and he deserves to play regularly. That's
my plan now.''
</P>
<P>
   Andrews, 27, asked to be traded during spring camp when told
Barrett would get time with him at third. Barrett's play has caused
a that time-sharing plan, which also included catcher Chris Widger,
to fall apart...
</P>
<P>
   Florida first baseman Derrek Lee could not contain himself after
making the final out in last Saturday's loss to Atlanta and kicked
a trash can across the Marlins dugout. Unfortunately, it landed on
his manager.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just sitting there,'' manager John Boles said, ``and all
of a sudden I was covered with all this stuff.'' Lee apologized.
Plenty.
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Farnsworth gets a shot
</P>
<P>
   The debut of Milton High School product Kyle Farnsworth with the
Chicago Cubs was a surprise last week, but only by a couple of
months. The Cubs had hoped to call up the former 47th-round draft
pick at midseason, but injuries _ six Cubs pitchers are on the DL _
forced the issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll be here for a couple starts, and more than
likely he'll go back,'' general manger Ed Lynch said. ``I've said
it all along _ when we bring people like Kyle Farnsworth to the
major leagues, we'd like for them to come and stay.'' ... Ex-Brave
Chad Fox, who had become Milwaukee's most trusted reliever, will
have his aching left elbow examined by Birmingham specialist James
Andrews this week. Fox, who underwent Tommy John surgery four years
ago, has had mysterious swelling and pain in the joint all month.
... The Astros' decision to trade away catcher Brad Ausmus is less
popular than ever in Houston, now that rookie Mitch Meluskey might
require shoulder surgery. NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   Blame pointed at Pirates
</P>
<P>
   The San Diego Padres say they have video of Pittsburgh's Jason
Schmidt and Turner Ward shining a laser pointer from the Pirates'
dugout during a recent game at Qualcomm Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Both Schmidt and Ward deny the charge, but a Padres staff
photographer has blurred vision after Schmidt allegedly shined the
laser into his lens.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Hallinan, baseball's director of security, said during the
offseason that MLB will prosecute anyone using one of the laser
devices. ``Those things are dangerous for fans and players,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   The photographer, Joel Swink, 44, says he saw Schmidt using the
light before his vision was affected as he looked through his
view-finder. Swink won't say if he is considering legal action. ...
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Brian Bohanon is alone on a new frontier, the first
pitcher in Colorado history to open a season 4-0. The rest of the
rotation is struggling. Until Darryl Kile's victory Thursday, no
other Rockies starter had won a game since the opener.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
