A0760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-NOTES02-COX     05-01 0566
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-NOTES02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia-Florida at night?
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Given the rowdiness that surrounds the annual
Georgia-Florida football game in Jacksonville, none of the parties
involved has wanted to play the game at night. That situation could
change soon.
</P>
<P>
   At the request of ESPN, which is negotiating an extension of its
contract with the SEC, the athletics boards at Georgia and Florida
have agreed to allow the game to be played at night this year or
sometime in the future, if CBS does not pick it for the network's
3:30 p.m. national telecast.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, ESPN, whose contract with the SEC ends
after the 2000 season, is promised only one opportunity to televise
the Georgia-Florida game at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have a much cleaner environment with the new
stadium and the surrounding area, we thought this was a restriction
we could lift on a one-time basis,'' Georgia athletics director
Vince Dooley said. ``If the game is managed well, we can talk about
whether or not we will do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   The chances of CBS passing on the Georgia-Florida game this year
are slim. The other SEC games set for Oct. 30 are Auburn-Arkansas,
Ole Miss-LSU and Tennessee-South Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   Auburn may be under lights
</P>
<P>
   Dooley, with the approval of his athletics board, made another
concession to help the SEC improve the value of its TV package with
ESPN. The Georgia-Auburn game in Athens on Nov. 13, which in years
past could start no later than 5:30 p.m., will be made available
for a night broadcast.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Dooley agreed to make as many as two of Georgia's six
home games available at night for ESPN. Dooley said he will not
change his policy against Thursday night games in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   Behind the scenes
</P>
<P>
   _ When a talented freshman like Duke's Corey Maggette talks
about turning pro, the natural assumption is that an agent is
whispering in his ear. But there are strong rumors in the ACC that
the Chicago native has heard from the hometown NBA Bulls, who have
promised to groom him as the next Michael Jordan if he comes out
now. If that turns to be true, Duke coach Mike Krzyzewski, also a
Chicago native, will not forget.
</P>
<P>
   _ Sophomore quarterback Tim Olmstead will transfer from Florida.
The former Parade All-American from Woodberry Forest, Va., never
was able to fully grasp the complex offense of coach Steve
Spurrier. The Gators have two freshman quarterbacks, Rex Grossman
and Chris Stephens, joining the team this season.
</P>
<P>
   _ Auburn football coach Tommy Tuberville has told five players,
including redshirt freshman wide receiver Willie Northern, that
their scholarships would not be renewed. The others are offensive
tackle Brandon Taylor, linebacker Manning Sumner, defensive end
Brian Parchinski and center Shawn Bushong.
</P>
<P>
   Worth noting
</P>
<P>
   _ Tennessee's spring tour of its booster clubs, known as the Big
Orange Caravan, will stop in Atlanta on May 11 with golf and dinner
at the Crooked Creek Golf Club. Football coach Phillip Fulmer and
basketball coach Jerry Green are scheduled to attend. For more
information call Kristen Olkowski at 404-636-1979.
</P>
<P>
   _ New Mexico State athletics director Jim Paul is leaving the
school to join the presidential campaign of Texas Gov. George W.
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
