<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cowboys uncertain Sanders will return
 &HT;    By Len Pasquarelli
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ The medical term for the injury that forced
Deion Sanders into surgery on Wednesday is ``hyperdorsiflexion of
the first metatarsal phalangeal joint.'' By any name, though, the
injury spells trouble for Dallas, which began a weekend mini-camp
here on Friday uncertain of the star cornerback's future.
</P>
<P>
   Surgeon Bill Hamilton spent three hours repairing the big toe on
Sanders' left foot but even conservative estimates put the rehab at
four months. What no one is saying aloud: A similar injury ended
the Hall of Fame tenure of Steelers linebacker Jack Lambert in '85
and is regarded as career-threatening for Sanders as well.
</P>
<P>
   The situation leaves owner Jerry Jones and coach Chan Gailey in
a tough spot. Sanders has a salary cap figure of $8.2 million. As
he did with Troy Aikman recently, Jones was hoping to negotiate an
extension to reduce that. But how can Jones huddle with agent
Eugene Parker and talk about a $10 million signing bonus when no
one is sure when or if Sanders, who turns 32 in August, will play?
</P>
<P>
   For now, Gailey is using Kevin Mathis at the corner spot
opposite Kevin Smith. But the Cowboys last week studied tape of
free agent corners Ashley Ambrose, Ryan McNeil, Cris Dishman and
Darrien Gordon and could sign one of them. The Cowboys will already
be without defensive tackle Leon Lett for at least a portion of the
season because of a positive drug test, so the defensive front
already is dented.
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgia star Champ Bailey had an auspicious debut in the
Redskins mini-camp, intercepting the first pass thrown at him. ...
Dallas may sign free agent quarterback Neil O'Donnell. ... A huge
element in owner Bob Kraft's decision to back out of the deal that
would have moved the Patriots to Hartford was that environmental
factors would have prohibited the team from playing there until
2003 at the earliest. ...Two reasons the Dallas draft was panned:
Three prospects were off most boards because of medical problems
and three failed drug tests in college. ... It won't be official
for a week, but Pittsburgh reached accord with quarterback Kordell
Stewart on a three-year extension through 2003. The deal includes
$22.45 million in ``new money,'' with a signing bonus of $8.1
million. ... Barry Sanders continues to send signals he's not
thrilled with the state of the Lions. As anticipated, he skipped
mini-camp and was fined $488 a day by coach Bobby Ross. He is 1,458
yards shy of supplanting Walter Payton as the NFL's career leader,
but is more concerned with winning. Preposterous as it sounds,
Sanders could sit out this season. Detroit is just 78-82 since he
arrived in '89 and has used 10 starting quarterbacks in that time.
Only Rodney Peete (47) and Scott Mitchell (57) had more than 15
starts. ... One more sign St. Louis coach Dick Vermeil is in a
must-win situation: The Rams cut guard Zach Wiegert, the team's
``transition'' free agent. Club president John Shaw and vice
president Jay Zygmunt were among the many Rams officials who
disagreed with Vermeil's ill-advised assessment of Wiegert. ...
Seattle wideout Joey Galloway, eligible for free agency next
spring, had a terrific mini-camp. One Seahawks coach timed Galloway
at an astonishing 4.19 in the 40. ...Miami coach Jimmy Johnson
isn't surprised the running back landscape has changed so
dramatically in the AFC East. ``With me, Jim Mora and Bill
Parcells, you have coaches who want to run the football,'' Johnson
said. ``No one throws 40 times a game anymore.'' In two years, the
division has undergone dramatic makeover. Antowain Smith (Buffalo)
took over for Thurman Thomas and Curtis Martin (Jets) for Adrian
Murrell in '97. This year, first-round pick Edgerrin James replaces
Marshall Faulk in Indy. The Patriots' Pete Carroll will consider
several candidates, including Kevin Faulk, to replace injured
Robert Edwards. And Johnson seems confident rookies James Johnson
or Rob Konrad will oust Karim Abdul-Jabbar. ... The Raiders quietly
hired New Orleans assistant general manager Chet Franklin. ...
Pittsburgh will release former first-round offensive tackle Jamain
Stephens after June 1. ... Colts line coach Howard Mudd felt
third-rounder Brandon Burlsworth, killed last week in a car
accident, would challenge Tony Mandarich for the starting job at
right guard.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
