</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KAYAK-CONVENTION-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOAT ROMANTICS GATHER WITH THEIR HANDMADE BEST
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Minn., Ore., Texas, Wyo.)  (rk) 
 By   TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DECEPTION PASS, Wash. _ In the upper left-hand corner of the
country, up where Puget Sound is littered with low, rocky islands,
about 65 hand-built boats lined the beach of a quiet, fog-filled
bay last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   There was a three-person touring craft inspired by Aleutian
fur-trading boats, open Alaskan rowboats known as umiaks, boats for
hunting caribou west of the Hudson Bay, and kayaks from East
Greenland, West Greenland and Southwest Greenland, with those from
each area distinct. And there were people who could tell them all
apart.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth Skin Boat Gathering here, scores of people from as
far away as Japan and Texas met to admire and learn about handmade,
skin-covered boats _ mostly kayaks, with wood or aluminum or
titanium frames, covered in nylon or canvas, the modern substitute
for sealskin.
</P>
<P>
   Skin boats are lighter than those made of fiberglass or plastic,
and they draw on indigenous design that has evolved over centuries.
Their proponents have revolted against what they call the
``over-the-counter culture'' of prefabricated, store-bought plastic
or fiberglass boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a romance,'' said Corey Freedman, who runs a
skin-boat building school in nearby Anacortes. ``People just fall
in love with them, and they don't know why. It has to do with the
elegance and the shape of the boats, the esthetics.''
</P>
<P>
   Freedman organized the gathering, which was advertised, mostly
by e-mail, as an ``informal, noncommercial, free education event.''
</P>
<P>
   Maligiaq Padilla, 17, the guest of honor, performed some of the
32 kayak maneuvers known as Eskimo rolls that he had learned in his
native Greenland. He became the youngest national kayak champion
last year. He capsized the boat and righted himself _ a 360-degree
roll _ using his paddle, a 2-foot-long harpoon stick, or just a
closed fist. All the while, Padilla was wedged into the kayak's
15-inch cockpit.
</P>
<P>
   People in the crowd of about 100, in wet suits, life jackets and
an occasional loin cloth, gave various reasons for their love of
skin boats.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's wonderful about this arena of recreation is the
personal innovation, the intuitive evolution, that has been taken
away by the production line, by the boats that have been poured
from cans into molds,'' said Steve Kaspar of Martinez, Calif., who
had brought along his two-person aluminum baidarka, an Aleutian sea
kayak.
</P>
<P>
   John D. Heath, 76, of Houston, has studied kayaks for 45 years.
``A kayak to me is like a violin that lasts, and has changed so
little in hundreds of years,'' he said. ``Why mess with the design?
A 300-year-old Stradivarius doesn't look out of place today.''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Golden, 28, of Portland, Ore., brought eight skin boats
he had built from boats he had seen in museums, one weighing as
little as 20 pounds and one designed to point directly into the
wind, for negotiating the gusty fiords of Greenland. He has studied
40 Arctic boats, he said, ``and I never found one to be badly or
poorly designed at all.''
 &UR;  &LR; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Golden's brother and sister-in-law, Dan Golden and Edith
Casterline, spent part of their honeymoon on the Columbia River in
a three-holer that Dan Golden built from designs made soon after
the first Russian made contact with the Aleutian Islanders about a
century ago. The center hole was reserved for the Russian hunter,
who shot otters while the natives paddled.
</P>
<P>
   Antonella Novi was 16 when she built her baidarka as part of a
school humanities project. ``Because I built it in the winter, I
really felt the coldness of building a boat, like they did in
Alaska,'' she said, recalling the hours she spent lashing the cedar
ribs to the frame. ``It really brought it home to my fingertips.''
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Gaydos, a Wyoming iron worker who had paddled for seven
weeks across northern Alaska, brought a birch-bark canoe to the
gathering and pointed out the spruce roots he had gathered in the
Minnesota woods to lash it together. The birch bark is peeled
before the sap rises, Gaydos said, so that he does not kill the
tree.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's utilitarian, it's lightweight,'' he said, of using skin
or wood, ``and there's just the satisfaction of creating it,
itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Ballenger, 23, a student at Western Washington University
in Bellingham, made her kayak in 1996, and works with a nonprofit
group called Team USAble, taking people with muscular dystrophy or
spinal cord injuries out paddling.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can get out in the water and connect with nature,'' said
Ms. Ballenger, who has cerebral palsy and enjoys helping people
exercise away from the mechanical devices like wheelchairs and
scooters that they use on land.
</P>
<P>
   Though her only previous woodworking experience dated to sixth
grade, she loved building her own boat. ``It really does have a
spirit.'' Ms. Ballenger said. ``It was a tree, it was a living
thing, and people are so moved by the boat. It's my baby. I made
it, and it takes me where I want to go.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
