<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-ADVANCE02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gordon slump gives rivals hope
 &HT;    By Mark Schalbach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Jeff Gordon couldn't run away with his third
Winston Cup title in a row in the first three months of the season,
leaving championship hopes for several other drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon, the Winston Cup champion three of the last four seasons,
is fifth in points entering today's California 500 at California
Speedway, trailing leader Jeff Burton by 210.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon's recent problems _ three DNFs in nine events, including
a 38th-place finish in last week's DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway _ have given several drivers, including Burton, Dale
Jarrett and Mark Martin, hopes for a first title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's nice that we have the talk about the
championship,'' said Jarrett, who trails Burton by 40 points.
``It's something that you have to concentrate on right from the
very beginning ... you have to race every single race with that
championship in mind. You can't have an off-week.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton and Jarrett were knocked out of the season-opening
Daytona 500 in the same multicar pileup, but they've had only one
off-day since. Both drivers have finished outside the top 10 only
once in the last eight events. Burton had victories at Las Vegas
and Darlington, while Jarrett is still searching for his first win
this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it is a little frustrating, but on the other hand, I
know we have 25 races left and we're doing the right things now,''
Jarrett said. ``Jeff Gordon has had his problems, but he's still
very much in striking distance. I heard somebody say that they
weren't sure that (Gordon) could make up that point differential.
Of course, you just have to laugh a little bit at that.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin, who was second to Gordon in points last season, says he
welcomes the parity, but the added pressure that accompanies it
``takes a lot of the fun out of the year.''
</P>
<P>
   With consecutive top-five finishes at Martinsville and
Talladega, Martin climbed to third in points. He slipped to sixth
in the standings after a wreck and 34th-place outing at Texas Motor
Speedway on March 28.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon has been in this position before. He was fifth in points
a year ago, trailing leader Rusty Wallace by 73 after nine events.
Gordon finished fourth at California, and then won at Charlotte two
weeks later to regain the points lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett says he expects more of the same from Gordon. ``Yes,
Jeff Gordon is still the one to beat. He's the only one in the top
five who has won a championship. The rest of us have to prove we
can get it done.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
