<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-CART-FRIENDS-600&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOUR UPCOMING DRIVERS ENJOYING LIFE AS AUTO RACING'S BRAT PACK
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By TARIK EL-BASHIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZARETH, Pa. _ For a small band of Champ Car drivers, life
doesn't necessarily slow down once they have climbed out of the
cockpit. Win or lose, the good times for these twenty-something
bachelors start after the race is finished.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Moore, Max Papis, Dario Franchitti and Tony Kanaan, all
rising stars on the Championship Auto Racing Teams open-wheel
racing circuit, are known loosely as the Brat Pack, a nickname
derived from the Frank Sinatra-led Rat Pack, which enlivened
Hollywood's party scene in the 1950s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   Like Sinatra's clique, Moore, Papis, Franchitti and Kanaan are
drawn together by an intense appetite for fun and all-night
parties. Whether they are judging beauty contests in Surfers
Paradise, Australia, or borrowing Harley-Davidsons for a ride up
the California coast, or staying up till dawn in Elkhart Lake,
Wis., or traveling from race to race in Moore's motor coach, these
guys know how to enjoy life.
</P>
<P>
   But for two hours on the track, Moore, Papis, Franchitti and
Kanaan put their friendship aside and have nothing on their minds
but being first to the finish. On Sunday, they are at the Bosch
Spark Plug 200at Nazareth Speedway, the fourth of 20 CART Fedex
championship series races this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all kind of get along,'' said Franchitti, who came into his
own last season, winning three races in the Team Kool Green
Honda/Reynard. ``We're different in a lot of ways, but we're also
incredibly similar. When we're on the road, they are like my
family. But when qualifying starts, they are the opposition. We can
all flick that switch.''
</P>
<P>
   The four are talented drivers who just happen to be young,
single and free to enjoy some of the world's most stimulating
cities, from Miami to Monterey.
</P>
<P>
   But, to a man, they are dedicated to their job, and they are
very good at what they do. Moore, 24, driver of the Player's
Mercedes/Reynard, is the CART points leader this season and is
favored to take his first series title, while Franchitti
(pronounced Fran-CHEE-ti), 25, is considered to have an outside
chance of capturing the title. Papis (PAP-iss), 29, driver of Team
Rahal's Ford/Reynard, and Kanaan (CAY-nen), 24, driver of
McDonald's Honda/Reynard, are with strong teams and want to climb
the Champ Car ranks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can give yourself freedom,'' said Papis, the group's
self-proclaimed leader, ``but you have to know your limitations.
I'm not a party animal. I'm a human being. Trying to achieve goals
in life shouldn't prevent you from enjoying life.''
</P>
<P>
   While many of their nocturnal adventures are kept secret by the
pack's members, there are plenty of wild nights that have become
conversational fodder in the garage area.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for example, the night after Franchitti's first-ever
victory last season at Elkhart Lake, when the pack celebrated at
the best (and only) tavern in town. At 4 a.m., the party was just
getting started. Needless to say, Franchitti was not on his 8 a.m.
flight home to Scotland. And Papis stopped to take a nap on the
lawn in front of his hotel; it was, after all, on the way back to
his room.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next morning they found me in bed,'' Papis said, ``wearing
all of my clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   And their friendship helps counterbalance the intensity and
loneliness of competition on one of auto racing's toughest
circuits. ``Because we're on the road so much,'' said Moore, who
invited Franchitti to spend a week at his family's home near
Vancouver, British Columbia, before last season's Molson Indy,
``it's nice to have friends. We're all similar ages and have
similar interests.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The four rarely discuss racing away from the track, instead
preferring to talk about women, golf and just about anything else.
There are exceptions, however, when shop talk is permitted and,
indeed, required: like that final-lap pass on the final turn of the
Long Beach Grand Prix, when Moore overtook Papis.
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes there are friendly wagers within the group, like
the $5 Australian that Franchitti claimed from Moore after taking
the pole position at last year's Surfers Paradise Grand Prix.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I did when I got out of the car was go looking
for Greg,'' Franchitti said. ``He's a very confident sort and he
thought for sure he would win the pole. I enjoy beating them.''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks from now, the Brat Pack will be in Rio de Janeiro, and
Kanaan, who is from that part of Brazil, will be in charge of
showing his guests a good time.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's time to have fun, we have fun,'' Papis said. ``My
philosophy is you better do it the way you drive your race car: 110
percent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
