<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-COL-CATS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNDER SIEGE BY STRAY CATS AND STRANGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; NEW PALTZ, N.Y. _ Robert Feldman, a New Paltz village trustee,
conceded that the Village Board had tried this ruse before:
floating a provocative proposal to force residents to confront a
difficult problem. It's just that none of the proposals had ever
involved killing stray cats.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the idea, and now New Paltz is in the cross hairs
of cat fanciers from up and down the Hudson River Valley. They have
been generous with long-term advice about the village's cat problem
(``educate people'' was a refrain at a recent town meeting), but
short on the kind of here-and-now help that a dozen homeowners in
the Millrock neighborhood are demanding.
</P>
<P>
   The residents say it has been more than a year since a neighbor
began feeding a handful of strays in his yard, and now they say
there may be as many as 100 howling, digging, copulating and
defecating cats shredding flower beds and gardens, chasing away
songbirds and leaving lawns under attack by beetles no longer kept
in check by starlings and cowbirds.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know what to do anymore,'' said Toni Simone, who
lives down the street from where Caleb Roderick, a retired merchant
seaman, holds his cat feedings. Sixteen people showed up for a
hearing last week, two from the village and the rest cat defenders
drawn here by news accounts of the proposed slaughter. They were
clear about their love for cats, but they left their feelings
toward humans a little in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you realize that your children are going to grow up as
harsh-minded as you are?'' Cathy Anderson, a member of Citizens
League for Animal Protection, asked Feldman. Fed up, Feldman
stalked out. (``I don't have to take that kind of abuse,'' he said
later. ``I'm not the president of the United States.'')
</P>
<P>
   Other board members got off no easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are in a supermarket checkout line and you're standing
next to someone with AIDS or someone who is incubating influenza,
would you want to shoot them, too?'' a woman from Woodstock asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think euthanizing cats and shooting people is quite
the same thing,'' Mayor Thomas Nyquist, who was worried about
feline diseases, tried to explain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the same thing, and it's the next thing,'' the woman
interrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you can't control something, you just want to kill it,'' a
third woman interjected.
</P>
<P>
   The outsiders accused residents of exaggerating the problem,
saying that Roderick fed only about 30 cats. Roderick might have
resolved the discrepancy, but he did not answer his door or return
three phone messages left at his house.
</P>
<P>
   But the cat foes had other statistics.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have four bird feeders, and we used to go through 400
pounds of bird seed in a year,'' said Judith Bogdanowicz, a high
school Spanish teacher who lives next door to Roderick. ``This
winter I bought a 40-pound bag down at Agway, and it's rotting into
the feeders.''
</P>
<P>
   Hilda Simon, a naturalist who has written several books on birds
and insects, says the cats have altered the ecological balance of
the neighborhood as birds have fled or been eaten and insects have
proliferated. ``We used to have wrens in our wren house, and robins
and starlings and hundreds of other kinds,'' she said. ``They have
all packed up and left.''
</P>
<P>
   The Village Board could find no easy solution. ``We tried all
the official routes _ the Department of Environmental Conservation,
the State Health Department _ and they all had their jurisdictions
that we weren't part of,'' Feldman said.
</P>
<P>
   In November, the village hired the Citizens League to remove the
cats. Its volunteers took about 35, but then released more than a
dozen back to Roderick. So the board fired the league and played
its gambit, telling local reporters that it was death to the cats.
</P>
<P>
   It worked. A shelter in Middletown called Pets Alive (``We don't
believe in euthanasia as a final solution,'' says its telephone
message) came forward, and has promised to take all the cats away
permanently. By the end of last week, it had collected 12.
</P>
<P>
   But what if new strays replace them? ``We're going to solve the
immediate situation, and we're going to pass a cat law,'' said
Laura Zeisel, another trustee. ``But what I'm concerned about is,
is it all going to start over again later?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
