603-1036.) 
(DW) 
 By DAVID J. MORROW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTE, N.C. _ Some of the nation's largest banks _ including
First Union and Nationsbank _ are based here, solidifying North
Carolina's reputation as the banking state. But if honest North
Carolinians have no trouble finding a bank, neither do bank
robbers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though bank robbery has been declining nationwide, the
crime has become remarkably common here. The state's banks, credit
unions and savings institutions were robbed 289 times last year, a
38 percent jump from 1997.
</P>
<P>
   While numbers are not yet fully reported, North Carolina's rise
in bank robberies last year appears to be near the nation's
highest, according to the FBI, North Carolina had 38.9 for each
million people last year, compared with Illinois and New Jersey,
which had 21 and 11 robberies per million, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   North Carolina's tally was so high that the FBI's field office
in Charlotte, which covers the entire state, ranked fourth
nationwide last year in the number of reported bank robberies,
trailing only Los Angeles, San Francisco and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   While bank officials are concerned about the rising number of
robberies in North Carolina, they have not taken harsh measures to
prevent them. In fact, the banks' friendliness to customers _
revered locally as Southern hospitality _ may increase the
frequency of robberies.
</P>
<P>
   Bank executives say robberies are a hazard of the industry. No
one has a good explanation as to why the number of robberies is up
one year and down the next. ``I don't know how you avoid them,''
Harold T. Keen, president of KS Bank in Kenly, N.C., said. ``This
is not something that happens every month. And you don't want to
have so much security that you inconvenience your customers.''
</P>
<P>
   With so many banks concentrated in its urban areas, North
Carolina has become a modern-day version of the Wild West, where
holding up stage coaches became a national pastime. The two crimes
are remarkably similar, law enforcement officials say, in that they
are sometimes so randomly planned that many criminals settle on a
target on the basis of convenience.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank robbery is a crime of opportunity,'' said Mark Rozzi, a
special agent for the Federal Bureau of Investigation's Charlotte
office. ``The banks in North Carolina have a lot of branches that
pride themselves on being friendly.''
</P>
<P>
   Robbing banks has changed little since Bonnie and Clyde became
household names in the 1930s. Then as now, the number of bank
holdups appeared to have less correlation with the economy's health
than with the personalities of the robbers themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bank robbers are antisocial,'' Dr. Ken Tardiss, a specialist
in violent crime and a professor of psychiatry at the Weill Medical
College of Cornell University, said. ``The economy may be doing
well for some people but not for them. Or they may just want more
money and have a feeling that they deserve it.''
</P>
<P>
   Once a bank robber has experienced the thrill of a holdup, it is
difficult to abandon the glare of a security camera. Some 20
percent of the bank robbers who were convicted nationwide last year
were repeat offenders; two of the most active were in North
Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   One, Mark Vernon Brindell, an unemployed landscaper from Wake
Forest, was sentenced last year to five years in federal prison for
holding up seven banks near Raleigh. The other, Isaiah Belcher III,
was sentenced to 20 years in federal prison for robbing eight banks
near Durham. Between them, Brindell and Belcher committed 5.2
percent of the state's bank robberies in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   While the FBI maintains that there is no stereotypical bank
robber, some crime experts insist that bank robbers are among the
dumbest thugs going. One North Carolina robber several years ago
actually wrote the holdup note on the back of his deposit slip,
while another tried to rob a bank's drive-through window from the
back seat of a taxi.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people are not physicists,'' said Thad Woodard,
president of the North Carolina Bankers Association. ``A lot of
times they are on drugs and need money to support their habit.''
</P>
<P>
   While some robbers do wear disguises, most enter banks wearing
street clothes, hand tellers written instructions and then make
quiet getaways.
</P>
<P>
   But there are exceptions. A masked man entered a KS Bank in
October and wasted little time terrorizing the place. Hopping over
the counter, he pushed the teller aside and yanked open the money
drawer. As he grabbed stacks of bills, he shouted obscenities, bank
officials said, until he leaped back over the counter and fled. He
has yet to be caught.
</P>
<P>
   According to statistics compiled last year by the FBI in North
Carolina, a majority of bank robberies occurred on Fridays between
9 and 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason these robberies happened when they did?'' Rozzi
said. ``The robbers wanted money for the weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI in North Carolina solved 70 percent of the state's bank
robbery cases last year, well ahead of the 60 percent rate in the
rest of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line of this is that bank robberies are just a
foolish crime,'' Rozzi said. ``There are easier ways to get more
money.''
</P>
<P>
   Bank officials balk at releasing amounts taken during robberies,
but crime experts insist that most of the time the loot is
insubstantial.
</P>
<P>
   FBI statistics for North Carolina put the average take last year
at $11,722, slightly above the nationwide average of $9,266, but
the numbers were skewed by several vault robberies. Many robbers
get only a few thousand dollars, bank officials said, since they
take money primarily out of teller drawers.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike most banks in the United States, branches in the
Southeast seldom use common security measures like armed guards or
bulletproof glass to protect tellers. Some bank officials say these
measures would upset customers, who have grown accustomed to
niceties like free coffee and personal greetings by branch
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand that we have a different way of doing
business down here,'' Woodard said. ``Customers don't want to be
frightened or overly stressed by security. Some customers feel so
welcome here that they carry the teller a card or cake on her
birthday.''
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, the banks were prone to a few other mishaps.
Since the average teller nationwide works only six to nine months
before quitting, it is difficult to provide extensive security
training. All too often, law enforcement officials say,
inexperienced tellers are unable to find the marked bills during a
robbery or give the holdup note back when the robber did not ask
for it.
</P>
<P>
   Concerned about the rise in robberies, several banks are
experimenting with new security technology. One program that has
been particularly successful is the $5,000 reward set up by the
North Carolina Bankers Association for information leading to the
arrest and indictment of someone who robbed any of its member
banks. A prime source of information is the robbers' friends and
family.
</P>
<P>
   The new programs appear to be lowering the number of bank
robberies in North Carolina, but law enforcement officials remain
cautious. In a meeting last month with other agents from the FBI's
office in Raleigh, one senior agent, John Werner, noted that the
rising number of bank robberies in the state was beginning to
decline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I may have been speaking for about half an hour,'' Werner
said. ``And by the time I had finished, two more banks had been
robbed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
