<SLUG> BC-R-FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HOW JOHN ELWAY MADE A TATTOO DISAPPEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo and graphic notes; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Chronology of
Elway's late-game comebacks is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   His curse turned into his blessing. As the Denver Broncos'
quarterback in three embarrassing Super Bowl losses, it was as if
John Elway had a tattoo that read, ``Can't win the big one.''
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that the Broncos were not the better team on any of
those three Super Bowl Sundays against the Giants, the Washington
Redskins and the San Francisco 49ers, he was the losing
quarterback. And the losing quarterback always gets the blame.
</P>
<P>
   But all that blame kept John Elway playing when his battered
body would have preferred to surrender. ``I would love another
chance,'' he said before the 1995 season. ``I want to retire a
champion.''
</P>
<P>
   Blessed with two consecutive Super Bowl rings, John Elway will
retire as a champion. Tattoos aren't supposed to disappear, but his
have. And for all of the arrows he has thrown with that archer's
bow of an arm, he made that tattoo disappear two seasons ago in
Super Bowl XXXII in San Diego by scrambling instead of passing.
</P>
<P>
   With the score, 17-17, late in the third quarter, Elway's
obsession to retire a champion was at stake. The Broncos had a
third-and-6 at the 12-yard line, but the Green Bay Packers had just
stuffed Terrell Davis for only a 1-yard gain. If the Broncos didn't
get a first down, they would have to kick a field goal.
</P>
<P>
   Taking the snap in the shotgun formation, Elway retreated beyond
the 20-yard line as he searched for a receiver. Finding none open,
he hurried upfield, then to the right, as he crossed the 10-yard
line.
</P>
<P>
   In another situation, hoping to get the first down, Elway might
have run out of bounds. Or he might have slid, as quarterbacks do
and he usually did. But this was the Super Bowl; this was his
chance to ``retire a champion.'' For all he knew, maybe his last
chance.
</P>
<P>
   Now, as safety LeRoy Butler and linebacker Brian Williams
converged on him, Elway dived for the first down. As the tacklers
hit him, his body whirled like the propeller of a helicopter and he
landed, sprawled, at the 4-yard line. First down.
</P>
<P>
   Two plays later, Davis pounded into the end zone and the Broncos
were ahead, 24-17. The Packers would rally for a 24-24 tie but
after the Broncos had won, 31-24, with Davis scoring three
touchdowns, their teammates pointed to Elway's theatrical first
down as the play that turned the game. And his reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him do that and then get up pumping his fist, I
said, `It's on,' '' tight end Shannon Sharpe said later. ``That's
when I was sure we were going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   And when the Broncos won, that's when the pro football realm was
finally convinced that John Elway was a champion. Until then, all
of his last-minute drives during the season and the playoffs had
been dramatic, and all those completions and all those yards and
all those touchdown passes had merely been impressive.
</P>
<P>
   All those stats hadn't been able to make that tattoo disappear
until the Broncos' owner, Pat Bowlen, lifted the Vince Lombardi
trophy that night at Jack Murphy Stadium and said, ``This one's for
John.''
</P>
<P>
   Even with the tattoo gone, some people sniped that Elway didn't
win until he had Terrell Davis, but that was only a reminder that
in his three earlier Super Bowl losses, he didn't have anybody like
Terrell Davis. Against the Giants, the Redskins and the 49ers, he
was out there alone.
</P>
<P>
   Even the best quarterbacks can't always do it alone.
</P>
<P>
   And then, as if to show that the diamonds in his Super Bowl ring
weren't fake, Elway did it again, this time as a passer. Against
the Atlanta Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII in Miami, he completed 18
of 29 passes for 336 yards, including an arrow to wide receiver Rod
Smith for an 80-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out to be his last roundup. And his best. As a
champion, he's now going out as few of the National Football
League's best quarterbacks have.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the best quarterbacks inspired a championship team, if
not two or three or four title teams, relatively early in their
careers, but most didn't retire from the reigning championship
team. Joe Montana didn't. Terry Bradshaw didn't. Roger Staubach
didn't. Joe Namath didn't. Johnny Unitas didn't. Bobby Layne
didn't. Sammy Baugh and Sid Luckman didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the quarterbacks in the Pro Football Hall of Fame, only
Otto Graham and Norm Van Brocklin decided to stop playing after
having guided their teams to the NFL title in their last season.
</P>
<P>
   Graham led the Cleveland Browns to the 1955 and 1956
championships, then departed. Van Brocklin sparked the Philadelphia
Eagles to the 1960 title, then coached the Minnesota Vikings.
</P>
<P>
   And now Elway, sure to be a first-ballot Hall of Famer when he
is eligible for election in five years, has done what only Graham
did: go out on top with two consecutive NFL rings.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's not the best quarterback ever. To most historians,
Baugh, Graham, Unitas and Montana are on that ``best ever'' level;
take your pick. He's on the next tier, with several others; take
your pick. But he retired a champion.
</P>
<P>
   And that's all John Elway was trying to do in Super Bowl XXXII
when he spun like a helicopter's propeller going for that first
down and made a tattoo disappear.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1917EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
