<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Kenseth wins Auto Club 300
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif._ Matt Kenseth spends much of his time in the
shadow of NASCAR Busch Series competitor Dale Earnhardt Jr.
</P>
<P>
   While Earnhardt has the familiar name, Kenseth is earning the
reputation of the series' best driver. On Saturday, Kenseth took
advantage of Earnhardt's mechanical problems to win the Auto Club
300 at California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, who is expected to jump to Winston Cup racing next
season in a car owned by Cup star Mark Martin, won for the second
time in 10 starts this season, moving within 95 points of Earnhardt
in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very surprising,'' said Kenseth, of Cambridge, Wis. ``I
definitely didn't expect to win this race. I felt like we were a
long, long ways off on the chassis setup. When the race started, we
were extremely loose. I was worried about hanging on until the last
caution, much less winning the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth, 27, took the lead from Elliott Sadler after a restart
on lap 133, 13 laps after Earnhardt spun on the backstretch. In the
final 17 laps, Kenseth was able to hold off Winston Cup points
leader Jeff Burton and Earnhardt, who finished second and third,
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth won the race under caution after Todd Bodine hit the
wall with only two laps remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who lost only five points to Kenseth, wrecked with
only 30 laps remaining. His No. 3 Chevrolet spun out when he tried
to pass the lapped car of Hank Parker Jr. Earnhardt lost a lap
because of the mishap, and then he lost third gear when he went to
the pits for repairs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to figure out a way to get around the lapped
traffic in front of us,'' Earnhardt said. ``We'd run two or three
laps behind (Parker) and he was racing us pretty hard. ... I told
him (after the race) that the next time he races me that hard, it
should be for positions. He wasn't on the lead lap, so he wasn't
going to lose anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing the gear, Earnhardt was able to rally. He
regained his lap from the leaders when another caution was thrown
only four laps after his spin. With 11 laps left, he'd climbed to
third but another wreck caused a restart. Earnhardt was passed by
two cars because of the transmission problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to figure out what's going on with that,'' Earnhardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte quits Busch
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Labonte, fourth in the Winston Cup points standings, will
not drive in another Busch race this year.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte has withdrawn as the Busch driver for the No. 18 Pontiac
owned by former Washington Redskins coach Joe Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
