<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: MILOSEVIC ADVANCES BY YIELDING ON SOLDIERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: This is a late add to page 1 of the New York Times.)  
(lh) 
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ By agreeing to the release of three
captured American soldiers and offering to accept a lightly armed
U.N. peacekeeping force to monitor a peace in Kosovo, President,
Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia has made it clear that he wants a
bombing halt, and that he is ready to deal.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Milosevic is putting NATO, and particularly
Washington and London, on the defensive, forcing the alliance to
confront its real war options: to keep bombing and risk the need to
put in ground troops over the summer to try to remove Milosevic
from office, or to negotiate seriously now to end NATO's first war
in Europe, even if it leaves Milosevic in place.
</P>
<P>
   Through the promised release of the soldiers and the diplomatic
moves, Milosevic is going below the heads of NATO country leaders
to appeal to their publics, who are showing increasing signs of
nervousness about this Nintendo war from the air, now in its sixth
week.
</P>
<P>
   In this effort, Milosevic is aided by the intensifying air war,
which means an increasing number and frequency of accidents, bombed
houses and buses and civilian deaths.
</P>
<P>
   In the last two days alone, residential areas of Belgrade were
bombed by accident and a passenger bus in Kosovo was split in half,
apparently by a NATO missile, reportedly killing 34 people. On
Tuesday, more than 20 people died, half of them children, when NATO
bombed a residential area of Surdulica, near the Bulgarian border.
On Friday, a NATO missile landed in Bulgaria itself.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, treading cautiously, still made exactly
the point Saturday that Milosevic wanted, and that the White House
feared: He called for a bombing halt, and asked Clinton and NATO
``to give peace and reconciliation a chance.''
</P>
<P>
   While the White House might regard the soldiers' release as a
cynical gesture by Milosevic, Jackson said, ``This is a gesture
that should not go ignored,'' and added: ``I hope that the
negotiators on both sides will seize this moment to go back to the
table.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO generals and politicians will argue that it is precisely
the pain of the bombing that is inducing Milosevic to be flexible.
</P>
<P>
   What he offers is not close enough to NATO demands to be taken
as anything but an opening position. He now says he would accept
lightly armed peacekeepers under the banner of the United Nations,
including possibly from NATO countries like Italy, Greece and
Spain.
</P>
<P>
   But NATO insists on a fully armed international force with NATO
troops at its core, a retreat from its prior demand for 30,000 NATO
troops in Kosovo. It is not clear how much more Washington will
bargain.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic is also offering to reduce his security forces in
Kosovo to 11,000; NATO wants nearly all to leave. Milosevic is
offering an internal political solution to Kosovo, leaving out the
Kosovo Liberation Army on the pretense that it has been defeated, a
position Washington is unlikely to accept. And Milosevic wants
Serbian sovereignty over Kosovo, while NATO wants some form of
international protectorate.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides say they want all refugees to return, Yugoslav
officials say the refugees must prove citizenship, even as security
forces rip up identity papers and remove license plates of those
fleeing Kosovo. Over the past two days alone, according to relief
officials, thousands have been driven from Prizren, in southwestern
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The patriotism of the Serbs and Milosevic's conduct of the war
have put pressure on NATO, as well. NATO is more than just
Washington and London, where the rhetoric remains bellicose. The
Greek, Italian, German and even French people are increasingly
anxious about the brutal civilian costs, for the ethnic Albanians
but also for the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   And their leaders are not necessarily happy about the model for
NATO's future that Kosovo, however accidental, seems to represent:
an aggressive arm of American foreign policy, no longer the purely
defensive alliance that kept the peace in Europe during the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   They are also concerned about the reaction of Russia. Europeans
are much closer to Russia, and thus more concerned that Moscow not
isolate itself again or elect a new president after Boris Yeltsin
who is a bigger threat to world peace than Milosevic has ever been.
</P>
<P>
   These Europeans _ as well as new NATO members like Hungary and
prospective members like Romania _ are particularly concerned about
the crisis that Milosevic has created, apparently to NATO's
complete surprise, as Albanians flee to neighboring countries and
even across the Adriatic to Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Milosevic has regionalized the conflict, broadening the issue
from the control of one southern Serbian province of Kosovo to the
political stability of Montenegro, Macedonia, Albania, Bulgaria,
Greece, Italy and even Germany, where the new leftist government,
like the Italian one, finds itself prosecuting a lengthy war it
never much wanted.
</P>
<P>
   These Europeans, who want the abuses in Kosovo to end and the
refugees to go home, are likely to find much sense in what Jackson
says. Most NATO countries, small enough to feel vulnerable, do not
see it as their duty to choose Yugoslavia's leaders or to reopen
the question of postwar international boundaries whenever old
nationality questions rear their heads.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
