<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 05/01/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MIAMI -- May 1, 1999 -- FBN-ANDERSON-COLUMN, 5-01 --
John Elway celebrating the Denver Broncos victory over the Atlanta
Falcons in Super Bowl XXXIII. Blessed with two consecutive Super
Bowl rings, Elway will retire as a champion this year. Most of the
best quarterbacks inspired a championship team, if not two or three
or four title teams, relatively early in their careers, but most
didn't retire from the reigning championship team. (Jose R.
Lopez/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NAZARETH, Pa. -- May 1, 1999 -- CAR-CART-FRIENDS, 5-01
-- From left, the CART drivers Max Papis, 29, Tony Kanaan, 24,
Dario Franchitti, 25, and Greg Moore, 24, all rising stars on the
Championship Auto Racing Teams open-wheel racing circuit, are known
loosely as the Brat Pack. The four are talented drivers who just
happen to be young, single and free to enjoy some of the world's
most stimulating cities, from Miami to Monterey. (Sal DiMarco
Jr./New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ORLANDO, Fla. -- May 1, 1999 -- FLA-SCHOOL-VOUCHER, 5-01
-- Katrina Thompson, 10, a fourth grader, reads a book while she
listens to it on tape at Orlo Vista Elementary School in Orlando.
Orlo Vista is one of four schools that the state has listed as
being critically low performing in reading. If the school fails to
meet state reading standards for the second year, its students will
be offered vouchers to attend any school of their choice. (Todd
Anderson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LAS VEGAS -- May 1, 1999 -- LASVEGAS-MAYORAL, 5-01 -- A
criminal lawyer who has spent a career ``fighting the system from
the outside,'' Oscar B. Goodman, 59, campaigning for election as
mayor of Las Vegas at the Clark County Government Center. ``It's
the first time in my life when I'll be on the inside trying to do
good and keep the government honest,'' he says. ``I intend to treat
Las Vegas as my primary client, with the same passion I've had for
all my less popular clients over the years.'' (John Gurzinski/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) HAGERSTOWN, Md. -- May 1, 1999 -- MD-BASEBALL-DISCRIM-2,
5-01 --Carl Silverman, 43, says that discount promotions like
Church Bulletin Day at the Hagerstown, Md., Suns' baseball games,
at which discounts are given to those who have a bulletin from
their church, discriminate against him as a professed agnostic.
``It irked me that if you bring a church bulletin, you are treated
better,'' says Silverman. ``It discriminates against atheists,
agnostics, humanists, pagans and lots of others, even Christians
who do not go to church.'' (Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) HAGERSTOWN, Md. -- May 1, 1999 -- MD-BASEBALL-DISCRIM-1,
5-01 -- To help fill the seats at the Hagerstown, Md., Suns'
baseball games, the team owner, Winston Blenckstone, holds several
promotion days, like Church Bulletin Day, when discounts are given
to those who have a bulletin from their church. But now, the offer
is under assault as religious discrimination, an accusation that
leaves Blenckstone scratching his head in bewilderment. ``Minor
league baseball is all about promotions,'' says Blenckstone.
(Justin Lane/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) MAAGAN MIKHAEL, Israel -- May 1, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ISRAEL-3,
5-01 --Davor Bakovic, 50, left, with Lamija Jaha, 44, whose parents
sheltered his mother during World War II in Nazi-controlled
Sarajevo. The Jaha family has now been granted refuge in Israel
after being forced out of their home in Kosovo. ``I don't know how
to express how much this means to me,'' says Mrs. Jaha. ``My father
did what he did with all his heart, not to get anything in return.
Fifty years later, it returns somehow. It's a kind of a circle.''
(Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- May 1, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-CLIQUE-2,
5-01 --Courtney Crone and Billy Santoro, sophomores at Chaparral
High School in Scottsdale, eating lunch outdoors at the ``ramada,''
the area for football players and their friends, according to the
rules that map the school's social geography. Some research on high
schools has found that where students fit in the school landscape
determines how they see it. (Jeff Topping/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SCOTTSDALE, Ariz. -- May 1, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-CLIQUE-1,
5-01 --Students gather on the grounds of Chaparral High School in
Scottsdale, where the social geography of the 1,850 students is
clearly mapped out. Adolescence has always been a time of identity
formation, with inclusion and exclusion, trying out new ideas,
styles and friends. Still, like Columbine High School in Littleton,
Colo., and hundreds of other well-regarded suburban high schools,
some students still have difficulty fitting in. (Jeff Topping/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) DENVER -- May 1, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-NRA, 5-01 -- Tom
Mauser, whose son, Daniel, was among those slain at Columbine High
School in Littleton, Colo., at a rally protesting the National
Rifle Association's meeting in Denver on Saturday. The rally drew
some 7,000 protesters. Led by Charlton Heston, the actor who is the
president of the organization, the pro-gun group had spurned calls
from state and local politicians and others to scrap its convention
out of respect for those killed just 10 miles away in Littleton.
(Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) MAAGAN MIKHAEL, Israel -- May 1, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ISRAEL-2,
5-01 -- The certificate of honor issued by the Yad Vashem Holocaust
memorial in Jerusalem, commending the parents of Lamija Jaha,
Dervis and Servet Korkut, both Muslims, for risking their lives to
save Jews during World War II. More than 50 years after her parents
sheltered Jews in their home, the certificate has helped Lamija
Jaha and her family to find refuge in Israel after being forced
from their home in Kosovo. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MAAGAN MIKHAEL, Israel -- May 1, 1999 -- KOSOVO-ISRAEL-1,
5-01 -- Davor Bakovic, 50, right, with Lamija Jaha, 44, whose
parents sheltered his mother during World War II in Nazi-controlled
Sarajevo. The Jaha family has now been granted refuge in Israel
after being forced out of their home in Kosovo. ``I don't know how
to express how much this means to me,'' says Mrs. Jaha, with her
husband Vlaznim, center. ``My father did what he did with all his
heart, not to get anything in return. Fifty years later, it returns
somehow. It's a kind of a circle.'' (Rina Castelnuovo/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) CLEVELAND -- May 1, 1999 -- TRANSPLANTS-2, 5-01 -- Tim
Heidler, 40, whose larynx was crushed in a motorcycle accident in
1978, had to use an electric voice box to speak for 18 years.
Heidler has regained his voice, thanks to a laryngeal transplant in
1998. Reflecting on his role as a human guinea pig, Heidler says,
``The only difference between me and a rat is I can talk and the
rat can't tell you how it feels.'' By last summer, Heidler was
singing. (Terry Clark/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ST. LOUIS -- May 1, 1999 -- TRANSPLANTS-1, 5-01 -- Susan
E. Mackinnon, a plastic surgeon at Washington University in St.
Louis, performs nerve transplants and has done research on the
subject for 20 years. Dr. Mackinnon has called the hand transplant
operation ``dangerous and irresponsible.'' ``All it's going to do
is save a limb, it's not going to save a life. I wouldn't save a
limb for immunosuppression for life.'' (Bill Stover/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
