<HEADER>
A0795 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT &LR;      05-01 0783
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. SAYS G.I. RELEASES WON'T ALTER THE AIR WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Administration and Pentagon officials said Saturday
that the release of the three American prisoners would not alter
the aims or methods of NATO's air war against Yugoslavia, which
continued with an unrelenting intensity made possible by clearer
skies over the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The officials welcomed the announcement that the three soldiers
would be freed on Sunday, but they did so warily lest it fall
through.
</P>
<P>
   They said it was too early to discuss whether NATO would respond
to the soldiers' release with any reciprocal gestures, as Yugoslav
officials suggested they should. The Pentagon announced Saturday
that a second Yugoslav prisoner was now in NATO's custody, but said
nothing about the possibility of a prisoner exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The prisoner, whose name and rank were not disclosed, was
captured by ethnic Albanian rebels in Kosovo and handed over to
Albania's government, which then turned him over to the United
States, the Pentagon's spokesman, Kenneth Bacon, said. Like the
first prisoner, a lieutenant, the soldier was flown to a U.S. base
in Germany.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson, in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, to negotiate
the Americans' release, appealed for a pause in NATO's attacks,
saying the three soldiers were being held in military installations
in or near the Yugoslav capital.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke Saturday to Sandy Berger, the White House national
security adviser, and to Secretary of State Madeleine Albright
after the release was announced.
</P>
<P>
   NATO and Pentagon officials ruled out a pause in the strikes,
but attacks in Belgrade eased overnight Friday, and by midnight the
capital had once again escaped the sort of thunderous barrages that
destroyed several government and military buildings earlier in the
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will persist until our military objectives are met,'' the
National Security Council's spokesman, David Leavy, said.
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's willingness to release the American prisoners came
a day after Milosevic met with Russia's special envoy, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, and offered his own plan for ending the war. U.S. and
NATO officials have dismissed Milosevic's plan, but they
interpreted the recent other events as signs that the Yugoslav
leader's defiance may be weakening.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are enough incidents to suggest that the military
campaign is starting to pinch,'' a senior administration official
said.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's air war entered its 39th day Saturday, U.S. and allied
aircraft struck targets across Yugoslavia. Taking advantage of the
longest stretch of fair weather since the strikes began on March
24, allied warplanes are flying about 600 missions a day.
</P>
<P>
   With the intensification came a new report of civilian
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO missile struck a bus in central Kosovo crossing a bridge
near the town of Luzane, 12 miles north of Kosovo's provincial
capital, Pristina, Serbian officials and witnesses told reporters
who were escorted to the site. There were conflicting reports on
the number of people killed in the attack, but Serbian officials at
the scene told reporters that 34 bodies had been recovered after
the bus was sliced in two.
</P>
<P>
   Bacon, the Pentagon's spokesman, said allied warplanes had not
targeted that bridge. Twelve hours after the first reports of the
attack, officials at NATO's headquarters said Saturday night that
they still could not confirm that an allied aircraft had fired on
the bus.
</P>
<P>
   But the Pentagon said that in addition to striking planned
targets, NATO's warplanes were now attacking targets that emerge
unexpectedly. It is possible the attack on the bus was one of
those.
</P>
<P>
   Overnight, NATO attacked 40 targets that had not been planned,
compared with 31 fixed targets, said Maj. Gen. Charles Wald, a
planner at the Joint Staff Chiefs of Staff.
</P>
<P>
   The ``targets of opportunity'' included such things as tanks,
armored vehicles, artillery batteries and command posts. ``What's
happening now is we're able now to respond faster to targets that
may pop up,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At NATO's headquarters, officials said the raids destroyed nine
radio and television transmission towers around the country and
seven highway and railroad bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``Two nights ago we attacked the brains behind the brutality in
Belgrade,'' a spokesman, Peter Daniel, said, referring to
Thursday's strikes on military and police buildings in the capital,
``and yesterday we went after the nervous system that keeps the
Milosevic machine informed and in touch.''
</P>
<P>
   With some 800 NATO aircraft involved, the strikes against
Yugoslavia are occurring around the clock.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
