</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-INJURY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENGUINS' JAGR DOUBTFUL FOR GAME 6, BUT DEVILS HAVE THEIR OWN
INJURY ISSUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHUCK FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH, Pa _ Jaromir Jagr's status is still uncertain, but
the Devils have health concerns of their own with the injured
center Sergei Nemchinov as they hurtle toward Game 6 against the
Penguins here Sunday with a long-time-no-see objective: to put a
playoff opponent away.
</P>
<P>
   That has not happened for the Devils practically since they won
the 1995 Stanley Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to play a Game 7,'' said Scott Stevens, the
Devils' captain, Saturday after a light workout at Civic Arena,
where the Devils carry a 3-2 lead in the best-of-seven series.
``Anything can happen when it comes down to one game.''
</P>
<P>
   Win this game, win this series, and the Devils may ease some of
the sting lingering from the first-round defeat by Ottawa last
season and the second-round defeat by the Rangers the year before.
</P>
<P>
   The presence of a healthy Nemchinov certainly could not hurt
their chances. The versatile forward, obtained from the Islanders
on March 22, blocked a shot by Jiri Slegr with five minutes left in
Game 5's second period on Friday night. He tried to play early in
the third period, but his bruised left leg would not allow it.
</P>
<P>
   Nemchinov skated Saturday, and his availability for Game 6
apparently will be a pre-game decision. If Nemchinov is unable to
play, Dave Andreychuk would most likely replace him on the line
with Brendan Morrison and Vadim Sharifijanov.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a guy who can play any situation: power play, penalty
killing, any defensive situation you want,'' Stevens said. ``He can
play center, he can play wing. He's a smart player.''
</P>
<P>
   He is not, however, as important to the Devils as Jagr, the
league's probable most valuable player, is to the Penguins. A groin
injury has scratched Jagr from the past four games, and he did not
hold much hope of playing on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils are straining to focus on their playoff path. The
last time they won a post-season series was in the first round in
1997, defeating Montreal. The Devils' last Game 6 triumph on the
road came in the 1994 semifinals at Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the Devils compiled the best road record in NHL history this
season at 28-10-3. The Devils arrived in Pittsburgh riding a crest
of momentum, after giving up two game-tying goals in 13 seconds
Friday before winning, 4-3, for their second consecutive victory in
the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of good things in this locker room right
now,'' center Petr Sykora said. ``We have a big chance to do some
things tomorrow. A Game 7? We don't really think that far. We think
about the next game, the next shift, and keep it rolling.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 1950EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
