A0806 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STARWARS-PARTY02-COX     05-01 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARWARS-PARTY02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Long lines, wet weather put damper on Star Wars party
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ ``The Force'' just wasn't with the folks planning a
three-day Star Wars Celebration in Denver this weekend.
</P>
<P>
   More than 15,000 loyal fans along with wet and windy weather
overwhelmed the Wings Over the Rockies Air and Space Museum. As a
result, lines grew long and patience grew short.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure this has got to be their worst case scenario,'' said
Jonathan MacKnight, as he stood under the sheltering wing of a B52
bomber outside the museum.
</P>
<P>
   Lines of fans waiting to see displays, watch shows and shop for
memorabilia stretched hundreds of yards across muddy fields and
parking lots. Although organizers claim there were 15,000 passes
sold each day, the crowd seemed larger and rumors circulated that
as many as 40,000 people were there on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they didn't expect all these people to show up
at the same time, and of course they didn't expect it to rain,''
MacKnight said. ``This is really pretty bad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Star Wars Celebration was a joint production of the
publishers of Star Wars Insider magazine and Lucasfilms, which is
producing what may be the most anticipated motion picture ever.
``Star Wars Episode I: The Phantom Menace'' premieres Wednesday,
May 19.
</P>
<P>
   Fans from all over the world on Friday and Saturday squeezed
onto the grounds of the museum where the celebration was held.
Friday's weather was horrible with constant hard rain and
temperatures in the 40s, but fan spirits were high.
</P>
<P>
   The weather was a little dryer and warmer Saturday, but the
crowd was larger, and the patience of the fans was beginning to
fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like it one bit,'' said Gerald Reedy of Fort Collins,
Colo. ``It's ironic that this event is being held on an old
military base, but there have been no logistics whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   At 10 a.m. Reedy was near the front of a line three or four
abreast that snaked back at least 100 yards across a muddy parking
lot. He had joined the line two hours earlier and expected to spend
another hour in line before actually making it into the vendors'
area where Star Wars toys, souvenirs and collectibles were on sale.
</P>
<P>
   People in line said they were willing to wait because the
vendors at the celebration had collectible items not available
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be so bad but I was in the same line for three and
a half hours yesterday, and by the time I got through the line they
were all sold out,'' Reedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Alvarado of Chicago abandoned the line after two hours on
Saturday without even reaching the vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was getting close, a vendor's representative came out
with a list of what they had for sale and it was nothing special.
I'm really disappointed,'' Alvarado said.
</P>
<P>
   Others complained that the event was poorly planned and that it
should have been held in a much larger indoor venue.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most p. He had joined the line two hours earlier and
expected to spend another hour in line before actually making it
into the vendors' area where Star Wars toys, souvenirs and
collectibles were on sale.
</P>
<P>
   People in line said they were willing to wait because the
vendors at the celebration had collectible items not available
anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wouldn't be so bad but I was in the same line for three and
a half hours yesterday, and by the time I got through the line they
were all sold out,'' Reedy said.
</P>
<P>
   Sean Alvarado of Chicago abandoned the line after two hours on
Saturday without even reaching the vendors.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I was getting close, a vendor's representative came out
with a list of what they had for sale and it was nothing special.
I'm really disappointed,'' Alvarado said.
</P>
<P>
   Others complained that the event was poorly planned and that it
should have been held in a much larger indoor venue.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the most popular events and personal appearances were
held in leaky canvas tents, and few provisions were made for the
thousands of wet fans waiting in lines.
</P>
<P>
   Those lucky enough to actually get into one of the shows or into
the main display area inside the museum were thrilled with what
they saw.
</P>
<P>
   Appearances by actor Ray Park, who portrays villain Darth Maul
in the ``Phantom Menace,'' were one of the hot ticket events.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was awesome,'' said Rick Towne of Omaha, Neb. ``He
basically showed us his best stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Park is an international martial arts champion chosen to play
Darth Maul because of his skill as an acrobatic fighter.
</P>
<P>
   Towne said Park easily demonstrated standing back flips and
no-hands cartwheels. ``And then he did this move where he flattens
out and flips sideways one and a half turns,'' Towne said. ``He was
pretty modest though. One of the ladies asked him to take his shirt
off and he declined.''
</P>
<P>
   About half the people attending the first two days of the
celebration were men in their early 20s or late teens.
</P>
<P>
   But also prevalent in the crowd were families where two or three
generations traveled to Denver to take part in the Star Wars hoopla
together.
</P>
<P>
   Lienor Maldonado from the Yakima Valley in Washington said she
took her son Esteban to see the original Star Wars movie when he
was about four years old.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he has paid my way to come here to Denver as a Mother's
Day present,'' Maldonado said. ``Since I took him to the movie
first, I think it's only fair.''
</P>
<P>
   David Bullat of San Diego said he's been taking his son to Star
Wars events for years. Now David Bullat II is 18 and can at least
share some of the driving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went up to Mann's Chinese Theater when the re-release of
Star Wars came out a few years ago,'' the younger Bullat said.
``I'm the real fan, but this is something we can enjoy doing
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Ellie Lowe, 2, was still in her pajamas huddled under blankets
in a stroller while her father, Tony, waited in line to get into
the vendors' area.
</P>
<P>
   Her nose was a little runny, and she was obviously spending most
of her time dosing.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked why she and her father had come across town to
wait in line so long, young Ellie pumped a tiny triumphant fist in
the air.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stah Wuhz!'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
