<HEADLINE>
EXPOS HAVE EX-FANS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Dodgers arrive in Montreal on Sunday
night they should not expect much of a reception. Wednesday night's
game between the Expos and San Francisco Giants drew a season-low
4,998, a little less than Tuesday's 5,202 total.
</P>
<P>
   It was the eighth straight game in which the Expos have drawn
under 10,000, raising speculation they will move to Northern
Virginia despite civic efforts to keep the club in Montreal.
Through 12 dates, the Expos are averaging 11,489, but that includes
an opening-day crowd of 43,918. Since the first game, the average
is 8,541.
</P>
<P>
   The cost-cutting Expos were able to keep manager Felipe Alou
from joining the Dodgers last winter by giving him $6 million for
three years and appealing to his sense of loyalty. But attempts to
build a new downtown ballpark appear to have failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This club can't stay (in Montreal) under these
circumstances,'' said Alou, who has spent 25 years with the Expos.
``We need to have a new stadium and a bigger payroll. People want
to blame the fans for a lack of support, but you can't keep letting
players get away and expect the fans to keep coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   Alou said he has no regrets about passing on the Dodgers offer.
</P>
<P>
   ``My promise here to these fans is to stay here and try to
develop this young club. I made that promise and I'd like to keep
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lefties for lunch: Against Randy Johnson last Sunday, Tony Gwynn
struck out twice, just his third two-strikeout game since Sept. 20,
1996 _ two against Johnson and one against Kevin Tapani of the
Cubs. Gwynn's hitting streak ended after 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   In his career, Gwynn is 0 for 8 with four strikeouts against
Johnson. That doesn't count a 1-for-6 effort in last year's
National League Division Series, with the one hit a double that led
to the first run in the Padres' 2-1 defeat of Houston in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn became just the third left-handed batter to start against
Johnson this season, after Atlanta pitcher Tom Glavine and
Philadelphia first baseman Rico Brogna. Atlanta pinch-hitter
Randall Simon (groundout) is the only other lefty to bat against
Johnson. From 1994-98, left-handed hitters batted just .197 against
Johnson. They were 0 for 11 against him this season entering
Friday's start against Milwaukee.
</P>
<P>
   Cookin' at home: The Braves' Brian Jordan says part of the
reason he's off to the hottest start of his career is being at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the weekend, Jordan, who makes his home in the Atlanta
suburb of Alpharetta, was hitting .347 with six homers and 21 RBI,
one shy of the league lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan also credits the workout program he follows each winter
with trainer Bob Kersee, husband of former Olympian Jackie
Joyner-Kersee, for getting him into baseball shape, rather than
football condition.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting behind Mark McGwire last season, Jordan hit a
career-high 25 homers and drove in 91 runs, 13 RBI shy of matching
his 1996 career high.
</P>
<P>
   ``(McGwire) cleaned the bases a lot,'' Jordan said. ``I could
have produced a little more, there's no question my RBI total could
have been better. But you've got to have somebody who can run in
front of you too. My doubles wouldn't score (McGwire) from first,
where my doubles will score Chipper (Jones) now. I don't know what
to expect, I don't know what my potential is. Hopefully I'll just
get better every year.''
</P>
<P>
   Solid start: Giants pitcher Joe Nathan pitched seven shutout
innings in his major-league debut April 21 against Colorado, then
followed that Wednesday by going eight innings in Montreal,
allowing seven hits and two runs during a 4-3 victory. He gave up
three hits and two runs in the first inning. He has a 1.20 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan, who replaced injured Mark Gardner in the Giants
rotation, pitched just two years in the minors before this season.
He was drafted by the Giants as a shortstop in 1995. He took all of
the 1996 season off when the Giants told him he should forget about
being a position player and concentrate on pitching. His fastball
has been clocked at 97 mph.
</P>
<P>
   Hurting in Houston: First Moises Alou. Then rookie catcher Mitch
Meluskey. Now shortstop Ricky Gutierrez is the third Houston
starter to go down to injury.
</P>
<P>
   Meluskey went on the DL on Monday after his shoulder popped as
he was swinging through a batting-practice pitch. Less than 24
hours later, the Astros lost Gutierrez to a fractured left hand.
Gutierrez, hitting .357, was hit by a pitch from Arizona's Armando
Reynoso during the fourth inning Tuesday night and is expected to
miss four to six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Out of control: After coming out of Tuesday's game after just
four innings because he got too close to his prescribed pitch count
of 85, right-hander Alex Fernandez went back into the Marlins
clubhouse, picked up a baseball bat and threw it at one of the four
television sets that hang from the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   The bat merely nicked the TV screen, however, and ended up
lodged in one of the ceiling tiles. ``That's really why I took him
out,'' Marlins manager John Boles joked. ``He didn't have any
control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
