<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: DUELING MOUNT RUSHMORES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to update and rewrite; some material repeated from earlier
version, but column is essentially new.)  (lh) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Bob Baffert's dream died. D. Wayne Lukas went
to heaven. It was the latest chapter in a compelling tale of
dueling egos, of two striking, media-savvy trainers who have carved
their profiles into the consciousness of a fading sport that was
crying out for a Rushmore of stars.
</P>
<P>
   The 1990s standing is final: Lukas won his third Kentucky Derby
of the decade Saturday, fourth overall, and Baffert failed in his
bid for an unprecedented third straight. While Lukas was exhorting
Cat Thief down the stretch, Charismatic burst past Cat Thief and
Worldly Manner to win the 125th Derby at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   Upon realization that his other horse had won and Cat Thief was
third, that he had gone from Hall of Fame election earlier in the
week to the Derby's winner's circle, Lukas looked as if he had
bought a winning lottery ticket more than the many who had trained
a champ. He would take it, though, and he would take credit for it,
because that's what coaches do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Best training job I ever did, this and Grindstone,'' the
one-time high school basketball coach said, dressed impeccably in a
dark blue suit, with the purple silk hankie standing stiffly in the
pocket.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1990s, Lukas, 63, had a run of six straight Triple
Crown victories and 7-of-8, then the silver-haired Baffert came
along with his golden touch to win the last two Derbies and
Preaknesses. In the expanding universe of entertainment and sports,
from the R-rated professional wrestling to the made-for-television
X Games, it makes sense that celebrity trainers who look as if
they've walked out of the opera more than a smelly barn have become
the marketing rage.
</P>
<P>
   This is a sport where the horses tend to sound alike and the
jockeys, for all their courage and skill, are existentially cast in
supporting roles. Trainers are the college basketball and football
coaches of thoroughbred racing. They represent The Program, the
continuum, as the horses pass in and out of prominence every few
years.
</P>
<P>
   Is there any coincidence that Lukas, who counts Bobby Knight
among his close friends, insists that his hefty stable of assistant
trainers address him as Coach? He refers to his ``system'' when he
talks about all the places he can't possibly be and the men who
implement his training techniques at a half-dozen tracks.
</P>
<P>
   If the recent dominance of Lukas and then Baffert suggests
anything, it is that the next wave of aspiring super-trainers had
better be part entrepreneur, part showman. They had better be good
recruiters, and jugglers, too. Trainers have always served
different masters, the way a college coach works for the school and
the shoe company. So you have these strange sports settings, such
as Lukas trying to root home a Derby winner with one owner, then
turning around to celebrate with another.
</P>
<P>
   ``You talk about being in a spot,'' he said. ``I'm standing
there with my closest friend, Bill Young, and we think we've got
Cat Thief winning the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Go figure. The next thing Lukas knew, he was hugging Robert and
Beverly Lewis, Charismatic's owners, while Baffert was living out
the axiom of yet another famous coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pat Riley said that when you compete at the championship
level, there's only winning and misery,'' Baffert said, his sad
eyes hidden behind his customary country-club cool shades. ``We
don't know how to act. We're sort of lost souls.''
</P>
<P>
   He had to settle for Friday's victory in the Kentucky Oaks with
Silverbulletday. His three horses, General Challenge, Prime Timber
and the touted filly Excellent Meeting, never threatened. Baffert
could only blame the luck and long odds of a 19-horse Derby field.
</P>
<P>
   It is no longer realistic for the big-time trainer to stake
one's Triple Crown season on a horse or two. There used to be four
Derby preps, and now there are 10. As Nick Zito, the New York
trainer and two-time Derby winner said, ``If you run strong in one
of them, how do you not come to the Derby?''
</P>
<P>
   That's a long way from what Charlie Whittingham believed. The
training legend who died last week at 86 waited a quarter-century
between Derby appearances after finishing ninth and vowing he would
not return until he had a horse who could win. At the age of 73, he
came back and won with Ferdinand in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Whittingham, from the very old school, from a time when the best
horse trainers looked like, well, trainers, was known as the Bald
Eagle and for his less polished lines than our contemporary
basketball geniuses. As even Lukas admitted that he had
underestimated this 31-1 long shot, right down to Charismatic's
final Derby strides, he may have recalled an old Whittingham
favorite: ``Don't say anything bad about a horse until it's been
dead for 10 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Lukas didn't. Instead, he remembered someone commenting to
Whittingham early last winter at Santa Anita that the great and
powerful Lukas was having a particularly poor week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Charlie told the guy, `Let sleeping dogs lie,''' said Lukas on
the day he put Bob Baffert's dream of three straight Derbies to
rest.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
