<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUKAS BACK IN WINNER'S CIRCLE WITH AN UNLIKELY LONG SHOT 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Bob Baffert missed his date with horse racing
history Saturday when none of his three horses ran in the money
while D. Wayne Lukas' 31-1 long shot, Charismatic, won the 125th
running of the Kentucky Derby by a neck over Menifee, and by less
than one length over Cat Thief.
</P>
<P>
   This was a drama with subplots that never materialized. For the
21st consecutive year, favorites lost: the filly Excellent Meeting
finished fifth and her entrymate General Challenge, winner of the
Santa Anita Derby, ran 11th. Baffert's third horse, Prime Timber,
ran fourth.
</P>
<P>
   The mystery horse Worldly Manner, who trained but did not race
in Dubai, ran seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The two fillies trying to outrun 17 colts also struck out:
Excellent Meeting, added to the race by Baffert only the day before
the Derby, and Three Ring, who finished last in the field of 19. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many horses,'' Baffert said. ``The race was decided on the
first turn. But you can't win 'em all.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Baffert tripped on the threshold of history when he was
shooting for his third straight Derby success, the story still was
spiced with melodrama, and redemption for his rivals. It started
with Lukas, who was replaced as king of the Triple Crown trainers
when Baffert came out of California in 1997 and won with Silver
Charm, then again in 1998 with Real Quiet.
</P>
<P>
   But this week Lukas roared back. Four days ago he was elected to
racing's Hall of Fame after some dispute over how long he had
worked as a thoroughbred trainer. And Saturday, before 151,051
spectators on a sparkling spring day at Churchill Downs, he struck
Derby gold for the third time in five years and the fourth time in
his career when his 3-year-old stars ran first and third in
America's most prestigious horse race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I probably never misjudged a horse early in his career as much
as Charismatic,'' Lukas said with some cheery chagrin. ``He looked
like he wanted to be a fat horse who would run every two weeks. I
thought, `If we get away with this, we ought to get out of the
business.'''
</P>
<P>
   Melodrama also accompanied the winning jockey, Chris Antley, who
overcame publicized drug problems in the late '80s to win the 1991
Derby on Strike the Gold. Since then, he has suffered more personal
problems, most recently a struggle to gain control of his weight.
But he returned to racing with new discipline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wayne asked me to ride,'' Antley said. ``I said I was open. I
told my father, I have a goal in life. Miracles were made.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was Charismatic, a well-bred son of Summer Squall.
Charismatic had lost seven straight times before he won the
Lexington Stakes at nearby Keeneland two weeks ago. And during his
losing streak, Charismatic was offered as a claimer who might have
been taken by anyone willing to risk a relatively few dollars.
Saturday he won the $1.1 million Kentucky Derby in his 15th start.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For his owners, Beverley and Bob Lewis of Los Angeles, there was
redemption. In the 1996 Derby they ran the filly Serena's Song, who
led for a mile before fading to 16th. But they won the race the
next year with Silver Charm, trained by Baffert.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought a few times, maybe we ought to quit paying the
bills for this horse,'' Bob Lewis said.
</P>
<P>
   The horse now will be able to pay his own bills. He won the
first prize of $886,200, and he returned $64.60 for a $2 bet to
win, the third largest payoff in Derby history. He also did it
before the second-largest crowd in Derby history _ only the 100th
Derby in 1974, attended by 163,628, drew more. And the entrants
were considered so evenly matched that strange betting patterns
resulted: the favored entry, Excellent Meeting and General
Challenge, went off at 4.8-1, the longest odds for any favorite in
Derby history.
</P>
<P>
   Another young star, Menifee, winner of the Blue Grass Stakes
three weeks ago, made a gallant late run through the homestretch
and missed catching Charismatic by inches. After half a mile, he
was far back, in 17th place. After one mile, 12th. In the stretch,
still sixth in traffic. But he closed like a rocket, losing by the
length of Charismatic's chestnut neck.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the second year in a row that Elliott Walden trained
the runner-up in the Derby. Last year his Victory Gallop ran second
to Real Quiet in both the Derby and the Preakness, but outran him
in the Belmont Stakes and for the second straight year kept Baffert
from sweeping the Triple Crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the widest horse on the first turn,'' Walden said.
``And Pat Day had to wait for room before he finally got him
moving. He ran big, but just got beat. In a 19-horse field,
anything can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   For the first three-quarters of a mile, wild drama was suggested
by the pace-setter, Valhol, the colt who won the Arkansas Derby at
odds of 30-1 and then became embroiled in a controversy over
whether his jockey had used an electrical device to get him to run
faster. Charismatic raced no better than seventh down the
backstretch. But after they had run a mile, Cat Thief took the
lead, Charismatic moved up to third place and Valhol faded to 15th
place.
</P>
<P>
   The stretch looked like a cavalry charge, with Cat Thief a
half-length in front of Charismatic, and Worldly Manner next,
despite the unusual training methods of his owner, Sheik Mohammed
bin Rashid al-Maktoum of Dubai. And as they flashed across the
wire, Charismatic had his neck in front of the hard-charging
Menifee, who had three-quarters of a length on Cat Thief.
</P>
<P>
   Charismatic ran the mile and one-quarter in 2:03 1/5, the
slowest time since Go for Gin's winning time in 1994. But he paid
such huge odds that he created a an exacta payoff, with Menifee, of
$727.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how to act,'' Baffert said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't have any luck. We're sort of lost souls.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
