<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Ligtenberg biding time with elbow
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sighting a long-lost friend across the clubhouse, John
Rocker walked up to Kerry Ligtenberg Saturday afternoon, pointed at
Ligtenberg's atrophied right arm and observed, ``Nice noodle, dude.
Your arm was bigger than that when you were 9 years old.''
</P>
<P>
   Welcome back, pal. One month after undergoing ligament
transplant surgery in his right elbow, Ligtenberg dropped by for an
exam by team orthopedist Joe Chandler and a spin on the treadmill
in the workout room, biding time until he feels half-human again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't really do much,'' he said. ``When I'm at least able to
play catch, it'll feel like I can do something. It's like Joe just
said. Just sit back and don't do anything stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of returning to his Minnesota home, he has decided to
remain in Atlanta with his new wife, Sara, and pursue his physical
therapy program here. Though he plans to be a more frequent visitor
now, he has stayed away from the clubhouse. Ryan Klesko had even
taken over Ligtenberg's locker, which is next to his, as a junk
overflow and removed it with apologies.
</P>
<P>
   Though Ligtenberg still cannot straighten his arm, Chandler
feels he's slightly ahead of schedule in recovery, given his range
of motion. Ligtenberg never could straighten his arm completely,
due to some calcium build-up in the elbow and is expected to have a
completely refurbished joint when his recovery is complete.
</P>
<P>
   For now, he works out on a treadmill, trains to keep his right
shoulder strong and loosens his elbow with whirlpool therapy. He
still eats, brushes his teeth and combs his hair left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   Now at third base
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones was back in the lineup Saturday night after a game
off for a jammed right ankle. Manager Bobby Cox left open the third
hole in the lineup until batting practice, but Jones was already
adamant about playing.
</P>
<P>
   Friday marked the second game Jones had missed in a week, after
sitting out Monday's game in Florida with a sore adductor in his
left leg. Though Jones is carrying 10 extra pounds after an
extensive offseason weight-lifting program, he maintained his new
size is not related to the two problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're going to turn (an ankle) over,'' he said, ``you're
going to turn it over regardless.''
</P>
<P>
   But two games' absence in one week is noteworthy for Jones, who
has sat out just seven games the last two years. He had not missed
two in the same week since opening the 1996 season on the disabled
list and sitting out the first four games following arthroscopic
knee surgery.
</P>
<P>
   The day after
</P>
<P>
   John Smoltz's first career one-hitter was still the subject of
clubhouse conversation one day after his 3-0 victory Friday night.
It took him 323 career starts to achieve it, but that reinforces
the difficulty of the feat. Neither Greg Maddux or Tom Glavine has
ever thrown a nine-inning, one-hit shutout.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if he had ever seen Smoltz throw a better game, catcher
Javy Lopez said, 'I've seen him that good once. It was in San Diego
(in 1996) when he almost had a no-hitter.''
</P>
<P>
   Walt at rest
</P>
<P>
   Ozzie Guillen made his third start of the year at shortstop
while Walt Weiss was given a night off. Weiss finished April
uncharacteristically with three errors in his last three games and
wound up with five misplays in the first month. He committed just
12 errors in 96 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
