<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IS THE RISING SUN SETTING?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It wasn't a good first month for many of
baseball's Japanese players.
</P>
<P>
   Hideo Nomo, who electrified fans just four years ago as the ace
of the Dodgers pitching staff, was released by two teams and
finally signed with the Milwaukee Brewers on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Hideki Irabu, who won 13 games last season for the World Series
champion New York Yankees, was chastised by Yankees owner George
Steinbrenner for poor work habits and buried in the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Masato Yoshii, Nomo's teammate in Japan and last year with the
New York Mets, has nearly pitched himself out of the starting
rotation.
</P>
<P>
   In Tuesday's 6-2 loss to San Diego, Yoshii allowed four runs on
six hits in just 4.2 innings. Yoshii's earned run average rose to
7.52. In 20 innings, he has allowed 25 hits and 17 runs.
</P>
<P>
   If ever there was a time this tradition-laden sport might
re-evaluate its interest in Japanese baseball, this might have been
it. After all, before Nomo there hadn't been a Japanese-born player
in the major leagues since the mid-1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, clubs are maintaining a strong presence in Asia. And
now teams aren't just looking at pitchers. Outfielders Hideki
Matsui and Alejandro Quezada are names to remember. It's clear no
one is willing to give up so quickly on one of the game's final
frontiers.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you go to a game over there, there are more major-league
scouts than ever,'' said Acey Kohrogi, Dodgers director for Asian
operations. ``It's probably harder than ever to get a player out of
Japan, but the feeling is it is definitely worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   The first is through the free-agent system, which doesn't kick
in until after a player has completed nine seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Nomo got out through a loophole by retiring first, then signing
in the U.S. But nine years for a pitcher in a sport that demands
you start what you finish leaves them little at the end.
</P>
<P>
   The second is through a new rule implemented this year and
designed to stop players from negotiating directly with
major-league clubs. Irabu went directly to the San Diego Padres,
who gave up players in return. Irabu then decided he didn't want to
play for the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a Japanese player informs their commissioner's office that
they would like to play in the U.S. Major-league teams are notified
and interested parties submit sealed bids. The one that wins has
exclusive rights.
</P>
<P>
   Japanese teams are willing to give up top talent for the same
reason big-league teams do. There is a widening gap between the
rich and poor teams in Japanese baseball. Small-market clubs need
to dump salaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have a lot of similarities there to us here,'' said
Minnesota GM Terry Ryan, who recently visited Japan. ``They have
teams with large payrolls and small payrolls, teams with high
revenues and low revenues. It's eerily similar.''
</P>
<P>
   Nomo's Japanese rights are still owned by his former club, the
Kintetsu Buffaloes, though he says he has no intention of going
back. But arrogance might be all he has left.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Cubs signed him to a minor-league contract after the
Mets released him in spring training. The Cubs wanted him to make
four minor-league starts before making a decision.
</P>
<P>
   And even though they had lost starters Kerry Wood (for the
season) and Kevin Tapani and Jon Leiber to the 15-day disabled
list, the Cubs wanted him to extend his Triple-A tryout a little
longer. Nomo was unwilling. All the Cubs had to lose was $800,000,
and they certainly can use pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our evaluators said other people were throwing better,''
manager Jim Riggleman said. ``(Nomo) was third on our list (at
Triple-A Iowa). The fact that he's a known person, it would have
been a popular decision. But other guys were pitching better.''
</P>
<P>
   After he left the Cubs, Nomo threw for several clubs and
displayed little of the form that made him reach 500 strikeouts
faster than any pitcher in major-league history. Despite a
baseball-wide shortage of pitching, Nomo's years of 200-pitch games
in Japan now appear too big an obstacle to overcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nomo was only so-so,'' said Cleveland pitching coach Phil
Regan after Nomo threw for him last Tuesday in Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians wanted Nomo to go to Triple-A Buffalo or extended
spring training, but the Brewers stepped up Thursday and said he
would be put in the rotation after one minor-league start.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu, meanwhile, has made it back to the Yankees rotation,
although not entirely because of merit. He will take the place of
Roger Clemens, who was placed on the DL because of a hamstring
injury. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
