<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-JOCKEY-625&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTLEY LOSES WEIGHT AND WINS RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Eight months ago, Chris Antley was a
broken-down jockey. His weight had ballooned to 147 pounds, or at
least that was the number he saw when he had the guts to look at
the scale. He had returned home to Columbia, S.C., to live with his
folks. He was lost, and his father, Les, tried to buck him up.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad told me to start another business,'' said the jockey
who was the leading money winner in the United States in 1985 and
the Kentucky Derby winner in 1991 aboard Strike the Gold. ``He told
me, `You don't need to ride.' He was trying to persuade me to ease
up.''
</P>
<P>
   But Antley, now 33, wasn't about to listen. ``I told my father I
have a goal in life, and I'll die trying to get there,'' he
recalled Saturday just minutes after stunning everyone by winning
the Derby again aboard a 30-1 long shot named Charismatic. And he
remembered asking his father this question: ``Wouldn't it just be
neat if I can ride in the Kentucky Derby?''
</P>
<P>
   As Antley recounted this conversation Saturday afternoon, his
voice caught with emotion, and he tried to fight back the tears.
It's a mile and a quarter in the Derby from the starting gate to
the finish line and the winner's circle, but for Antley, and all
his struggles in recent years, it was a much longer route.
</P>
<P>
   He had been a golden-handed rider in New York before shifting to
the California tracks in 1993. For all his success in New York, he
had also encountered suspensions for drugs. And as the 1990s
progressed, he wasn't the elite rider he once was, either.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday Antley had all the answers. He seemed to push a
button on Charismatic in the stretch, and the colt, who was as
lowly regarded as his jockey, barreled down the stretch with
151,051 people roaring them along. Three months ago, Charismatic
was a $62,500 claimer, and Antley was earning the name Forest Gump
for his long-distance runs _ on foot, without a horse in sight _
through his hometown in South Carolina as he tried to lose enough
weight to get back in the business. Overall, from November 1997
until February 1999, the confused and overweight jockey didn't ride
a single mount.
</P>
<P>
   But on the first Saturday in May, however, the Chestnut colt was
wearing the roses and awarding his few backers a $64.60 payoff. His
rider? Well, he was trying to absorb a miracle. ``I'm still kind of
in awe,'' Antley said softly. ``This was a dream. It's a new
beginning for me.''
</P>
<P>
   How did it happen? Both horse and rider were given a second
chance. Just two weeks ago, D.Wayne Lukas sent his unheralded colt
to Keeneland and the Lexington Stakes. The day before that race,
Antley had a mount for Lukas in California. He had finally returned
to Santa Anita, and riding, in February and had put up modest
numbers _ 23 victories in 138 mounts. ``I want you to watch the
Lexington tomorrow,'' Antley remembers Lukas telling him. ``He's
coming around to the top of his game. Tell me what you think and
get back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   When Charismatic romped home by two and a half lengths at 12-1
odds _ with the great Jerry Bailey aboard _ Antley made two phone
calls: first to Lukas, then to Les Antley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going back to the Derby,'' he told his father.
</P>
<P>
   Even as Lukas was focused on winning his fourth Derby and
perhaps wrestling the spotlight back from rival Bob Baffert, the
trainer saw something different, something better in Antley than
when Lukas had passed him over for rides before.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was hungry,'' Lukas said. ``He had a passion to get back
into it. He's always been a great rider _ a great finisher that fit
this horse. But he seemed more interested in his work, more serious
in the morning.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In fact, Antley was starved for more riding success. He dabbled
in the stock market at his folks' home in South Carolina _ he calls
himself a ``long-term day trader.'' But mostly he ran through town,
to the bookstore, for groceries, building up to 25 miles a day. He
sighed when asked his current weight. ``One hundred and fourteen
pounds,'' he said, then smiled proudly.
</P>
<P>
   When he injured his knee before Thanksgiving and was laid up
until Christmas, he found something in himself that hadn't been
there before. It was something that made this Kentucky Derby
victory more rewarding than the Strike The Gold triumph eight years
ago. ``I've had things handed to me and always been able to come
through my career pretty quick,'' he said. ``But this time I
couldn't just come back nonchalant, I had to find the depths of
myself to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   He found something else on Charismatic, a big, fleshy horse,
ironically, that Lukas had worried all week about because he was so
friendly with the feed tub. When Antley turned for home, he bore
down on the chestnut, much the way he had bore down on himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we approached the quarter-pole, I was three or four deep
and was confident,'' he said. ``I hadn't put him down hard yet.
From that point on, it's just a matter of hoping nobody comes and
gets you. There's no use looking back.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
