<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRING LEAVES BRUINS WITH MANY QUESTIONS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ What became apparent to the Bruins during four
weeks of spring practice was obvious to the 2,000 fans who attended
UCLA's final scrimmage Saturday at Spaulding Field.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback situation is murky, the defense has improved,
and a plethora of questions must be answered in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   In the 70-play scrimmage, the offense scored just two touchdowns
and a field goal while the defense held continuously on third down
and repelled several scoring drives.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, coach Bob Toledo reaffirmed his decision to delay
naming a starting quarterback until training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so close, and all five feel they're in the hunt,'' he
said. ``We've got three or four months to make a decision.''
</P>
<P>
   Junior Drew Bennett and redshirt freshman Cory Paus were the
most impressive Saturday. Bennett completed 5 of 9 passes for 47
yards and scored on a 5-yard run. Paus completed 4 of 7 for 60
yards and directed a scoring drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only goal I had this spring was to compete with Drew the
best I could and make it hard for the coaches to decide,'' Paus
said. ``Now, I just have to get better and keep the pressure on
Drew.''
</P>
<P>
   Sophomore Scott McEwan, a Thousand Oaks native, completed 2 of 4
passes for 34 yards. Redshirt freshman Ryan McCann, an Agoura
native who played well in the final week, was 2 of 6 for 10 yards.
</P>
<P>
   And J.P. Losman, the true freshman from Venice who enrolled a
month ago, completed 2 of 4 passes for 9 yards.
</P>
<P>
   The quarterbacks were without their top receivers. Danny Farmer
(volleyball) and Brian Poli-Dixon (wrist) did not play, and Freddie
Mitchell was used sparingly.
</P>
<P>
   The tailbacks looked good. DeShaun Foster rushed for 62 yards
and a touchdown, and Jermaine Lewis gained 47 yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not concerned about the team,'' Toledo said. ``Once we get
the right guys in, we'll be OK. I was concerned (this spring) about
individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   No safe bet: Other than the quarterback position, UCLA's primary
concern is safety. Jason Stephens was solid at one spot, but
neither Eric Whitfield nor Audie Attar emerged as a consistent
performer at the other safety position.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Toledo and defensive coordinator/secondary coach
Bob Field might move a cornerback to safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two candidates are Marques Anderson and Ryan Roques,''
Field said. ``It's something we're contemplating in order to get
our four best (defensive backs) on the field. And unless something
happens otherwise, three of the four best are Marques, Ryan and
(starting cornerback) Jason Bell.''
</P>
<P>
   Recruiting update: Two of UCLA's top recruits _ Sherman Oaks'
Notre Dame defensive lineman Travis Johnson and Bellflower's St.
John Bosco offensive tackle Paul Mociler _ attended the scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said he will visit five schools before deciding and
listed UCLA, USC, Michigan, Ohio State and Florida State as his top
choices.
</P>
<P>
   Mociler listed UCLA, Notre Dame, Stanford, Michigan and USC, and
said UCLA ``is my first choice at this point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 2106EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
