<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-GIANTS-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCRAE'S GRAND SLAM LETS FRANCO RELAX ON HIS DAY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JUDY BATTISTA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Mets seemed to have been grinding and churning
toward John Franco on his day, overcoming all manner of potential
disappointment, setting up what would have been a poetic conclusion
to an afternoon of honor for their reliever.
</P>
<P>
   As Franco sat in the bright sunshine of the Mets' bullpen,
watching yet another video tribute to him, he awaited the call that
everyone in Shea Stadium figured would come. Instead, Franco saw
Brian McRae blast a 1-0 fastball over the right-field fence in the
seventh inning. The grand slam, the Mets' first of the season, blew
open a close game and helped send the Mets to a 9-4 victory over
the Giants.
</P>
<P>
   Franco went home with a new motorcycle and the Mets (15-9)
walked away with their fourth victory in a row, and second straight
over the Giants (16-9), who had entered the series with the best
record in the National League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good teams don't always have to play good to win,'' McRae
said. ``It was good to add some runs because you look at the way
the Giants were swinging the bats, they were going to get back in
it. We're finding ways to win when we're not playing our best
ball.''
</P>
<P>
   Until McRae's shot gave the Mets an 8-2 lead, it seemed very
likely that they would need Franco to stave off any damage before
this victory dissolved. There were passed balls and wild throws and
hit batsmen. The Mets' starting pitcher, Orel Hershiser (2-2),
struggled almost from the moment he took the mound. He made an
error on a wild pickoff throw in the first inning _ he later called
his outing a war _ and the Mets at times struggled behind him.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had a 1-0 lead after Edgardo Alfonzo launched a home
run over the left-field bullpen in the first inning, but the Giants
took a 2-1 lead in the next inning on two Met fielding plays that
make managers wince.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on first and second, and one out, the Giants' Rick
Aurilia singled to left. Charlie Hayes lumbered from second base
and had barely rounded third when left fielder Matt Franco threw
home for what appeared to be a play at the plate. Catcher Todd
Pratt mishandled the ball, and Hayes scored, tying the score. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the next at-bat, with runners at the corners, pitcher Chris
Brock (2-2) hit a grounder to second base that Alfonzo fielded. But
Alfonzo hesitated, failing to either tag Aurilia in the base path
or throw to second to start a potential double play. Aurilia
advanced to second, and Brent Mayne scored the second run of the
inning on the out at first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I should have made the play,'' Alfonzo said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good it happened early in the season when we didn't need
it, instead of late. Next time I'll make that play. Once in a while
we're going to have a tough game like that. You don't give up in
the first few innings.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   They didn't. In the third inning, Pratt threw out Armando Rios
trying to steal second and the Giants could not score. In the
bottom of the third, the Mets rallied with two out after Brock
walked Roger Cedeno. Consecutive singles by Alfonzo, John Olerud
(who has reached base in all 24 games this season) and Robin
Ventura added two runs, giving the Mets a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were lacking the big bat of the injured Barry Bonds
and could not come back. Hershiser settled in just enough to hold
the lead, the Mets produced another run in the sixth and then came
McRae's bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a long season, and you're going to have games like
that,'' Ventura said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not look pretty, but you're going to have a lot of
them and you better win them. Offensively you have to make sure
everybody is going to have good at-bats. You know you're grinding
and every at-bat is important and everybody can't try to hit a home
run.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 2123EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0239 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 21:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0825 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FAMILYREAX02-COX     05-01 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAMILYREAX02-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Families hopeful as POWs release negotiated
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Will they come home?
</P>
<P>
   The families of three American prisoners of war being held in
Yugoslavia could only hope and wait Saturday after learning that
the Rev. Jesse Jackson apparently had negotiated the release of
their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting for the big call that they're on the bus and on
their way out,'' said Vivian Ramirez, the mother of 24-year-old
Staff Sgt. Andrew Ramirez, at a news conference in Los Angeles. She
said she planned to watch television reports all night and ``wait
with the phone next to me ... until they call.''
</P>
<P>
   In Huntsville, Texas, the reaction was much the same from the
family of 22-year-old Spec. Steven Gonzales. ``We're just
overwhelmed emotionally at the moment,'' said the soldier's mother,
Rosie Gonzales. ``God just keeps answering our prayers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Smiths Creek area of Michigan, the family of 25-year-old
Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone remained secluded. But a friend and
spokesman, Army National Guard Major James McCrone, said Stone's
father, stepmother and two sisters are relieved but ``trying to
keep everything in perspective.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not out of there yet,'' McCrone added. `` As soon as they
know for sure that he is on the way out, they'll feel a lot better.
But they are very excited, very optimistic.''
</P>
<P>
   Stone's wife, Tricia, is ``packed and ready to go'' once her
husband is released, said Lisa McKinney, her stepmother. Tricia and
the couple's 4-year-old son, Ryan, have been staying with McKinney
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The caution of the families equalled that of Clinton
administration officials in their initial responses to the
announced release. President Clinton declined comment to reporters
enroute to play golf in Virginia. His national security adviser,
Sandy Berger, said the release of the soldiers would be ``a
positive development.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, Gonzales and Stone were captured while patrolling the
Yugoslavia-Macedonia border March 31, seven days after President
Clinton initiated a NATO bombing campaign to force a peace treaty
between Yugoslavian President Slobodan Milosevic and ethnic
Albanians in the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Since their capture and their display on Yugoslavian television
- all three appeared to have been beaten - the soldiers'
communities have kept vigil in remarkably similar ways. Homes and
schools in their neighborhoods have been bedecked with yellow
ribbons, as a reminder of their plight.
</P>
<P>
   All three families learned of Jackson's apparent success in
freeing the POWs from the Pentagon and media reports. None heard
directly from Jackson, who expects to depart from Belgrade with the
soldiers Sunday and travel to Croatia with his delegation of
religious leaders.
</P>
<P>
   Pentagon spokesman Ken Bacon said Saturday night that, if they
are released, the three men will go by bus to Zagreb, Croatia where
an Air Force jet will be waiting. From there, they will be flown to
Ramstein Air Force Base in Germany where they will be reunited with
their families. ``We will do everything we can ... to get the POWs
out quickly,'' said Bacon.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian Ramirez said the first news reports she heard of
Jackson's success frightened her. ``I got scared,'' she said. ``I
said I cannot really believe the news. I have to hear it from
someone else.'' She telephoned the Pentagon and was told to ``pack
my things.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Jackson, she said, ``He is a life saver. He will be my hero
when he brings my little Andy home. I really do thank him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Wow, I've never liked Jesse Jackson so much in my life,'' said
Terri Sumrall, a friend and former high school classmate of
Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
   Sumrall, now a senior at the University of Texas in Austin, said
Gonzales looked well in a television appearance with Jackson in
Yugoslavia on Friday. ``It was good to see him smiling and in good
spirits,'' she said. ``I expected so much worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, Vivian Ramirez said her son looked a little thin but
otherwise healthy. She said the first thing she will do when she
sees him will be to cry, then hug him ``and I will not let go.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
