<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 21:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0829 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN     05-01 0942
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLY PLAYOFFS CAN SAVE SEASON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Still waiting for this shortened season to become
relevant?
</P>
<P>
   Here we are in the final few days of the 50-game year, and it
seems like the only suspense revolved around whether the Lakers
would ever get their act together.
</P>
<P>
   OK, maybe that question was really answered last month.
</P>
<P>
   As the season concludes, it's painfully evident only the
playoffs can rescue the league. So let's take a peek at how these
brackets really match up.
</P>
<P>
   There is still a little bit of jockeying to be done here, such
as whether Utah or Portland will enjoy home-court advantage
throughout the playoffs, but things should stay fairly intact. &QL; 
WESTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   Utah vs. Sacramento: The Jazz won the season series 2-1, while
the Kings are just thrilled to be here. Next.
</P>
<P>
   Lakers vs. Houston: Only homecourt is up in the air, with Lakers
owning it today. The Lakers won the series 2-1, but were routed in
final meeting. The teams' dislike for each other will make this a
great first-round matchup. Remember, Rockets eliminated Lakers in
1996, despite being lower seed.
</P>
<P>
   Portland vs. Minnesota: The Blazers swept T'Wolves 3-0 in
regular season, and without Stephon Marbury or Tom Gugliotta, this
should also go three-and-out.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio vs. Phoenix: It just seems like these guys play each
other every season. The regular-season series tied 2-2, and the
Spurs could be in danger of an early exit, especially with Jason
Kidd looking like the league's MVP. &QL; 
EASTERN CONFERENCE
</P>
<P>
   Miami vs. New York: The Heat lead the regular-season series 2-1,
but the bookies in Manhattan are more concerned about how many
fights will take place. Knicks might be overtaken by Charlotte if
they stumble this week.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta vs. Detroit: The Hawks have become a post-lockout
success story, but Detroit won two of three meetings. Atlanta is
hot, having won seven of its past eight games, nearly overtaking
Indiana for the Central Division title.
</P>
<P>
   Indiana vs. Milwaukee: The Pacers should make a run to the NBA
title, and swept the season series 3-0. But throw in their
unimpressive 15-7 record at home, and this could be a land mine.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando vs. Philadelphia: Sixers won series 2-1, but Chuck Daly
has figured out how to make shooting guards Penny Hardaway, Darrell
Armstrong and Nick Anderson happy. He's starting all three of them.
</P>
<P>
   Mailman keeps delivering: The last time Phoenix played at Utah,
Karl Malone fouled Luc Longley so hard the Australian suffered a
hyperextended knee and missed seven games.
</P>
<P>
   The encore took place Monday, when the Jazz again hosted the
Suns. Longley's backup and buddy, Joe Kleine, took a hard elbow
from Malone as Malone put up a shot near the basket.
</P>
<P>
   No foul was called on either Malone or Kleine, but Kleine's face
was a bloody mess. He stalked down court, caught up with Malone,
yelled at him and gave him a shove, streaking Malone's jersey with
blood.
</P>
<P>
   Kleine was called for a technical, and Malone had to leave the
floor to change his jersey. Kleine probably wished he had gotten
off so easily.
</P>
<P>
   He was taken to Lakeview Hospital in nearby Bountiful, where Dr.
Richard Kjar, a plastic surgeon, used 30 stitches to repair
Kleine's lower lip. He also had to be checked for a broken nose.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karl showed zero remorse,'' Phoenix coach Danny Ainge said.
``All he's done is bash Joe and Luc Longley. All he does is play
dirty and show no remorse for the players he leaves injured on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   Malone pleaded ignorance to the incident: ``I was going to the
basket and he stuck his nose in there.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton lets off steam: After the Sonics got trashed by the Trail
Blazers on Wednesday, Payton was overheard in the locker room
cursing to his agent, Aaron Goodwin, about Seattle's sorry season.
</P>
<P>
   Goodwin told Payton to calm down because general manager Wally
Walker was close by. Payton responded: ``I don't (care) if Wally
hears me.''
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the G-rated version of what he said.
</P>
<P>
   The episode lasted no more than 30 seconds but was turned into
screaming headlines by the Seattle papers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't reported correctly,'' Payton said. ``Frustration is
always going to come out. And I'm frustrated right now about us
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   Payton is apparently also upset that Walker let Jerome Kersey
and Greg Anthony leave, and brought in benchwarmer Billy Owens.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so does Payton want to be traded?
</P>
<P>
   ``I do want to be in Seattle,'' Payton said. ``(The incident)
has nothing to do with it. My contract isn't up until 2003 so I'm
going to be here until then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I'm going to be here until I retire.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting mad: Golden State's normally placid Chris Mills got
into it with Sacramento guard Vernon Maxwell this week, exchanging
words with him on the court. Mills has never had warm feelings for
Mad Max and actually went to the Kings locker room to seek him out
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   The would-be combatants shouted at each other but were separated
and Mills never actually made it into the visitors' locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I've calmed down,'' Mills said afterward. ``He had me
pretty upset out there. It seemed like he was mad at the world and
I guess he was trying to take it out on me.''
</P>
<P>
   Mills, who posted up the smaller Maxwell several times during
the game, said Maxwell's fouling antics and constant trash talking
eventually got to him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully when I see him next time we won't have to come to
blows and we can have a civilized basketball game,'' Mills said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-05-01-99 2134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990501.0243 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0833 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN--HILL-COLUMN-LBPT     05-01 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN--HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOODBYE AND GOOD RIDDANCE, SPORTS ARENA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If you happen to be trapped inside the Sports
Arena late at night - after the ``announced crowd'' has piled into
the same car and escaped, after the dance team has gone off to some
nightspot where the bouncers can sniff a sportswriter at 50 paces,
after Chris Ford's last accusation of defense (``illegal!'') has
dusted the rafters don't be surprised to hear a conversation
between the ghosts of Randy Woods and Benoit Benjamin.
</P>
<P>
   Woods: Hey, I've found your left shoe!
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin: Great ... now I have three.
</P>
<P>
   And if you see the ghost of Larry Brown, tell him the UCLA job
isn't open. Then run like hell.
</P>
<P>
   OK, we're not here to tear down the Sports Arena, because USC
still needs it. But after Wednesday's last dance with the Seattle
SuperSonics, the Clippers will drive downtown and commence yelling
for the Staples Center construction crew to hurry it up.
</P>
<P>
   Will the Clipper family invest even one respectful sniff for the
sake of bitter history?
</P>
<P>
   If you bet on it, give the points. With that in mind, here's a
sample of Sports Arena sentiment:
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll miss this red carpet,'' Clipper Lorenzen Wright said
while studying a locker room rug that still waits for its first
champagne stain. ``I'll miss watching birds fly through the
arena.''
</P>
<P>
   To the best of our recollection, the place has seemed like a
nest that seats 16,021 cuckoos.
</P>
<P>
   When compared to other NBA venues, the 40-year-old Sports Arena
is a bran muffin in a row of wedding cakes. Its playing surface has
more dead spots than a referee's heart. Its game-night witnesses
include barely enough celebrities to staff a game show.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little wedge of Siberia in the bread basket of L.A.
</P>
<P>
   It is where on April 24, 1994 there was no legal or illegal
defense committed, because San Antonio's David Robinson managed to
score an arena-record 71 points.
</P>
<P>
   It is where the Kings made their home in the halcyon days before
scribes realized players were saying ``out'' instead of ``oat.''
</P>
<P>
   It is where NBA teams arrived to challenge the Lakers, whose
superstar forward Elgin Baylor retains diplomatic immunity as the
Clippers' vice president of basketball operations.
</P>
<P>
   It is where they wouldn't dare build a new Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   And it is where since 1984 visiting losing streaks have gone to
die.
</P>
<P>
   Subhead Meanwhile, at the Forum
</P>
<P>
   Recent episodes of the Laker soap opera have inspired the gods
of sports-talk radio to pose the following question:
</P>
<P>
   If you were (Laker personnel lord) Jerry ``Out'' West and were
required to trade either Shaquille O'Neal or Kobe Bryant, what
would you do?
</P>
<P>
   Best answer: become personnel lord of another team.
</P>
<P>
   One room-temperature rumor has the Laker idea man joining the
Knicks and becoming Jerry East. Yeah, loyal followers around town
are becoming disloyal to West. They refuse to forget that he traded
two guys with at least one letter `D' in their first names Eddie
and Elden for Glen Rice and J.R. Reid.
</P>
<P>
   We think he should stay in Tinseltown and become executive
producer of a film that pays tribute to the 1999 Lakers: ``Star
Warp: The Phantom Dennis.''
</P>
<P>
   (Subhead) Draft update
</P>
<P>
   The NBA stages a draft every year, and every year the league's
talent buzzards say the draft stinks.
</P>
<P>
   They said it reeked last year, and the current rookie crop has
responded by providing the NBA with a whiff of ambrosia.
</P>
<P>
   But the buzzards still fly.
</P>
<P>
   And they're hoping suspects for the 1999 NBA Draft are
reinforced by early entry declarations from UCLA point guard Baron
Davis and Lamar Odom, the 6-foot-9 Swiss Army Knife of Rhode
Island.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of talent, Davis is a top-five lock. But the biggest
question posed by Davis-watchers we've interviewed has nothing to
do with his repaired knee. No, the NBA is concerned about Baron's
willingness to be coached.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps he became more suit-friendly while coaching two high
school all-star teams in Saturday's showcase event at L.A.
Southwest College.
</P>
<P>
   If Odom can convince suitors he has a severe passion for the
game, he could be chosen first, ahead of Maryland guard Steve ``I
Can Too Play The Point'' Francis. If not, Francis could be the
first junior-college product taken at No. 1 since Larry Johnson
(1991).
</P>
<P>
   Recent early entry additions who might spice up the end of the
lottery or the middle of the first round include gifted-but-raw
UNLV small forward Shawn Marion and Georgia small forward Jumaine
Jones, whose jumper has more range than a John Wayne movie.
</P>
<P>
   Still straddling the fence, but leaning toward the NBA side, is
Duke sophomore-to-be Corey Maggette.
</P>
<P>
   (Subhead) Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   Tyrone Nesby, the Clippers free-agent rookie small forward, is
absolutely mad for Chinese food. One of Nesby's long-term goals is
to open two restaurants that specialize in Chinese chow - one in
California and one in Las Vegas (he played at UNLV). Suggested
name: ``Ty Cuisine.'' ... Before you dismiss the playing-time
whining by the agent of Portland point guard Damon Stoudamire,
remember that Damon spelled backward is Nomad. ... Leon Smith of
Martin Luther King High in Chicago has decided to make himself a
vailable for the NBA Draft. After bow-wowing scouts in a recent
all-star tilt at Pauley Pavilion, the 6-10 Smith looks like a minor
reach in the second round. ... Bet you've been wondering who
invented the game-morning shootaround, right? If you're an NBA
player who likes to sleep in, blame former Lakers coach Bill
Sharman. ... As was demonstrated in his ugly exchange with
Portland's Greg Anthony, Utah Jazz owner Larry Miller likes to
insult visiting players from his courtside seat. According to a
rumor we might have made up, Clippers owner Donald T. Sterling
prefers to harass opposing players by threatening to acquire them
in a trade.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
