<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    K.C. fans walk out in protest
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Kevin Millwood has spent all spring answering
questions about his new role in the Braves rotation. Saturday
night, he gave the best response yet from the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Holding the Cincinnati Reds to scoreless into the eighth,
Millwood extended a brilliant stretch of Atlanta starting pitching
in a 5-1 victory at Turner Field, the Braves' fourth straight win
and seventh in eight games. Chipper Jones homered from each side of
the plate in the seventh two-home run game of his career and Andruw
Jones and Bret Boone each homered once, taking some of the thunder
away from Millwood's finest performance this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Braves starters have now allowed just one run in their last 31
innings.
</P>
<P>
   Millwood (3-2) allowed three hits, walked two and struck out
eight, retiring 20 of 21 batters after a first-inning run until
pinch-hitter Mark Sweeney singled with one out in the eighth.
Following a walk to Mike Cameron, Rudy Seanez relieved him and
stranded both runners.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie Odalis Perez (0-1) faces former Brave Denny Neagle at
1:10 p.m. today in the final game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Andruw Jones' solo homer in the seventh provided some insurance
while extending a productive streak of the Braves' hottest hitter.
The home run was Jones' fourth in seven games as he continued to
batter Reds' pitching. He now has a .359 career average against
Cincinnati with 13 of his 25 hits going for homers.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones, who had gone 2-for-13 during this homestand,
struck his sixth homer of the season on Harnisch's first pitch of
the fourth inning for a 2-1 lead. The homer was Jones' first in 10
days, after hitting five in his first 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   The Braves tied it 1-1 in the third with a least likely RBI
source. After Ozzie Guillen singled and was sacrificed to second by
Millwood, Otis Nixon came to the plate with just 4 hits in his
previous 33 at-bats and hitting .167 with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   But Nixon legged out an infield single to the right side and
Guillen came around to score when first baseman Sean Casey's throw
got away from Harnisch. The run was unearned with an error charged
to Casey.
</P>
<P>
   In his first four starts, Millwood averaged better than a walk
every other inning, a bad habit that cost him an early lead. He
walked Greg Vaughn with two outs in the first and Casey, whose .372
average ranked fourth in the league entering the night, launched a
double off the wall in right-center, scoring Vaughn without a play
for a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
