<SLUG> BC-BBC-UCLAUSC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA RALLIES TO BEAT USC
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It wasn't the first ninth-inning comeback that won
a baseball game for UCLA this season; it was the fifth, which is a
feat in itself.
</P>
<P>
   And considering the opponent, the situation and the environment,
this one was the sweetest for the Bruins. UCLA scored all of its
runs in the top of the ninth to beat rival USC 3-2 Saturday
afternoon at Dedeaux Field.
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins improved to 25-26, 9-8 in the Pacific-10 Conference.
No.15-ranked USC (30-21, 15-5) dropped out of a first-place tie
with Stanford, which beat Oregon State 10-5.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans and right-handed starting pitcher Justin Lehr
carried a 2-0 lead into the ninth. UCLA rallied to tie the game
with two outs on Jason Green's single to right field, then went
ahead one batter later when Garrett Atkins scored from second base
on an infield single by Matt Pearl.
</P>
<P>
   Green, who was hitless in his first three at-bats, fouled off
four consecutive pitches with two strikes before getting the base
hit off USC reliever Dominic Correa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to put the ball in play,'' said Green, the
Bruins' catcher and senior co-captain. ``(Correa) was throwing some
tough pitches.''
</P>
<P>
   On each two-strike pitch, most of the crowd of 1,242 was on its
feet. Green said he gained motivation from the cheering, even
though it was directed toward the Trojans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It juices you up a little bit,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Even the USC team started celebrating when Green nearly struck
out on a high fastball. He fouled-tipped the ball at the last
second and USC catcher Beau Craig couldn't hold on for the third
strike.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were about as close to a loss as I've ever seen a team
being close to losing,'' said UCLA head coach Gary Adams, who is in
his 30th season as a college coach.
</P>
<P>
   Adams technically wasn't supposed to have witnessed the
comeback. He was ejected by umpire Steve Williamson in the seventh
inning after arguing a balk call against UCLA reliever Tyler Dersom
(Chaminade High).
</P>
<P>
   But Adams snuck peeks at the game from the stairwell leading
into the visitor's locker room, as did UCLA pitching coach Tim
Leary, who was kicked out of the game by home plate umpire Gus
Rodriguez just minutes after Adams was tossed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told (assistant) coach (Vince Beringhele) before the game,
`sooner or later I'm going to get tossed, so you better be
prepared,''' Adams said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams might have been ejected, but the finish left Lehr
dejected.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr, a transfer from UC Santa Barbara who hasn't lost in six
decisions, struck out 10 and walked none in 81/3 innings. He was
taken out in the ninth after he gave up a single to Chase Utley,
who went 3 for 4.
</P>
<P>
   Rik Currier came in and walked former Alemany standout Bill
Scott, and Correa moved from second base to the mound to try to
pick up his second save.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins singled to drive in Utley, which made it 2-1. Designated
hitter Eric Reese struck out and then Green got the tying hit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We debated whether to take out (Lehr) after he got the first
hitter,'' USC head coach Mike Gillespie said.
</P>
<P>
   Lehr said he was disappointed with losing the game, not with
watching the Bruins rally after he was taken out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hindsight is 20-20,'' he said. ``Bill Scott hits into a double
play and it's a great call.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
