<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-DERBY02 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Charasmatic takes Kentucky Derby
 &HT;    By John Crittenden
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ For six months last year, Chris Antley ran 25
miles a day to take off more than 30 pounds, a weight loss that
would allow him to ride horse races again.
</P>
<P>
   Three months ago, trainer Wayne Lukas decided Charismatic was so
heavy that the only way to make him lose weight was to race him
every two weeks instead of once a month.
</P>
<P>
   The two former fat boys outran Menifee by a neck after 1 1/4
miles Saturday to win the the 125th Kentucky Derby at odds of 31-1.
</P>
<P>
   It was a triumph that put Wayne Lukas, at age 63, into the Derby
racord books as the race's top trainer of the 1990s. The newest
member of the Racing Hall of Fame, inducted on Tuesday, was first
in 1995 with Thunder Gulch and won again in 1996 with Grindstone.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Baffert did not come close in his bid to become the first
trainer to win three straight in the Derby. The Baffert entries
finished fourth, fifth and 11th. Moreover, Lukas won the Derby with
owners who are top Baffert clients, Bob an d Beverly Lewis, first
in the Derby in 1997 with Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't know how to act,'' said Baffert. ``We're sort of lost
souls. There were too many horses and so much traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   The owners nearly lost Charismatic in a claiming race for
$62,500 on Feb. 11 and they were willing to see him go. ``Sometimes
you have to cut your losses,'' Bob Lewis said. Previously,
Charismatic, purchased for $200,000, had won one of 10 races.
</P>
<P>
   But the Kentucky-bred son of Summer Squall is now a millionaire.
His first in the Derby, with a dues-paying field of 19, was worth
$886,220.
</P>
<P>
   The size of the field knocked out many of the top horses as soon
as the race began.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest disappointment fell to Vicar, first in the Florida
Derby. ``He never had a lane to run in, we never could get into any
kind of position,'' said trainer Carl Nafzger. Vicar came in
next-to-last.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was my worst trip ever,'' said Gary Stevens, 11th with
General Challenge, co-favored with entrymate Excellent Meeting at
4-1. ``I got squeezed in the first turn and thrown around so much
it was a wonder we didn't fall.''
</P>
<P>
   No favorite has won the Derby since 1979. No Breeders' Cup
Juvenile champion has ever won. Answer Lively, 1998 2-year-old
champion, finished 10th Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In fifth, the filly Excellent Meeting was the highest finisher
among Baffert's three entries. The other filly, Calder-based Three
Ring, came in last. ``She got bumped out of the staring gate,''
said trainer Ed Plesa. Jr. ``Then, just when the jockey was taking
hold of her, his saddle slipped. That was all she wrote.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the race's moderate successes was Worldly Manner, trained
in Dubai. But after a challenge in the stretch for jockey Jerry
Bailey, he fell to seventh.
</P>
<P>
   No. 2 betting choice at 5-1, Stephen Got Even came in 14th. ``He
never got any kind of traction,'' said jockey Chris McCarron.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas said before the race that the the outcome would likely
depend on how trouble-free the winning horse's route was and how
well the jockey rode.
</P>
<P>
   It worked out that way for Antley and Charismatic, as well as
the Lukas-trained third-place finisher, Cat Thief, ridden by Mike
Smith. Charismatic was the most experienced horse in the field,
with 15 races, which could not have hurt him.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth Derby winner for Lukas. Only one trainer has
won more, Ben Jones with six.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight year, Elliott Walden supplied the
excitement at the end. This time it was Menifee, not Victory
Gallop, left with second money after a furious rush. ``We had to
wait for room too long to win it,'' said the trainer. ``I had to
stop and start one time too many,'' said jockey Pat Day.
</P>
<P>
   Lukas said he always meant to send Charismatic to the Derby,
even before he won the Lexington Stakes at Keeneland on April 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``He might not have made it if he had not won the Lexington,''
said Lewis, the winner's
</P>
<P>
   owner. ``He might not have had enough earnings. We might have
been bumped from the field.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis said Mike Mitchell, a California trainer, almost claimed
Charismatic at Santa Anita Feb. 11. But Lewis, who sponsors race
cars, had given the trainer tickets that week to an auto race. ``I
just couldn't take a horse that belonged to Mr. Lewis,'' said
Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   ``So for four tickets worth $10 apiece I got to keep a $1
million horse,'' said Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
