<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 22:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0946 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-SHELL-HNS &LR;      05-01 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-SHELL-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
It's far from lonely at the top for Sutton
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By EDDIE SEFKO &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
THE WOODLANDS _ The crowded Kentucky Derby on Saturday had nothing
on the horse race that has developed going into the final round of
the Shell Houston Open.
</P>
<P>
   Down the stretch they are coming at the Tournament Players
Course at The Woodlands with Hal Sutton holding a tenuous two-shot
lead thanks to a birdie-birdie finish in the third round Saturday.
Sutton's 3-under-par 69 was his third consecutive round in the 60s
and left him at 11-under 205 for the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But there's a mass of humanity within striking distance on what
promises to be a round filled with fireworks today. Joey Sindelar,
the second-round co-leader with Sutton, saw a one-shot lead slip
away when he bogeyed No. 17 and finished at 9-under 207 after a 71
Saturday. A dozen more players are within five shots of Sutton,
including Steve Elkington, who was in the second group on the
course Saturday morning but leaped into contention with a 7-under
65.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hal and I definitely would have loved to have run out three or
four shots further to keep people away from us,'' Sindelar said.
``But it didn't happen. And so the battle will be filled with a lot
of people.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Sutton has a two-shot lead, Saturday's play proved
that anybody within five or six shots of the lead could come out of
the pack. Elkington's early round was upstaged by Clarence Rose,
who shot 8-under 64 to pass 53 players and join a four-way tie for
third at 208.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, posting an eye-popping early score is a possibility,
and Sutton is taking nothing for granted. But he has every
intention of making everybody earn it if they intend on passing
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll probably be fairly aggressive (today),'' Sutton said.
``There's a lot of good players right behind me and I can guarantee
that they're going to be aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``This golf course is set up for you to make mistakes. That's
the only way I know how to put it. You can't fear making a mistake.
If you fear making a mistake, then you're going to be paralyzed
(today). So I'm going out to put a hook in the water and try to
catch a fish.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton persevered Saturday, weathering a couple of bogeys in the
middle of the round, then turned up the heat on Sindelar and the
other chasers on the final two holes.
</P>
<P>
   Sutton hit a 7-iron approach on the 17th 10 feet short of the
cup and drilled the putt. It proved to be a fateful hole. Sindelar
had stepped to the tee with a one-shot lead after making birdie on
the par-5 15th. But he hit a weak 1-iron into the light rough on
the right, then tried to punch a low 6-iron into the green.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got over the top of it from 165 yards,'' Sindelar said. ``I
knew full well that I didn't want to miss it on the left. I was
aiming three steps to the right, but I still hit it left. That's
golf.''
</P>
<P>
   The ball avoided the lake that wraps around the green, but it
came to rest just inches from the bulkhead boards.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a little trough there and it just caught the ball,''
Sindelar said. ``I'm awfully lucky not to have double-bogeyed that
hole.''
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar bumped his chip shot onto the fringe, then missed the
15-footer and tapped in for bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, his one-shot lead had turned into a one-shot
disadvantage. And when Sutton hit a wedge within five feet on the
18th for an easy birdie, the lead became two shots.
</P>
<P>
   The course was brutal to those who started later in the day.
David Duval was 6 under par for the tournament after six holes
Saturday, then suffered a double-bogey on No. 7 and triple-bogeyed
the 13th. That means over his last 22 holes, Duval has two doubles
and a triple. Golf's No. 1 player usually can count on going months
without a double bogey.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is a chance of rain today, if conditions don't
change, the leaders will have their work cut out for them. The TPC
has shown a tendency in the past few days to dry out quickly in the
afternoon, making the greens firm and giving a distinct advantage
to those playing earlier in the day.
</P>
<P>
   Sindelar said he spent part of Saturday re-learning the art of
being in contention. He couldn't remember the last time he was in
the final pairing on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why today was so meaningful,'' he said. ``To me, the
reason guys stay in contention for weeks at a time is because they
get into a comfort zone. That's huge. To look back and realize
there's nobody playing behind you is important. I'm getting
comfortable all over again. And today went a long way toward that
for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Sutton, meanwhile, will be trying to extend the comeback he
began last fall when he won the Westin Texas Open and the Tour
Championship after having only one win in the previous 11 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel more comfortable now,'' he said. ``If I don't win, I
won't feel like I missed my chance. The only thing about winning is
that when it's your time, you win. And when it's not your time,
you're not going to.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot more confident in my game than I was last year at
this time. I believe in what I'm doing. I think probably the best
thing I'm doing now is that I'm not allowing myself to be paralyzed
by a mistake. I'm human, just like everybody else. And everybody
makes mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``But now I'm doing a better job of putting them behind me and
walking to the next tee, saying, `OK, let's play from here.'''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy should come in handy today when he'll be wearing
the bull's-eye on his back and have a slew of competitors aiming
for him.
</P>
</TEXT>
