<SLUG> BC-AT-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING THE POOL FOR SUMMER 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With summer fast approaching, homeowners with swimming pools are
about to engage in an annual rite of spring _ opening up the pool
in time for the Memorial Day weekend.
</P>
<P>
   While many will hire experts to do the job, others will tackle
the task themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Opening your pool is relatively easy _ as long as you know
what you're doing,'' said Scott Wechsler, president of Pal Pools in
Bohemia, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   For many in-ground pool owners, Wechsler said, the biggest
challenge is getting the cover off without allowing dirty water and
debris to get into the relatively clean water underneath. The best
way to do that, Wechsler said, is by pumping standing water off the
cover to remove leaves or other debris. That sounds simple enough
until one realizes that the accumulated debris is probably sitting
smack in the middle of the cover. One way to make it easier to
remove the debris is to increase the water level of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Wechsler said, raising the water level in the pool also
makes it easier to remove the cover itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to fill the pool to the middle of the skimmers,'' he
said, referring to the inlets around the perimeter of the pool that
allow water into the filter.
</P>
<P>
   With the water at that level, he said, the cover can usually be
removed by two people _ with each grabbing a corner at the shallow
end of the pool and dragging the cover 5 feet or so onto the pool
apron.
</P>
<P>
   ``People think that if they drag the other end of the cover into
the water, it's going to fall in and sink,'' he said. ``But if you
drag uniformly, the cover should float across the top of the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   Dragging from the shallow end also makes it easier to ``fan
fold'' the cover for storage.
</P>
<P>
   ``You pick it up, walk 5 feet back, and fold,'' he said. ``You
keep doing that, folding it on top of itself as you go, and it will
come off in a breeze.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Svatek, the owner of Sundance Swimming Pools in St. James,
N.Y., said that if the cover _ and the homeowner removing it _ have
done their jobs well, the water in the pool should be fairly clean.
If not, Svatek said, any debris or sludge at the bottom of the pool
should be removed using a commercial-grade net with an extension
pole that will not bend or break.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners should resist the temptation to ``start fresh'' by
emptying a pool, he said, particularly if it is vinyl-lined.
``Vinyl pools are designed to be filled and remained filled,''
Svatek said. Should the pool be emptied, the liner can shift, tear
or pull loose from the shell it covers.
</P>
<P>
   Once the pool has been opened and cleaned of solid debris, the
next thing to do is to get the water moving through the filter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We generally tell customers to let the filter run for about 24
hours,'' said Nick Spalletta, store manager for Dover Pools and
Supplies in Toms River, N.J. ``That way you get the water on top
mixing with the water on the bottom,'' he said. He added that such
circulation was necessary to assure the success of the next step _
testing the water to get a picture of the overall chemistry of the
pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the most common mistakes people make is putting
chemicals in the pool before they have the water tested to find out
what chemicals they need,'' Spalletta said. Most pool-supply
companies will test customers' water samples free and provide a
detailed analysis of the water, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Testing leads to the part of pool preparation and maintenance
that is most perplexing to homeowners _ pool-water chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   Rob Cox, creator of www.poolcenter.com _ an Internet Web site
that is a repository of information about pools and spas _ said
that there were four parameters to test for: the pH level of the
water in the pool, its alkalinity, its calcium hardness and its
chlorine content. Water samples may be taken to a pool-supply
company for testing or may be tested with an ``in-home'' kit, which
should have its testing chemicals replaced every year.
</P>
<P>
   The pH level, Cox said, is a measure of how acidic or basic the
water is, with levels below 7 considered acidic and those above 7
basic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ever hear of acid rain?'' Cox said. ``That is rainfall with a
very low pH.''
</P>
<P>
   He explained that the pH level of the human eye is about 7.35,
just slightly basic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is in range with proper pH levels for your pool,'' he
said, explaining that the proper pH range _ 7.2 to 7.8 _ can be
obtained by adding to the water chemicals known as pH increasers or
pH decreasers, which are available at pool stores and home centers.
</P>
<P>
   The pH level is important, Cox said, because water that is too
acidic _ a low pH _ can eat away at a pool's interior finish and
corrode the copper tubing inside the pool heater. Water with a high
pH, he said, can create mineral-deposit buildups on the pool
surface and in pipes in the filter and heater.
</P>
<P>
   The next thing to test for _ alkalinity _ affects the resistance
of the water's pH level to change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The right alkalinity keeps the pH from bouncing all over the
place,'' Cox said. Low alkalinity, he explained, can be increased
by adding a pH increaser, such as common baking soda, while high
alkalinity can be reduced by adding acids, which are the chemicals
in pH decreasers.
</P>
<P>
   The calcium hardness level, Cox said, is the measure of how hard
or soft the water is.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to keep the calcium level in the range of 200 to 400
parts per million,'' Cox said, noting that calcium levels in
general this year appear to be unusually low.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the pools we're opening are taking 20 to 30 pounds of
calcium,'' he said. The better test kits, he added, will indicate
how much calcium is needed.
</P>
<P>
   After the pH, alkalinity and calcium levels of the pool are in
proper balance, Cox said, it is time to ``shock'' the pool with
chlorine to kill any algae or micro-organisms that may be present.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you shock a pool, its like you're sending a lightning
bolt through the water,'' he said. ``The lightning bolt slashes and
burns its way through the cell walls of microcontaminants and
destroys them.''
</P>
<P>
   Shocking the pool, however, Cox said, involves more than just
adding a lot of chlorine.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a threshold known as `breakpoint chlorination,''' he
said, explaining that the term refers to the point at which
chlorine levels in the pool reach the critical mass necessary to
produce the ``lightning effect.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally speaking, it takes 1 pound of shock chlorine for
every 10,000 gallons of water to reach breakpoint chlorination,''
Cox said, cautioning that it was always important to follow the
manufacturer's instructions when using any pool chemical.
</P>
<P>
   After the pool has been properly shocked, he said, the chlorine
content should be maintained at a level of 1 to 2 parts per
million. The pool should be shocked at least once a month or
whenever the chlorine content falls below the recommended level, he
added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
