<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WINS MEET IN CLOSE CALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Somehow, some way, the UCLA track team found a way
to beat USC again.
</P>
<P>
   The underdog Bruins squeaked by the Trojans 82-81 to win the
men's division for the 21st year in a row Saturday at USC's
Cromwell Field.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome of the men's meet was the closest in the 66-meet
series started in 1934 and led by USC 38-28. And it might also be
the last cross-town victory for UCLA coach Bob Larsen, who is
rumored to be retiring after 15 seasons with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still here. I made it through the relays and I didn't head
for the beach,'' Larsen said. ``When you are going against a team
as good as USC is _ and look how well they competed today _ we had
to go to the wall to get it done. That's always satisfying, when
you see your guys come through.''
</P>
<P>
   No one came through better than pole vaulter Steven Michels. The
sophomore cleared a lifetime-best 17 feet, 7 inches on his third
and final attempt to defeat Dennis Kholev of USC. Michels' victory
and a third-place finish by Brian McLaughlin gave UCLA a critical
six points.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA had trailed 73-58 with four events to go but rallied with
Michels' clutch vault and sweeps in the discus and 5,000 meters to
clinch the meet heading into the final event, the 1,600-meter
relay.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were supposed to lose it, but we came through with heart,''
Michels said. ``We've won it 20 years straight and we had to do it
for everyone who came before us. Being at UCLA, this has to be one
of my biggest moments. SC has an incredible team and I'm just glad
we could compete with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bruins' victory overshadowed USC senior Jerome Davis, the
NCAA defending 400 champion who won the 200 and 400 in 20.70 and
45.61, then ran on the Trojans' 400 and 1,600 relays.
</P>
<P>
   The UCLA women, led by senior hurdler Joanna Hayes (who had a
hand in three victories) defeated USC 91-63. UCLA extended their
dual-meet winning streak to 61 in defeating USC for the seventh
consecutive year, and took a 13-3 edge in the all-time series.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes won the 100-meter hurdles in a wind-aided 12.7, the
400-meter hurdles in 56.02 by a hundredth of a second over USC's
Natasha Danvers, and ran on the Bruins' victorious 1,600-meter
relay, which timed 3:35.15.
</P>
<P>
   The USC women's 400-meter relay team of Angela Williams, Torri
Edwards, Malika Edmonson and Candace Young set a national dual meet
and all-time Pacific-10 record to win in 43.35 despite running a
solo effort after UCLA dropped the baton on the first exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Williams, a freshman who holds the national high school 100
record, won the 100 in a wind-aided 11.02 to turn back 1998 World
Junior champion Shakedia Jones of UCLA. Edwards, the 1996 Pac-10
champion, rebounded from a false start in the 100 to defeat Jones
in the 200 in 23.33.
</P>
<P>
   After Michels' victory in the pole vault, UCLA's Luke Sullivan
(187-4), Travis Haynes and Scott Moser went 1-2-3 in the discus.
Haynes and Moser also responded with efforts of 185-11 and 184-3 to
bump USC's Gordon Hovey to a non-scoring fourth at 184-3. Bryan
Green, Will Bernaldo and Kevin Bowes 1-2-3 finished in the 5,000
put the Bruins over the top.
</P>
<P>
   The meet took unusual turns on both sides. The Trojans received
a surprising 1-3 finish by USC basketball player Jeff Trepagnier
and football player Kori Dickerson in the high jump. Trepagnier
cleared 6-9} with two days of practice and Dickerson, a defensive
end, cleared 6-8.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
