<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWS-FAMILIES-HNS &LR;      05-01 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWS-FAMILIES-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
FAMILIES OF CAPTURED U.S. SOLDIERS ANXIOUSLY AWAIT THEIR RELEASE
<TEXT>
<P>
   By EDWARD HEGSTROM &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HUNTSVILLE _ Rosie Gonzales awoke Saturday morning prepared to
wait indefinitely for her son's release from a Yugoslav prison.
</P>
<P>
   So when an urgent message scrolled across her television screen
at 11:30 a.m. announcing that Army Spc. Stephen Gonzales and two
other American prisoners of war would be released, she thought it
was a mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just couldn't believe my eyes, I thought maybe I was just
reading it wrong,'' an elated Gonzales told reporters just hours
later.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was almost too shocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Gonzales and husband, Gilbert, could be forgiven for being just
a little bewildered by the sudden news of the plan to release the
prisoners to the Rev. Jesse Jackson, who had met with Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Hours earlier, Army officials had called to warn the couple not
to get their hopes up. Now the Army has instructed them to pack
their bags and prepare for a flight to Germany for a possible
reunion with their son.
</P>
<P>
   Family members of the other two prisoners being held _ Staff
Sgts. Andrew Ramirez and Christopher Stone _ also seemed to be
slowly recovering from the shock of good news.
</P>
<P>
   In San Antonio, Sgt. Stone's wife, Tricia, ``is praying and
hoping that it is true,'' according to her step-mother, Lisa
McKinney.
</P>
<P>
   ``She is waiting on a call from the military,'' McKinney said,
although Stone received unofficial word from television interviews
that her husband's release was imminent.
</P>
<P>
   McKinney said Sgt. Stone will have to undergo three days of
debriefings after reaching Germany before he is reunited with his
wife and son.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has three days to get there,'' McKinney said, but added
that as yet they did not know whether Stone will use military or
civilian transportation.
</P>
<P>
   Tricia Stone already is packed and ready to leave for Germany
just as soon as official word of her husband's release is received
from the government. She has been staying with her step-mother in
San Antonio during the ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   And in California, the parents of Ramirez were also cautiously
optimistic about the news trickling out of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm waiting for the big call that they're on the bus and on
their way out (of Yugoslavia),'' Ramirez's mother, Vivian Ramirez,
said at a news conference, according to the Associated Press. She
said she would ``wait with the phone next to me until they call
me.''
</P>
<P>
   For the parents of Stephen Gonzales, news of the release capped
a particularly bizarre string of events over the previous 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   After an agonizing several days with no word about their
22-year-old son, the family saw a videotape Friday of the three
meeting with Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Army officials at first warned that Jackson's mission
would not likely succeed in freeing the three men taken captive at
the Macedonian border on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had prepared ourselves'' for the possibility of a long
wait, said Rosie Gonzales. So news of Stephen's release was a
``double shock.''
</P>
<P>
   After meeting with the press Saturday afternoon, the Gonzales'
went to dinner with friends. They said they planned to spend the
night watching television news programs for any possible updates on
their son's condition.
</P>
<P>
   They said the Army has asked them to prepare to fly to Germany
as early as today for a later reunion with their son.
</P>
<P>
   And what will they say once they finally come face-to-face with
him?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't even think we'll have to say anything,'' said his
mother. ``We'll just look into each other's eyes and hold each
other.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gonzaleses said they hoped to be able to meet Jackson to
pass on their gratitude for his tireless efforts, particularly
since others were so doubtful that he would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thank (Jackson) from the bottom of my heart because he was
determined'' to get the three soldiers freed, Rosie Gonzales said.
</P>
<P>
   The couple also said they support Jackson's claim that the
United States should now move to attempt to resolve the conflict in
the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes tearful but more often beaming an electric smile,
Rosie Gonzales appeared at the press conference in a white T-shirt
with a picture of her son under the letters: ``POW'' for prisoner
of war.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Gonzales wore a POW bracelet given by a veteran in North
Carolina and a pin donated by a fellow Texan.
</P>
<P>
   Both Gonzales's gave thanks for the outpouring of support they
have received from the people in Huntsville and from around the
world.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe in the power of prayer, and I truly believe that it
was all those prayers that made this possible,'' Rosie Gonzales.
</P>
<P>
   As news of the pending freedom spread across Huntsville, people
in the town festooned in yellow ribbons already began preparing for
a party.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about time!'' declared shopkeeper Beverly Conner. ``We'll
have to have a parade.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Chronicle reporter Carlos Byars contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
