<SLUG> BC-RENOVATIONS-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAW SPACE IN TRIBECA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By TRISH HALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There is a huge puddle in the middle of the loft that
has just been sold for $577,000 to David and Julienne Dweck. The
real estate people don't particularly want it to be photographed,
but the Dwecks don't mind. When they first saw the place, it had
exposed pipes, and no windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to have some imagination,'' said Dweck. So a puddle in
their future living room bothers them not at all.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, they wanted raw space, something that is increasingly
difficult to find in what are considered the good parts of
Manhattan, and they believe they've snagged a bargain in getting
2,800 square feet, including a storage closet and parking space, in
TriBeCa. Even if it does look out on a brick wall _ and a sign that
says Shaftway.
</P>
<P>
   And they probably have. Because as nearly every commercial and
industrial building in TriBeCa is being converted to residential
use, large lofts are selling for more than a million dollars, often
after renovation with materials like marble and granite. The
Dwecks, who are expecting their first child in July, wanted a
nearly empty space that they could shape to their taste.
</P>
<P>
   Dweck, who has been living in a rented loft in SoHo for seven
years, married 15 months ago and soon began looking for a place to
buy. He does the design work for a 77-year-old family business,
S.S. Dweck and Sons, which manufactures sheets and towels, so he
has his own ideas about how things should look.
</P>
<P>
   So does his wife, who is just finishing her degree in art
history at New York University. (Although she is now Mrs. Dweck,
she was also Miss Dweck. She and her husband were born with the
same last names, which are typically Syrian, and they met at an
engagement party being held for a man named Dweck.)
</P>
<P>
   They looked at ``30 or 40'' places in SoHo and TriBeCa, but the
ones they liked were all priced at more than a million dollars.
Then one day, they decided to get on their bicycles and go around
to open houses. When they got to 195 Hudson St., they knew they had
found what they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need high ceilings,'' said Mrs. Dweck. ``It gives you a
feeling of openness.'' Their friends, says Dweck, tend to live on
the Upper East Side, in smaller, ``cookie-cutter'' spaces. And they
definitely did not want that.
</P>
<P>
   Their building, erected in 1929 as the US Rubber headquarters,
is still being renovated. When done, it will have a doorman, heated
garage, landscaped roof deck and central air-conditioning, but its
commercial history will not be obliterated. The doors to the
apartment are huge, and made of metal, and it has oversized
industrial windows.
</P>
<P>
   Like many loft buildings, its location is far from ideal, right
next to the entrance on Canal Street to the Holland Tunnel. To
block out the noise, the developer has installed triple-paned
windows.
</P>
<P>
   The Dwecks are so pleased with the building that they have
referred a number of potential buyers, and two are moving in,
including one of Dweck's best friends, who has taken the space
directly below.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as they close on the loft, they plan to begin building
their space, which will have three bedrooms, two baths, and wood
floors instead of the existing concrete floors. The bulbous,
mushroom-like pillars in the loft will be integrated into the
walls, so they will be only partially visible. They hope to keep an
open feeling, but still have privacy, and doors.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we're in a fight,'' said Mrs. Dweck, ``I want to slam a
door.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
