<SLUG> BC-CAR-BUSCH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENSETH WINS BUSCH 300
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA _ Matt Kenseth did not have the fastest car or the best
set-up for Saturday's Busch Grand National Auto Club 300 at
California Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   But the 27-year-old from Cambridge, Wis. had enough of both to
win Saturday's 300-mile race.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely did not think we were going to win the race,''
said Kenseth, who is second in the series standings. ``We had to
make a major, major chassis adjustment. I would have been pleased
to finish second.''
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth said the car's set-up is usually a turn or two away, but
when he entered the pits on Lap 31 in fifth place, ``we needed four
or five rounds and about 2 pounds. We were way off.
</P>
<P>
   But by the time the 150-lap race finished _ under a yellow flag
where Todd Bodine scattered debris in Turn 2 after hitting the wall
three laps from the end _ the set-up was just fine. Jeff Burton
finished second and polesitter Dale Earnhardt Jr. was third.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very difficult to pass here,'' said Kenseth, who had
finished third in his two previous California Speedway races. ``I
had just enough to hold off Jeff Burton. If I were behind him, I
would not have got by him. He couldn't pass me when I got in front
of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt Jr. had the fastest car in the field, easily pulling
away from Kenseth and Burton in the early going. But four yellow
flags in the first 57 laps kept Earnhardt from getting the upper
hand and when he pulled in for a green-flag pit stop on Lap 94,
third gear broke on the downshift.
</P>
<P>
   But that was the least of the series point leader's worries.
Twenty-five laps later, trying to get around a lapped Hank Parker
Jr., the two touched in Turn 2. Earnhardt spun but did not hit
anything. And instead of running for the lead, he was running to
catch up.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was trying to pass traffic, (Parker) was motioning me
to pass. He was drifting high and I went down with Jeff Burton
under me,'' Earnhardt said. ``(Burton) was juking and jiving me. I
just stayed on the gas and tried to not hit the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt went down a lap to mid-race leader Elliott Sadler, but
a three-car wreck put Earnhardt back on the lead lap with 23 to go.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth and Burton hooked up after the sixth caution and the
pair ran past Sadler with 18 laps to go, giving Kenseth the lead
for good.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, meanwhile, worked his way to third with six laps
remaining. But he said he knew his day was finished.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to catch 'em, it's another to pass 'em,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Kenseth won $73,200 for the victory.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
