A1068 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WAREHOUSING-REAL-800(     05-01 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAREHOUSING-REAL-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
I-95'S EXIT 8A IS A MAGNET TO HIGH-TECH WAREHOUSES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By JOHN HOLUSHA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CRANBURY TOWNSHIP, N.J. _ The Graybar Electric company is
starting up a distribution center here whose managers promise
overnight delivery of electrical parts as far away as Boston or the
suburbs of Washington. ``If someone orders by 5 p.m., we'll have it
on their loading dock before they open up the next morning,'' said
Paul J. Milata, Graybar's regional manager here.
</P>
<P>
   He can make that promise because he is managing a new building
that is installing the latest equipment. But another important
factor is the location of the building in Cranbury Business Park,
about two miles from Exit 8A of the New Jersey Turnpike.
</P>
<P>
   Not only is the site, about 60 miles southwest of New York City,
midway between New York and Philadelphia, but it is almost
equidistant from Boston and Washington. It is also an overnight
ride west to important industrial centers in Pennsylvania and Ohio
or east to the consumer markets of Long Island, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Because there is very little housing in the area, trucks have
largely unimpeded access over local roads to the Turnpike, part of
Interstate Route 95, which connects with the national highway
system.
</P>
<P>
   These are among the reasons that the area off Exit 8A has become
one of the East Coast's prime centers for warehousing and
distribution. Real estate executives estimate that there are 35
million square feet of industrial space within a few miles of the
exit, most of it built over the last 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The area is so identified with warehousing and distribution that
one developer, Kerzner Associates, named its project Eight A
Corporate Park.
</P>
<P>
   According to a year-end report by Cushman &AMP; Wakefield, the real
estate services company, buildings in the 8A area accounted for 54
percent of the 2.6 million square feet of industrial construction
in the northern and central parts of the state last year. Little
building is going on now _ about 54,000 square feet _ but brokers
and real estate executives say many applications are awaiting
approvals and add that they expect further speculative construction
to begin as the existing space fills up.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a market that has always had speculative
construction,'' said Michael Nachamkin, a vice president of
Prologis Trust, a real estate investment trust that bills itself as
as much an expert in global logistics as a real estate owner. ``You
need to have an inventory of space for your national customers,''
added Lisa R. Clark, a marketing executive with Prologis. She
explained that companies operating on a national scale want
distribution facilities ready when they decide to enter markets,
without the delays involved in securing permits and construction.
</P>
<P>
   A flurry of leasing in the first quarter of this year took 1.35
million square feet of space off the market in the 8A corridor,
according to Cushman &AMP; Wakefield. In the largest single deal, Home
Depot, a household products retailer, leased an entire
812,739-square-foot warehouse in Cranbury. Caliber Logistics took
150,000 square feet at 24 Charles Court in South Brunswick.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an active market,'' said Paul D. Cohen, executive vice
president of SBWE, a real estate services company based in New
Jersey. ``The inventory builds up for a while and then it gets
leased.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Exit 8A is the northernmost spot on the Turnpike with land
available,'' said Jonathan B. Tesser, director of leasing for
Matrix Development Group, one of the pioneer developers in the
area. ``Every time rents start to creep up, people start building
on spec again.''
</P>
<P>
   Rents are modest compared to office space, but given the size of
the buildings, can add up to a hefty annual total. For example,
Building Two in Cranbury Business Park has 151,200 rentable square
feet. Brokers say modern warehouse space typically rents for $4.25
to $4.75 a square foot annually, with older buildings ranging from
$3.75 to $4.25 a square foot. But brokers reported that some owners
have been bumping up asking rents for the most modern and best
located buildings to the $5.10 to $5.25 a foot range in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Tesser estimated there is land near the exit for an additional
15 million to 20 million square feet of development. This land,
which is, in effect, being warehoused for warehouses, has produced
an interesting phenomenon: actively farmed fields running up to the
edge of industrial parks. ``I've got a spinach field on the east
side of the plant, corn on the other and winter wheat in the
back,'' said Milata of Graybar.
</P>
<P>
   The continuing agricultural activity notwithstanding, real
estate executives say almost all of the land is available for
development when needed. ``The owners keep it planted, but all of
it is under contract or option for development,'' said Lou Belfer,
a senior vice president of SBWE.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Real estate executives say the 8A market developed the way it
did because the large blocks of land suddenly became easily
accessible to the Turnpike when the exit was built in 1966. The
highway was widened in the late 1980s, providing separate car and
truck lanes down to 8A.
</P>
<P>
   ``Exit 8A was an afterthought,'' said Cohen, noting that it is
almost midway in the 17 miles between Exits 8 and 9, which were
part of the original layout of the highway, which was built in the
early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Development started here around 1982, but there really wasn't
mass development until 1985,'' Cohen said. He said development
continued actively until 1991, when a recession in the real estate
business brought everything to a halt. Activity resumed in 1995, he
said, with existing property being absorbed, and then new
construction began.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the early building in the area was done by local
developers, such as Matrix, Frank A. Greek and Son and I. Heller.
But in recent years, the real estate investment trusts have become
a factor, with Prologis and Trammell Crow entering the market and
Reckson Associates Realty Corp. combining with the local Morris
Companies.
</P>
<P>
   Matrix took over the old Phelps Dodge building, a dark, brooding
structure long familiar to motorists on the Turnpike. It changed
the appearance of the 650,000-square-foot structure by lightening
the color of the walls. Matrix added 550,000 square feet of space
to what is now called 200 Docks Corner Road and recently finished
leasing it all to tenants that include Barnes &AMP; Noble and Cooper
Tire.
</P>
<P>
   The Graybar operation is in a building built and owned by
Prologis Trust, formerly Security Capital Industrial Trust, which
claims to be the largest owner of warehouse-distribution space in
the country, with 166 million square feet. Like the other buildings
in Cranbury Business Park, this one is tall enough so goods can be
stacked 32 feet high, and it has an advanced fire suppression
system, an ultraflat floor and broad areas outside the building for
trucks to maneuver.
</P>
<P>
   Brokers and other real estate executives say a building of this
sort represents the current state of the art and renders obsolete
buildings put into operation less than a decade ago. Advances in
forklift truck technology have allowed goods to be stacked higher
in the steel racks that fill most warehouses.
</P>
<P>
   Higher stacking is more economical for distributors because it
allows more goods to be stored on the same piece of land. ``Ten
years ago 24-foot clear was state of the art,'' said Nachamkin,
referring to the vertical distance between the floor and the
trusses that support the roof. ``Today 32 feet is standard,'' he
said, noting that some buildings have 36 feet of stacking space.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can get one-third to one-half more product in a building
with 36-foot clear height than 24 feet,'' said Benjamin Katz, a
senior managing director of Insignia/ESG, the real-estate services
company.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a trend toward fewer but bigger boxes in the
warehouse business,'' said Stanley Danzig, a senior director at
Cushman &AMP; Wakefield. ``But only about 10 percent of the product at
8A has ceiling heights over 32 feet.'' However, he pointed out that
not every business needs the greatest height. ``Some people don't
need 32 feet,'' he said. Those older facilities, he said, will be
leased at lesser rents than the new tall buildings can command.
</P>
<P>
   Although the economics of higher stacking are generally
favorable, the technique has imposed some additional demands on
builders. One is for floors that are really, really flat.
</P>
<P>
   Even a minor variation in floor flatness can be a problem when
hoisting pallets of goods over 30 feet and trying to fit them into
closely packed racks. One Prologis estimate is that one millimeter
of variation at floor level can result in a load being as much as
12 inches out of line at the top shelf of a rack.
</P>
<P>
   ``Above 30 feet, you will have things dropping through or they
simply won't go into the rack,'' said William L. Mascharka,
president of Frazier Industrial Co., a major manufacturer of racks
based in Long Valley, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   So builders are using laser-guided devices known as screeds to
produce flat, smooth floors that resemble ice skating rinks. And
the concrete is compounded with a chemical additive that makes the
floor smoother as it is cleaned.
</P>
<P>
   In the Graybar distribution center, a line of grout patching
compound runs down the center of each aisle of racks. The ground
conceals a wire that sends signals to a device on a forklift truck
to keep it squarely in the center of the aisle, so all the driver
has to think about is forward and back and up and down motion.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the forklift in the precisely right position allows
narrow aisles and the ability to pack goods in more closely.
Because of the sensor system, a forklift measuring 76 inches wide
operates in an aisle of just 84 inches. Because the truck cannot
turn in such a narrow space, the building is equipped with
forklifts whose lifting masts pivot to insert and remove pallet
loads of electrical equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of a big population in much of the area off Exit 8A
means that companies can operate at all hours without complaints
about noise from the neighbors. ``Home Depot supplies its stores
overnight,'' said Robert Sager, a managing director at
Insignia/ESG. ``In an industrial park, they can operate any hours
they want without getting residential complaints.''
</P>
<P>
   Real Estate executives say the three main towns in the area,
Cranbury, South Brunswick and Monroe Township, have had varying
attitudes toward development.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first Cranbury was against development, so the early
projects were in Monroe and South Brunswick,''' Cohen said. ``But
then taxes in Cranbury started going through the roof, and coming
out of the recession they changed their master plan and accepted
development.''
</P>
<P>
   Tesser of Matrix Development said that ``20 years ago Cranbury
was the most difficult to deal with.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Now,'' he said, ``Cranbury has most of the available land and
is into development.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
