u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PULLMAN-REAL-900(2TAK     05-01 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PULLMAN-REAL-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAYERS OF HISTORY, BUT AN UNCERTAIN FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By DAVID W. DUNLAP   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ A tumultuous strike more than a century ago settled
the question of whether the model town of Pullman _ built
practically in a single stroke by George M. Pullman to house
thousands of workers of the Pullman Palace Car Co. _ was a new
American utopia.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as a landmarked but beleaguered neighborhood on Chicago's
far South Side, Pullman is struggling to define exactly what it is.
</P>
<P>
   The question is more than an existential exercise, for it bears
on a new effort to restore the remaining public buildings and
attract the visitors _ and visitors' dollars _ needed to bolster
its economy.
</P>
<P>
   The critical state of affairs was underscored in December, when
the main office building and an adjacent erecting shop, both
abandoned, were set afire by an arsonist. The blaze ravaged the
clock tower, a red-brick Victorian confection that marked Pullman's
picturesque spot in an otherwise unforgiving industrial landscape
along Lake Calumet, closer to Indiana than to the Loop.
</P>
<P>
   Although Pullman was developed in 1880 as a self-sufficient
community within the greater township of Hyde Park, it was long ago
subsumed into the city of Chicago. It is now a neighborhood of
roughly 35 blocks, with some 4,000 residents. Under court order,
the Palace Car Company gave up its role as landlord by 1909, but
its successor, Pullman-Standard, was building and refurbishing
railroad cars here through the 60's.
</P>
<P>
   Red-brick workers' cottages and two-story flats still line
Pullman's verdant blocks in neat, tight arrays. The Hotel Florence,
a rambling Queen Anne dowager, still greets visitors with a deep
veranda and a tiny mountain range of gables, dormers and chimneys.
The abandoned market hall is ringed by four curving colonnades that
recall the loggias of Renaissance Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring over the town square is the steeple of the Greenstone
Church, made of a stone that ranges in color from moss to lichen to
jade, with stained-glass windows as delicate as doilies. The town
stable, now an auto-repair shop, is still ornamented with two
carved horse heads.
</P>
<P>
   But the clock tower, Pullman's cynosure, is a tumbled and
charred ruin whose arched windows are now empty portals to the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's swaying in the breeze,'' said Keith Herron, the assistant
superintendent of historic sites in the Illinois Historic
Preservation Agency, which owns the clock tower. The state plans to
spend $2.1 million to stabilize the structure by wrapping steel
bands around it and filling in the windows with wood braces to
increase lateral stability.
</P>
<P>
   Preservationists in Pullman are encouraged by the renewed
attention that has accompanied the catastrophe. After a long spell
of what seemed like official indifference, the city and state are
forming a task force to chart a fresh revitalization effort.
</P>
<P>
   The panel is to be headed by James Thompson, a former Illinois
governor whose administration bought the clock tower and hotel 10
years ago to create what Thompson called ``the greatest railroad
museum in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Although nothing came of those plans, great fires seem to have a
galvanizing effect on Chicagoans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Isn't it sad that it has to be something tragic like this that
has to be a catalyst?'' asked Deborah Bellamy-Jawor, executive
director of the Historic Pullman Foundation, a nonprofit group
concerned with preservation, restoration, education and research.
``But from now on, it's a bright future.''
</P>
<P>
   The Florence (named for George Pullman's daughter) was already
scheduled to undergo a $1.9 million stabilization later this year.
And a $200,000 renovation is under way at the market hall.
</P>
<P>
   Restoring the public structures, no easy task in itself, may be
the most straightforward challenge facing the task force. More
vexing _ and more interesting _ is how to interpret and convey
these 19th-century buildings to a 21st-century audience.
</P>
<P>
   Is Pullman a monument to transportation? Certainly, the name was
once synonymous with travel, since the sleeping and dining cars
that emerged from Pullman's factories made long-distance train
trips ``comfortable, inexpensive and safe enough for the middle
class,'' Stanley Buder wrote in ``Pullman: An Experiment in
Industrial Order and Community Planning'' (1967).
</P>
<P>
   Is it instead a monument to city planning and that long
tradition of American utopianism that spawned experimental
communities like New Harmony, Ind.; Columbia, Md., and, more
recently, the Florida towns of Seaside and Celebration?
</P>
<P>
   Is it a monument to organized labor? The 1894 strike, which grew
out of the Pullman company's refusal to abate rents even as it
slashed wages and jobs, was a milestone in the union movement. It
reverberated nationally when it was joined by the American Railway
Union under Eugene Debs, which refused to move trains carrying
Pullman cars, prompting the government to use federal troops as
strike breakers.
</P>
<P>
   Or is Pullman a monument to civil rights? The men who tended to
Pullman cars were Pullman employees (the cars were leased, not
sold, to railroads) and their union, the Brotherhood of Sleeping
Car Porters, was one of the most potent advocates in the early 20th
century for the equal treatment of African-American workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is some of the richest history that we have at any site,''
said Herron, whose agency owns about 60 properties throughout
Illinois.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Added to the historic complexity is the complicated economic and
racial reality of modern Pullman, which cleaves along 111th Street
into a poorer north neighborhood, largely of renters, and a more
affluent _ though scarcely wealthy _ south neighborhood, where many
homeowners have fixed up their properties. The districts are
separated by the old Pullman works, where some residents would like
to see a shopping center, while others would prefer a more purely
historic restoration.
</P>
<P>
   Pullman said he built the town to ``exclude all baneful
influences'' _ taverns, brothels and labor agitators chief among
them _ and to provide homes ``of such character and surroundings as
would prove so attractive as to cause the best class of mechanic to
seek that place for employment.''
</P>
<P>
   His architect was Solon S. Beman, who had worked under Richard
M. Upjohn of New York on the Connecticut State Capitol in Hartford.
The landscape designer was Nathan F. Barrett, who had laid out
estates in the New York area.
</P>
<P>
   ``George Pullman understood the commercial value of beauty,''
said Michael Wolski, the foundation's tour coordinator. And
properties in Pullman _ even the church, which was to be rented by
different denominations _ were expected to earn a 6 percent return
annually on investment.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure revenues, the company cut two checks for workers: one
for the current amount of rent due, the other for whatever was left
over in pay. Workers would endorse the rent checks back to the
company at the Pullman bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have seen men with families of eight or nine children to
support crying there because they only got three or four cents
after paying their rent,'' said Thomas W. Heathcoate, a car
builder, testifying in 1894 before the federal commission
investigating the strike. The U.S. Strike Commission concluded that
``the esthetic features are admired by visitors, but have little
money value to employees, especially when they lack bread.''
</P>
<P>
   In a blighted state by the 1960s, Pullman was relatively
inexpensive. ``A lot of people moved here because the housing was
affordable,'' said John Cwenkala, who has lived in Pullman 16
years. ``Pullman is one of the only communities that was really
restored by blue-collar workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Like most of his neighbors, Cwenkala is eager to see action
after decades of talk. ``There has been no lack of studies,'' he
said. ``It would be nice to see something happen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
