<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERBS SAY ALLIED MISSILE KILLED 34 ON A BUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUZANE, Yugoslavia _ Under the light of a bright moon Saturday
night, the wreckage of a bus that had been sliced in two,
apparently by a NATO missile, still smoldered. At least four bodies
and many body parts lay scattered around. The Serbs Saturday night
said 34 bodies had been recovered, and 15 children were believed to
be among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Five people survived the missile strike Saturday afternoon, said
police and Defense Ministry officials who escorted reporters from
Belgrade to this hamlet of seven houses 12 miles north of Kosovo's
capital, Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   The bus, a bright red vehicle known as the Nis Express that
passed this spot every day, was traveling south from southern
Serbia's largest city, Nis, to Pristina and was crossing a concrete
bridge across a gorge when the missile slammed into it, according
to the police and witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   The missile sliced the bus in two and sent half of the vehicle
plunging 40 feet into the gorge below. In the darkness, it was not
possible to see whether parts from the missile were strewn around
the bus wreckage.
</P>
<P>
   Nine hours after the reported attack, said by witnesses to have
occurred around 1 p.m., wreckage still smoldered, and the stench of
burned flesh and burning rubber filled the air.
</P>
<P>
   The body of a man wearing cheap brown trousers and worn shoes
lay in the gorge. Up on the bridge, near a large hole apparently
gouged by the missile, the other half of the bus lay tipped on its
side, smoldering in the moonlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I heard the plane, and then saw it,'' said Rajko Maksic, a
burly 45-year-old farmer who said he was working in his field just
yards from the bridge when the attack occurred. ``Then I heard a
bang, and I looked up and saw bodies falling down, and children
falling, and I ran for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Maksic said the bus was the only vehicle on the bridge, which is
part of the main highway linking Pristina with Serbia proper.
Within 20 minutes, he said, ambulances arrived, taking the five
survivors _ including two children _ to a hospital in Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Policemen on the scene said that a bridge further down the
highway toward the provincial capital had also been attacked by
NATO planes, and that one of the ambulances was damaged during that
raid. There was no way to confirm this account, as the police told
reporters that the bridge where the bus was hit was not safe to
pass and that they could not travel further down the road.
</P>
<P>
   As they spoke, planes flew loudly overhead, and very heavy
explosions were heard behind the hills that separate Luzane from
Pristina.
</P>
<P>
   Maksic said that there had not been much bombing in this
immediate area, but that NATO had targeted a nearby railway. He
could think of no reason for hitting the bus, and was haunted by
all he had seen.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is impossible that there could have been a mix-up, because
there are no military objects around here,'' he said. ``My head is
completely confused. All I can think of is the kids I saw.''
</P>
</TEXT>
