<HEADLINE>
LAKERS' RICE BURNED ABOUT HIS ROLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Glen Rice arrived in March, presumably as the missing
piece to the Lakers' championship dreams. But as the regular season
winds down, the sharpshooter admits he's frustrated with his role
in the offense and ambivalent about his future with this team.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview Saturday, Rice said the Lakers have failed to
maximize his skills, and it's showing in his performance. His 42.2
percent field-goal mark is the lowest of a 10-year career in which
he's averaged 46.3 percent. A career 40.9 percent shooter from
3-point range, he's hitting just 36.4 percent this year, worst
since his rookie season.
</P>
<P>
   Playing a secondary role for the first time in his career, Rice
said he still doesn't feel like a vital part of the offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not really,'' he said. ``I feel that when you have a player
like myself, you got to be willing to set more screens, get me
involved in the offense more than what I have been. I'm not just a
spot-up shooter. I got a lot of other things to my game _ post-up,
coming off screens, penetration dribble _ and I want to use all
those things to help this team. And thus far I haven't had too many
opportunities to do that. So it is frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   It also shouldn't be too surprising, and perhaps that's why Rice
was initially hesitant to be traded to the Lakers from Charlotte.
Accustomed to being the go-to guy, Rice is trying to fit into an
offense where Shaquille O'Neal and Kobe Bryant combine for 34 shots
a game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I haven't adjusted to it as well as I wanted to.
This definitely thus far is not the type of basketball that Glen
Rice is capable of playing,'' Rice said. ``I try and go out there
and I try and stay focused. I feel that we definitely got to be
able to use me a lot more than we have been.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't shot like this in quite awhile, and it's something
that I'm not proud of. It's something that I think about every day.
I just think that if I'm in the flow of the offense a little
better, the (shooting) percentage definitely will be higher than
what it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Several weeks ago, coach Kurt Rambis indicated the Lakers had
tweaked the offense to provide more opportunities for Rice to shoot
off of screens, as he prefers. But asked about those changes, Rice
shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see it every now and then, and it's not as much as I would
like it to be,'' Rice said. ``It just has to do with the
play-calling.''
</P>
<P>
   Rice might accept the third-fiddle role and diminished stats if
the Lakers were winning, but they're 13-13 since his arrival.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not OK. No way in the world that I'm OK with the way
things have gone to this point,'' he said. ``I could be somewhat a
little more satisfied (with a lesser role) if we were playing up to
our capabilities and we were winning a lot more. But that hasn't
happened, so no, I'm not OK with it. It's a very, very bad
combination.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers hold a $7.1 million option on Rice for next season,
but had planned to sign him to a long-term extension; or they could
let him walk as a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Does Rice's experience so far make him hesitant to stay? He
laughed, then said, ``I tell you what, I'll hold onto that
comment.'' &UR; !end! &LR;  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
