<HEADLINE>
SCHOOL TRAGEDY HAUNTS NRA ANNUAL MEETING
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ He stands alone on a pedestal at the foot of the
concrete steps leading to the Colorado state Capitol, eyes always
forward, shoulders set, rifle at the ready. As the spring fog
lifted Saturday morning, however, the stoic Civil War statue found
himself surrounded by row after row of neatly stacked red and white
placards, each reading, ``Shame on the NRA.''
</P>
<P>
   Already hundreds had gathered at the Capitol, some holding
protest signs on their shoulders the way a infantryman holds his
weapon. Before long, the crowd would grow to more than 7,000. They
had come to protest the annual meeting of the National Rifle
Association, which was being held just down the street in the
cavernous Adam's Mark Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I simply can't understand it,'' said Merrill Evans, a retired
engineer with a T-shirt reading ``Colorado Coalition Against Gun
Violence'' pulled snugly over his wool jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Evans lives in Littleton, where two teenagers massacred 12 stu
dents and a teacher less than two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``The NRA, out of respect, should have canceled all their
convention programs here, not just some of them,'' Evans said.
``But, no. They bring Charlton Heston and others into town and it's
like rubbing the violence and the evil in our faces, and we won't
stand for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Only a few blocks away, in the plaza ballroom of the Adam's
Mark, a huge cheer went up after an NRA official took to the podium
to say the program would be delayed several minutes because more
members showed up than expected. Eventually, more than 3,000
crammed into a room designed for 2,000.
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Denver resident Allen Upshaw, said he wasn't about
to be intimidated by those who said the NRA didn't belong in his
town at this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to make us feel like we had something to do with
those kids dying,'' he said. ``That just isn't so, and we can't let
the liberal media, which spreads such foolishness, dictate what we
do.''
</P>
<P>
   Some NRA members carried signs, too. One proclaimed, ``Hitler
was in favor of gun control.''
</P>
<P>
   Each side had buttons and posters and T-shirts. Each was armed
with pamphlets and propaganda. Each had a slate of speakers waiting
for the cameras to roll. These were the opening volleys, the first
shots, a skirmish in a daylong battle of sound bites, in an
unending war of words.
</P>
<P>
   And I'd almost missed it.
</P>
<P>
   Before dawn I drove to Littleton, watching the sun rise above
the low hills of Clement Park, not far from Columbine High School.
The night before, the father and grandfather of murder victim
Daniel Rohrbough had cut down and hauled away two of the 15 crosses
that had been erected on one of the hills. Thirteen crosses were
for victims. These two were for the killers, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day, they were re placed by smaller, cruder
versions.
</P>
<P>
   Everywhere in the park there are flowers and gifts left for the
families of the dead. The saplings lining West Bowles Avenue are
covered with ribbons and droop under the weight of teddy bears and
memen toes. On other trees, deflated bal loons hang like withered
fruit.
</P>
<P>
   After all these days, mourning has lost its freshness.
</P>
<P>
   Tents and sheets of plastic cover most of the offerings. There
are poems and plaques and signs with messages like, ``Columbine
must be doing some thing very good and special for Satan to try so
hard to mess it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The grass around the memorial has been rubbed to mud by constant
visitors. Each day the paths are cov ered with straw, which is
ground into mud again by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   It's a difficult place to visit, and an even more difficult
place to leave.
</P>
<P>
   By the time I got back to the Adam's Mark, the crowd in the ball
room was standing for an opening prayer, heads bowed. Looking down,
it seemed I was the only one in the room with muddy shoes.
</P>
<P>
   At the Capitol, protesters listened as Rabbi Steven Foster told
them this was not a rally but a ``holy convoca tion.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A collection of morons is what it is,'' said Bill Lee, a tall,
barrel-chested former gun dealer at the edge of the Capitol crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're all fools,'' said Lee, who lives in Fort Collins and
boasts of having sold 35,000 weapons during his career. ``You're a
bunch of sheep.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I pity you,'' answered Nancy Coleman, who was in town from
California visiting relatives. ``It's people like you that got me
out here today. I used to be in the silent ma jority who are
against this insane proliferation of guns. Now, I'm in the
semi-silent majority.''
</P>
<P>
   As the protesters finished their rally and begin marching down
16th Street toward the Adam's Mark, the NRA was bringing out its
big guns.
</P>
<P>
   Executive Vice President Wayne LaPierre attacked ``the Clinton
Jus tice Department'' and promised to fight against waiting periods
for gun purchases, against restrictions on private gun sales or gun
shows, and in favor of laws that would protect gun manufacturers
from lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of LaPierre's speech, protesters had reached the
hotel, the lead group singing We Shall Over come.
</P>
<P>
   Outside to confront them was Rick Reeser, carrying a sign read
ing, ``Clinton &AMP; Cronies Capitalize on Columbine Killings.''
</P>
<P>
   Reeser wore a ball cap with ``NRA'' stitched on the front and a
necktie made to look like the U.S. flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``These people have been brain washed,'' he said. ``I'm here to
tell them that Ted Kennedy's car has killed more people than my
gun.''
</P>
<P>
   Inside, Charlton Heston, the actor and NRA president, delivered
the same basic message to his organiza tion, though in deeper, more
lofty, more pious tones.
</P>
<P>
   It was as if Moses had descended from the Colorado mountaintops
to say the original stone tablets contained a typographical error
in line six, and should have read, ``Thou SHALT kill, sometimes.''
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand NRA faithful stood and cheered.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand protesters sur rounded the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   When the speeches were over, some NRA members went outside.
Under a gunmetal sky and constant drizzle, the enemies met,
matching one another sign for sign, word for word. I stood and
watched, and lis tened, the rain washing off my shoes as the
discourse dirtied the street and everyone in it.
</P>
<P>
   Afterwards, I drove back to Little ton. On this day, the only
way to get clean was to walk again in the mud.
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
