<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-01 23:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1102 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-BLACKS-IN-BASEBAL     05-01 1736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BLACKS-IN-BASEBALL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL STRIKING OUT WITH BLACKS  
 MAJOR LEAGUES STILL WHITE GUYS' GAME, CRITICS SAY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Twelve years after Jackie Robinson broke baseball's
color line, the last of the then-16 existing major-league clubs
finally integrated. Pumpsie Green wore a Boston Red Sox uniform in
1959, completing baseball's cycle of breaking racial barriers.
</P>
<P>
   Forty years later, some are wondering whether those barriers
really have been broken.
</P>
<P>
   Amazingly, the percentage of U.S.-born Black players in the
major leagues has declined since 1959. Of the 750 players on
Opening Day rosters this season, 108, or 14.4 percent, were
U.S.-born Blacks. When Green joined the Red Sox, the figure was
17.25 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the scarcity of African-Americans extends beyond the
field, to the coaching staffs, to key front-office personnel, to
scouts and fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if there's any validity to it, but I think Black
kids look at baseball and ask, `Why should I invest the time and
effort into a sport where the players who look like me are so few?'
'' said Dave Stewart, Toronto Blue Jays assistant general manager,
who is African-American. ``You look at baseball and you do not see
a lot of Black faces in the seats and you definitely don't see them
on the field. As a Black kid, why would you be encouraged to play
baseball?''
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League and the National Basketball
Association have become the focus of many young Black athletes, who
see college stars move to the pros with regularity. In many cases,
it takes longer to develop major-league baseball skills, and
chances of instant success are slim. Time in the minor leagues is
almost guaranteed for any young prospect.
</P>
<P>
   ``No matter what you do in this game, you have to wait for your
opportunity,'' said the Diamondbacks' Tony Womack, who toiled six
years in Pittsburgh's minor league system before catching his break
in 1997. ``Some may not want to, but that's the way it tends to be.
If anything, I'd like to see more Blacks with front office or
manager's jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks have two U.S.-born Blacks _ Womack and Bernard
Gilkey _ on their active roster.
</P>
<P>
   Two clubs had only one U.S.-born Black each on their Opening Day
rosters _ the Kansas City Royals (Jermaine Dye) and the New York
Yankees (Derek Jeter). At the other end were the Cincinnati Reds,
who had seven, and Baltimore Orioles, with six plus one, Delino
DeShields, who was on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The overall figure of 14.4 percent, calculated in a survey by
``The'' ``Arizona Republic,'' does not include eight Black players
who were on the disabled list when the season began, but even if
they were added, the percentage rises only to 15.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is not only touchy but murky as well. Major League
Baseball doesn't count minorities, and ``The Republic's'' survey
was not scientific. Some players of mixed heritage were counted as
Latino because that is their preference. New York Mets right
fielder Bobby Bonilla, for instance, was born in New York. Even
though his parents are of African descent, they came from the
Dominican Republic and identify with a Latin heritage.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the confusion, the figures should sound warning bells
throughout baseball, Stewart and others say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it look like bringing Jackie Robinson into the game
was a joke. Me personally, as a Black athlete, I appreciate the
fact the barrier was broken. But if things continue, then what was
it all for? The changes have to come from management,'' Stewart
said. &QL; 
In the stands &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A few years ago, a group of serious baseball fans played a game
of spotting the minorities at major-league parks. They were amazed
at the low number of Black faces among fans who showed up to watch
games in Minnesota, Atlanta, Baltimore and many other cities.
</P>
<P>
   It's a trend that should worry baseball officials, said Charles
Farrell, director of Rainbow Sports, a branch of the Rev. Jesse
Jackson's Rainbow Push Coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The interesting part is Blacks will watch the game on TV,''
Farrell said. ``The numbers prove it. Why is it that
African-Americans watch but won't come out to the ballpark?
Baseball is infinitely more affordable than football and certainly
more than basketball. Baseball is a game that if you get hooked on
it, you're hooked for life.
</P>
<P>
   ``As salaries escalate and new stadiums are built, baseball has
to find ways to fill those seats for it to remain economically
viable. What better fans to bring to the game than
African-Americans and Latinos? If they aggressively do that, out of
those communities will come future players. And the next generation
of fans has to come from the Black community, because baseball
already has the White fans.'' &QL; 
Blacks not playing game &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The raw numbers speak for themselves. Blacks are simply not
playing baseball in the numbers they once did. Then again, baseball
is not the marquee sport it once was and that, some believe, is the
reason for the dwindling number of African-Americans in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1959, baseball was really the way to go for all athletes,''
Diamondbacks General Manager Joe Garagiola Jr. said. ``The other
sports, basketball and football, were nowhere near being where they
are now. The big money, if you could call it that back then, was in
baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   The number of Black athletes in the NBA and NFL in the late
1950s barely registered a blip on the screen. The number of Black
players in the NBA (79 percent) and NFL (66 percent) dominate over
baseball, and the total number of Black athletes in professional
sports has shot through the roof. Baseball's number of 14.4 percent
is just slightly more than the percentage of Blacks in the total
U.S. population, which was 12.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It's also true that salaries in basketball are higher than in
any other sport and that icons such as Michael Jordan and Magic
Johnson have placed basketball on a much higher pedestal in the
Black community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone got a bald head because Michael had it,'' said Joe
Black, the 1952 National League rookie of the year and one of the
first Blacks in the game, who now works with Major League Baseball
and the Diamondbacks. ``The kids look on TV and see all they have
to do is dunk a basketball and they'll make millions. They're led
by emotions rather than common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course, hardly anyone can reach the level of being a pro
basketball or football player. A baseball career is clearly longer.
Maybe it's slower to achieve, but you eventually can get the same
notoriety. I try to talk to young kids about playing and they tell
me it's too hot to play baseball. The problem is, you cannot become
a major leaguer unless you play the game.'' &QL; 
RBI for poor kids &QL;
</P>
<P>
   That is where RBI (Reviving Baseball in Inner cities) wants to
make a difference. The program started in 1989, and two years later
Major League Baseball took it over. It provides places and
equipment to be used primarily by Boys and Girls Clubs of America.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of the 100,000 participating players come from
economically deprived families and might not normally have an
opportunity to play organized baseball. But RBI is not entirely for
Black children. It is in inner cities for any underprivileged
child.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly getting a lot more kids playing who would not
be playing at all,'' said RBI's director, Thomas Brasuell. ``We
could always get more. It's hard to say if we're going backwards or
moving ahead with the addition of Latino players. It's a tough one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've read where by the year 2010 Latinos will be the largest
minority in the country. When you look at it that way, we are going
in the right direction. Then you look at New York City, where 30
percent of our players are Black. Well, in the entire city, 13
percent is Black. So I'd say RBI is doing all right in New York.''
</P>
<P>
   So far one player has made it from RBI to the majors _ Florida
Marlins outfielder Vic Darensbourg, who grew up in south central
Los Angeles, where the RBI program was founded.
</P>
<P>
   RBI has its backers and its skeptics.
</P>
<P>
   ``RBI is working in selective cities, but not everywhere,''
Black said. ``Once most kids finish with it (at age 16) they don't
think about going on to play high school or college ball. The next
thing you see them doing is dunking in a park. Maybe RBI needs to
have people like Frank Robinson, Juan Marichal, Willie Mays and
Larry Doby go out and talk to the kids. Let them know they can make
it all the way. Being a professional baseball player beats the
nine-to-five job most of them will end up with.'' &QL; 
Black scouts needed &QL; 
Like Black, Stewart, who won 168 major-league games, wonders aloud
how much of an effort scouts, the lifeblood of baseball, make in
getting into the inner city or to predominantly Black colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The predominant race of scouts is White,'' said Stewart, one
of four minority assistant general managers in baseball. ``You
can't get them to go into a neighborhood like the one I grew up in.
They just don't feel comfortable or safe. I grew up in Oakland, the
same place that produced Willie Stargell, Joe Morgan, Rickey
Henderson, Frank Robinson and myself. Are you telling me baseball
players stopped coming out of Oakland?''
</P>
<P>
   Said Cleveland outfielder David Justice: ``Obviously they aren't
scouting in Black neighborhoods. The talent is there. Maybe the
scouts just aren't looking in the right places. To me, the
shrinking number is not amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Negro League great Buck O'Neill, a member of the Hall of
Fame and the man who discovered Lou Brock while he was playing at
Southern University in Baton Rouge, La.: ``It's a problem all over
baseball. We've all got to do a better job of getting the Black
kids to play baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the biggest perceptions baseball has been fighting for
decades is the preponderance of White front office officials. Of
the 30 general managers in the game, none belong to a minority
race. Commissioner Bud Selig recently sent out a letter ordering
each club to identify five minority candidates for future posts.
</P>
<P>
   But Selig himself has been criticized recently after he hired
four new vice presidents over the winter. All were White. &QL; 
Pedro Gomez can be reached at (602) 444-2364 or at
pedro.gomez(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
